<HEAD><TITLE>August 22, 1996-What's New in Nuclear Waste in Minnesota?</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY>

<H2>News Item - August 22, 1996<P></H2>

<H3>What's New in Nuclear Waste in Minnesota?
</H3>
Sustainable Minnesota posts this update on Nuclear Waste Siting in Minnesota from Carol A. Overland, an attorney representing Florence Township in Goodhue County, Minnesota.<P>

 <HR>
Overland Law Office<BR>
Carol A. Overland, Attorney at Law<BR>
209 Oak Street<BR>
PO Box 202<BR>
Farmington, MN  55024<BR>
612-460-6461<P>

<P>
<B>Topics:</B><BR>
<li>Florence Townships Appeals Nuclear Waste Decision<BR>
<LI>Northern States Power Submits Application to the NRC<BR>
<LI>Lake City is Denied Right to Review and Comment on NSP's Emergency Plan Prior to Application Submission to NRC<P>

<B>Florence Townships Appeals Nuclear Waste Decision</B><BR>
In January, 1996, Florence Township filed a claim against Northern States Power (NSP), the Minnesota Environmental Quality Board (EQB), the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (PUC), and Goodhue County.  The claim was made under the Minnesota Environmental Rights Act (MERA) and it charged the Defendants with violations of environmental law.  Florence asked the court to suspend the siting of nuclear waste and declare that the siting process violated the 1994 siting mandate, the Power Plant Siting Act, and the Certificate of Need statute.  <P>

On May 1, 1996, Judge Shumaker of the Ramsey County Court issued his opinion. That opinion dismissed Florence Township's claim, holding that a claim could be made under MERA only when there was pollution, impairment, and destruction to the environment, and that there was no pollution , impairment and destruction, only a threat.<P>

Florence Township's appeal is based upon the definition of "pollution, impairment, and destruction" found in MERA, which states very clearly that it is "conduct by any person which violates, or is likely to violate, any environmental quality standard, limitation, rule, order, license, stipulation agreement, or permit of the state..."  By statutory definition, pollution, impairment, and destruction  has occurred, and Florence Township has a ripe claim against the defendants.  The lower court did not address the definition of pollution, impairment, and destruction, and in error required that actual impairment, and destruction, and error required that actual physical damage occur before Florence Township could make a claim.<P>

We are asking the appellate court to review Florence Township's claim in light of the statutory definition of pollution, to determine ripeness of that claim within the parameters of MERA and Uniform Declaratory Judgment Act, and to find that ht lower courts dismissal was an error of law.  the lower court must be required to examine the acts of NSP, the EQB, PUC, and Goodhue County and issue a declaratory judgment as to whether their acts have in fact violated environmental law.  If the defendants have violated the law with the siting process used to select "Site P," that site must not be considered a s a site form nuclear waste.  It must not be used in an NRC application.<P>

<P>
<B>NSP Applied to Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC)for a License to Store Nuclear Waste in Florence Township on August 8, 1996</B><P>

NSP has made its application to the NRC to use Site P in Florence Township as a nuclear waste storage facility--the first off-site part 72 application ever reviewed by the NRC.  This site has had NO state environmental review-- the EQB has taken NO action on the EQB task Force Report submitted last January, and most of the EQB meeting scheduled since that time have been canceled.  EQB staff has issued a report (call 612-296-2871 and ask for "Staff Report to the MEQB on the Siting of a Dry Cask Storage Facility in Goodhue County")  with four options for Board consideration.  Comments are due August 23, 1996.<P>

Here are the options being considered:<BR>
1.  Continue the siting process<BR>
2.  Suspend the siting process<BR>
3.  Terminate the siting process<BR>
4.  Broaden the scope of the site search<P>

These options are illusory.  None of these options have any effect on NSP's application to the NRC.  None of the options address the faulty and illegal siting process.  No matter which option the EQB selects, the NRC continues to work toward s licensing "Site P, " and until Site P is eliminated from consideration, Florence township will continue to actively oppose siting efforts.  Until the legislation changes, and until NSP is required to withdraw its application, the application moves forward and NSP moves closer to having a second option for the storage of nuclear waste.  By now, NSP must realize the benefits of the Florence Township site- if it is sited in Florence, they will not pay the $500,000 per year penalty for waste stored at Prairie Island after 1999.  After just a few years, it is more economical for NSP to store waste in Florence Township.  <P>

The result of this application is that there are going to be two nuclear waste dumps on the river in the middle of human population.  This was not the intention of the 1994 legislation, but this is the result.<P>

<B>Lake City was Denied the Right to Review and Comment on NSP's Emergency Plan Prior to NSP's Submission of Application to the NRC</B><P>

On August 2, 1996, Lake City made a formal request o NSP to review the emergency plan for the Florence township Nuclear Waste Storage Facility.  NRC regulation requires the utility to allow emergency response organizations expected to respond to an emergency to review and comment upon the proposed emergency plan.  Not only did NSP refuse to allow Lake City to review the plan-- Lake City has had no notification from NSP that it was even under consideration as the responder.<P>

When Lake City discovered that it was indeed the primary responder, it demanded a copy of the plan for the required review.  NSP arrogantly refused and did not send a copy until after its application was sent to the NRC on August 8, 1996.  Lake City was denied its right to comment on the plan prior to the application.<P>

Concerns were raised by the Minnesota Department of Public Safety, which told NSP that it should specifically identify the organizations expected to respond, and was concerned that NSP has had NO discussions with Lake City.  The Departments of Public Health and Public Safety were not allowed by NSP to review its Safety Analysis Report (SAR), which is often cross-referenced in the emergency plan.  Because they could not review the SAR, they could not determine the adequacy of some aspects of the plan.  NSP refused to provide sufficient information to the state agencies charged with protecting the public.<P>

Both departments stated that Pressurized Ion Chambers must be used for radiation monitoring, and that due to the close proximity of the site to residents, "it would be irresponsible to propose any monitoring capability for Florence township site which is less than what is currently in place at the on-site ISFSI."  NSP refuses to provide such monitoring.  The departments also advised that a meteorological station be on location.  NSP also refuses to monitor weather on-site.<P>

<B>Township Takes Action</B><P>

What is the Township doing?  Administratively, we are actively working with the EQB, PUC and NRC process.  We're commenting on the dockets, and faithfully attend meetings, however, the EQB has been consistently denying us any opportunity to speak since last January.  Given that the focus of our lawsuit was denial of participation to the township, it's amazing that they continue to deny us any opportunity to speak.  We've also met with DPS Commissioner Kris Sanda, the Emergency Management Division Administrators, and Department of Health to keep our foot in the door and let them know we're concerned and working on the issue.<P>

On the NRC level, we're getting up to speed on the NRC regulations.  They are not at all concerned that NSP has flagrantly violated NRC's 10 CFR 72.32 (a)(14).  The township will file a petition with the NRC regarding that violation.  The township will also file a petition asking that NSP not be allowed to use Site P as its proposed site because it was selected in an illegal siting process and it is not a legitimate site.  Legally, as shown above, we're moving up to the Appellate Court with hopes of reinforcing the MERA.  The appellate argument will probably be scheduled for November.<P>

Lake City's City Council will decide if it will hire outside counsel to join the legal battle.  It is the governmental organization with standing to oppose NSP's violation of NRC regulation.<P>

Legislatively, we're proposing a clean, short, and achievable lobbying strategy:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Eliminate the alternate siting mandate (which breaches the contract between the state, NSP to which the tribe intended third-party beneficiary) and require that NSP withdraw its NRC application.<BR>
<LI>Compensate the Prairie Island tribe for this breach of contract<BR>
<LI>Minnesota agencies charged with oversight of nuclear waste must address the issue and site nuclear waste responsibly with full state review.
</UL><P>
We're making a decidedly non-partisan effort, working with the Republicans, Democrats, Prairie Island Dakota Community, and environmental groups to develop common ground and pave the way for results this year.  This is a Minnesota issue that goes beyond party politics and requires everyone's concerted efforts.  As our bumper stickers say, "Prairie Island is Our Backyard, Too!"  Fingerpointing an holding any community hostage will not solve this problem.  We must all become involved and work towards responsible siting of nuclear waste.<P>

Florence Township needs your support in these efforts. Call the EQB to get their report and submit comments.  Send contribution to support our appeal to the Dry Cask Storage Opposition Fund c/o Florence Township Treasurer Elaine Wurst, 34890 Staehli Park Road, Lake City, MN  55041.  Write to your legislators urging their support of this legislative strategy.  Finally, write to every paper in the state about this issue. <P>

If you have any questions, feel free to give me a call at 612-460-6461.  I'll also gladly provide other names and numbers for further information.<P>

Sincerely,<P>

Carol Overland<BR>
Attorney at Law for Florence Township on Dry Cask Issues<BR>

<HR>
