<HEAD><TITLE>July 24, 1996 - Green Scissors Votes Imminent in the House:  Nuclear Subsidies, Water Projects Targeted</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H2>News Item - July 24, 1996</H2>

<H3> Green Scissors Votes Imminent in the House:  Nuclear Subsidies, Water Projects Targeted</H3>

Friends of the Earth Action Alert: <BR>
July 23, 1996<P>

 
<B>Action: </B> <P>
Call your Representative and ask him/her to support three Green Scissors
amendments to the House Energy & Water Appropriations bill for fiscal year
1997 (H.R.  H.R. 3816).  A vote is expected on Wednesday, July 24. <P>
 
<B>Summary:  </B><P>

The Green Scissors campaign has been leading the charge to cut subsidies for the nuclear industry.  In addition, we have targeted pork-barrel projects that waste taxpayer dollars and hurt the environment.  This week, the House of Representatives will vote on three high priority amendments: <P>
 
<LI>The Foley (R-FL)-Obey (D-WI)-Minge (D- MN)-Royce (R-CA) amendment to kill the Department of Energy's Advanced Light Water Reactor Program (ALWR).  The ALWR program is a textbook example of corporate welfare -- subsidizing companies like Westinghouse and General Electric to design and engineer nuclear reactors.  The program has received more than $230 million in federal support since 1992.  The ALWR lacks a U.S.  market and poses a threat to non-proliferation policy.  Utilizing this technology would add to our growing nuclear waste disposal problem.  The ALWR program was created to be a five year program -- FY97 would be the sixth year.  A "yes" vote on this amendment would cut $17 million and terminate the program.<P> 

<LI>The Petri (R-WI)-DeFazio (D-OR) amendment to cut FY97 funding for the Bureau of Reclamation's Animas-LaPlata water project.  The Animas-LaPlata project (ALP) is a $715 million boondoggle that would benefit a handful of ranchers and growers at the expense of federal taxpayers, downstream water users, and endangered fish species.  Appropriating funds to build the current design would commit federal taxpayers to an unnecessarily expensive, environmentally harmful project that fails to accomplish its purported mission of delivering water to Native Americans.  The Petri-DeFazio amendment would cut the $9. 5 million currently included in the bill to begin construction. <P>

<LI>The Markey (D-MA) amendment to cut Department of Energy funding for nuclear pyroprocessing.  Pyroprocessing is nuclear fuel reprocessing that proponents claim reduces the toxicity and volume of certain kinds of nuclear waste.  The technology is a wolf in sheep's clothing -- separating nuclear materials and complicating the disposition of high-level radioactive waste poses significant proliferation and environmental risks.  Congress has killed similar programs twice in recent years.  The bill provides $45 million cumulative for pyroprocessing for FY97.   <P>
These amendments closely track the recommendations of environmentalists, taxpayer groups, and deficit hawks in Green Scissors '96. <P>
 
<B>Timing and Logistics:</B><P>  
The House Appropriations Committee approved the Energy & Water Appropriations bill for fiscal year 1997 on June 12.  The full House of Representatives is expected to consider the bill on June 23rd or shortly
thereafter. <P>
 
The House Energy & Water Appropriations bill provides annual funding for Department of Energy and Interior Department activities related to energy and water projects.  The amendments to cut funding will be offered when the House considers the bill. <P>

For more information please contact Gawain Kripke, Friends of the Earth, at 202/783-7400 ext. 212 or email at gkripke@foe.org. <P>

To check out Green Scissors '96, check out the Friends of the Earth Website:  <A HREF="http://www.foe.org/"> http://www.foe.org</A>.
<HR>
