<HEAD><TITLE>July 24, 1996 - Statement Of Charlie Higley, Senior Policy Analyst With Public Citizen, On H.R. 3790, The "Electric Consumers' Power To Choose Act Of 1996," Introduced By Rep. Dan Schaefer (R-Co)</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H2>News Item - July 24, 1996</H2>

<H3> Statement Of Charlie Higley, Senior Policy Analyst With Public Citizen, On H.R. 3790, The "Electric Consumers' Power To Choose Act Of 1996," Introduced By Rep. Dan Schaefer (R-Co)</H3>

Rep. Schaefer's bill (H.R. 3790) to restructure the electric power industry contains both negative and positive features.  The restructuring bill includes a federal mandate that would force States to adopt retail competition for their regulated and non- regulated electric utilities, even if individual States and non- regulated utilities determine that retail competition will not benefit the interests of consumers and the environment. <P>

Public Citizen believes that States, not the federal government, must be able to decide whether retail competition will provide their citizens with better service, lower prices, and enhanced environmental protection. Rep. Schaefer's bill would allow the federal government to dictate to States how they should regulate the sale of electricity at retail, even though most States have had this responsibility for more than 70 years.  <P>
The bill, which would repeal the Public Utility Holding Company Act and the Public Utility Regulatory Policies Act, also lacks mechanisms to protect consumers from excessive market power of utilities.  Public Citizen opposes the repeal of these laws until each State has enacted legislation protecting its citizens as well as competitive markets from the potential abuses of large, multi-state holding companies.  <P>
Although Public Citizen opposes the bill's federal mandate for retail competition, Public Citizen supports Rep. Schaefer's provision that encourages the generation of electricity from renewable sources, including wind, solar, geothermal, and biomass.  The development of renewable electricity sources will provide our Nation with clean energy systems, creating jobs and revenues in local economies as well as reducing our dependence on nuclear and fossil fuels.  Although we would prefer a more aggressive schedule for the development of renewable resources, we support the "renewable energy credit" mechanism introduced in Schaefer's bill. <P>

Public Citizen, along with other public interest groups, recently released "Power for the People," a blueprint on how to restructure the electric power industry in ways that protect consumers and the environment.  Since States currently have jurisdiction over retail sales of electricity, "Power for the People" contains policy proposals intended for implementation at the State level.  Copies of "Power for the People" can be obtained from Public Citizen (202-833-3000) at a price of $20.<P>

For additional information about electricity restructuring call Charlie Higley at 202-546-4996 or send e-mail to cmep@citizen.org<P>

To receive regular energy policy alerts, summaries and updates from Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy Project, send the following message to listproc@essential.org: SUBSCRIBE CMEP-LIST [your name - organizational affiliation - home state]<P>

The Critical Mass home page is located at <A HREF="http://www.essential.org/CMEP/">http://www.essential.org/CMEP</A>. 
<HR>
