<HEAD><TITLE>July 2, 1996 - Action Alert:  Tell Congress to Preserve Renewable Energy Funding!</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H2>News Item - July 2, 1996<P></H2>

<H3>Action Alert:  Tell Congress to Preserve Renewable Energy Funding!<P></H3>

<B>BACKGROUND</B>:  Renewable energy solar, wind, biomass, geothermal, hydropower is essential both for a healthy, sustainable economy and for the health of the planet.  Increased use of renewables will
create jobs, reduce US dependence on foreign oil, and protect the environment.  <P>

All the renewable energy research and development programs at the Department of Energy cost each American only about $1 per year.  Nonetheless, federal support for renewables is in jeopardy in Congress.  For fiscal year (FY) 1996, Congress chopped over $100 million from funding for renewables research and development.  While President Clinton has proposed a return to 1995's strong support with a request of $389 million for renewables for FY 1997, renewable energy funding is facing cuts by Congress to below 1996 levels.  The Energy and Water Appropriations Subcommittees in the House and Senate oversee the renewables budget.  The House subcommittee has been required to cut its total expenditures for FY 1997, and the interests competing with renewable energy for this portion of the budget are
extremely powerful.  Prospects are somewhat better in the Senate, because subcommittee Chairman Pete
Domenici is a supporter of renewables, but budget-slashing seriously threatens these programs in the
Senate as well.  <P>

 
 <B>CONGRESS NEEDS TO KNOW THAT THERE IS STRONG SUPPORT FOR RENEWABLE ENERGY FUNDING! </B>     <P>

                                 

All Representatives and Senators need to hear from vocal supporters of renewables, because every member may have the opportunity to vote on this issue.  A floor amendment to increase renewables funding is expected in the House and a similar amendment may be introduced in the Senate.      <P>

<B>ACTION:</B> Call, fax or email your US Representative and Senators as soon as possible and ask them to support President Clinton's request of $389 million in funding for renewable energy research and development. The Senate subcommittee is expected to consider the bill shortly after the July 4 recess; the House subcommittee will also act sometime after the recess, and a floor vote in the House will follow.  There is not much time, so it is essential that you act soon.  <P>



If you have a Senator who is on the subcommittee, keep in mind that he or she is especially involved in the decision over renewables funding.  You can reach your Senators and Representative through the Capitol Switchboard at (202) 224-3121.  You can also find their phone and fax numbers, addresses and email on the Internet's congressional homepage: <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://policy.net/capweb/congress.html">http://policy.net/capweb/Congress.html</A>.  <P>

If you have any trouble reaching a Senator or Representative, contact Tom Cormons (see below) for specific contact information.  For more information, contact Lara Levison or Tom Cormons of the Union of Concerned Scientists by phone or email: (202) 332-0900, <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:llevison@ucsusa.org">llevison@ucsusa.org</A>, <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:dcintern@ucsusa.org">dcintern@ucsusa.org</A>          <P>
<HR>
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="http://www.me3.org">Sustainable Minnesota Home Page</A>


</BODY> 
