<HEAD><TITLE>May 21, 1996 - Renewable Energy Grants Available</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<h2>News Item - May 21, 1996</h2>
<P>
<h3> Renewable Energy Grants Available</h3>
<P>
<P>
     Department of Administration Secretary James R. Klauser announced today 
that Wisconsin local governments, state agencies, businesses and nonprofit 
organizations interested in building or modifying small or medium-sized 
renewable energy systems may apply for financial assistance from Wisconsin's 
Renewable Energy Assistance Program.  Administered by the Wisconsin Energy 
Bureau in the Department of Administration, the program offers grants for 
both feasibility studies and construction.<P>
     A total of $320,000 is available for grants in this grant cycle.  Up to 
$200,000 will be available for construction grants, which will be awarded on 
a first come, first served basis.  About $120,000 will be available for 
technical assistance grants, which will be awarded on the basis of merit 
after the close of the application period June 28, 1996.  <P> 
     "This administration is keenly aware of the benefits of renewable 
energy to the state's environment and economy," Klauser noted.  "Providing 
seed funds to worthwhile projects is a cost-effective way to bring renewable 
energy projects on line in Wisconsin."<P>
     Construction grants will generally cover 10 percent to 20 percent of 
total project costs.  The grant amount, however, will be based not on 
project cost but rather on renewable energy output, efficiency, and energy 
utilization.  Grant levels are set up to encourage energy efficiency and 
full utilization of the output of the renewable energy system.  Technical 
assistance grants will cover 50 percent of costs up to a maximum grant of 
$15,000.<P>
     Funds for the program come from payments to the state by oil companies 
which overcharged customers for petroleum products during the 1970s.  This 
is the program's seventh grant cycle. <p>
     For the purposes of the program, renewable energy refers to solar 
energy, wind energy, hydropower and energy derived from biomass waste or 
geothermal sources.  Examples of recent grants include:<P>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI>    A project to monitor wind speed at promising sites across the 
state;<P>
<LI>      A project to refurbish and an abandoned ethanol plant near Plover. 
The plant will utilize cheese whey permeate as a feedstock;<P>
<LI>        An assessment of the technical and economic feasibility of using hydrogen as a vehicle fuel in Wisconsin;<P>
<LI>        The installation of a 430 Horsepower wood-fired boiler to burn 
5,500 tons per year of dry wood residue to provide heat for lumber drying 
kilns; and<P>

  <LI>  The construction of a landfill gas conversion plant at a landfill 
in south central Wisconsin.  The gas is cleaned and burned in an engine to 
produce electricity.<P>
</UL>
     For more information about the program, or for an application package, 
call or write: the Renewable Energy Assistance Program, Wisconsin Energy 
Bureau, P.O. Box 7868, Madison, WI  53707; Dan Moran, (608) 266-1067, 
<!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:morand@mail.state.wi.us">morand@mail.state.wi.us</A>.<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
