<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --></head><title>May 10, 1996 - NSP EnergyWise Solar Advantage
program</title><p>
<body><P>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>May 10, 1996 - NSP EnergyWise Solar Advantage
Program</H3>
<p>
This spring NSP's EnergyWise Solar Advantage program for homes will
bring solar electricity to several homes in the Twin Cities metro area.
Sturdily mounted photovoltaic (PV) solar panels on the roof generate
electricity from the sun.  The panels absorb light and convert the light
directly into electricity.  The electricity powers the home, and any excess
electricity is channeled back to NSP.<p>
<p>
The Solar Advantage system's installed cost totals between $15,000 and $20,000.
During 1996, NSP will pay for this installation and equipment cost for a
limited number of homes.  Participants will pay a $50 monthly charge for five
years to use the system, a total of $3,000.  In return, the solar system can
generate about $14 worth of electricity during an average month.  All the
solar-generated energy the home uses is free of charge.  Any excess is sold
back to NSP at the household's rate.  That makes the out-of-pocket cost of the
Solar Advantage program less than the $50 monthly charge.<p>
<p>
Besides being on the leading edge of solar technology, electricity generated
through the Solar Advantage program is good for the environment.  It's
pollution-free and renewable.  Trying solar power through the Solar Advantage
program is an economical way to do your part to help keep air and water clean
far into the future.<p>
<p>
<b>To Learn More:</b><p>
<b></b>Call Ask NSP at (612) 282-1234 or Mark Rogers, Senior Research Engineer
at NSP, (612) 330-7608<p>
<p>
</body></html>
