<HEAD><TITLE>04-22-96-BEA Attacks Plan to Slash Biomass R&D</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>BEA Attacks Plan to Slash Federal Biomass R&D</H2><P>

<I><B>For immediate release,			Contact: Mike Fourcher, (202) 639-0384<P> 
April 22, 1996</B></I><P>			

A draft proposal by Rep. Bob Walker (R-PA), Chairman of the House Science 
and Technology Committee, to sharply reduce federal funding for energy 
research and development would cut the federal biomass energy R&D program by 
almost $50 million from the administration's request and more than $22 
million from last year's appropriation.  Overall, the planned cuts would 
reduce renewable energy R&D by more than $97 million, a 30% cut from the FY 
1996 appropriation.<P>

"At a time when we are beginning to commercialize years of research and 
bring it from the lab bench into the field, a budget like this would 
devastate the future," said BEA Executive Director Reid Detchon.  "As a 
direct result of biomass research, Americans are seeing the growth of a new 
domestic energy source and jobs in rural America.  Facilities designed as a 
direct result of federal R&D are planned across the country that will create 
new jobs and markets, produce energy that reduces air pollution, and limit 
American dollars spent on Middle East oil."<P>

A poll conducted only a few months ago by the Sustainable Energy Budget 
Coaltion showed that 74.8% of Americans believe something should be done to 
reduce dependency on foreign oil, and that 49% of Americans believed that 
renewable energy and energy efficiency "should receive federal tax 
incentives to attract efforts from the private sector to develop and promote 
it."<P>

Also, in reports released last fall by two opposing factions on the 
Presidents' Policy Dialogue Advisory Committee to Develop Options for 
Reducing Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Personal Motor Vehicles (or "Car 
Talk"), few items were agreed upon, except that the federal government 
should increase support for "liquid biofuels research and development, in 
particular ethanol produced from cellulosic biomass."<P>

"Americans know that renewable energy creates domestic investment and jobs, 
reduces our need for foreign oil, and helps the environment," said Detchon. 
"Rather than attacking renewables, we should support the final stages of 
development of renewables like biomass which are just beginning to bear 
fruit after years of investment."<P>

The Biomass Energy Alliance is a non-profit organization created for the 
purpose of public education on biomass energy and to accelerate the 
development of a major new American industry.  More information about the 
BEA's activities can also be found at the BEA web site at: 
http://www.biomass.org<P>

                                                             
<I><B>Contact:</B></I>
<CENTER><!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD>Mike Fourcher<BR>                                 
Biomass Energy Alliance<BR>                        
1001 G St., NW  Suite 900 East <BR>                  
Washington, DC  20001</TD><TD>Phone (202) 639-0384<BR> 
Fax: (202) 393-5510<BR> 
<!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:fourcher@biomass.org">fourcher@biomass.org</A><BR> 
<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.biomass.org/">http://www.biomass.org</A></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

