<HEAD><TITLE>04-22-96-AWEA BLASTS HOUSE COMMITTEE PLAN
TO SLASH WIND RESEARCH</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>AWEA BLASTS HOUSE COMMITTEE PLAN
TO SLASH FEDERAL WIND RESEARCH</H2><P>

<I><B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>

Contact: Karl Gawell (202) 383-2506,
               (voicemail will be checked during weekend)</B></I><P>


     The American Wind Energy Association (AWEA) today blasted a
proposal by U.S. Rep. Robert Walker (R-Pa.), Chairman of the
House Science and Technology Committee, to eliminate the federal
wind energy research and development (R&D) program.<P>



     According to AWEA Director of Governmental Relations Karl
Gawell, the plan "zeroes out wind and slashes funding for all
renewables and energy efficiency technologies by more than 50%
from the President's budget, while making only token cuts in
other research programs."  Overall, Gawell said, Walker's
proposal would reduce funding for efficiency and renewables from
the $908 million proposed by the President to $421 million, for a
cut of 54%.  Other energy R&D programs, meanwhile, would be
trimmed from the President's proposal of $3.889 billion to $3.580
billion--a cut of less than 9%.<P>

     Additionally, Gawell said, the Walker proposal has not yet
been made public, even though the Committee is scheduled to act
on it Wednesday morning:  "This is a stealth attack on programs
which are vital to our environment, economy, and national
security."<P>

     Walker's plan to ax renewables and efficiency is "extremely
short-sighted--a classic case of being penny wise and pound
foolish," said Gawell.  AWEA, Gawell noted, released market
projections April 11 that predict that international sales of
wind equipment will total $18 billion through the year 2005.
"U.S. industry is in danger of losing out in one of the most
dynamic new energy markets on the horizon."<P>

     "Federal wind program personnel at DOE and the National
Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) have worked long and hard,"
Gawell added, "to develop a research program that cooperates
closely with industry and is directed toward real-world problems.
Now that wind, after more than a decade of technology improvement
during which its cost has plummeted by more than 80%, is the
fastest-growing energy technology worldwide, it is stunningly
misguided for the U.S. to throw in its chips."<P>

     This view is confirmed in a recent Atlantic Monthly article
(April issue) by two high-ranking U.S. Department of Energy (DOE)
officials, Deputy Secretary of Energy Charles B. Curtis and
Deputy Assistant Secretary for Energy Efficiency and Renewable
Energy Joseph J. Romm.  The pair describe Congressional plans to
substantially reduce federal research funding for renewable
energy and energy efficiency technologies as "a blunder of . . .
potentially historic proportions."  Renewable energy
technologies, Romm and Curtis write, "may well be the single
largest new source of jobs in the next century," since most
manufacturing industries are now mature.<P>

     They cite an energy scenario outlined by Royal Dutch/Shell
Group--one of two alternative scenarios looking at energy supply
during the next century--as projecting a $150 billion annual
worldwide business in renewables.<P>

     The ability of the United States to compete in markets for
these technologies, Romm and Curtis argue, will be strongly
influenced by federal R&D:  "Federal investments clearly make a
difference in technology development and global market share.
Consider the case of photovoltaics.  In 1955, Bell Laboratories
invented the first practical PV cell.  Through the 1960s and
1970s investments and purchases by NASA [the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration], the Pentagon, and the National Science
Foundation helped to sustain the PV industry and gave America
leadership in world sales.  In 1982, federal support for
renewable energy was cut deeply, and within three years Japan
became the world leader in PV sales.  The Bush Administration
began to increase funding for solar energy and, in 1990,
collaborated with the American PV industry in efforts to improve
manufacturing technology; three years later the United States
regained the lead in sales in this rapidly growing industry . . . "<P>

     Concluded Gawell, "As the saying goes, those who do not
learn from history are condemned to repeat it.  We should be
redoubling our efforts to carve out a leading role for U.S.
industry and workers in the growth of this clean, sustainable
energy technology."<P>

--------------------------------------------------------------<P>
The complete text of the Atlantic Monthly article is
available through AWEA's World Wide Web site at
<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.econet.org/awea/aweapol.html/">http://www.econet.org/awea/aweapol.html</A>.<P>

     Formed in 1974, AWEA is the national trade association of
the U.S. wind energy industry.  AWEA's membership of over 800
includes turbine and component manufacturers, project developers,
utilities, academicians, and interested individuals from 49
states.<P>

                                                             

