<TITLE>
November 7, 1995-Power Play in Norway
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-November 7, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Power Play in Norway </H3>                                   
 
Beginning in January 1996, the State Electricity Market will begin operation in Oslo, Norway.  It will become the first of its kind in the world, letting power be bought and sold internationally.<P>

The new market will allow Scandinavian brokers and companies, whose countries already swap power, to trade and buy electricity as if it were livestock, grain or other commodities.  Norway deregulated power in 1991, allowing almost everyone-not just power companies- to bid on electricity.  Even homeowners can now shop around for a better deal from power companies.
    
<P>                                            

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  Star Tribune, November 6, 1995  </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
