<HEAD>
<TITLE>
November 2, 1995- SMUD Plant Turns Steam Into Ice-Making Jobs  
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-November 2, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>SMUD Plant Turns Steam Into Ice-Making Jobs   </H3>
                         
                                                                                                                                                       
   The Sacramento Municipal Utility District turned on the switch Wednesday in a
unique partnership involving the utility's first cogeneration plant and a       
private ice-making company that will provide 45 jobs.    <P>                       
                                                                                
   The new power plant, Carson Ice-Gen, is a 97 MW, $ 142.7 million project that will  
generate electricity for more than 54,000 local homes.     <P>                     
            
   The facility is the first of four cogeneration plants planned by SMUD to help
stabilize rates and improve air quality.  Steam generated will be piped to the new Glacier Ice Co., which makes 
party ice. SMUD should earn about $ 50,000 a year from steam sales.    <P>         
                                                                                                                                                            
   The cogen and ice-making ventures, a public-private partnership, reflects    
SMUD's commitment to bringing new industry and jobs to the Sacramento area, a   
 goal outlined in the utility's 1995 Integrated Resource Plan.                   
                                                                         
   The joint venture will create 15 jobs at Carson Ice-Gen and 30 at Glacier Ice
and should contribute more than $ 3.9 million in economic benefits to Sacramento
County, officials said.    <P>                                                     
                                                                                
   The cogen plant will be run by Carson  Energy  for the Central Valley        
Financing Authority, which was created to pay for the project.  The authority financed the project through issuance of tax-exempt bonds.   <P>  
                                                                                
   The 97-megawatt power plant will run partially on
methane gas produced by the county's wastewater treatment plant. <P>               
                                                                                
   SMUD plans three additional cogeneration plants: near Procter & Gamble, near Campbell Soup , and one
that will help produce the gasoline additive ethanol from crop residue when     
constructed in 1999.   <P>                                                         
                           
   SMUD's cogeneration plants are expected to add more than 500 megawatts of    
electricity by 2000. The plants should produce power at 3.7 cents a kilowatt hour, 1.5 cents less per    
kilowatt hour than a conventional power plant.                                                                       
<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2>  Source:  Sacramento Bee,   October  19, 1995 </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
