<HEAD>
<TITLE>
November 1, 1995- Group Opposes Shipping Spent Fuel to Interim Storage In Nevada  
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-November 1, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Group Opposes Shipping Spent Fuel to Interim Storage In Nevada</H3>
                                        
                                                                                
  Members of a citizen coalition Oct. 17 protested         
against pending congressional legislation that would create what they called    
"a hasty interim storage plan" to transport spent reactor fuel from 75          
utility power plants to an interim storage facility in Nevada.   <P>               
                                                                                
   Fred Millar, a spokesman for the Nuclear Waste Citizens Coalition, said at   
a news conference the group opposed "a very dangerous legislative juggernaut    
moving through the Congress...a phony 'solution' to the                                  
problem of nuclear waste."     <P>                                                 
                                                                                
   The coalition also released a revised report projecting where highway and    
rail transportation routes would fall across 43 states to an interim storage    
site in Nevada. <P>                                                                
                                                                                
   According to Mary Olson of the Nuclear Information and Resource Service, each multipurpose canister shipped by the Department of  Energy      
will contain "200 times more cesium than was released by the bomb dropped on    
Hiroshima." <P>                                                       
                                                                                                                                            
   Several proposed bills in Congress would establish an interim storage        
facility in Nevada to begin accepting radioactive waste in 1998 until a         
permanent repository is available.  <P>                                            
                                                                                
   One of the bills, HR 1020, was scheduled to be marked up Oct. 19 by the      
House Resources Committee.                                                                                    
   A similar Senate bill (S 1271) introduced by Sen. Larry Craig (R-Idaho)      
also would direct the construction of an interim storage facility in Nevada,    
but no action has been taken on the bill since it was referred to the Senate    
Committee on  Energy  and Natural Resources Sept. 25. <P>

   The coalition's latest report on nuclear waste shipments, High-Level         
Nuclear Waste Shipping Route Maps to Yucca Mountain and Shipment Number         
Estimates: Multi-Purpose Canister Base, uses DOE data.  <P>                                
                                                                          
   The coalition asserted that as wet pool storage sites at reactor become      
full, the waste can be more safely managed in dry-cask storage at reactor       
sites than if shipped to an interim facility. The Nuclear Regulatory            
Commission claims that waste can be stored on-site safely for 100 years, the    
coalition said.<P>                                                                                                                                                                              
                                                                                
   The transportation report is available from the Nuclear Waste Citizens       
Coalition, 110 Maryland Ave. N.E., No. 307, Washington, D.C. 20002, (202)       
547-5796. <P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2> Source:  BNA State Environment Daily, October 18, 1995  </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
