<TITLE>
October 22, 1995- Electricity Users Like Existing Service: But Residents See Competition's Benefits 
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 22, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3> Electricity Users Like Existing Service: But Residents See Competition's Benefits </H3>                                                        
                                 
                                                                                
                                                                   
   As state regulators mull plans for a major overhaul of Wisconsin's electric  
utility industry, most consumers say they are "very satisfied" with the way they
now get their electricity  and also expressed concern that     
prices will rise over the long term if the industry becomes more deregulated. <P> 
                                                                                
   But Wisconsin residents told an independent        
research group that they think competition is a good thing "either because it   
eliminates inefficiencies seen as inherent in monopoly structures, or simply    
because it is the American way."    <P>                                            
                                                                                
 The study was conducted by the Madison-based  Energy  Center of Wisconsin for the         
Wisconsin Public Service Commission.   <P>                                         
                                                                                 
   The attitudes of those queried will be used by the three-member PSC in       
December as it decides whether to revamp the current system of utility          
regulation.   "This whole issue is a major discussion point around the nation," said Mark  
Hanson, executive director of the non-profit  Energy  Center, formerly known as 
the Wisconsin Center for Demand-Side Research.<P>  
                                
      The report, which cost $80,000, was financed by government agencies and the  
utility industry.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2> Source:  Milwaukee Journal Sentinel,  October  12, 1995  </FONT></I>


