<TITLE>
October 20, 1995-Officials See Wide Solar Electricity Use on the Horizon
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 20, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Officials See Wide Solar Electricity Use on the Horizon  </H3>                                   
 
                                                                           
 About 250 utility,  energy  and solar industry officials gathered in Sun     
Valley for a three-day conference on business and public opportunities for solar
photovoltaic technology, known as PV technology.   <P>                               
                                                                                
Christine Ervin of the U.S. Department of Energy expects that PVs will supply 50 percent of the world's energy needs by the year 
2050.<P>  

                                                                           
Remote applications for PV technology is cost effective right now.  It costs an average of $30,000 a mile to extend powerlines, while it costs   
about $20,000 to $40,000 to install a roof-top solar electric system for a      
family of four.  <P>                                                 
                                                                                                     
   Idaho Power is among about 25 utilities across the nation that have formed a 
private-public partnership to boost the use of solar electricity in domestic    
markets. New orders for solar panels have sliced the price of panels in half;   
technological advances have boosted the panels' efficiency by 300 percent,      
officials said.  There are 25,000 homes in the United States powered exclusively with solar   
panels.                  
       
                                           
<P>                                            

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:    Idaho Falls Post Register, September 19, 1995  </FONT></I>


