<HEAD>
<TITLE>
October 19, 1995-Greens Say Forget Flat Tax and VAT Tax, Go For Envirotax  
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 19, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Greens Say Forget Flat Tax and VAT Tax, Go For Envirotax  </H3>                                                        
              
                                                                                                                                                       
                                                                                        
    In the September-October issue of World Watch, World Watch Institute
researcher David Roodman says a national environmental tax could ease the tax   
                                          
                                                                                
burden on "good things"--employment, sales, investment and corporate profit--and
increase it on "bad things"--pollution and natural resource exploitation.      <P>    
                                                                                                      
                                                                                
    Roodman says the current tax structure creates a negative stimulus that discourages
growth and encourages pollution while increasing the social and economic costs  
for non-polluters.  <P>                                                                                                                                               
                                                                             
    Roodman says that oil, mining and other natural resource companies benefit  
from several economic and demographic factors that allow them to pursue         
environmentally destructive activities while enjoying steadily rising profits. <P>    
                                                                                                               
    The intention of the environmental tax is
to change how the economy works--change the environmental impact, the health    
impact, change how industries operate.    <P>                                                   
                                                                                
                                                      
    "We should let the market do most of the work by taxing where pollution     
occurs," says Roodman, and the best way to do that is to let consumers know how 
much environmental tax is being paid by producers of the goods they consume. <P>      
                                                                                
      "The more information, the better for consumers to see the impact," says    
Roodman. "For utilities, they might find the optimal thing for them to do would 
be to pass the tax on to consumers. That would produce a higher electricity     
price--so consumers would conserve, and that would have the same positive effect
on the environment" as some of the existing clean air and water regulations, but
at less cost.                       <P>                                               
                                                                                
    That market effect of the environmental tax--combined with its direct       
proportional relationship to the amount of pollutant generated--would lessen the
need for prescriptive regulation, according to Roodman.  <P>                         
             
                                                                                
    Although environmental taxes are not unknown--Roodman cites one study       
listing more than 250 such levies at the state level in the U.S.--only Sweden   
has used them as part of a combination tax shift and anti-pollution program.  <P>     
                                                                                
    Roodman notes that environmental taxes passed by the Swedish Parliament in  
1990 and 1991 have generated $1.25 billion in annual revenues that have been    
used to pay for reductions in payroll and investment taxes.                     
                                                                             
                          
<P>                                            

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  The Energy Daily, September 14, 1995  </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
</DOC>
