October 18, 1995-East Coast Utilities BGE, PEPCO Plan to Merge 
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 18, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>East Coast Utilities BGE, PEPCO Plan to Merge </H3>                                                        
                                                                        
           
                                                                                
                                                                      
   The Baltimore Gas and Electric Co. and Potomac Electric Power Co. plan to    
merge and move their new headquarters to the Annapolis area, the companies      
announced this morning.           <P>                                               
                                                                               
   Officials said the merger would create a company with $ 15 billion in assets,
putting it in the top 10 utilities nationwide.          <P>                         
                                                                                
   The deal would allow the companies to save money by consolidating and cutting
their work force by 10 percent.  The merger would be subject to approval by       
several agencies. <P>                                                               
                                                                                
 The new  energy  company would serve 4.5 million people in Maryland and
Washington.  The combined company would have more than 1.8 million electric customers and 
530,000 gas customer,  with annual revenues of about $ 5 billion.   The companies expect the merger to save them about $ 1.3 billion over 10     
years.  <P> 
                                                                               
   The merger agreement is subject to the approval by shareholders of both      
companies and several federal and state regulatory agencies, including the      
Federal  Energy  Regulatory Commission, the Public Service Commissions of       
Maryland and the District of Columbia, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission and the
Securities & Exchange Commission.                                               
                                                                               
                                                         
<P>                                            

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  The Capital, September 25, 1995  </FONT></I>


