<TITLE>
October 17, 1995-A Challenge to Urethane Foam: Vacuum Panels Gain Ground 
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 17, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>A Challenge to Urethane Foam: Vacuum Panels Gain Ground </H3>                                                        
                                                                        
 
                                                                                
                                                                          
   Whirlpool Corp. is replacing some polyurethane foam insulation with a vacuum 
panel in a new generation of super-efficient refrigerators, the first by a major
North American appliance maker.     The panels  
are excellent insulators and don't need ozone-depleting blowing agents.         
Additionally, they are less bulky than normal refrigerators. <P>                                 
                                                                                
                                        
                                                                                
   Because vacuum panels are more costly than conventional urethane foam        
insulation, appliance majors have been slow to adopt them. However, urethane    
suppliers have developed their own vacuum panel versions-just in case.  <P>          
                                                                                
   Whirlpool uses two Aura Superinsulation panels that helps   
reduce  energy  consumption in refrigerators 38 to 41 percent below 1993  
Department of  Energy  standards.    The insulation efficiency, however, comes with increased price.      <P>                  
                                                                                
                                                                             
   Whirlpool so far isn't overly concerned with costs in its  Energy  Wise line.
The new refrigerators in effect are subsidized by the 24 utilities in the Super 
Efficient Refrigerator Program (SERP), which put up $30 million in 1993 for development
of more efficient refrigerators that don't contain CFCs.  Whirlpool won first   
prize in the SERP competition last year.                                        
                                                                                
 The refrigerators are sold in SERP utility markets across the U.S.   <P>          
                                                                                
   Whirlpool is committed to making 250,000 refrigerators in the SERP program,  
which is expected to last a few more years.   Whirlpool's first 35,000 refrigerators-the first-generation  Energy  Wise    
model-used only urethane foam insulation.      Whirlpool said it plans to make the second generation with freezer-side      
vacuum panels for the rest of the SERP production run.                                                            
<P>                                            

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  Rubber and Plastics, September 25, 1995</FONT></I>


</BODY> 
