<TITLE>
October 15, 1995-Prototype Energy Efficient House Draws 2,000 Visitors in First Weekend
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 15, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Prototype Energy Efficient House Draws 2,000 Visitors in First Weekend </H3>                                                        
                                                                         
                                                                                                                                                        
    Over 2,000 people toured Wisconsin Public Service Corp.'s new energy        
efficient house during the first weekend it was opened September 9-10, learning 
about the prototype energy management system that features interactive computer 
technology. The 2,400-square-foot house in Ashwaubenon, Wis., a suburb of Green 
Bay, is the result of a cooperative effort among telephone, cable TV, electric, 
and natural gas companies.<P>                                                       
                                                                                
    Included is technology that allows the homeowner to video teleconference    
with a WPS customer service representative to discuss any aspect of energy  
                  
                                                                                
usage.     <P>                                                                       
            
                                                                                
    Customer programming enables a homeowner to     
program certain appliances to operate off-peak when energy prices are lower.    
Remote access is possible, allowing a customer to remotely warm a cool     
house before arriving or to turn the sprinkling system on or off from a       
telephone. <P>                                                                      
                                                                                                                                                            
    The house is expected to record a total annual energy bill of
about $ 300, compared to bills of between $ 500 and $ 600 for a typical new     
house.                                                                          

  <P>                                                               

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  Electric Utility Week's Demand-Side Report, September 14, 1995 </FONT></I>


