<TITLE>
October 14, 1995-Site In Remote West Texas Sprouts Turbines
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 14, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Site In Remote West Texas Sprouts Turbines </H3>                                                        
                      
                                             
   
   Those 112 turbines cost about $40 million and constitute the first fully 
operational  wind  power plant in Texas. The 65,000-acre site in Culberson      
County, on the Six Bar Ranch about 100 miles east of El Paso, has room for      
several hundred more turbines, enough to generate 750 megawatts.   <P>              
                                                                            
   The Lower Colorado River Authority is buying the 35 megawatts generated by   
the Kenetech  wind  plant. The Austin-based LCRA, in turn, is selling 10        
megawatts to the City of Austin Electric Utility Department. The LCRA has signed
an agreement with Kenetech to expand the project to 250 megawatts by 2002.     <P>  
                                                                                
   The turning propellers generate electricity that feeds into a transmission   
line. That line stretches 28 miles to other transmission lines owned by Texas   
Utilities Electric Co. The power then flows 400 miles east to the LCRA and its  
Central Texas customers.       <P>                                                  
                                                                                
   Two other major Texas utilities, Central and South West Corp. and TU         
Electric, are putting their fingers to the West Texas  wind,  too. <P>              
                                                                                
   Central and South West, a Dallas-based utility holding company, last week    
dedicated a six-megawatt plant with 12  wind  turbines on a 75-acre site near   
Marfa. TU Electric, also based in Dallas, is seeking regulatory approval to     
                                                                                
buy the power from a 40-megawatt plant that would be built near Big Spring by   
New World Power Corp.  of Newport Beach, Calif.     <P>                             
                                                                                
   The Kenetech  wind  plant is the largest in the United States outside        
California.        <P>                                     
                                                                                
   The LCRA contract with Kenetech requires it to pay 4.7 cents per kilowatt    
hour for the next 25 years. <P>                                              
                                                                                
   The 138,000-volt transmission line that connects the  wind  plant to the TU  
Electric grid cost $6 million. Construction costs and wheeling charges through  
TU Electric adds 1.1 cents per kwh to the 4.7-cent per kwh cost of the power    
from the plant.  <P>                                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                     


<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  Austin American-Statesman, October 01, 1995  </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
