<HEAD>
<TITLE>
October 12, 1995- Dutch Utility to Expand 'GREEN PRICING' Renewables Program Due to Response
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 12, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3> Dutch Utility to Expand 'GREEN PRICING' Renewables Program Due to    
Response   </H3>                                                        
                                                                                                                                           
    A Dutch utility's test of whether residential consumers are willing to pay  
extra for electricity generated by  wind  and other renewable resources has proven so successful that the program is being expanded. <P>
                                                                                
    N.V. Provinciale Noordbrabantse Energie-Maatschappij (PNEM) of Holland said 
it launched its ''green pricing'' project after a survey of customers found that
68% strongly supported development of renewables and 49% were willing to pay an 
extra (U.S.) $ 10-$ 11/month for electricity generated from renewables.         <P>
                                                                                
                                                                                                                 
    In Holland,  wind  power costs customers about 17.99 cents/kWh, or about    
5.79 cents/kWh more than average power prices.   <P>                               
                                                                                
    PNEM, currently generates 16 MW of  wind  power, but it intends to expand capacity to 
60 MW by 1998.  Proceeds from the sale of the green power will be invested in new renewables
projects. PNEM said it may either buy the renewable power from independent      
producers or build its own generation. PNEM plans to have up to 3% of its total 
installed capacity come from renewables by the year 2000.<P>                                                        
                                                                                
 The Dutch government is expected to exempt renewables from a new 2.28     
cents/kWh  energy  tax set for 1996.                                            
<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  Utility Environment Report, September 15, 1995     </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
</DOC>
