<TITLE>
October 9, 1995- Wind  Power Re-Emerging as  Energy  Source
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 9, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3> Wind  Power Re-Emerging as  Energy  Source </H3>
                             
                                                                                                                                                     
   At the recent ribbon-cutting of the Central and South West Corporation's     
(CSW) six-megawatt windpower facility in far west, Texas Land Commissioner Garry
Mauro announced the state had entered "the next century's new generation of     
clean, renewable power from a source that will never dry up -- the  wind. "   <P>  
                                                                                
   Mauro, also chairman of the Texas Sustainable  Energy  Development Council,  
(SEDC) said "CSW is just one example of how renewable  energy  will change the  
face of Texas."<P>

   "Texas is now a net  energy  importer," explained Mauro. "That...means we are
faced with some hard choices. We can accept our new status...and sit back and   
watch our urban areas deteriorate as the cost of housing, gasoline and utilities
skyrocket. "  <P>                                                        
                                                                            
   The three reports issued by the SEDC, "Texas Renewable  Energy  Resource     
Assessment," "Efficiencies in the Transportation Sector" and "Opportunities for 
 Energy  Efficiency in the Texas Industrial Sector" are available from the Texas
General Land Office by contacting Judith Carroll at 512/463-1871 by on Internet 
at <!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="http://sedc.twdb.texas.gov/">http://sedc.twdb.texas.gov</A>.                                                                                                                                                                                          
<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2> Source:  Global Warming Network Online Today , October 4, 1995 </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
