<TITLE>
October 8, 1995- DOE Releases HERS: Use of  Energy  Efficient Mortgages Lag 
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 8, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3> DOE Releases HERS: Use of  Energy  Efficient Mortgages Lag </H3>
    
                                                                                                                                      
    The U.S. Dept. of  Energy  has published its proposed national voluntary    
home  energy  rating system (HERS), which will be used to rate the  energy      
efficiency of new and used homes. The proposed    
rules were published in the Federal Register July 25 and hearings are scheduled 
for October 2 in Washington, D.C. <P>                                              
                                                                                
    At the same time, Dept. of Housing and Urban Development pilot projects     
designed to promote  energy  efficient mortgages (EEMs), have not produced any increase in the number of EEMs awarded.<P>
                    
    Before EPACT, about a dozen states had developed home  energy rating       
systems, most of which were different from each other. Ratings are used by home 
buyers and lending institutions to qualify for EEMs which can be added to home  
loans, thereby funding upgrades to make the home more efficient and reduce      
 energy  bills.  <P>                                                               
                                                                          
    The proposed system is designed to compare a home against a reference       
 energy  efficient house based on the Council of American Building Officials    
Model  Energy  Code (CABO MEC).  A rating between zero and 100 is then assigned. 
Trained raters rate the house and provide a list of potential improvements with their maximum       
installed costs. The homeowner, in turn, uses this rating to apply for the EEM  
in conjunction with a home loan.                                                                                                                                           
<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2> Source:  Electric Utility Week's Demand-Side Report, September 28, 1995    </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
