<HEAD>
<TITLE>
October 6, 1995- Utilities Fear Market Power of WEC/ NSP Union  
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 6, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Utilities Fear Market Power of WEC/ NSP Union   </H3>
 
   
                                                                                                                                             
                                                                              
    In a July 10 FERC filing for approval of both the merger (EC95-16) and an   
open-access tariff (ER95-1358), the utilities quantified $ 1.9 billion in cost  
savings (IF, 17 July, 3). More important to other utilities that submitted      
comments last week on the merger, though, is how the combined company would     
affect the upper Midwest market. And that effect could well be to reduce        
competition, they maintained.    <P>                                               
                                                                                
    Wisconsin Public Service Corp. said it ''believes that the proposed merger  
would eliminate a significant competitor in the relevant geographic and product 
markets....''     <P>                                                                                                                                                                                      
                                                                                
    WPS, a customer and competitor of both WEPCO and NSP, said the wholesale    
power market between utilities in the Wisconsin-Upper Michigan Systems and those
within the Mid-Continent Area Power Pool has become increasingly active and     
competitive in recent years. Most power imports into WUMS are from generation in
MAPP and move across a 345-Kv transmission line controlled by NSP on the western
end. On the eastern end, WEPCO has rights to 52% of the transfer capability, WPS
20% and Wisconsin Power and Light Co. 28%.  <P>
                                                                      
    Raising similar issues was a group of Minnesota Power, the Lincoln, Neb.,   
municipal utility and Otter Tail Power Co., all of which are MAPP members. The  
merger ''would drastically alter the market for electric  energy  and           
transmission in the upper Midwest region of the United States,'' they said.<P>

    Under the applicants' own analysis, Primergy would control more than 23% of 
the installed generation capacity in the region. <P>                                         
                                                      
    The Minnesota Municipal Utilities Assn. voiced three main concerns about the
merger: ''the relatively rapid consolidation of generation suppliers in the MAPP
region''; the applicants' failure to commit that NSP will remain within MAPP    
''at precisely the time that MAPP's members are investigating the feasibility of
reconstituting MAPP and forming a regional transmission group''; and Primergy's 
control over the Minnesota/WUMS interface.                   
<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2>  Source:  Inside F.E.R.C., September 18, 1995  </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
