<HEAD>
<TITLE>
October 4, 1995-DSM Shuts Out Supply-Side Proposals in Integrated     
Resource Bid   
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 4, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>DSM Shuts Out Supply-Side Proposals in Integrated     
Resource Bid</H3>
                                                                    
                                                                        
    In California's first integrated resource bid program designed to test how  
well supply-side and demand-side resources compete for the same block of        
capacity, demand-side proposals beat the supply-side projects hands down. <P>                                                 
                                                                                
    Not a single supply-side proposal was shortlisted under Pacific Gas &       
Electric's January solicitation, despite more than 900 MW of proposals. <P>               
                                                                                
    PG&E shortlisted nine demand-side proposals representing 37.5 MW and expects
to have signed contracts, most of 10 years in duration, by the end of the year. <P>
                                                                                
    In April, the utility announced it had received proposals totaling 1,018 MW.
Energy service companies and customers submitted 31 DSM proposals totaling 114  
MW and nine utilities, independent power companies, power marketers and         
operating power plants submitted supply-side bids totaling 904 MW .<P>

    The following companies made the shortlist:  <P>                               
                                                                                
    -- Conservation Services Group, Inc., Boston, Mass.: 1.22 MW of savings from
repairing heat pumps in 10,000 PG&E customer residences. Building shell treatments such as duct sealing and repairs will also be included. Its partner  
is Procter Engineering Group of San Rafael which has done pilot studies and     
targeted the specific residential market.   <P>                                    
                                                                                
    -- Electro-Test, Inc., Danville, Calif.: 8-10 MW of savings from testing and
improving the efficiency of wastewater treatment plant process equipment, and   
upgrading commercial and industrial lighting. <P>

    -- Enersave, Inc., New York, N.Y.: 5 MW of savings from lighting and HVAC   
measures in the commercial sector. <P>
                 
    -- Envirotech Services, Inc., Enid, Okla.: 3 MW from improving the          
efficiency of public water agencies and agricultural water users.<P>

    -- Financial Energy and Savage Engineering, Inc., Denver, Colo.: 4 MW from  
projects for industrial and commercial PG&E customers, including industrial     
process controls, variable speed drives and lighting retrofits in both          
industrial and commercial facilities.   <P>                                        
                                                                                
    -- Onsite Energy Corp., Carlsbad, Calif.: 4 MW from measures implemented in 
industrial, institutional and commercial facilities within the PG&E service     
territory. <P>
                                                 
    -- Orion Energy, Inc., Sausalito, Calif.: 8.2 MW from a joint venture with  
the Hospital Council of Northern California to do lighting and HVAC retrofits at
41 hospitals.       <P>                                                            
                                                                                
    -- Pacific Bell, San Ramon, Calif. Almost 2 MW from changing HVAC operating 
protocols at 100 Pacific Bell facilities in the Bay area. <P>

    -- Tamal Energy Services of California, Richmond, Calif.: 2 MW from         
installing adjustible speed drives at industrial facilities. <P>
                                                                                                                                                                         
 


<I><FONT SIZE=2> Source:  Electric Utility Week's Demand-Side Report, September 28, 1995    </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
