<HEAD>
<TITLE>
October 3, 1995-Gingrich, Clinton Want to Keep Tax Exemption For Ethanol   
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 3, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Gingrich, Clinton Want to Keep Tax Exemption For Ethanol  </H3>

             
                                                                         
   Ethanol supporters have rounded up some influential bi-partisan support in   
their quest to maintain the excise tax credit for ethanol producers that would  
be reduced in the House budget reconciliation bill.    <P>                         
                                                                                
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., emerged from a meeting  in support of
deleting the provision from House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer's,        
R-Texas, committee recommendation that would scale back the exemption from 54   
cents/gallon to 51 cents/gallon.     <P>                                           
                                                                                
   The Clinton administration also weighed in last week with a strong           
endorsement of maintaining the corn-based fuel tax exemption.   <P>  
                                                                                
   Ethanol supporters are touting a General Accounting Office report that   
concludes the tax breaks for ethanol encourage the production of ethanol and    
indirectly help reduce the federal budget deficit.    <P>                          
                                                                                
   According to GAO, increased demand for grain lifts market prices and lowers  
federal farm subsidies. <P>
                                          
   The issue of ethanol tax exemptions has traditionally been a rallying point  
for farm interests regardless of party. But with this session's focus on        
"corporate welfare," opponents have increased their efforts to tag the tax      
subsidy as one of the most flagrant examples of the federal government providing
unneeded economic support for a particular industry.     <P>                       
                                                                                
   Besides the federal tax exemption, small producers also qualify for an       
additional 10 cents/gallon exemption and many farm states offer tax incentives  
for corn production with an ethanol end-use.                                                                                                                           
 <P>


<I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
