<HEAD>
<TITLE>
October 1, 1995-Michigan Groups Petition NRC To Halt Palisades Dry Storage 
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-October 1, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Michigan Groups Petition NRC To Halt Palisades Dry Storage </H3>

          
                                                                         
    Lake Michigan Federation and Don't Waste Michigan, opponents of dry storage of spent nuclear fuel at Consumers Power Co.'s     
Palisades plant petitioned the NRC last week to fine the utility $ 1.3-million  
and suspend its general license for spent fuel storage.  <P>                       
 
The opponents say that Consumers Power lacks an adequate procedure --    
contrary to what the company asserted earlier in its license application -- for 
unloading spent fuel from the Sierra Nuclear Corp. VSC-24 casks on site.   <P>                         
                                                                                
    Consumers Power contends it does have a plan for unloading fuel.                                                                                 
    ''The plan we had we felt is a more destructive method that we wouldn't want
to use in a non-emergency situation,'' Mark Savage, public affairs director for 
the utility, said September 21.  The reason the utility feels it needs to develop
a new unloading procedure is that in August 1994 it discovered two flaws in a   
weld of one of the casks that had been loaded with spent fuel the previous      
month. The     
flawed cask is one of 13 VSC-24 casks at the Palisades dry storage site, which  
is located on sand dunes about 150 yards from Lake Michigan.   <P>                 
 
 Consumers Power announced  
plans to unload the cask and reload the spent fuel into a new cask by the end of
1994. Later, the company said it would transfer the spent fuel at the end of the
August 1995 refueling outage.  <P>                                
                                                                                
    More than a year later, the cask is still in place, because, critics charge,
the utility does not know how to transfer spent fuel from one cask to another.<P>  
                                                              
    NRC agrees that Consumers Power is under no obligation to unload the fuel   
from the flawed cask. ''It's a voluntary action and a voluntary                 
procedure...because there's nothing wrong, so far, with the operation of the    
cask,'' NRC spokesman Joe Gilliland said. <P>

                                                                                                     
                                                   





<I><FONT SIZE=2>Source:  Nuclear Fuel, September 25, 1995   </FONT></I>


</BODY> 
