<TITLE>
September 18, 1995-LEGISLATIVE ALERT
FROM THE
AMERICAN WIND ENERGY ASSOCIATION: Wind Production Incentives Threatened
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 18, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>LEGISLATIVE ALERT
FROM THE
AMERICAN WIND ENERGY ASSOCIATION: Wind Production Incentives Threatened</H3>


This is to advise you of the need for urgent action to prevent the
threatened repeal of the U.S. wind energy industry's production tax
incentive.  The Ways and Means Committee announced its plans only
yesterday).  Please contact your Member of Congress (U.S. Capitol
switchboard is 202-225-3121) and Senators (202-224-3121) immediately
regarding this matter.<P> 

<!-- MailTo Tag -->
<a href=mailto:tgray@igc.apc.org>Tom Gray</A>,
Northeast Representative
American Wind Energy Association<P>

<HR><P>

<B>WAYS AND MEANS THREATENS TO
REPEAL PRODUCTION TAX CREDIT</B><P>

<B><CENTER>Wind Industry Argues that Committee Developed Plan
Based on False Assumptions, Unrealistic Revenue Costs</CENTER></B>

In yet another Congressional jab to the U.S. wind energy 
industry, the House Ways and Means Committee has threatened to 
abolish the wind energy production tax credit (PTC), which plays 
an important role in encouraging wind energy development in the U.S.<P>

Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer (R-Texas) released 
the plan for corporate and other tax reforms on September 14 as 
"an effort to reduce corporate welfare" and comply with House 
budget legislation.<P>

According to the proposal, "the income tax credit for 
electricity produced from wind and closed-loop biomass would be 
available only for . . . facilities placed in service before 
September 14, 1995, with an exemption placed in service before 
September 14, 1996, pursuant to a binding contract in existence 
on September 13, 1995 . . . "  The credit originally was to 
extend to June 30, 1999.<P>

Members of the wind energy industry denounced the proposed plan. 
Wind projects are in advanced planning stages in Washington,
Oregon, Wyoming, California, Texas, Vermont, Minnesota, Maine and
Wisconsin, and the financing of each of these projects was
predicated on availability of the production tax credit.  "It
isn't fair and it makes no sense to further undermine such a
promising technology," said AWEA Executive Director Randall
Swisher.  "We have reduced our costs 90% in the last 14 years, we
are just emerging into the bulk power market for
utilities--Archer would strangle the U.S. wind industry in its
crib with this proposal." <P>

Attorney and AWEA Board Member Ed Ing said, "This plan is unfair 
and will kill all wind development.  Aside from wind and 
closed-loop biomass, which is also eligible for the credit, 
Archer's package affects only two other energy sectors, the 
alcohol fuels credit and the utility conservation allowance.  
These two sectors are trimmed back, but the wind production 
credit will be completely eliminated.  Archer leaves all other 
energy sectors untouched."<P>

Industry insiders also expressed concern over the plan's 
disproportionate effect on wind energy versus natural gas, which 
is largely untouched by Archer's plan.  As the current utility 
fuel of choice, natural gas does not need incentives for 
development as other fuels do, they pointed out.<P>

Ing also explained that the proposal is based on false revenue 
cost assumptions.  "Repeal of the credit is supposed to save 
$400 million over the next five years to help close the federal 
deficit.  This assumes that from 1996 to 2000, wind and 
closed-loop biomass will generate about 23.5 billion kWh from 
new facilities--an impossible production figure.  The estimated 
revenue cost savings used to develop the plan are unrealistic."<P>

The House Ways and Means Committee is scheduled to begin 
consideration of the proposal on Monday, September 18, with a 
committee vote likely by Wednesday, September 20.  A full report 
on the committee's actions will be included in the September 25 Weekly.<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2>From Wind Energy Weekly #664, 18 September 1995</FONT></I>


</BODY> 
