<TITLE>
September 15, 1995-FERC To Hold Public Hearing on Crown Hydro Company's Hydroelectric Project
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 15, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>FERC To Hold Public Hearing on Crown Hydro Company's Hydroelectric Project</H3>

The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) will be in Minneapolis on September 27, 1995 to hold the final public hearing on a proposed small-scale hydroelectric facility in Minneapolis.  The facility would be located in the former Crown Roller Mill building adjacent to the Army Corps of Engineers Lock and Dam at St. Anthony Falls.  The facility will be owned and operated by the Crown Hydro Company.<P>  

Crown Hydro is seeking approval for a 30 year operating license from FERC (Docket #11175-002) The planned facility will generate up to 3.4 MW of power that would be sold into the electric grid. Tom Griffin of Crown Hydro states, "although the capacity factor of the facility is expected to be 65%, we still feel the project will generate electricity competively."<P>  

The Shakopee Mdewakanton Sioux Community has entered into a formal agreement with Crown Hydro as a partner and financial backer for $2.9 million of the projected $4.2 million total cost of the project. The project will restore for public use and education an area of the historic West Bank Mills District by reopening a section of tunnels where falling water played a key role building the flour milling industry in Minneapolis during the early part of this century.<P>

The public hearing will be held on September 27th from 2 p.m.- 4 p.m. in the Sarasota Building on the west bank in Downtown Minneapolis.<P>

<B>Contact:</B> Tom Griffin, Crown Hydro Company, 612-825-1043<P>

