<TITLE>
September 14, 1995-NSP Shareholders Approve Merger with Wisconsin Utility
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 14, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>NSP Shareholders Approve Merger with Wisconsin Utility</H3>
Northern States Power Co. shareholders overwhelmingly 
approved the utility's
proposed merger with Wisconsin Electric Corp. at NSP's annual 
meeting Wednesday, although a few expressed concerns that the 
merger would turn out to be bad for them.<P>
    The two companies have proposed a "merger of equals," with 
shareholders of
each firm holding 50 percent interest in a $ 6 billion utility 
holding company
that would be based in Minneapolis.<P>
    The utilities have said they expect $ 2 billion in annual 
savings from
consolidation efficiencies; Howard said Wednesday that much of 
the savings would
come from a staff reduction of about 10 percent, or about 1,200 
employees,
across the two companies.<P>    
    At the NSP meeting, about 96 percent of the votes were in 
favor of the
merger, about on par with the 97.2 percent of Wisconsin Energy 
shareholders who
approved the deal at their own meeting in Milwaukee Wednesday.<P>
    The merger still must be approved by a contingent of federal 
and state
regulators, who are expected to decide by the second or third 
quarter of 1996,
said NSP Chief Executive Jim Howard; that means the merger could 
become reality
about a year from now, he said.<P>

    A resolution
recommending that NSP stop producing radioactive waste was 
defeated, winning about 5.5 percent
of the vote. A second resolution calling for support of 
regulatory reform that
would tie NSP earnings to its success in promoting energy 
efficiency was
defeated by about the same margin.<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2>From:   Star Tribune, September 14, 1995 </FONT></I>


