<TITLE>
September 11, 1995-Detroit Utility to Offer PV Program Using 'Green  Pricing
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 11, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Detroit Utility to Offer PV Program Using 'Green  Pricing</H3>
                                                                      
                                                                        
    Detroit Edison will offer     
solar energy service to residential and small commercial customers after the    
Michigan Public Service Commission approved the utility's ''green pricing'' rate
proposal for the service.   <P>                                                    
                                                                                
    Under a program announced Aug. 2, residential customers will be allowed to  
sign up for a two-year ''SolarCurrents'' rate at an additional $ 6.59 per month,
on average, for each 100 watts of service from a planned 28.4-kW photovoltaic   
facility.      <P>                                                                 
                                                                                
         The PV facility will be installed at the Michigan    
Electric Power Coordination Center site near Ann Arbor, and is expected to begin
operation in May 1996.        <P>                                                  
                                                                                
    The $ 250,000 system will include 100 rigid crystalline silicon PV modules  
on four-by-six-foot glass panels. The PV system will produce as much electricity
as 14 rooftop residential solar installations and will generate power for at    
least 10 years. The peak solar season in Michigan runs from May through August. <P>
                                                                                
 Residential customers signed up for a two-year period.       
Commercial customers will subscribe for10 years but have options to end        
agreements.  <P>                                                                   
                                                                                
   The Utility Photovoltaic Group, an industry
consortium working with DOE to boost PV commercialization, selected Detroit Ed's
program to receive the funding and is negotiating related contracts. <P>           
                                                                   
 <FONT SIZE=2><I>Source: Electric Utility Week, August 7, 1995 </I></FONT>
