<TITLE>
September 10, 1995-High Plains Corporation Seeks Financing For Two Minnesota Ethanol Plants
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 10, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>High Plains Corporation Seeks Financing For Two Minnesota Ethanol Plants</H3>
High Plains Corporation, based in Wichita, KS, is continuing efforts to obtain acceptable financing for ethanol plants planned for Dawson and Appleton, MN.  Both cities have signed letters of intent to provide complete financing for construction of the facilities.  High Plains would operate the city-owned facilities and have the option to purchase them at a future date. Once financing for the plant is finalized, production could begin within 12 months.<P>

High Plains is the largest publicly traded company whose sole business is ethanol production.  High Plains currently operates two ethanol plants, one in Nebraska the other in Kansas, producing up to 58 million gallons per year.  In 1995, the company had $53 million in sales up from $33 million in 1994.<P>

High Plains was attracted to Minnesota because of the state's strong support for ethanol.  President Stanley Larson notes, "The state of Minnesota has a great incentive program (up to $3 million per year for ten years) for ethanol production and has legislated a year-round oxyfuel requirement statewide beginning in 1997, creating a large ethanol demand within the state."   He adds, "we continue to believe that the environmental benefits of ethanol will continue to expand our markets and increase our product's value." <P> 

High Plains has announced that demand for ethanol is very strong already for the wintertime Federal Oxygenate program and the company is contracting a good portion of their production at $0.10 - $0.25 per gallon above the current sales price of $1.00 - $1.05 per gallon.<P>



<DT><B>Contact:</B><BR>
Raymond Friend, High Plains Corp., 316-269-4130<P>
