<TITLE>
September 7, 1995-Minnesota Agri-Power Project Negotiating For Federal Assistance
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 7, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Minnesota Agri-Power Project Negotiating For Federal Assistance</H3>
The U.S. Department of Energy has included the Minnesota Agri-Power Project (MAP) as a finalist for funding under the DOE's Biomass Power for Rural Development Solicitation.  MAPP is a biomass energy project that will use alfalfa stems as the feedstock.  The Minnesota Valley Alfalfa Producers (MnVAP) Cooperative is hoping to get $900,000 in financial assistance from DOE for research and development of the pilot plant.  This money will go towards the estimated $5.0 million to set up the pilot facility.<P>

The Pilot Plant will be used to demonstrate that there is a market for the processed alfalfa products and the economics justify the full-scale joint venture known as the MAP project.  The pilot plant will require 120,000 tons of alfalfa per year, representing production from 30,000 acres.<P>

MnVAP has issued its initial offering to farmers interested in buying into the cooperative.  The initial offering is being made only to the 443 initial members who have put up the $200 membership fee.  Any shares leftover will be available to other interested farmers.  The 120,000 shares will be issued in two pools at $40.00 and $47.50, respectively.  There is a 120 share minimum and 12,000 share maximum with 20% due in cash upon signing the subscription agreement.  MnVAP hopes to begin construction on the Pilot Plant in January 1996.<P>



<DT><B>Contact:</B><BR>
Chris Hanson, MnVAP, 612-564-2451<P>
</BODY> 
