<HEAD>
<TITLE>
September 4, 1995-Rock Valley, Iowa, Residents To Experiment with Natural Gas Competition
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 4, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Rock Valley, Iowa, Residents To Experiment with Natural Gas Competition</H3>
Beginning in November, residents of Rock Valley, a northwest Iowa community of 2500 will be able to do something few if any other homeowners in the United States can do: choose a different natural gas utility. <P>
   MidAmerican Energy Co. will conduct a competition experiment in the town by letting customers choose from among MidAmerican or three other gas providers from Minneapolis, Pittsburgh or Columbus, Ohio. They can switch gas companies much as they would switch long-distance telephone companies. The Iowa Utilities Board, a three-person panel,  regulates natural gas companies in Iowa.<P>
The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission allowed competition among natural gas providers on the wholesale level in 1992 when it rewrote its rules, breaking apart pipeline monopolies that had exclusively supplied gas.<P> 
That permitted utilities and large industrial customers who purchase gas on a wholesale basis to shop around for better prices. In addition to the gas they buy, they now pay a transportation fee to the pipelines.  In 1990, wholesale gas prices were an average $ 2.10 per million cubic feet. Now they average $ 1.35. <P>
The experiment in Rock Valley is bringing competition to the retail level, allowing residential and smaller businesses to participate.<P>
What do customers think?   "I doubt whether I'm going to change even if it will be a few dollars in savings," said Hale Pember, a druggist. "It gets to be too complicated, just like all those telephone companies." <P>
Del Knobloch, who owns Valley Pharmacy, said if the gas companies call as many times as some of the long-distance companies do, asking him to change, "I'll switch to electricity in no time flat."
Minnegasco's affiliate, called Interlink, is participating.  "It gives us a chance to learn a lot of different things, including how customers react to choices," said Andrea Newman, director of new services development. "The real intent is more from a market-research standpoint. It isn't designed for us to make big amounts of revenue."<P>
No one knows whether the program will end up saving consumers money, since they use very small quantities of natural gas.
<P>


(From GANNETT NEWS SERVICE, September 1, 1995)

</BODY> 
</HTML> 
</DOC>
