<HEAD>
<TITLE>
September 3, 1995-Ethanol Safe for Use in Small Engines: Report from the American Lung Association of Minnesota
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-September 3, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Ethanol Safe for Use in Small Engines: Report from the American Lung Association of Minnesota</H3>
The following was released today by the American Lung Association (Minneapolis Affiliate):  In response to claims made by Amoco, one of the nation's largest petroleum suppliers, the American Lung Association (Minneapolis Affiliate) has released new research results on ethanol-blended fuels' performance in small engines.  The findings: Ethanol-blended gasoline does not harm or cause performance problems in small engines.<P>


The research results are based on a quantitative telephone survey conducted the week of Aug. 14, 1995, with 347 separate gas station service managers (161
were from Amoco stations) throughout Minnesota.  A series of questions revealed that, of all stations that had repaired small engines, only four reported a problem possibly related to the oxygenate ethanol.  Furthermore, of the 161 Amoco stations contacted, there was only one potential ethanol-related problem reported. (Important Note: Of the minuscule problems reported, ethanol was a suggested cause only and not proven to be the source of the problem.) 
<P>


The survey results further disprove Amoco's claim that there is a ground swell of Minnesotans bringing their small engines into Amoco for repairs directly related to ethanol.  As recent as this past July, Dan Gunderson, public affairs and government affairs representative for Amoco Corp., made the following statements on the KTCA-TV news show "Almanac" (7 p.m., July 7, 1995):    "We're not anti-ethanol.  There are some uses where ethanol isn't the best fuel.  It's not recommended for some uses...Polaris, Arctic Cat, MerCruiser, Harley-Davidson all caution their purchasers of those engines about the use of ethanol -- and those people come to us because we're the largest repairers of cars in the state.<P>


Larry Johnson, fuels specialist at the Minnesota Department of Agriculture notes: "Gasoline containing up to 10 percent ethanol is an approved fuel by the American Standard of Testing and Materials and is covered by all engine warranties.  Polaris, Arctic Cat, MerCruiser and Harley-Davidson all approve the use of 10 percent ethanol blends in their engines.  In fact, this type of gas can be used in any engine designed to operate on unleaded gasoline." He further reports that the results of several studies by the state's Ethanol Commission have shown there are no performance problems in small engines from using ethanol blends.<P>



<B>Contacts:</B><P>
Jerry Orr, Executive Director-American Lung Association, Minneapolis, 612-871-2804, ext. 126(work)<BR>

Larry Johnson, Minnesota Department of Agriculture, 612-297-4654<BR>

Bruce Stockman, Executive Director - Minnesota Corn Growers Association, 612-447-2676 (work) or 612-440-3570 (home)<P>

(From PR Newswire, September 1, 1995)

</BODY> 
</HTML> 
