<HEAD>
<TITLE>
August 31, 1995-Minnegasco and Department of Defense Demonstrate Small-Scale Fuel Cell Application
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-August 31, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>Minnegasco and Department of Defense Demonstrate Small-Scale Fuel Cell Application</H3>
Minnegasco, Minnesota's largest gas utility, is demonstrating a natural gas fuel-cell technology at the Air Reserve Station at the Twin Cities International Airport.  The project is one of 11 Department of Defense (DOD) sites to recieve funding for on-site energy production using fuel-cells.<P>

A fuel cell converts fuel (i.e. natural gas, ethanol, biomass) using a chemical reaction directly into heat and electricity.  This process increases the efficiency of power generation and lowers the amount of potentially harmful emissions.  The Minnegasco/DOD project uses a fuel cell manufactured by ONSI, a subsidiary of International Fuel Cells Corporation.  The power plant has a capacity of 200 kW and is expected to generate nearly 1.7 million kWhs per year and 5,800 MMbtus of usable steam heating.<P>

ONSI and Minnegasco estimate that the fuel cell will result in annual savings of $46,000.  With a capitol cost of $1500 per kW, the project has a simple payback of about 7 years.<P>

  

Contact: Patty Pederson, Minnegasco Public Relations, 612-321-4609;  Mark Davidson, 934th Airlift Wing, 612-725-5337

</BODY> 
</HTML> 
