<HEAD>
<TITLE>
July 27, 1995-Renewable Energy Budget Under Attack in Congress
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H2>News Item-July 27, 1995</H2>
<HR> 
<UL>
<LI><FONT SIZE=5>July 27,1995- Renewable Energy Budget Under Attack</FONT><BR>
Federal Congressional leaders have proposed major cuts to the DOE's programs covering Solar Energy, Wind Power and Energy Efficiency.  Nuclear power and Fossil Fuel research are being cut by a much lower percentage and still enjoy significantly higher appropriations.  Contact <a href=mailto:cmep@citizen.org>Matt Freedman</a> of Public Citizen at 202-546-4996 for further information and the key senators and representatives that need to hear from concerned citizens.<BR>
<BR>
 
<LI><FONT SIZE=5>July 27,1995- Renewable Energy Budget Under Attack</FONT><BR>
The Senate Appropriations Committee's Subcommittee on Energy and Water
Development yesterday marked up DOE's FY 1996 budget for solar and renewable
energy, providing $283.6 million (vs. $266.4 million in the House, $388
million last year, and $423 million requested by the Administration).

For the Biofuels Energy Systems account, the subcommittee provided $54.3
million (vs. $48 million in the House, $62 million last year, and $80
million requested).  This 13 percent reduction from last year was the least
cut from any of the major renewable energy accounts.  That's the good news.
The bad news is that the direction should be up, not down.  The other energy
supply accounts fared better than renewables -- funding for the whole
package is down 15.6% vs. 27% for the renewables.

The full Senate Appropriations Committee will mark the bill up tomorrow
(7/27).  Floor action could occur as soon as next week.

***  Senator Jeffords plans to offer an amendment restoring funds to the
solar and renewable energy account.  I urge anyone interested in saving
biomass and other renewable energy research funding to write their Senators.
If you would like more information, please e-mail <a href=mailto:detchon@podesta.com>Reid Detchon</a> Executive Director of the Biomass Energy Alliance, or
call (202) 639-0384.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>

</BODY> 
</HTML> 
