<HEAD><TITLE>Energy Assistance Bill</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 

<H1>Energy Assistance Bill 1996 - HF 2878, SF 2389; </H1>

<H3>January 15, 1997</H3>
For those of you who are still looking at this page, the 1997 Minnesota legislative session began on January 7.  To keep track of 1997 energy initiatives follow this link to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/leg/legwatch97.html">Sustainable Minnesota's 1997 Legislative Watch</A>. 

<H3>April 25, 1996</H3>
Here is a summary of this bill from the latest issue of <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/newsletters/me3spr96.html">Sustainable Minnesota</A>.<P>

<B>LIHEAP - Federal Energy Assistance Program Gets Help From State</B><p>

  In 1984 Minnesota received $82.2 million in federal funds for energy assistance for low income households. About 139,000 customers were served. By 1995, Minnesota's federal funds plummeted to $34.3 million and only 105,000 households were served. From 1994 to 1995 alone LIHEAP funding decreased by almost 40 percent. A typical LIHEAP recipient in Minnesota has an annual income of $7,583 and receives about $420 in heating assistance. This year only $280 will be available per recipient. In Minnesota only about 40 percent of those households eligible for LIHEAP assistance actually apply for it. Reasons for this vary from not knowing about LIHEAP to an unwillingness of potential applicants to ask for assistance.<p>

  This year the U.S. House of Representatives voted to zero out funding of LIHEAP. As a result of a filibuster by Senator Paul Wellstone and a persistent political coalition of legislators from cold-weather states, the Senate passed a budget resolution to continue LIHEAP funding at 90 percent of the  previous year's funding levels. The House agreed and although the Federal government has yet to complete its budget, the money is beginning to flow into the states.<p>

  The Minnesota legislature agreed to make up a portion of the federal budget cutbacks. The Jobs, Energy and Community Develop-ment Omnibus Appropriations bill signed by the Governor (HF3243/ SF2852) contains a provision to allocate at least $1 million in additional funding for LIHEAP. As Pam Marshall of the low-income advocacy organization Energy CENTS says, "the consequences of doing nothing about cuts to LIHEAP are real and dangerous. This program is about protecting the health and safety of the lowest income Minnesotans."<p>

Contact: Pam Marshall, Energy CENTS, 612-872-3293<p>

<H3>April 4, 1996</H3>
The Jobs, Energy and Community Development Omnibus Appropriations bill signed by the Governor (HF3243/SF2852) contains a provision to allocate at least $1 million  and up to $10 million in additional funding for LIHEAP.  As Pam Marshall of the low-income advocacy organization Energy Cents says, "the consequences of doing nothing about cuts to LIHEAP are real and dangerous.  This program is about protecting the health and safety of the lowest income Minnesotans."<BR>

Contact:  Pam Marshall, Energy Cents, 612-872-3293
<H3>April 1, 1996</H3>

The Joint Conference Committee passed the home energy assistance bill, which now awaits approval by the governor.

<P>
<H3>March 26, 1996</H3>
<A HREF="gopher://gopher.revisor.leg.state.mn.us:70/00/.revisor/senate/publicbills/1995-1996/S2800-2899/S2852">Senate File SF 2852 </A> (<A HREF="gopher://gopher.revisor.leg.state.mn.us:70/00/.revisor/house/publicbills/1995-1996/H3200-3299/H3243">House File HF 3243</A>) is the most current bill with language that provides funding for low-income energy services.<P>

The Senate Jobs, Energy and Community Development Committee approved a bill that appropriates $1 million in home energy assistance to low-income households.  The committee also approved a Minnegasco proposal to provide assistance to low-income natural gas customers over the next three years.  This plan will be financed through rate increases to other customers.  The rate increase, as projected by Minnegasco, will be approximately $2.50 per household annually.  <P>








