<HEAD><TITLE>Prairie Island Bill-1996  HF 2784, SF 2495</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H1>Prairie Island Bill-1996</H1>
<H3>( SF 2495, HF 2784; HF 3236, SF 2866)</H3>


<H3>January 15, 1997</H3>
For those of you who are still looking at this page, the 1997 Minnesota legislative session began on January 7.  To keep track of 1997 energy initiatives follow this link to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/leg/legwatch97.html">Sustainable Minnesota's 1997 Legislative Watch</A>. 

<H3>April 4, 1996</H3>
To say the bill related to the Prairie Island nuclear plant was on-again off-again would be an understatement.  It seemed that every day of the session brought a new proposal.  In the end no deal could be reached.  The sticking points throughout were over the compensation for the Prairie Island Tribe including land and money.  NSP initially tried to tie any compensation to expanded radioactive waste storage at the plant but that proposal lost in the first few weeks of the session.  From then on NSP became the primary opponent to any legislation.<P>



ME3 supported financial compensation for the Tribe.  ME3's proposal was to pay the Tribe from the renewable energy development account.  The account was set up as part of the original legislation in 1994 .  It requires NSP to put $500,000 per year for each dry cask that remains on Prairie Island beyond January 1, 1999.  At the full allotment of 17 casks given to NSP, payments to the fund would amount to $8.5 million per year.  ME3 proposed that at least $2 million per year would go to the tribe.  One legislative proposal would have paid the Tribe from general appropriations.  That proposal was defeated.  Unfortunately, the ME3 proposal was never submitted to a vote.  We're convinced that since the proposal would not have required any new money, it would have passed.<P>



A catalyst for the NSP/Tribe proposal was the legislative requirement for NSP to search for an alternative site in Goodhue County for the dry casks.  Most of the proposals put forward would have put the process on hold.  In January 1996 the EQB's Site Advisory Task force issued its report to the EQB which stated that there are "no additional sites in Goodhue County that should be considered further by the EQB."  At the EQB's hearing in March the Board tabled a resolution that, if adopted, would have suspended the alternative siting process.  The Board chose to wait for the end of the legislative session in case the resolution became unnecessary.  Since legislation related to Prairie Island did not pass, the EQB is expected to pass the resolution at their meeting in late-April.  Community groups around the Prairie Island plant that want the waste to be sent off the island may file a lawsuit against the EQB.<P>



We can expect that Prairie Island will be revisited again next session.<P>


Contact:  John Hynes, EQB Public Advisor, 612-296-2871 or 1-800-657-3794<P>

<P>




<H3>February 28,1996</H3>
Representative Alice Hausman has introduced a bill (HF 3236) that is  similar to the bill introduced on February 1 (see below), but eliminates NSP's ability to rerack and increase storage capacity beyond the level agreed to in 1994.  She has requested that this bill be heard by the House Environment Committee. For more information on the status of the bill, please call Committee Administrator Betty Goihl at 296-8879. <P>



<H3>February 12, 1996</H3>
Last Friday the Prairie Island bill was pulled from the agenda of the Environment committee by author Steve Novak.  A memo with signatures of a majority of committee members opposed to the bill was circulated prior to the hearing making a hearing meaningless.<P>

Under legislative rules the bill has not met committee deadlines and should be dead for the rest of the session.  However, the Governor has publicly stated his intention to bring the parties together to work for a compromise.   Therefore, it is likely that some of the provisions will show up in some form or another later in the session.  Stay Tuned.<P>



<H3>February 7, 1996</H3>
The Prairie Island Bill passed the Senate Jobs, Energy, and Community Development Committee on a vote of 7-6.  Two changes were made to the original bill by chief author Steve Novak including the following provisions: the renewable energy fund was partially restored, and state oversight for any reracking at Prairie Island was restored.<P>
Swing votes include for the next hearing scheduled for Friday February 9th in the Senate Environment Committee include:<BR>

<!-- MailTo Tag -->
<A HREF="MAILTO:sen.skip.finn@senate.leg.state.mn.us">Sen.Skip Finn</A> (DFL - Cass Lake) (612) 296-6128<BR>
<!-- MailTo Tag -->
<A HREF="MAILTO:sen.arlene.lesewski@senate.leg.state.mn.us">Sen. Arlene Lesewski</A> (IR - Marshall) (612)296-4125<BR>
<!-- MailTo Tag -->
<A HREF="MAILTO:sen.ted.mondale@senate.leg.state.mn.us">Sen. Ted Mondale</A>(DFL - St. Louis Park) (612)297-8065<BR>
<!-- MailTo Tag -->
<A HREF="MAILTO:sen.len.price@senate.leg.state.mn.us">Sen. Len Price</A> (DFL - Woodbury) (612) 297-8060<P>

 


<H3>February 1, 1996</H3>
A bill has been introduced that would drop the controversial requirement of Northern States Power Company finding an alternative site to store nuclear waste away from the nuclear power plant at Prairie Island.   The initial proposal worked out between NSP and the Prairie Island Dakota Tribe will contain the following provisions:<P>



<!-- List Tag -->
<UL>
<LI>NSP will buy land and give it to the Tribe<P>

<LI>NSP will enter into a contractual agreement with the Tribe for annual payments for the dry cask facility.<P>

<LI>NSP will pay the tribe an amount equal to the real and personal property taxes that would have accrued from the storage facility as long as the casks remain on Prairie Island<P>

<LI>The bill allows NSP to maximize the space in the spent fuel pool inside the plant by reracking.  This will allow the plant to operate until the end of its license in 2013 and 2014<P>

<LI>A provision providing an annual $500,000 per cask payment by NSP into a renewable energy development account for casks still at the plant after January 1, 1999 is slated to be repealed<P>
</UL>



