<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>EEPRA 1996 Summary</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>The Economic Efficiency and Pollution Reduction Act (EEPRA) of 1996 HF 3063, SF 2721 
</H2>
<H3>January 15, 1997</H3>
For those of you who are still looking at this page, there will soon be a new EEPRA 1997 bill introduced at the 1997 Minnesota legislative session which began on January 7.  To keep track of the new EEPRA follow this link to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/leg/legwatch97.html">Sustainable Minnesota's 1997 Legislative Watch</A>. 

<H3>April 4, 1996</H3>

The initiative bill for a $1.5 billion tax shift, the Economic Efficiency and Pollution Reduction Act of 1996 ,was heard in both the Senate and the House tax committees.  No votes were taken this session but the bill appears to have support.  Over the summer and fall, ME3 will initiate an educational campaign and develop further economic analysis and case studies on the issue. 
<P>


The Minnesota initiative has received national and international attention.  The Sustainable Minnesota web site has become a vehicle for information exchange.  Materials and updates are available on the web at http://www.me3.org/projects/greentax<P>


Contact:  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="bailey@ilsr.org/">John Bailey</A>, ILSR, 612-379-3815<P>




<H3>February 15, 1996: </H3>
A general informational meeting about the bill was held today before the MN House Committee on Taxes, but no vote was taken. <P>

Here is a copy of ILSR Vice President <!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="taxtest2.html">David Morris' Testimony before the House Tax Committee</A> in support of EEPRA.

<H3>February 8, 1996: </H3>
A general informational meeting about the bill was held last night at the MN Senate Committee on Taxes-Subcommittee on Property and Sales Taxes, but no vote was taken.  The chair of the tax committee will now decide whether to re-hear the bill before the full committee.<P>


<H3>February 5, 1996</H3><P>


</BODY> The Economic Efficiency and Pollution Reduction Act of 1996 (EEPRA)</b> is a
$1.5 billion tax shift.  Taxes on pollution are raised by $1.5 billion a year
while taxes on property and payroll fall by an equal amount.  <p>
<p>
<b>Key Elements of EEPRA</b>:<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL>
<LI>A $50 per ton carbon tax imposed on all fuels and electricity consumed in
Minnesota.  The tax shift is phased in over 5 years. <p>
<LI>Nuclear electricity is taxed at the same rate as the average for all
non-nuclear electricity.<p>
<LI>Renewable fuels like wind, hydroelectricity, ethanol are exempted.<p>
<LI>A reduction of $750 million in residential and business property taxes.<p>
<LI>A reduction of $750 million in employer and employee payroll taxes.<p>
<LI>An appropriation of $80 million for low-income fuel assistance and
weatherization programs.<p>
<LI>Businesses are exempted from additional taxes if the net increase in taxes
from the tax shift exceeds 1 percent of sales. </ul><P



<P>
