<HEAD><TITLE>Wind Energy:  Sales Tax Exemption for Wind Equipment-HF 2654, SF 2362</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H1>Wind Energy:  Sales Tax Exemption for Wind Equipment-HF 2654, SF 2362</H1> 

<H3>May 20, 1996</H3>
We have received a copy of Mn Dept. of Public Service Commissioner Kris Sanda's response to the DPS involvement in Governor Carlson's veto of this legislation.  Below is a copy of her letter dated April 30, 1996<P>
<HR>
April 30, 1996<BR>
<BR>
The Honorable Janet Johnson
Room 321, State Capitol
St. Paul, MN  55155

Dear Janet:
Thank you for your letter regarding the Governor's veto of Chapter 466, House File 374.   The bill contained language mandating that the final 200 MW of wind electric generation required under current state law be built in Minnesota.  I, too, am extremely disappointed by the manner in which this issue was handled in the legislative process.

House file 374 was intronduced early in the 1995 legislative session.  Over the course of nearly two full legislative sessions, the "Minnesota only" mandate was never offered as an amendment in any House or Senate policy committee for public comment and testimony.  Even though this language carries important policy considerations, it was slipped into a non-controversial bill at the last minute in the waning hours of the 1996 session.  It is this sort of action that contributes to the public's disenchantmment with the process.

As wonderful as the "Minnesota only" mandate may appear at first glance, there are a number of significant concerns.

The exclusionary "Minnesota only" language opens the door for a lengthy and costly lawsuit by interested bidders from outside Minnesota under the federal interstate commerce clause.  At the very least such a suit could lead to delays and at worst, impact the project in a range of other ways as well.

DPS analysts found credible the projection that mandating the final 200 MW of this wind development to sites in Minnesota will result in an estimated $43 million dollars in additional costs to Minnesto


<H3>April 17, 1996</H3>
We have talked to the attorney at the Minnesota Department of Revenue and he believes that most of the components of a wind energy system will remain exempt from sales taxes under the capital equipment exemption statutes discussed below in the April 15th report.<P>

The major drawback for companies that plan to purchase wind energy equipment is that they will have to pay the 6.5% sales tax upfront and then apply for a refund.  Only two applications for sales tax refund can be filed per year.  Applicants can expect a refund in 4-8 weeks.<P>

It should also be noted that any replacement parts and equipment only receive a partial exemption. (see <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="gopher://gopher.revisor.leg.state.mn.us:70/00/.revisor/statutes/296_299/297A_/297A.02.txt">Minnesota Statutes 297A.02</A>)<P>
Contact:  Greg Heck, Attorney, MN Department of Revenue, 612-296-1902 ext 142<P>

<H3>April 15, 1996</H3>
<H3>Governor Carlson Vetoes Wind Equipment Sales Tax Exemption</H3>
<I>He Opposes Requirement that Prairie Island Mandate Be Met By Minnesota Based Wind Plants</I><P>
The bills shown below (HF2654, SF 2362) did not go anywhere during the 1996 legislative session. However, during the the session provisions that would extend the wind equipment sales tax exemption was amended to another bill that passed the legislature. The bill, HF374 was originally introduced in the 1995 session.  It provided large power plants an exemption from the Certificate of Need process if they were selected through a competitive bidding process approved by the Public Utilities Commission. <P>

HF 374 was vetoed by the Governor on April 12.  Governor Carlson explained his veto in a letter to House Speaker, Irv Anderson:
<HR>

The Honorable Irv Anderson<BR>
Speaker of the House of Representatives<BR>
463 State Office Building<BR>
Saint Paul, MN  55155<P>

Dear Speaker Anderson,<P>

I have vetoed and am returning Chapter 466, House File 374.<P>

This bill in the original form was a non-controversial housekeeping measure for the Public Utilities Commission.  However, an amendment added in the final days of the legislative session significantly altered the scope of the original bill and, if signed, would mean higher consumer costs.<P>

The amendment, which was never discussed in committee, changes the wind power mandate in the 1994 Prairie Island legislation by requiring that the additional 200 MW of wind power required by December 31, 2002 be generated only in Minnesota.  It effectively eliminates competitive bids from areas in North Dakota and South Dakota which may have better, more cost-effective wind energy production potential.  Under current law, wind generation sites in Minnesota have every opportunity to compete for contracts to supply the additional 200 MW of power.  The amendment language is anti-competitive and costly.<P>

According to the Department of Public Service, this "Minnesota only" option will carry an estimated $43 million of additional costs, and these costs will be paid by NSP customers through higher rates.  Since the higher costs are directly attributable to a state mandate, this becomes yet another tax increase hidden in consumer utility bills.<P>

This administration stongly supports cost-effective development of wind generated electricity, but mandating that wind energy only be produced in Minnesota works against this goal.<P>

Warmest regards, <P>

Arne  H. Carlson<BR>
Governor<BR>
<HR>
<B>Commentary</B><P> In essence, Governor Carlson has raised the cost of generating electricity from Minnesota wind energy facilities while encouraging out of state wind energy development.   The wind equipment sales tax exemptions expire on July 1, 1996. <P> 

The MN Department of Revenue did a fiscal impact study on the effects of extending the sales tax exemption for wind energy equipement and determined that the state would lose $400,000 in FY 1997, $400,000 in FY 1998, $700,000 in FY 1999 if the exemption was extended. The amounts reflect an assumption that 90% of the purchase prices of a wind energy system would qualify for an exemption under the capital equipment exemption section of Minnesota Statutes. (<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="gopher://gopher.revisor.leg.state.mn.us:70/11/.revisor/statutes/296_299/297A_">297A</A>, <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="gopher://gopher.revisor.leg.state.mn.us:70/00/.revisor/statutes/296_299/297A_/297A.01.txt">297A.01(subd. 16)</A>, <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="gopher://gopher.revisor.leg.state.mn.us:70/00/.revisor/statutes/296_299/297A_/297A.02.txt">297A.02 (subd. 5)</A> and <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="gopher://gopher.revisor.leg.state.mn.us:70/00/.revisor/statutes/296_299/297A_/297A.25.txt">297A.25 (subd. 42</A>)).  The capital equipment exemption only applies to commercial power producers and not establishments using their own power.  The purchaser still pays the sales tax up-front and then applies for a refund from the state.<P>

Ending the sales tax exemption could delay the construction of the next 100 MW of wind power.  Zond's bid price did not take into account the increased cost from ending the sales tax yet, according to NSP's bid guidelines, the bidder was liable for future changes in the tax code.  Zond, working on tight margins to begin with, may feel it has to renegotiate the bid terms to take into account the additional costs due to sales tax.  According to the Department of Revenue analysis, Zond would see about $400,000 in increased costs due to a 6.5% sales tax on 10% of the value of their equipment.<P>

Contrary to the Governor's assertion in his letter, the $43 million estimate of the cost to Minnesota ratepayers from a Minnesota only wind energy option did not come from the DPS but from NSP.  It is contained in NSP's1995 Resource Plan.   There is little supporting data in the tables that provide that number.  In any case, the estimates, by NSP's own admission, are highly speculative.  Governor Carlson does not address any of the issues related to losing a $200 million development to a neighboring state such as jobs that will be lost.<P>

On the subject of capacity factors, the key to the cost analysis, NSP says, "while available data may be sufficient to define the limitation of Minnesota sites, the resources available in the Dakotas are not well defined and decisions made based on assumptions about these resources carry a substantial risk.  A minimum of two years of wind resource data would better define location for development and provide the basis for an assessment of actual production potential."  In fact one wind developer noted that it is very unlikely that there are any suitable sites in North Dakota that are better than any along the Buffalo Ridge in Minnesota.<P>

NSP adds several cautionary sentences for people interpreting the data.  NSP notes, "The results of the scenarios described in the process discussion are sensitive to numerous elements of uncertainty which constrain their usefulness for decision-making purposes at this time."<P>

John Dunlop, the Great Plains Representative of the American Wind Energy Association says, "there's no data that we have seen that supports the contention that there are better sites in North and South Dakota."   He adds, "the Governor's message seems to say that since wind electricity would be cheaper to buy from other states that he would prefer that wind energy development takes place outside of Minnesota."<P>

  



