<HEAD><TITLE>Closed-loop Biomass Redefined-HF 2419,SF 2238</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H1>Closed-loop Biomass Redefined-HF 2419,SF 2238</H1>
<H3>January 15, 1997</H3>
For those of you who are still looking at this page, the 1997 Minnesota legislative session began on January 7.  To keep track of 1997 energy initiatives follow this link to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/leg/legwatch97.html">Sustainable Minnesota's 1997 Legislative Watch</A>. 
<H3>April 4, 1996</H3>
The law requiring Northern States Power (NSP) to acquire 125 MW of electricity using biomass was revised this session (HF 2419).  The bill allows project developers to use biomass feedstocks that are not "farm-grown closed-loop" for as many as six years after the plant is operational.  This means that the power plants would not have to be primarily fueled by new plant matter grown for this purpose until 2008.  The interim and final feedstock, however, must be grown within 400 miles of the generating facility to recieve the full six year exemption.  A three year exemption is given to biomass feedstocks that are grown more than 400 miles from the power plant.<P>



The bill requires that to satisfy the legislative mandate, the power plant must use biomass for at least 75 percent of its fuel requirements.  Thus co-firing, a process by which 2-10 percent biomass is mixed with coal in coal-fired power plants would not be eligible.  The bill also allows fossil fuels to be used to generate as much as 25 percent of the power from the biomass power plant.  <P>


The legislature changed the definition of  "farm-grown closed-loop biomass". It is now defined as herbaceous crops, trees, agricultural waste, and aquatic plant matter, excluding mixed municipal solid waste that is: <BR>

1) intentionally cultivated, harvested, and prepared for use, in whole or in part, as a fuel for the generation of eletricity;<BR>

2)  when combusted, releases an amount of CO2 that is less than or approximately equal to the carbon dioxide absorbed by the biomass fuel during its growing cycle; and<BR>

3) is fired in a new or retrofitted power plant that is located within 400 miles of the biomass production and is designed to use biomass to meet 75% of its fuel requirement.<P>
<H3>April1, 1996</H3>
The biomass bill passed the Joint Conference Committee and will now be presented to the governor for approval.

<P></P> 
<H3>February 6, 1996</H3>
A bill has been introduced that would redefine the term "farm grown closed-loop biomass" with respect to the biomass energy mandate requiring Northern States Power Company to acquire 125 MW of biomass fueled electricity.<P>








