<html><head><title>Koch Refinery Bill - 1996 SF 1147,HF 637</title></head><body><H1>Koch Refinery Bill - SF 1147,HF 637</H1>
<H3>January 15, 1997</H3>
For those of you who are still looking at this page, the 1997 Minnesota legislative session began on January 7.  To keep track of 1997 energy initiatives follow this link to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/leg/legwatch97.html">Sustainable Minnesota's 1997 Legislative Watch</A>. 

<H3>April 25, 1996</H3>
Here is a summary of this bill from the latest issue of <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/newsletters/me3spr96.html">Sustainable Minnesota</A>.<P>

<B>Big Oil vs. Big Energy - Legislature Passes Sliding-Scale Tax for Power Plants</B><p>

  The "Koch Bill" introduces a sliding-scale property tax exemption for electric generating facilities that is based on the efficiency of the power plant. In the final days of the session, Department of Public Service Commissioner Kris Sanda helped to persuade NSP and Koch to reach an agreement. NSP was concerned that the bill could lead to the loss of a major industrial customer and to the sale of Koch's electricity on the open market. The NSP/Koch agreement gives NSP the option of purchasing Koch's power. The likely result is that Koch will build a larger power plant than its originally proposed 250 MW. The agreement also requires NSP to negotiate a lower electric rate for Koch for the period prior to the construction of the plant.  One advantage, from an environmental perspective is that Koch will build the cogeneration plant in response to a utiliity's growing need for power rather than creating excess capacity in the region.  This will reinforce rather than undermine the resource planning process in Minnesota.<p>

  The new law (Minnesota Statutes 1996 [[section]]272.0211) revamps the current system of property taxes on new and existing electric power plants, aside from wind-energy facilities. A power plant earns a five-percent reduction in market value for each percentage point of efficiency above 35 percent. Plants with efficiencies of 55 percent or greater receive a 100 percent personal property tax exemption. Currently only one power plant, NSP's King plant in Bayport, MN (a cogeneration facility), operates above 35 percent and therefore qualifies for a modest market-value reduction.<p>

  ME3 was concerned that Koch would sell its power through a wholesale utility to an industrial customer in Minnesota Power's territory, thereby forcing MP to raise its rates to its remaining customers and also opening up the possibility of widespread retail wheeling in Minnesota. ME3 was successful in persuading legislators to attach amendments to the  bill that require Koch to sell power only to utilities that have a demonstrated need for power. In NSP's most recent 15-year Resource Plan, the utility predicts that it will issue a request for bids to supply base-load power in 1996 for up to 600 MW. The power will come on-line in 2005.<p>

  ME3 supports that the legislature providing additional incentives for high efficiency cogeneration power plants, although the coalition opposed providing a 100% property tax break, enabling fossi- fueled cogeneration plants to be taxed at a lower rate than wind energy.<p>

  Contact: <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:billgrant@igc.apc.org">Bill Grant</A>, Izaak Walton League, 612-922-1608<p>
<H3>April 4, 1996</H3>
The "Koch Bill" introduces a sliding-scale property tax exemption for electric generating facilities based on the efficiency of the power plant.  In the final days of the session NSP and Koch reached an agreement.   NSP was concerned that the bill could lead to the loss of a major industrial customer and the sale of Koch's electricity on the open market.  The NSP/Koch agreement gives NSP the option of purchasing Koch's power.  The likely result is that Koch will build a larger power plant than its originally proposed 250 MW.  The agreement also requires NSP to negotiate a lower electric rate for Koch.<P>



The new law (Minnesota Statutes 1996  272.0211) revamps the current system of property taxes on new and existing electric power plants, aside from wind energy facilities.  A power plant earns a five percent reduction in market value for each percentage point its efficiency is above 35 percent.  Plants with efficiencies of 55 percent or greater receive a 100 percent personal property tax exemption.  Currently only one power plant, NSP's King plant in Bayport, MN (a cogeneration facility), operates above 35 percent and therefore qualifies for a modest market value reduction.<P>



ME3 was concerned that Koch would sell its power  through a wholesale utility to an industrial customer in Minnesota Power's territory, thereby forcing MP to raise its rates to its remaining customers and also opening up the possibility of widespread retail wheeling in Minnesota.  ME3 was successful in persuading legislators to attach amendments to the final bill that requires Koch to sell power only to utilities that have a demonstrated need for power.  In NSP's most recent 15-year Resource Plan, the utility predicts that it will issue a request for bids to supply base-load power in 1996 for up to 600 MW.  The power will come on-line in 2005.<P>




Contact:  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://billgrant@igc.apc.org/">Bill Grant</A>, Izaak Walton League, 612-922-1608<P>
<H3>March 28, 1996</H3>
Both the House and the Senate have passed the Koch Refinery Bill, which eliminates the personal property tax levied against the equipment and machinery of highly efficient power plants.  Despite NSP's initial opposition to this proposed tax break,
Koch Refining Co. and NSP have reached an agreement by which NSP has the option to buy most of the electricity to be produced by Koch's proposed co-generation facility.  


<H3>February 6, 1996</H3>	A bill has been  introduced that  allows for a market
value exclusion for electric power generation facilities based on facility
efficiency.     Although the bill is designed to encourage the construction of
the facility proposed by the Koch Refinery, at least two other generating
plants could benefit from the property tax exemption.  <P>

<P>






