<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --></head><body><p>
<B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE			  	FEBRUARY 1, 1996</B><p>
<p> <title> Prairie Island Press Release February 1, 1996 </title> 
<p>
<sup>ENERGY COALITION SUPPORTS PRAIRIE ISLAND INDIAN COMMUNITY,</sup><p>
<sup>SUPPORTS ELIMINATION OF ALTERNATIVE WASTE SITING PROCESS, </sup><p>
<sup>REJECTS ENDING THE ENERGY TRANSITION CENTRAL TO THE </sup><p>
<sup>1994 PRAIRIE ISLAND AGREEMENT.</sup><p>
<sup></sup><p>
<sup></sup><B>Contact</B>: <BR>
	Michael Noble, executive director: 612/225-1133; Pager
649-7262<BR>

				Steve Hoffman, board chair:  612/962-5723; 612/457-4904<p>
<p><!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR>

	St. Paul, MN--In response to proposed legislation regarding Prairie Island,
the coalition Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy (ME3) today adopted a
policy position that is win-win-win for the Prairie Island Community, Northern
States Power (NSP) and the citizens of Minnesota. ME3 concurs with the
Environmental Quality Board Task Force, the Tribal Council and NSP that there
is no suitable alternative site for nuclear waste in Goodhue County. The
alternative siting process should be either dropped altogether, or expanded to
a search throughout NSP's service territory in Minnesota and Wisconsin.<p>
<p>
	ME3 also agrees with the Tribal Council and NSP that the Prairie Island Indian
Community should be offered the option to relocate to protect the health and
safety of the community and should be suitably compensated for the loss of
their homelands.<p>
<p>
	However, to accomplish these worthy goals, NSP seeks to overturn the central
purpose of the 1994 legislation--the orderly transition to new sources of
energy based on renewable energy and efficiency. <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
	According to ME3 executive director Michael Noble, " We honor the right of the
Prairie Island Indian Community to control its destiny, and we must forge ahead
with a transition to a clean energy future for the health and economic vitality
of the whole State." To refocus the debate on this central principle, ME3
proposes that:<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag -->
<UL>
<LI> NSP should pay for purchase of 1750 acres of land for the Prairie Island
Community and an up-front payment of $2 million, as agreed. Additional annual
compensation to the Community agreed upon should be assured.<p>
<LI> The renewable energy development fund, slated for elimination under the
NSP/Tribal proposal, should be reorganized as an Energy Transition Trust Fund,
independent of the control of NSP.<p>
<LI> The annual payments to the Indian Community proposed in the agreement should
be made as the first commitment of the Trust Fund, rather than through special
tax breaks to NSP as proposed. <p>
<LI> The NSP "reracking" proposal to dramatically increase the total amount of
nuclear waste needing storage should be eliminated from the bill, so the State
of Minnesota retains control of future decisions affecting nuclear waste
storage in Minnesota.<p>
<LI> The alternative siting should be repealed, as agreed by the Prairie Island
Indian Community and NSP.
</UL><p>
<p>
	According to ME3 Board member George Crocker, "Reracking means stacking and
packing of nuclear waste. Why would Minnesota decide in 1996  to dramatically
expand the total amount of nuclear waste storage capacity? Such expansion
directly contradicts previous findings of the Department of Public Service, the
order of the Public Utilities Commission and the will of Minnesotans as
expressed by the 1994 State legislative action. This bill declares that
Minnesota has nothing to say about whether more waste is crammed into a pool
already brimming with irradiated spent fuel." <p>
<p>
<p>
	The ME3 coalition calls upon the legislature to pass a bill assisting the
Prairie Island Indian Community, compensating them through an Energy Transition
Trust Fund, reorganized from a Renewable Development Fund which NSP seeks to
eliminate. <p>
<p>
	There is no urgency for a decision on whether to expand storage capacity for
nuclear waste. According to NSP, there's plenty of storage capacity through
2002 or 2004. Such decision-making authority must be retained by the State,
where it now resides. The urgent decisions are compensation for the Prairie
Island Indian Community and the ending the alternative siting process. The
central core of the Prairie Island compromise must not be set aside:  the State
authorized continued operation of the plant through the early part of the next
century, and in exchange NSP would agressively develop renewables and other
alternatives. In the future, the State could revisit whether electricity from
other sources is more economic or more beneficial than from Prairie Island.<p>
<p>
<p><!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR>

<p>
<p>
<sup>Sustaining members of the ME3  Coalition: </sup><p>
<sup></sup><!-- List Tag -->
<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI>Center for Energy and Environment  <LI>Clean Water Fund and Clean Water
Action Alliance 

<LI>Institute for Local Self-Reliance<LI> Izaak Walton League of
America (Midwest Office) 
<LI>The Minnesota Project <LI>Minnesota Renewable Energy Society <LI> Minnesota Wind
Energy  Association <LI>North American Water Office <LI> Saint Paul Neighborhood
Energy Consortium Sustainable Resources Center <LI> Union of Concerned Scientists
<LI> University of St. Thomas Environmental Studies Program
</UL><p>
<p>
