<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>Testimony Prairie Island 2/6/96</title></head><body><b><H2>Where Do
We Go Now With the Prairie Island Legislation?</H2></b><p>
<p>
<p>
<H3>Testimony by  David Morris , Institute for Local Self-Reliance<p>
<p>
February 6, 1996</H3><p>
<p>
<p>
	Two years ago this legislature was engaged in a highly charged dispute about
the future of nuclear power in Minnesota.  After a long and divisive debate the
legislature worked out a compromise law that addressed three key concerns.
First, the need to protect the work force at Prairie Island and the communities
within Goodhue County from the significant economic disruption that would occur
if Prairie Island's nuclear reactors were abruptly shut down.  Second, the need
to accelerate the speed with which we harness homegrown renewable fuels to
generate electricity.  And third, the need to address the ethics of continuing
to generate radioactive wastes when neither we nor any other community appears
willing to become a permanent home for those wastes.<p>
<p>
	The final Prairie Island law allowed NSP to continue to operate its nuclear
reactors for 7-9 years by giving the utility the right to construct 17 dry
casks.  As an aside, I will note that at the time my organization argued that
the same objective could be achieved without requiring dry casks if NSP would
imitate other utilities and expand the storage capacity of its existing pools
(see ILSR Report, <i>The Costs and Benefits of Closing Prairie Island,
</i>November 1993).  Then NSP insisted that was not feasible.  Now it agrees it
is. <p>
<p>
	During the next 7-9 years,  NSP was required to aggressively seek another
community that would voluntarily be home to radioactive wastes.  And during
that time NSP was to dramatically accelerate its use of renewable electricity
sources and to aggressively investigate alternative sources of electricity to
nuclear power. <p>
<p>
	It was an worthy compromise.  But one group was left out:  the Prairie Island
Dakota Tribe.  They are back today because they believe they are owed
something.  I agree.  The tribe has gained little if anything from having been
the closest neighbors to the two nuclear reactors for over 20 years.  <p>
<p>
	The concerns of the tribe are easily met within the context of the original
Prairie Island legislation.  In that law NSP is required to invest $500,000 per
dry cask in a renewable energy fund, or $8.5 million for 17 casks, so long as
they remain on Prairie Island. That money was to be used both as a means to
accelerate renewable energy in Minnesota and also to act as a financial
incentive for NSP to move the dry casks off of Prairie Island. <p>
<p>
	This legislature could easily divert about $1 million per year from the $8.5
million generated from the dry cask payments and give it to the tribe as
compensation.  <p>
<p>
	The Prairie Island legislation also contains a requirement that NSP search for
an alternative site in Goodhue County for the radioactive wastes.  That search
has demonstrated, as if we needed further evidence, that no one wants to be a
neighbor, even a distant neighbor, to this type of facility.  I'm sure you will
not be surprised to discover that the citizens of New Mexico and Nevada feel
the same way as the citizens of Goodhue County.  <p>
<p>
	The results of the search for an alternative site reinforces the message that
if there are reasonable alternatives available we cannot in good conscience
continue to generate radioactive wastes while refusing to take responsibility
for them.<p>
<p>
	In brief, I support revising three elements in the original Prairie Island
agreement:  compensation to the tribe;  an end to the alternative siting
process; a more effective home for the renewable energy fund.<p>
<p>
	Unfortunately, there is a fourth change which this bill contains. It gives NSP
the right to continue to operate its nuclear reactor at Prairie Island until
the year 2014.  Enacting that provision would overturn the core of the Prairie
Island legislation because it would give legislative approval to the generation
of as much radioactive waste in the future as Prairie Island has generated in
the past.  <p>
<p>
	There is absolutely no reason for doing this at this time.  There is no
urgency.  NSP is not going to begin reracking for another 7 or so years.   <p>
<p>
	Twenty four months have passed since the Prairie Island law was enacted.
Nothing has happened to make us think that the federal government now is more
likely to take radioactive wastes off our hands.  Indeed, a national repository
has become such a tenuous idea that the head of the Minnesota Department of
Public Service now insists that we should no longer send money to Washington to
finance further explorations for a permanent radioactive waste repository.  <p>
<p>
	There has been no progress in finding communities willing and able to take
responsibility for our radioactive waste.  But there has been a great deal of
progress in identifying low cost replacement electricity for Prairie Island's
nuclear reactors.  <p>
<p>
	Indeed, the last two years have witnessed a remarkable ferment in the electric
utility industry, spurred in large part by the rise of low cost independent
power suppliers.  A number of us argued two years ago that the costs of closing
Prairie Island by around the year 2000 would be modest.  Two years later we
find that our cost projections were too high.   The most recent bid price for
wind electricity is about a third lower than NSP had predicted during the
Prairie Island debate.  And today we find ourselves flooded with new low cost
electric generation.  For example, we now have the prospect of a power plant at
the Koch Refinery which if fully built out would be about the sizes of one of
Prairie Island's nuclear reactors and will produce electricity cheaper than
Prairie Island does  <p>
<p>
	To sum up.  We should compensate the Dakota Tribe, the one clear loser in the
Prairie Island legislation.  That can easily be done by transferring money from
the $8.5 million annual payment to the renewable energy fund by NSP.  But there
is no justification for overturning the core of the Prairie Island legislation
and there is absolutely no urgency in giving NSP the right to expand its
radioactive waste storage capacity when they would not exercise that right
until the beginning of the next century.<p>
<p>
	Thank you.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p><!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR>

<p>
The Institute for Local Self-Reliance (ILSR) is a nonprofit research and
educational organization that provides technical assistance and information on
environmentally sound economic development strategies.  <p>
<p>
<b>Institute for Local Self-Reliance</b><p>
<b></b>	1313 5th Street SE, Suite 306	<BR>

	Minneapolis, MN  55414	<BR>

	Phone:  (612) 379-3815	<BR>

	Fax:  (612) 379-3920

<P></P>

	<p>

2425 18th Street NW<BR>

Washington, DC  20009<BR>

Phone:  (202) 232-4108<BR>

Fax:  (202) 332-0463<BR>


