<DOCNO>WT15-B07-114</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA007-000067-B027-38</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.me3.org:80/leg/amocobill.html 198.174.235.57 19970222010745 text/html 11605
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 01:08:03 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 11433
Last-modified: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 22:24:23 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --></head><body><title>Ethanol Testimony</title></head><body><b><H2>Oxygen Vs.
Benzene:  Do Minnesotans Need a Choice?</H2></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<B>Testimony by  David Morris , Institute for Local Self-Reliance</B><p>
<p>
<I>February 13, 1996</I><p>
<p>
	My name is David Morris.  I am Vice President of the 22 year-old Institute for
Local Self-Reliance, a non profit and unaffiliated research organization based
in Minneapolis.  I am the author of several technical and policy reports on
alternative fuels, with a special emphasis on oxygenated fuels.<p>
<p>
	I come before you to speak in opposition to Senate Bill 2040.  The current law
on oxygenated fuels was clearly fashioned to encourage the growth of a
homegrown and locally owned transportation fuels industry based on renewable
resources.  In that respect it has been highly successful.<p>
<p>
	But we should also remember that the existing law was fashioned to allow
motorists a choice of fuel additives.  When the law was designed some wanted to
set the oxygen content level at 3.5 percent.  Since ethanol contains more
oxygen than MTBE, the other leading oxygenate which, by the way, has
consistently captured almost two thirds of the oxygenate market on a national
basis, a 3.5 percent oxygen mandate would, in effect, have become an ethanol
mandate.  Instead the legislature enacted a 2.7 percent oxygen standard.  That
standard can be met by using ethanol or MTBE or several other oxygenates.<p>
<p>
	The current law is an oxygen mandate.  It is not an ethanol mandate.  Ethanol
is the oxygenate of choice in Minnesota.  But gas stations can offer petroleum
and natural gas derived oxygenates.  And given sufficient customer demand, they
undoubtedly will.<p>
<p>
	We should also keep in mind that oxygenate mandates have been in place for
several years as a result of federal as well as state mandates.  Beginning in
October 1992 the Clean Air Act required oxygen levels of 2.7 percent in
gasoline sold during the winter months in 44 metropolitan areas.  More than 40
million people are living in these metropolitan areas, including more than 2
million in the Twin Cities area.<p>
<p>
	Beginning in January of 1995 more than 15 million motorists in nine major
urban areas have been using gasoline with 2.0 percent oxygen year round.  In
1995 almost two-thirds of all gasoline sold in Minnesota contained oxygen. <p>
<p>
	The bottom line is that we are several years into the age of oxygenated fuels.
We have hundreds of billions of miles of operating experience with these fuels
in a wide assortment of vehicles.  If there were significant problems we would
have seen empirical evidence of it.  I assure you the automobile and oil and
snowmobile companies would not have kept such data a secret.  Yet to date I
have seen no such studies.<p>
<p>
	Which is not to say there is no longer any fear out there of oxygenated fuels.
Americans love our cars and our snowmobiles and our motorcycles.  And although
they are remarkably reliable, we all have our personal stories of how they have
exhibited mysterious symptoms that neither we nor our mechanics have been able
to quite figure out.  Since the early 1980s gasoline formulations have changed
dramatically as have fuel injection and handling systems. This has increased
the number of times our vehicles have acted strangely.  <p>
<p>
	By their own admission, since last August  proponents of this bill have been
engaged in a statewide publicity campaign that plays on these fears.  Through
radio ads and toll free phone numbers, they aggressively encouraged Minnesotans
to express their fears.  It should not be surprising that many of us have
enthusiastically responded to that request.  Even though the opponents of
oxygenated fuels have come up with no empirical evidence that supports their
claim that it harms engines, there is no question that they have sparked
widespread grassroots concerns.  Indeed, at this point it appears that those
supporting oxygenated fuels are shouldering the burden of proof about their
safety and effectiveness.  And as members of this Committee know, it is very,
very difficult to prove a negative.  <p>
<p>
	Let me offer you an instructive story on this subject.  Back in the mid 1980s,
alcohol blended fuels were under attack.  After "No Alcohol" signs popped up on
gas stations, motorists assumed that any time their car coughed it was because
it had ethanol in the fuel tank.  Chevron, a major ethanol marketer in Kentucky
decided to investigate the issue.  It evaluated over 150 complaints attributed
to ethanol blends and could not find a single one that could be traced to the
use of ethanol.  Nevertheless, bowing to the widespread fear, Chevron stopped
marketing ethanol and began distributing "No Alcohol" signs to its customers.
<p>
<p>
	Proponents of overturning the current oxygenate mandate argue that all they
want is a choice.  Consumer choice has become the motherhood and apple pie word
of the 1990s.  I know that members of this Committee have received a pamphlet
that cites environmental organizations in apparent support of this bill.
They're not.  I am not aware of any environmental organization that opposes the
use of oxygen in fuels.<p>
<p>
	What shall we make of the issue of choice?  As you know, we don't give
motorists the choice of leaded gasoline.  We phased out lead because it is a
public health hazard.  By the way, back in 1985, when the federal government
was phasing out the use of lead in gasoline, Amoco surveyed leaded gasoline
buyers and found that nearly 40 percent of them feared using unleaded gasoline
would harm their cars. Amoco told the National Petroleum News that it would
respond to those fears by continuing to produce and market a leaded gasoline
"for as long as there is a demand for the product."<p>
<p>
	The Ethyl Corp., a manufacturer of lead antiknock additives, claimed that
almost 1.2-million cars and trucks would experience unleaded-related engine
damage and break down prematurely. <p>
	<p>
	Those fears didn't materialize then.  And the fears of those concerned about
using oxygen containing fuels haven't materialized in the last few years and
won't in the future. <p>
<p>
	Proponents of this bill are not asking for the right to choose a gasoline
without ethanol.  We already have that right.  They are asking for the right to
choose a gasoline that doesn't contain oxygen.  When an oxygenate like ethanol
is blended into gasoline, it displaces 6-10 percent of the gasoline.  Gasoline
is not a single chemical.  It is a chemical stew composed of hundreds of
different chemicals.  To boost octane levels oil refineries increase the
proportion of aromatics, like benzene and toluene.  These are the nastiest of
all chemicals in gasoline.  They are highly toxic and known carcinogens.  <p>
<p>
	Benzene can constitute 2-4 percent of premium gasoline.  The Clean Air Act
requires that in ozone non attainment areas, reformulated gasoline that
contains a maximum of 1 percent benzene be sold.  But no part of Minnesota is
under this mandate.  <p>
<p>
	Therefore it may be accurate to say that  proponents of this bill are asking
for the right to choose benzene and toluene over oxygen.  Should motorists be
given that right?  <p>
<p>
	I think that depends on the environmental and economic impact that would
result.  Let me speak to the economic impact.  Ethanol plants today offer a
significant boost to rural and the state economies.  They generate two to four
times the number of jobs per million gallons produced than oil refineries.
They are small in size and therefore lend themselves to local and cooperative
ownership.  Indeed, over 90 percent of Minnesota's ethanol is produced by
cooperatives owned by over 6,000 farm families.  About a quarter of a billion
dollars has been invested in ethanol plants to date, with $60-100 million of
that coming from the farmer owners themselves.  <p>
<p>
	Proponents argue that enactment of this bill would have very little impact on
ethanol sales because sales of premium gasoline constitute only about 10
percent of total gasoline sales in Minnesota and the ethanol industry doesn't
have the capacity even now to meet the state demand for oxygenates.<p>
<p>
	Yet the Minnesota's ethanol industry is growing.  Minnesota's six ethanol
plants produce about 65 million gallons today.  By the summer they could
produce over 100 million gallons.  Within two years, given the current number
of plants proposed, Minnesota could meet virtually all of its oxygenated fuel
demand from in-state plants.<p>
<p>
	But what could happen if this bill is passed?  According to business
magazines, about 50 percent of Amoco's earnings come from the sale of premium
gasoline, the highest proportion of any oil company.  Profits on premium
gasoline are in the 4-8 cents per gallon range, versus a fraction of a penny
for regular gasoline.  Amoco is also recognized as one of the most aggressive
marketers of premium gasoline.  <p>
<p>
	We can fully expect that Amoco and other oil companies will undertake a
massive marketing campaign to get motorists to fill up at their most profitable
pumps.  The central message of that marketing campaign, as has been the central
message of the marketing campaign these past six months, will be that ethanol
is bad for your engines.<p>
<p>
	We've been here before.  Back in 1985 and 1986,  "Contains No Alcohol" signs
sprouted up on gas stations throughout Minnesota.  Terrified motorists assumed
that alcohol harmed their engines.  Within 12 months the sales of ethanol
dropped in half.  This was not only the case in Minnesota.  In Florida they
dropped by 60 percent in 90 days.  In Alabama sales shrank from 20 percent to 5
percent of the market.  <p>
<p>
	It is truly remarkable that ethanol should be on the defensive.  Ethanol is,
in effect vodka.  The only reason you can't drink it is that federal law
requires producers to poison it with petroleum derivatives before blending it
with gasoline.  Maybe they do so because the liquor stores don't want you to
wonder why you can buy vodka at only $1.20 a gallon at the gas pump.<p>
<p>
	This legislature has embraced a formal policy of encouraging the use of
homegrown renewable resources.  Even if ethanol constituted 100 percent of the
oxygenates used under the state mandate, this renewable, environmentally benign
and drinkable fuel would capture only 6-10 percent of the automobile
transportation fuel market in Minnesota.  That seems a very, very modest
proportion.   <p>
<p>
	To sum up.  The existing law offers gas stations in Minnesota the option of
using a variety of oxygenates.  There is no empirical evidence that oxygenates
are harmful to engines.  Ethanol is an environmentally benign and homegrown
fuel that has been a boon to both the environment and the economy.  Enactment
of this law would make it possible and indeed highly profitable for oil
companies to engage in a massive anti-ethanol marketing campaign for their
premium fuels that, based on previous experience here and elsewhere, could not
only stop any further growth of an in-state vehicle fuel industry but seriously
erode existing markets.  <p>
<p>
Thank you.<p>
<p>
<p>
Institute for Local Self-Reliance<BR>

1313 Fifth Street SE, Suite 306<BR>

Minneapolis, MN  55414<BR>

Tel:  612-379-3815<BR>

Fax:  612-379-3920<p>
</body></html>
