<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Will Minnesota Farmers Benefit from Wind Power?
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY> 

<H3>Will Minnesota Farmers Benefit from Wind Power?</H3>
<H4>by John Bailey, Institute for Local Self-Reliance</H4>
<H5>August 1994</H5>

The strong winds blowing across western Minnesota have become a hot and very marketable commodity.  The Legislature made it so by guaranteeing a market for the electrical output of more than 1300 large wind turbines.<P>   

The stampede is on.    Speculators, utilities and wind companies are going door-to-door buying up wind rights from mostly uninformed and inexperienced landowners.  Hundreds of wind rights contracts are already on file at the Lincoln County Courthouse.  Wind developers may have purchased the rights to more than 85 percent of the land needed to supply Northern States Power Company (NSP) with its next 100 MW of power.  In the next 6-24 months most of the good wind sites in Minnesota will be under contract. <P>  

Minnesota farmers must quickly learn the new math of windpower.   Or they will end up like their brethren in Texas, West Virginia and Kentucky did at the dawn of the coal and oil era.  Then coal and oil companies paid rural landowners a price based on the value of the land.  Only later did farmers realize they should have demanded a price based on the value of their sub-soil wealth.  At the dawn of the renewable energy era Minnesotans need to learn that the value of their above-soil wealth is the crucial factor.  <P>

In the future, landowners with prime wind resources could generate a significant portion of their income from wind rights.  But, as is almost always the case, the pioneers may benefit the least.  At its Lake Benton 25 MW wind farm, NSP paid the owners of 2800 acres of land a lump sum in return for a "perpetual easement".  In return for a single payment farmers sold NSP the right to harness the wind over their property forever. <P>  

Lump sum payments attract farmers because they receive a significant sum of money, sometimes in the low six figures, up front.   But such contracts, in the long run, are almost always unattractive.   For one thing, the farmer has lowered the market value of the property.  Around 3-5 percent of his or her acreage is now assigned to another party.  On the other hand, if the farmer were to receive a royalty payment from the wind turbine it would significantly increase the value of the property because future landowners could still use 95-97 percent of the land and receive a significant annual wind rights payment. <P>
 
Indeed, these "in perpetuity" contracts may be unconstitutional.  Article 1, section 15 of the Minnesota Constitution declares, "Leases and grants of agricultural land for a longer period than twenty-one years hereafter made, in which shall be reserved for any rent or service of any kind, shall be void."<P>

The basic economics of wind power are simple.   A 330 kW turbine, typical of those being placed in operation, will generate about $40,000 a year in gross operating revenue if the wind company is paid 5 cents per kWh, about $32,000 a year if the utility pays 4 cents per kWh.  Wind turbines are spaced about one every 10-20 acres.  <P>

NSP's lump sum contracts pay landowners less than 2 percent of gross operating revenues over 25 years.  Some Minnesotans will receive 4-6 percent of gross revenues.  Contracts as high as 8 percent of gross revenues have reportedly been negotiated in other states.  The difference between 2 percent and 8 percent is the difference between $800 and $3200 per year per turbine or $40 and $160 per acre per year.  <P>

Of course wind companies can't pay exorbitant rates to landowners.  They need to make a profit too.  Right now negotiations between farmer and wind developer seem decidedly one sided.  Wind contracts, as with any contracts, are complex.  They come in many forms.  Some developers pay per turbine, others per acre, others as a percentage of gross and still others on a kWh produced basis.  There is often a modest up front payment for monitoring the wind speed and for an option to lease, and then a payment until the turbines are installed and then an increasing percentage payment of gross revenues. <P> 

There are contractual elements aside from money that are important.   For example, according to California based Randall Tinkerman, a consultant to landowners, a key provision should allow landowners to have access to complete wind data and to know precisely how much electricity has been generated from machines on his or her property.   <P>

Minnesotans decided earlier this year to guarantee wind developers a fair price for their electricity.  Now we need to make sure that Minnesota farmers receive a fair price as well.  This cannot be done by legislative mandate.  It can only be done through individual or collective negotiation. <P>
<HR>
