</DOCHDR>
<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>Speech: The Wind
Electric Industry and Economic Development</title></head>

<body><b>The Wind
Electric Industry and Economic Development</b><p>
David Morris, Institute for Local Self-Reliance<p>
<p>
<HR>
<I>The Wind Electric Industry and Economic Development</I> was originally delivered at the 1994 annual conference of the American Wind Energy Association on May 10, 1994.<p>
<p>
<HR>
	The development of the wind industry is an excellent example of how citizens
and industry working together can change our energy future.  Citizen activists
changed the rules that govern our electricity sector and the private sector
responded by channeling investment capital, scientific knowhow and
entrepreneurial energy into creating technologies that took advantage of those
changed rules.  <p>
<p>
	In 1978 the U.S. Congress abolished the century old monopoly that utilities
had over the production of electricity. That made independent power production
possible.  A few years later Congress and several states like California
enacted favorable tax incentives for renewable energy.  California then
established long term purchase contracts for wind power at rates very
attractive to investors.    <p>
<p>
	In response to these favorable public initiatives, individuals and businesses
invested over $1.5 billion in wind electricity, reducing the cost of wind power
by some 80 percent between 1982 and 1992.   Wind power is now viewed as a
reliable technology.  With the 1.5 cent per kWh production incentive under the
Energy Policy Act of 1992, wind power may be competitive in high wind regime
areas with new power plants.   Technological advances may well reduce the cost
of wind electricity even more.<p>
<p>
	Meanwhile citizens continue to assist the wind industry by changing the rules.
 A few months ago Minnesota became the eighth state to quantify the
environmental costs of electric generation.  This was done as a result of
legislation.  In February the Public Utility Commission established interim
estimates for these environmental costs.  Currently Minnesota is about to
undertake an extensive contested case hearing to determine final values.   If
the final values mirror the interim values, wind generated electricity might be
given a half a cent per kilowatt hour "bonus" when compared to coal fired power
plants.<p>
<p>
	Last week the citizens of Minnesota gained an historic victory by enacting
legislation that mandates the state's largest utility,  Northern States Power,
expand its previous commitment to renewable electricity by almost 500 percent.
By 1998 Minnesota will have more than 225 MWe of wind generated power and by
2002 this will rise to 425 MWe.   <p>
<p>
	As this conference convenes,  the wind industry is moving into its third stage
of development.  No longer fragile and embryonic, wind power is increasingly
the basis for a large national and international industry.  Currently wind
developers are negotiating for more than $1.5 billion in contracts.   The
industry has achieved its take off stage.  And it has done so by selling itself
to citizens on the basis of environmental protection and economic development.
The claim to environmental benefits is probably safe from dispute, although as
the industry knows,  questions about the impact of large turbines on birds and
about the aesthetics of closely packed wind turbine farms, are still
unanswered.  <p>
<p>
	Assuming the environmental concerns are allayed, the most important issue
affecting the wind electric industry is its impact on local and regional
economies.  Is wind power truly an economic development vehicle?<p>
<p>
	As I've said, Minnesota now has a law that guarantees to wind developers a 425
MW market by the year 2002.  The citizens of Minnesota have guaranteed a profit
for investments of about $400 million.  Yet today wind turbines are exempt from
property taxes.  Let's assume that the industry continues to press for this
exemption and that localities therefore gain no revenue from the hundreds or
thousands of wind generators within their jurisdictions.  Let us further
suppose that the wind industry drives very tough bargains with uninformed
landowners regarding land leases.  Landowners receive only 1-2 percent of the
revenue generated by the wind turbine rather than the 4-8 percent that may be
possible.  And let us further assume that Minnesota attracts no assembly or
manufacturing jobs.  The only jobs are for the erection of the wind turbines
and maintaining the wind farms.  And finally, let us assume that one company
comes to dominate the wind electric market.  <p>
<p>
	If all of these things come to pass I predict that the enthusiasm for wind
power in Minnesota will wane.  The citizen constituency that has worked so hard
to change the rules to enable large scale introduction of wind electricity will
no longer be available.   Which isn't to say that people will prefer coal or
natural gas or nuclear to wind but they will no longer be willing to change the
rules to favor wind power.<p>
<p>
	 The wind industry must work to develop strategies that make good on its
promise of economic development.   And it should reach out behind wind to the
renewable energy constituencies that are building in the Great Plains states.
Unlike other parts of the country, here wind turbines can be placed relatively
far apart and most will be on agricultural lands.  Not only should wind
developers develop friendly contracts with land owners but they should develop
contacts with agricultural organizations that also are moving into renewable
energy production.<p>
<p>
	For farmers, ethanol is the first major energy crop, but biodiesel made from
vegetables oils is entering the market while biomass electricity is gearing up.
 Biomass energy doesn't compete with wind energy.  Indeed one might argue that
there is a good fit.  Biodiesel or biomass electricity provides the backup or
base load for wind electricity.    <p>
<p>
	In Minnesota, where we have the highest winds, we also have the largest amount
of corn being converted into ethanol, a liquid transportation fuel.  This
session of the legislature also passed an incentive to encourage ethanol plants
to generate electricity by burning plant matter.  And the renewable electricity
mandate enacted this session that requires 425 MW of wind electricity also
requires 125 MW of biomass fueled electricity.<p>
<p>
	Thus we need to integrate together wind and liquid, gaseous and solid biomass
fuels.  <p>
	The wind industry will continue to lobby for its own interests and that is
both inevitable and welcome.  But it might consider also supporting some
initiatives that cut across renewable resource lines. Currently the EPA is
proposing a 30 percent renewable oxygenate standard.  That standard will
require that 30 percent of the oxygenate additives to gasoline in many urban
areas will have to be derived from plant matter.  The oil industry considers
this an ethanol mandate but the wind industry might consider it the first
federal renewable standard.  Never before has the federal government ever
required that any percentage of our fuels or electricity or products be derived
from renewable resources.<p>
<p>
	Why not require that 30 percent of the fleet vehicles that are converted to
alternative fuels be converted to renewable fuels.  This would not only mean
ethanol cars but electric cars if the electricity is generated from wind or
biomass.  Why not lobby the federal government to adopt a 30 percent renewable
standard for any additional electricity generated or purchased by federal power
agencies?  This session the Minnesota legislature, in effect,  adopted such a
standard.  Thirty percent of the increased electric demand projected by NSP to
the year 2002 must be met by renewable energy.    <p>
<p>
	Wind energy has a bright future in Minnesota and the Great Plains.  The wind
industry would do well to begin to make real its promises of linking
environmental and economic development benefits.  It needs to begin to work in
concert with rural development officials and agricultural organizations, to tie
together wind and plant matter, the two primary resources of the Great
Plains.<p>
<HR>
Return to the <a href="http://www.me3.org/">Sustainable Minnesota Home Page</a>
</body></html>
