<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version 2.7.5 --><title>Sustainable Minnesota-Spring 1996</title></head><body><H2>Sustainable Minnesota Spring 1996, Vol. 6, No. 2</H2><p>

  <p>

  <p>

  <b><H3>I.  1996 Legislative Wrap-Up</H3></b><p>

  <b></b>The short legislative session of 1996 has ended and although ethics violations, school vouchers, and the new Twins stadium received a lot of attention, energy issues were in the spotlight once again this year. Here is a brief overview of what did and didn't happen with energy legislation this year.<p>

  <B>Big Oil vs. Big Energy - Legislature Passes Sliding-Scale Tax for Power Plants</B><p>

  The "Koch Bill" introduces a sliding-scale property tax exemption for electric generating facilities that is based on the efficiency of the power plant. In the final days of the session, Department of Public Service Commissioner Kris Sanda helped to persuade NSP and Koch to reach an agreement. NSP was concerned that the bill could lead to the loss of a major industrial customer and to the sale of Koch's electricity on the open market. The NSP/Koch agreement gives NSP the option of purchasing Koch's power. The likely result is that Koch will build a larger power plant than its originally proposed 250 MW. The agreement also requires NSP to negotiate a lower electric rate for Koch for the period prior to the construction of the plant.  One advantage, from an environmental perspective is that Koch will build the cogeneration plant in response to a utiliity's growing need for power rather than creating excess capacity in the region.  This will reinforce rather than undermine the resource planning process in Minnesota.<p>

  The new law (Minnesota Statutes 1996 [[section]]272.0211) revamps the current system of property taxes on new and existing electric power plants, aside from wind-energy facilities. A power plant earns a five-percent reduction in market value for each percentage point of efficiency above 35 percent. Plants with efficiencies of 55 percent or greater receive a 100 percent personal property tax exemption. Currently only one power plant, NSP's King plant in Bayport, MN (a cogeneration facility), operates above 35 percent and therefore qualifies for a modest market-value reduction.<p>

  ME3 was concerned that Koch would sell its power through a wholesale utility to an industrial customer in Minnesota Power's territory, thereby forcing MP to raise its rates to its remaining customers and also opening up the possibility of widespread retail wheeling in Minnesota. ME3 was successful in persuading legislators to attach amendments to the  bill that require Koch to sell power only to utilities that have a demonstrated need for power. In NSP's most recent 15-year Resource Plan, the utility predicts that it will issue a request for bids to supply base-load power in 1996 for up to 600 MW. The power will come on-line in 2005.<p>

  ME3 supports that the legislature providing additional incentives for high efficiency cogeneration power plants, although the coalition opposed providing a 100% property tax break, enabling fossi- fueled cogeneration plants to be taxed at a lower rate than wind energy.<p>

  Contact: <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:billgrant@igc.apc.org">Bill Grant</A>, Izaak Walton League, 612-922-1608<p>

  <B>Prairie Island Nuclear Waste Storage</B><p>

  To say the bill related to the Prairie Island nuclear plant was on-again off-again would be an understatement. It seemed that every few days of the session brought a new proposal. In the end no deal could be reached. The sticking point throughout was compensation for the Prairie Island Tribe, including land and money. NSP initially tried to tie any compensation to expanded radioactive waste storage at the plant, but that proposal lost in the first few weeks of the session. <p>

  ME3 supported financial compensation for the Tribe. ME3's proposal was to pay the Tribe from the renewable energy development account. The account was set up as part of the original legislation in 1994 . It requires NSP to invest $500,000 per year for each dry cask that remains on Prairie Island beyond January 1, 1999. At the full allotment of 17 casks given to NSP, payments to the fund would amount to $8.5 million per year. ME3 proposed that the first $8 million accrued would go to the tribe in addition to the $2 million pledge from NSP.  One legislative proposal would have paid the Tribe from general appropriations. That proposal was defeated. The ME3 proposal was the focus of a final effort in the last days to pass a bill.  We're convinced that since the proposal would not have required any new money, it would have passed if it had been brought to a vote.<p>

  A catalyst for the NSP/Tribe proposal was the legislative requirement for NSP to search for an alternative site in Goodhue County for the dry casks. Most of the proposals put forward would have eliminated the alternative siting process. In January 1996 the EQB's Site Advisory Task force issued its report to the EQB which stated that there are "no additional sites in Goodhue County that should be considered further by the EQB." At the EQB's hearing in March the Board tabled a resolution that, if adopted, would have suspended the alternative- siting process. The Board chose to wait for the end of the legislative session in case the resolution became unnecessary. Since legislation related to Prairie Island did not pass, the EQB is expected to pass the resolution at an upcoming meeting.<p>

  Contact: John Hynes, EQB Public Advisor, 612-296-2871 or 1-800-657-3794<p>

  <p>

   <B>Oxygenated Fuel Exemption</B> <p>

  State law requires all gasoline sold in the Twin Cities area to contain oxygen year round and all gasoline sold in the state of Minnesota to contain oxygen after January 1997. A bill carried by Rep. Alice Johnson on behalf of Amoco and a coalition of snowmobile, boat and classic car owners, was vigorously debated during the session. The street rodders insisted that gasoline with oxygen could harm their vehicles, although no empirical evidence was introduced in the session. Environmentalists were concerned about the possibility that Minnesota could become the first state to promote the idea that oxygenated fuels are harmful to vehicles. The federal Clean Air Act requires oxygenated fuels to be used year round in many urban areas.<p>

  Ethanol supporters also were concerned that the proposed legislation in effect would encourage industry to substitute highly toxic chemicals like benzene and xylene for a renewable and environmentally benign fuel like ethanol.<p>

  The final law represented a  compromise. Gas stations will be allowed to sell non-oxygenated fuels from one pump. This gas is only to be sold to owners of classic cars and other recreational vehicles. Marinas can also dispense non-oxygenated fuels. Initial versions of the bill would have given an exemption for an entire grade of premium gasoline that could be dispensed by several pumps.<p>

  One irony of the law is that it allows the most energy-inefficient and polluting engines to burn the dirtiest fuel.<p>

  What happens now depends in part on whether gas station owners install non-oxygenated fuel tanks and whether there is a large demand for this fuel. Although the year-round mandate for oxygenated fuels has been in effect in the Twin Cities for almost 9 months, it does not go into effect in rural areas until 1997. Thus it is possible that the issue will be revisited in the next legislative session.<p>

  Contact: <A HREF="MAILTO:dmorris@ilsr.org">David Morris</A>, ILSR, 612-379-3815<p>

    <B>Economic Efficiency and  Pollution Reduction Act of 1996</B><p>

  The legislative initiative for a $1.5 billion tax shift, the <a href="http://www.me3.org/leg/EEPRA96.html">Economic Efficiency and Pollution Reduction Act of 1996 (HF 3063)</A>, was heard in both the Senate and the House tax committees. The bill appears to have support among tax committee members in both houses. Over the summer and fall, ME3 will initiate an educational campaign and develop further economic analysis and case studies on the issue. <p>

  The Minnesota initiative has received national and international attention. The Sustainable Minnesota web site has become a vehicle for information exchange. Materials and updates are available on the web at <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/greentax/">http://www.me3.org/projects/greentax</A><p>

  Contact: <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:bailey@ilsr.org">John Bailey</A>, ILSR, 612-379-3815<p>

  <p>

  <B>Biomass Power Mandate Sees  Significant Changes</B><p>

  The law requiring Northern States Power (NSP) to acquire 125 MW of electricity using biomass was revised this session (HF 2419). The bill allows project developers to use biomass feedstocks that are not "farm-grown closed-loop" for as many as six years after the plant is operational. This means that the power plants would not have to be primarily fueled by new plant matter grown for this purpose until 2008. The interim and final feedstock, however, must be grown within 400 miles of the generating facility to receive the full six-year exemption. A three-year exemption is given to biomass feedstocks that are grown more than 400 miles from the power plant.<p>

  The bill requires that to satisfy the legislative mandate, the power plant must use biomass for at least 75 percent of its fuel requirements. Thus co-firing, a process by which 2-10 percent biomass is mixed with coal in coal-fired power plants would not be eligible. The bill also allows fossil fuels to be used to generate as much as 25 percent of the power from the biomass power plant. Although passage of this bill did not change the dates for NSP to acquire biomass-fueled electricity it may have effects on future and existing bids to supply NSP with biomass electricity.<p>

  <p>

  The legislature changed the definition of  "farm-grown closed-loop biomass". It is now defined as herbaceous crops, trees, agricultural waste, and aquatic plant matter, excluding mixed municipal solid waste that: <p>

  <UL> <LI>is intentionally cultivated, harvested, and prepared for use, in whole or in part, as a fuel for the generation of eletricity;<p>

  <LI>when burned, releases an amount of CO2 that is less than or approximately equal to the carbon dioxide absorbed by the biomass fuel during its growing cycle; and<p>

  <LI>is fired in a new or retrofitted power plant that is located within 400 miles of the biomass production and is designed to use biomass to meet 75% of its fuel requirement.</UL><p>

  <p>

   <b><H3>II.  Renewables/Efficiency Update</H3></b> <B>LIHEAP - Federal Energy Assistance Program Gets Help From State</B><p>

  In 1984 Minnesota received $82.2 million in federal funds for energy assistance for low income households. About 139,000 customers were served. By 1995, Minnesota's federal funds plummeted to $34.3 million and only 105,000 households were served. From 1994 to 1995 alone LIHEAP funding decreased by almost 40 percent. A typical LIHEAP recipient in Minnesota has an annual income of $7,583 and receives about $420 in heating assistance. This year only $280 will be available per recipient. In Minnesota only about 40 percent of those households eligible for LIHEAP assistance actually apply for it. Reasons for this vary from not knowing about LIHEAP to an unwillingness of potential applicants to ask for assistance.<p>

  This year the U.S. House of Representatives voted to zero out funding of LIHEAP. As a result of a filibuster by Senator Paul Wellstone and a persistent political coalition of legislators from cold-weather states, the Senate passed a budget resolution to continue LIHEAP funding at 90 percent of the  previous year's funding levels. The House agreed and although the Federal government has yet to complete its budget, the money is beginning to flow into the states.<p>

  The Minnesota legislature agreed to make up a portion of the federal budget cutbacks. The Jobs, Energy and Community Develop-ment Omnibus Appropriations bill signed by the Governor (HF3243/ SF2852) contains a provision to allocate at least $1 million in additional funding for LIHEAP. As Pam Marshall of the low-income advocacy organization Energy CENTS says, "the consequences of doing nothing about cuts to LIHEAP are real and dangerous. This program is about protecting the health and safety of the lowest income Minnesotans."<p>

  Contact: Pam Marshall, Energy CENTS, 612-872-3293<p>

  <B>Biomass Bid Hits Brick Wall</B><p>

  The competitive bidding process to supply Northern States Power Company (NSP) with 50 MW of biomass-fueled electricity has come to a halt. NSP planned to announce the winning bid three months ago but the utility had concerns about the independent evaluator's recommendations and legislative initiatives that could affect the biomass mandate. Indeed, the 1996 legislature did change the provisions of the biomass mandate (HF2419).  One of the three finalists, Energy Performance Systems' Whole Tree Energy(TM) project was dropped from the shortlist after its financial partner, Kenetech, backed out. In recent months Kenetech has seen problems with their wind turbines, huge layoffs, plummeting stock prices, and a massive lawsuit by shareholders.<p>

  As for the two remaining projects, the evaluator reportedly considered the price offered by the Minnesota Valley Alfalfa Producers as too high and the proposal from the NRG /Linroc joint venture, Northstar Power, as being unable to satisfy the requirements of the biomass mandate. Northstar Power proposed to use wood chips from Mexico that would be transported up the Mississippi on otherwise empty barges. North-star sought to get a clarification on whether the project would satisfy the "closed-loop" language of the law but the Public Utilities Commission (PUC) declined to hear the motion.<p>

  Staff of the PUC, NSP, Department of Public Service, the Izaak Walton League and the Office of Attorney General have been meeting to determine how to proceed. NSP would like to reject the bids and either issue another request for bids or have the ability to negotiate directly with the bidders, including the proposal offered by Energy Performance Systems which has found a new financial partner.  <p>

  The PUC must give NSP approval to reject the bids but it is unclear whether the PUC has the authority to grant NSP permission to begin negotiating directly with potential suppliers. The mandate requires that NSP contract for 125 MW of biomass power by December 31, 1998; 50-MW to be operational by December 31, 2001, and an additional 75-MW by December 31, 2002. <p>

  Contact: Betsy Engelking, PUC, 612-296-1337<p>

  <B>Zond Wind Project Breaking Ground in May</B><p>

  NSP's 100 MW wind project known as Phase II, awarded to Zond Systems Inc., has begun site preparations for the wind turbines. Zond anticipates signing a formal contract with NSP by the end of April. Ken Hach of Zond's Lake Benton office predicts that initial construction will commence in late May or June.<p>

  The 143-turbine wind farm was expected to come on-line by the end of 1996 but ran into potential problems when Kenetech Windpower refused to relinquish wind rights within the approved site near Lake Benton, MN. NSP claimed that it had the right of eminent domain and could seize Kenetech's wind rights. But NSP has found itself in a court battle with Kenetech and the issue may not be settled until 1997. The court battle could prevent or delay Zond from installing about 55 percent of the turbines for the project.<p>

  Many of the components for Zond's 700-kW wind turbines will be manufactured in the Midwest and the blades and towers may come from Minnesota-based manufacturers. Zond has been having ongoing discussions with officials in southwestern Minnesota to site an assembly facility for the 700-kW, Z-46 turbines. If built, the assembly facility could employ from 15-20 full-time employees. Zond will need about 10 employees for ongoing operation and maintenance of the 100 MW wind farm.<p>

  Contact: Ken Hach, Zond, 507-368-9222<p>

  <B>Iowa Municipals Consider Jointly-Owned Wind Farm</B><p>

  The Iowa Municipal Utilities Association (IMUA) is working to remove legislative restrictions that limit the ability of cities to jointly finance electric generating facilities. The Iowa municipal utilities feel that the law puts them at a competitive disadvantage with investor-owned utilities (IOUs). <p>

  On the basis of interest from their members, IMUA has completed a feasibility study for a 15-20 turbine wind farm in northwest Iowa. Results will be used to attract municipal partners  to finance the $12 -$15 million project. Initial drafts of the study have shown that the cost of energy from the small-scale wind farm ranges from 3.5 - 5.0 cents per kWh (excluding federal renewable energy tax incentives).<p>

  Contact: Bob Haug, <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.imua.com/">IMUA</A>, 515-289-1999<p>

  <p>

  <p>

  <b><H3>III.  Regulatory Update</H3></b><p>

   <B>Environmental Externalities Decision: Summary and Reaction<p>

 </B> <p>

  The proceeding to quantify the environmental costs of electricity moved one step closer to completion when Administrative Law Judge Allan Klein issued his findings and recommendations on March 22. The table below provides a summary of the recommendations.<p>

   <B>Judge Klein's Proposed Range of Environmental Costs for Electricity Production</B><BR> (1993 dollars per ton)<p>

  <!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1> <TR><TD></TD><TD>Rural</TD><TD>Metropolitan Fringe</TD><TD>Urban</TD></TR> <TR><TD>Particulate Matter (PM10)</TD><TD>$530 - $806</TD><TD>$1873 - $2720</TD><TD>$4206 - $6054</TD></TR> <TR><TD>Nitrogen Oxides (NOx)</TD><TD>$17 - $96</TD><TD>$132 - $251</TD><TD>$350 - $922</TD></TR> <TR><TD>Lead (Pb)</TD><TD>$379 - $422</TD><TD>$1557 - $1881</TD><TD>$2951 - $3653</TD></TR> <TR><TD>Carbon Monoxide (CO)</TD><TD>$0.20 - $0.39</TD><TD>$0.72 - $1.26</TD><TD>$1.00 - $2.14</TD></TR> <TR><TD>Carbon Dioxide (CO2) (1995 $)</TD><TD>$0.28 - $2.92</TD><TD>$0.28 - $2.92</TD><TD>$0.28 - $2.92</TD></TR> <TR><TD>Sulfur Dioxide (SO2)</TD><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD></TD></TR> <TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>Before year 2000</TD><TD>$9 - $24</TD><TD>$43 - $104</TD><TD>$106 - $178</TD></TR> <TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>After year 2000 </TD><TD>$0</TD><TD>$0</TD><TD>$0</TD></TR> </TABLE> <p>

   Translated into cents per kWh, Klein' estimates an environmental cost on coal-fired electricity of about .04 - .40 cents and on natural gas of about .016 - .17 cents.  At these levels, using the externality values will not significantly enhance the prospect of renewables being chosen over traditional power plants in future resource plans, except when market costs are equal.  In that case external costs could serve as a tiebreaker.<p>

  The key pollutant in terms of its economic impact is carbon dioxide. The Environmental Coalition, which includes ME3, had proposed an environmental cost of $25 per ton. <p>

  <B>Klein's Analysis of Testimony <p>

  Criteria Pollutants</B><BR> In determining the values for PM10, NOx, Pb, CO, and SO2, Judge Klein relied on a damage-cost study commissioned by Northern States Power (NSP) from Triangle Economic Research (TER). Klein noted that the TER study was "the only study presented in this proceeding that focused on effects in Minnesota." NSP reportedly spent $500,000 on the study.<p>

  <B>Carbon Dioxide (CO2)</B><BR> In determining the value of carbon dioxide emissions Judge Klein based his recommendation on the testimony of the MN Pollution Control Agency (MPCA). The MPCA used existing published damage estimates of CO2 and proposed a range of $4.28 - $28.57 per ton for CO2. The lower range assumed global damages of 1 percent of global domestic product (GDP) and a discount rate of 2 percent. The higher range assumed a reduction of 2 percent of the GDP and a discount rate of 1 percent. Klein chose the lower damage rates and chose a much higher range of discount rates from 3-5 percent. As Klein noted, the "selection of a discount rate largelycontrols the ultimate cost figure." Environmentalists have for more than 30 years been arguing that discount rates, which by definition discount the value of the future, must be very low when evaluating impacts that have intergenerational implications. <p>

  <B>Mercury</B><BR> The Environmental Coalition, MN Office of Attorney General, and the MPCA pushed strongly for the adoption of an environmental cost value for mercury. These parties recommended values for mercury ranging from $28 - $50 million per ton. Klein decided that the record did not contain enough scientific information "to support a quantified range of environmental cost values for mercury emissions." He went on to say, "it is frustrating to conclude that there is insufficient  evidence to recommend a value for mercury in light of the broad  consensus about mercury's toxicity and the need to reduce human (as well as animal) exposure." Klein noted that both the federal government and the State of Minnesota are undertaking scientific studies of mercury that will be available within the next two years and recommended that the Public Utilities Commission (PUC) should require utilities to explain how mercury was taken into account in resource planning filings.<p>

  Once exceptions to the decision are filed, Judge Klein's decision goes to the PUC which will determine the final environmental cost values. The PUC is under no obligation to accept the Judge's conclusions. <p>

  The Environmental Coalition and MPCA's filings in this proceeding as well as Judge Klein's decision are on-line at the Sustainable Minnesota web site: <p>

  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/costs/">http://www.me3.org/projects/costs/</A><p>

  <B>What Do Nukes, Dry Casks,  and Primergy Have In Common?</B><p>

  NSP and Wisconsin Energy Corporation (WEC) propose to merge into a mega utility to be known as Primergy. Merger supporters don't tell us that Primergy would be the proud owner of 5 nuclear reactors at 3 sites and bear the enormous financial liability that nuclear plants carry far into the future. Two of the reactor sites, NSP's Prairie Island and WEC's Point Beach, have been involved in regulatory battles over dry cask storage of nuclear waste because of limited storage space in spent fuel pools. Prairie Island's problems were temporarily solved in 1994 when the MN Legislature gave approval for up to 17 dry casks to be set outside the plant on the shores of the Mississippi River. <p>

  As an interesting aside, Wisconsin Public Service Commission (PSC) staff have estimated that it would cost about $500 million for replacement power if one of the two reactors at Point Beach were shut down prematurely. During the Prairie Island debates NSP often cited a $2 billion cost if Prairie Island closed early. Point Beach generates nearly the same amount of power as Prairie Island.<p>

  In February 1995 the PSC issued an order allowing WEC's electric company, Wisconsin Electric Power Company (WEPCO), to build a storage facility containing 12 casks at the 1000-MW Point Beach nuclear plant. The order was challenged by consumer and environmental groups in Dane County District Court. In December 1995, the Court ruled that the PSC's final environmental impact statement (FEIS) was deficient in several areas, including the lack of an analysis of the effects of long-term storage of nuclear waste in dry casks at Point Beach.<p>

  WEPCO had already filled one cask at the facility but the Court's ruling put a hold on any further casks. The utility is under pressure because their spent- fuel pool will barely accommodate a full-core offload and they need that capability to do a steam generator replacement in one of the reactors. WEPCO estimates that replacement of steam generators in Unit 2 will cost $100 million.<p>

  Because of the pressure on WEPCO, the supplemental environmental impact statement was done in almost record time. Within 30 days of the Court's order, a supplemental FEIS analyzing the impacts of dry cask storage to the years 2023 and 2050 had been completed. Those are the dates when it is assumed that DOE would begin removing casks to a national repository. However, as critics point out, at least 103 casks would be needed to store all of the wastes generated at the Point Beach reactors if they remain operational to the end of their licenses in 2010 and 2012. If the Department of Energy (DOE) managed to get a national repository opened it is estimated that it would take 38 years for the DOE to remove all 103 casks.<p>

  The PSC will hear oral arguments on April 10th and make a decision on April 16th. Surprisingly, on April 1st the PSC staff issued a brief to the Commissioners which showed the staff divided between those who wanted the PSC to approve the steam generator replacement and those in favor of shutting down Unit 2 this year. This issue may have ramifications for Minnesota ratepayers if the NSP/Wisconsin Energy Corporation merger goes forward as planned.<p>

  There are important questions to be answered before approving the formation of Primergy. Do Minnesota ratepayers want to take on the responsibility of even more nuclear waste? Do Minnesotans want potentially to  become the host for nuclear waste generated in Wisconsin? Could the merger of these two utilities lessen the control of state regulators and put more control in the hands of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC)? The MN Department of Public Service has come out in favor of the merger and has submitted testimony that urges the MN Public Utilities Commission to forgo any environmental impact statement or lengthy contested case proceeding. ME3 supports a full environmental review of the merger and believes that a contested case hearing is the only way to ensure that all of the issues of concern are addressed.<p>

  Contact: Nancy McGee, PSC, 608-266-7706; Citizen's Utility Board of Wisconsin, 608-251-3322<p>

   <B>EQB Seeks Comments on Rules for Siting Large Wind Farms</B><p>

  The MN Environmental Quality Board (EQB) will soon issue a set of proposed rules governing the review of site permits for large wind energy conversion systems (LWECS) with a nameplate capacity of more than 5 MW.  The proposed rules will address many issues including:  1) environmental and human impacts of a proposed LWECS and, 2) turbine type and design, site layout, site operation and maintenence.  Interested parties may submit comments on the proposed rules by May 6, 1996.<p>

  Contact: <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:larry.hartman@mnplan.state.mn.us"> Larry Hartman</A>, EQB, 612-296-5089, 1-800-657-3794<p>

  <p>

  <H3>IV.  Information Resources</H3>  <B>Energy Efficiency and the Low-Income Consumer</B><p>

  This report from Roger Colton of Fisher, Sheehan &amp; Colton is one of a three-volume series addressing energy efficiency, and heating and cooling needs of low-income households. The reports provide state-by-state and utility-by-utility data on the impacts of energy use on low-income consumers.<p>

  Contact: Roger Colton, FSC, 617-484-0597<p>

  <B>Minnesota's Cooperative and Municipal Electric Utilities: Opportunities for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy</B><p>

  This February 1996 report prepared by William Brakken for the Environmental Law &amp; Policy Center (ELPC) examines the strategies available to Minnesota's municipal and cooperative electric utilities to increase investments in energy efficiency and renewable energy.<p>

  Contact: William Brakken, 612-224-7759; Howard Learner or Jimmy Seidita, ELPC, 312-759-3400<p>

  <B>Boosting Prosperity: Reducing the Threat of Global Climate Change Through Sustainable Energy Investments</B><p>

  This January 1996 report by Douglas Ogden examines how a host of new technologies being used by industries and utilities can reduce greenhouse- gas emissions and simultaneously boost the economy. The report argues through case studies of dozens of initiatives that energy efficiency can increase profitability and competitiveness by lowering the cost of doing business.<p>

  Contact: Douglas Ogden, Energy Foundation, 415-561-6700<p>

  <p>

   <B>Key Factors Responsible for Changes in Electric-Utility DSM Usage</B><p>

  This September 1995 report by Martin Schweitzer (Oak Ridge National Laboratory) and Mirriam Pye (American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy) examines how the potential restructuring of the electric industry is affecting utility-sponsored demand-side management programs.<p>

  Contact: ACEEE, 510-549-9914<p>

  <B>Perspectives in Electric Utility Restructuring: A Compilation of Papers</B><p>

  This February 1996 report from the Regulatory Assistance Project (RAP) identifies and analyzes many of the key issues underlying the transition to a more competitive electric industry.<p>

  Contact: <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:rapmaine@aol.com">RAP</A>, 207-582-1135,<p>

  rapmaine@aol.com<p>

  <B>Electric Power Systems For Small, New or Incremental Capacity Addition in Remote or Underdeveloped Areas</B><p>

  This September 1995 report prepared by William Hauserman of the Energy &amp; Environmental Research Center (University of North Dakota) provides a review of available and emerging technologies for electric power generation at small or remote sites, at capacities below 10 MW. <p>

  Contact: William Hauserman, P.E., EERC, 701-777-5169<p>

   <B>Report to the Minnesota Legislature  on DPS/PUC Reorganization</B><p>

  This January 16th, 1996 report submitted by the Chairs of the MN Public Utilities Commission and the MN Department of Public Service examines the duties, responsibilities and effectiveness of the two agencies. The review concludes that combining the two agencies would seriously impair their advocacy, enforcement, regulatory, and quasi-judicial functions.<p>

  Contact: David Sampsel, DPS,  612-296-7128<p>

   <B>Annual Energy Outlook 1996</B><p>

  This January 1996 report from the Energy Information Adminis-tration (Report No. DOE/EIA-0383 (96)) presents projections of energy supply, demand, and prices through the year 2015. <p>

  Contact: EIA, 202-586-8800;  <H REF="http://www.eia.doe.gov"http://www.eia.doe.gov</A> or <H REF="ftp://ftp.eia.doe.gov">ftp://ftp.eia.doe.gov"</A><p>

  <B>Alternatives to Traditional Transportation Fuels 1994</B><p>

  This February 1996 report (Report no. DOE/EIA-0585(94)/1) from the Energy Information Administration provides data on the status of alternative fueled vehicles and alternative transportation fuels including; liquid petroleum gas, compressed natural gas, methanol, ethanol and electricity. The report also contains a listing of companies that manufacture or convert alternative fueled vehicles.<p>

  Contact: National Energy Information Center, 202-586-1181<p>

  <B>The State Carbon Tax Model</B><p>

  This Excel spreadsheet developed by the Center for Global Change will estimate the total revenues generated and tax rates for individual fuels from a state-based carbon tax. Users need to input their state energy consumption data, contained in reports from the Department of Energy. The results also include the effects on an average household.<p>

  Contact: Center for Global Change, 301-403-4165 or <A HREF="http://www.bsos.umd.edu/cgc">http://www.bsos.umd.edu/cgc</A><p>

  <p>

  <b>V.  Calendar</b><p>

  <b></b>7th Annual Midwest Renewable Energy Fair, sponsored by the Midwest Renewable Energy Association will be held on June 21-23, 1996, in Amherst, WI.<BR> Contact:  Tehri Parker, MREA, 715-824-5166<p>

  <p>

  1996 Solar Boat Regatta sponsored by the Minnesota Renewable Energy Society will be held June 1, 1996, at Lake Phalen in St. Paul, MN.  <BR> Contact:  Tom Koehler, MRES, 929-3393  <p>


  Windpower '96, sponsored by the American Wind Energy Association is its 26th annual conference and exhibition.  It will be held June 23-27, 1996, in Denver, CO.<BR> Contact:  Linda Redmond, AWEA, 202-383-2500<p>


  <b>VI.   Miscellaneous</b><p>

  <b><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/">Sustainable MN Web Site</A> Has Moved to <A HREF="http://www.me3.org/">http://www.me3.org</A></b><p>

 

  ME3's home on the internet has moved to a new location at the <A HREF="http://www.mtn.org/">Minneapolis Telecommunications Network (MTN) </A>.  ME3 thanks the <A HREF="http://www.great-lakes.net/">Great Lakes Information Network</A> (http://www.great-lakes.net) for the use of their server for the past year.  ME3's old web address will be operational for only a short time so point your browsers and change your bookmarks to reflect our new home at <A HREF="http://www.me3.org/">http://www.me3.org</A><p>

     <H2>VI. ME3 Board of Directors  </H2> Minnesotans for An Energy-Efficient Economy (ME3) is a coalition working to improve the quality of life, the environment and the economy of Minnesota by promoting energy efficiency and the sound use of renewable energy.  Through a program of research, public education, and intervention in the decision-making process, ME3 seeks to develop and build consensus for an energy vision that will ensure the well-being of future generations.<BR> <BR>  <B>George Crocker</B> - North American Water Office<BR> <B><!-- MailTo Tag --> <a href=mailto:jrdunlop@mcimail.com>John Dunlop</A></B> - Minnesota Wind Energy Association<BR> <B><!-- MailTo Tag --> <A HREF="MAILTO: billgrant@igc.apc.org">Bill Grant</A></B> - Izaak Walton League of America, Midwest Office<BR>  <B>Mary Jane Heinen</B> - MN Renewable Energy Society<BR>  <B>Steve Hoffman</B> - St. Thomas University<BR>  <B>Anne Hunt </B>- St. Paul Neighborhood Energy Consortium<BR>  <B>Ralph Jacobson</B> - Innovative Power Systems<BR>  <B>Diane Jensen</B> - Clean Water Action Alliance<BR>  <B><!-- MailTo Tag --> <A HREF="MAILTO:tekoehler@aol.com">Tom Koehler</A></B> - MN Renewable Energy Society<BR>  <B><a href=mailto:dmorris@mtn.org>David Morris</a></B> - Institute for Local Self-Reliance<BR> <B>Gary Nelson</B> - Sustainable Resources Center<BR> <B><a href=mailto:me3noble@mtn.org>Michael Noble</a></B> - ME3 Executive Director<BR>  <B>Sheldon Strom</B> - Center for Energy and Environment<BR>  <B><!-- MailTo Tag --> <A HREF="MAILTO:water007@gold.tc.umn.edu">Beth Waterhouse</A></B> - Minnesota Project<BR> <BR>  Newsletter Editor:  <a href=mailto:jbailey@great-lakes.net>John Bailey</a> - <A HREF="http://www.ilsr.org">Institute for Local Self-Reliance</A><BR> <BR> ME3 Minnesota Building, Suite 1106<BR> 46 East Fourth Street<BR> St. Paul, MN  55101<BR> Tel:  612-225-1133<BR> Fax:  612-225-0870<BR> E-mail:  me3noble@me3.org     hamilton@me3.org    http://www.me3.org <HR> Return to <A HREF="http:/