<HEAD><TITLE>Motion For Stay Of Proceeding And Request For Certification To The Commission  Of Petition Of The Environmental Coalition, Energy Cents Coalition And Citizens' Utility Board For Reconsideration And Rehearing Of Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication
</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 

<CENTER><H3>Motion For Stay Of Proceeding And Request For Certification To The Commission  Of Petition Of The Environmental Coalition, Energy Cents Coalition And Citizens' Utility Board For Reconsideration And Rehearing Of Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication
</H3><P>


STATE OF MINNESOTA<BR>
BEFORE THE OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE HEARINGS<BR>
FOR THE MINNESOTA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<BR>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<P>


In the Matter of Northern States Power Company's<BR>
Petition for approval to Merge with Wisconsin Energy Corporation<BR>
MPUC Docket No. E-002/PA-500<BR></CENTER>


<P>

<B>Motion For Stay Of Proceeding And Request For Certification To The Commission  Of Petition Of The Environmental Coalition, Energy Cents Coalition And Citizens' Utility Board For Reconsideration And Rehearing Of Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication
</B><P>

<P>

	The Environmental Coalition , Energy CENTS Coalition and the Citizens' Utility Board ("Environmental/Consumer Coalition") respectfully request, pursuant to Minn. R.  1400.7600, that the Administrative Law Judge ("ALJ") certify the attached Petition for Reconsideration and Rehearing to the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission ("Commission").   The Petition requests reconsideration and rehearing of the Commission's Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication, which was issued on October 28, 1996 in the above-captioned docket.   Although the ALJ was not directly involved in the Commission's investigation of the ex parte matter, certification is required because the Commission issued its final order after "assignment of a judge and prior to the completion and filing of the judge's report."  Minn. R. 1400.7600.   The Environmental/Consumer Coalition also respectfully  requests a stay of all proceedings in this docket pending the disposition of our Petition for Reconsideration and Rehearing.<P>
<H3>I.	REQUEST FOR CERTIFICATION OF PETITION FOR RECONSIDERATION AND REHEARING TO COMMISSION.</H3><P>

	Minnesota Rule 1400.7600 delineates the factors the ALJ should consider in determining to certify a motion to the agency.  Among the factors are:  whether a final determination by the Commission on the motion would materially advance the ultimate termination of the hearing,  or whether certification is necessary to promote the development of the full record and avoid remanding.  Minn. R. 1400.7600(B) and (E).  Certification of the Environmental/Consumer Coalition's Petition for Reconsideration and Rehearing would materially advance the ultimate termination of the hearing, and is necessary to promote the development of the full record and avoid remand.  In addition, the rule governing petitions for rehearing and reconsideration clearly indicates that the Commission shall decide the petition.  Minn. R. 7829.3000 Subp. 6.  Therefore, the Environmental/Consumer Coalition's Petition should be certified to the Commission.  <P>
	If the Commission determines on reconsideration or rehearing that prohibited ex parte communication has taken place, it will then have to determine the appropriate remedy.  The remedy could affect the scope of the hearing, or even require dismissal of the case in its entirety.  Minn. R. 7845.7500.  Since both Commissioner Jacob and Commissioner Johnson participated in the decision which set the scope of the issues for hearing, that decision may have  been tainted by improper ex parte influence.  Therefore, the Commission's order setting the scope of the hearing would need to be revisited if the Commission modifies on rehearing its original decision on the alleged ex parte communication. Modification of the scoping order after the hearing is well underway would necessitate rehearing of some issues and delay the close of the hearing.<P>

	As is discussed below, the Environmenta/Consumer Coalition requests a stay of these proceedings until the matter of ex parte communication is finally resolved.  If a stay is ordered pending ultimate resolution of the ex parte question, certification of the Petition will certainly advance the ultimate termination of the hearing.  <P>
	Even if the stay is not ordered, certification could still advance the termination of the hearing:  a finding of impermissible ex parte communication as a result of rehearing and reconsideration could result in modification of the order establishing the scope of the hearing.  A change in the scope of the hearing could necessitate filing of additional testimony, reexamination of witnesses who had already testified, and calling of additional witnesses, all of which would extend the time for termination of the hearing.<P>
	For these same reasons, certification of the Petition to the Commission is necessary to promote the development of the full record and avoid remand.  For example, if prohibited ex parte communication is ultimately found, an appropriate remedy may require expanding the scope of the hearing to include issues which were excluded before the ex parte contact was disclosed.  If by the time the decision reaches the Commission the hearing has concluded and the record has been closed, the record would not be complete with respect to excluded issues and remanding would be required.<P>
	Finally, the rule on petitions for rehearing and reconsideration mandates that the Commission decide a petition for rehearing or reconsideration of its decision or order.  The rule states:  "The commission shall decide a petition for rehearing, amendment, vacation, reconsideration, or reargument. . ."  Minn. R. 7829.3000 Subp. 6 (emphasis added).  The rule does not appear to allow for the ALJ to decide such a petition. <P>
	Therefore, for all the reasons stated above, the Environmental/Consumer Coalition respectfully requests that its Petition for Reconsideration and Rehearing of the Commission's Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication be certified to the Commission.<P>

<H3>II.	MOTION FOR STAY PENDING DISPOSITION OF PETITION FOR RECONSIDERATION AND REHEARING.</H3><P>

	The Environmental/Consumer  Coalition also requests that the ALJ stay proceedings in this docket pending the ultimate disposition of the issue of alleged ex parte communications.  A stay is necessary to avoid deprivation of due process and fundamental fairness to movants' interests.  If the Commission's reconsideration and rehearing results in a determination that prohibited ex parte communication occurred, as movants believe it should, then the Commission must also make a determination of the extent of the prejudice caused by the ex parte influence and the appropriate sanction.  Movants allege that the ex parte influence tainted the Commission's decision setting a very narrow scope for these proceedings.  Since the Commission may need to revisit its decision on the appropriate scope of the proceedings, the hearing should not proceed until the question of the existence of and prejudice from prohibited ex parte communication reaches ultimate resolution.<P>
	The Commission rendered its decision on the scope of the hearing in this docket on June 6, 1996.  This decision was made after the ex parte contact on May 15, 1996, but before any disclosure whatsoever  had been made of the contact, either by the Commissioners themselves, as required by Minn. R. 7845.7300, or by any other witness.  Both Commissioner Jacobs and  Commissioner Johnson participated in that decision.  Considering that the vacancy on the Commission at that time meant that the decision was reached by only four Commissioners, the deliberation and votes of Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson were certainly influential in the Commission's final determination.<P>
	If there was prohibited ex parte communication between the applicant NSP and Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson, then Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson should have immediately recused themselves from all decisions in the Primergy docket, including the very important June 6 decision on the scope of the hearing, and filed written disclosure of the contact within 48 hours.  Minn. R. 7845.7600.  If prohibited ex parte communication is found, and Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson remain recused for the duration of the Primergy docket, then the Commission will have to revisit its decision on the scope of the hearing in order to assure that the taint of the ex parte contact is removed from the proceedings.<P>
	The consequence of the potentially tainted June 6, 1996 decision on the scope of the hearing issues was the striking of all testimony filed by the Environmental Coalition and Energy Cents and the exclusion from consideration in this docket of all environmental issues and low-income consumer issues.  The subject of the ex parte communication in question was a report which raised concerns about the effects of the proposed merger on broad market power issues.  The FERC staff economist's concerns encompassed both generation and transmission market power.  The environmental and low-income customer issues raised by the movants concern market power under this broader view, but the issues were excluded from consideration based on the very narrow view of market power adopted by the Commission in its June 25th Order defining the scope of hearings.   If that decision was tainted by prohibited ex parte communication, then movants' interests have been severely prejudiced by the taint, and movants have been deprived of due process and fundamental fairness.<P>
	Recent revelations in Wisconsin, in which WEC appears to have engaged in repeated ex parte contacts with a Commissioner of the Public Service Commission of Wisconsin, suggest a pattern of improper influence by the Primergy merger partners.  These revelations underscore the importance of considering the likelihood that the May 16 contact by NSP was not an isolated incident.  Until the ex parte matter is finally resolved, all decisions in which Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson participated must be held in abeyance.  If the hearing continues prior to an ultimate determination on the existence and/or scope of the ex parte influence, the taint that that influence may have introduced into the proceedings cannot be adequately purged.  <P>

	Wherefore, the Environmental/Consumer Coalition respectfully requests that the ALJ issue a stay of these proceedings to preserve due process and fundamental fairness.<BR>

Date:   November 18, 1996<P>

Respectfully submitted,<P>


Susan Hedman<BR>					
Environmental Law & Policy Center	<BR>		
203 North LaSalle; Suite 1390<BR>			
Chicago, Illinois 60601<BR>				
(312) 759-3400		<BR>
ATTORNEY FOR THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION AND ENERGY CENTS COALITION<P>	
		
Margaret Becker<BR>
Cullen, Weston, Pines & Bach<BR>
20 North Carroll Street<BR>
Madison, Wisconsin 53703<BR>
(608) 251-0101<P>
ATTORNEY FOR THE CITIZENS' UTILITY BOARD, INC.<BR>


