<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Petition Of Environmental Coalition,  Energy Cents
Coalition And Citizens' Utility Board For Reconsideration And Rehearing Of Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication
</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<P>
<CENTER><H3>Petition Of Environmental Coalition,  Energy Cents
Coalition And Citizens' Utility Board For Reconsideration And Rehearing Of Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication
</H3><P>


STATE OF MINNESOTA<BR>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<P>
Joel Jacobs, Chair<BR>

Marshall Johnson, Commissioner<BR>
Dee Knaak, Commissioner<BR>
Mac McCollar, Commissioner<BR>
Don Storm, Commissioner
<P>

In the Matter of Northern States Power Company's<BR>
Petition for approval to Merge with Wisconsin Energy Corporation<BR>
MPUC Docket No. E-002/PA-500<BR></CENTER>


<P>

<B>Petition Of Environmental Coalition,  Energy Cents
Coalition And Citizens' Utility Board For Reconsideration And Rehearing Of Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication
</B><P>



	The Environmental Coalition , Energy CENTS Coalition and the Citizens' Utility Board ("Environmental/Low Income Consumer Coalition") respectfully request, pursuant to Minn. Rules  7829.3000, that the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission reconsider and set for rehearing certain matters decided in the Commission's October 28, 1996 Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication in the above-captioned docket.   This Petition for Reconsideration and Rehearing is submitted in conjunction with a Request for Certification to the Commission, filed with the Office of  Administrative Hearings pursuant to Minn. Rules  1400.7600. <P>
	The Environmental/Low Income Consumer Coalition requests that the Commission reconsider its Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication and requests that the Commission set the matter for rehearing: (1) because the Commission's decision is not supported by substantial evidence in the record;  (2) in light of new evidence suggesting that NSP's contact with MPUC Commissioners was part of a pattern of ex parte contact by the merger partners; and  (3) because the Commission's decision violates the Environmental/Low Income Consumer Coalition parties' fundamental due process rights in this proceeding.<P>

<H3>I.	THE ENVIRONMENTAL/LOW INCOME CONSUMER COALITION FILED COMMENTS ASKING THE COMMISSION TO HOLD COMPREHENSIVE HEARINGS ON THE PROPOSED MERGER.</H3><P>

	On August 4, 1995 Northern States Power Company ("NSP") filed an application for approval of its proposed merger with Wisconsin Energy  Corporation (WEC).    The Commission requested initial comments on the merger application by January 16, 1996 and reply comments by  March 1, 1996.    Several parties to the proceeding, including the Environmental/Low Income Consumer Coalition parties, raised questions about the NSP/WEC proposal and asked the Commission to hold comprehensive hearings on the merger.   The Commission allowed the parties to file a final round of comments, due April 2, 1996, addressing "specific issues of procedure, including the identification of any material factual disputes which would require a contested case hearing, and the proposed scope of any hearing which has been requested."  Notice of Additional Comment Period; March 13, 1996.<P>


<H3>II.	NSP ATTEMPTED TO CONVINCE THE COMMISSION, ON AND OFF THE RECORD, THAT A CONTESTED CASE HEARING WAS UNNECESSARY</H3><P>

	The written comments which NSP filed with the Commission argued that "no contested case hearing is needed prior to approval of the merger."  NSP Comments, at 1; April 2, 1996.    The company vigorously reinforced this point during its oral presentation on June 6th, when the Commission met to decide whether to hold hearings on the merger.   In contrast, virtually all of the intervenors who filed written comments and presented oral argument urged the Commission to hold comprehensive evidentiary hearings to investigate the proposed merger -- including a wide range of vertical and horizontal market power impacts associated with the merger and the extent to which the  merger impaired the effectiveness of state regulation.  <P>
	After the deadline for written comments and before the Commission met to decide whether to hold hearings, NSP lobbyist Ron Jerich invited MPUC Chair Joel Jacobs to join him for lunch at the St. Paul Pool and Yacht Club -- without telling Chairman Jacobs that he would be bringing two of his NSP clients along.   Attorney General's Summary of Investigation, at 2. Commissioner Marshall Johnson decided to join Chairman Jacobs for that luncheon, which occurred on May 15, 1996.   During the lunch meeting, Chairman Jacobs and NSP's then-
Director of State and Metropolitan Governmental Affairs, Merle Anderson, discussed a newspaper article about  Federal Energy Regulatory Commission staff testimony that was critical of the proposed NSP/Wisconsin Energy merger.    AG Summary, at 2.    Betsy Engleking, the lead MPUC Analyst on the NSP merger filing, told investigators from the Office of the Attorney General that on the afternoon of May 15th Chairman Jacobs told her (in Commissioner Johnson's presence) that NSP's Director of Governmental Affairs characterized the FERC staff testimony as "just one economist's opinion."  <P>
<H3>III.	THE COMMISSION, INCLUDING THE TWO COMMISSIONERS WITH WHOM NSP HAD EX PARTE CONTACT, VOTED TO NARROWLY RESTRICT THE SCOPE OF  HEARINGS ON THE MERGER</H3> <P>

	On June 6th, after hearing oral argument by the Environmental/Low Income Consumer Coalition and other parties regarding the need for a comprehensive contested case hearing on the proposed Primergy merger, the Commission voted to restrict hearings to five very narrow issues.  See, MPUC Order Establishing Procedural Framework, at 21.   The two market power questions which the Commission did set for hearing -- the impact of the merger on Minnesota utilities and the extent of Primergy's ability to manipulate the MAPP-WUMS interface to its advantage -- were very  narrow in scope compared with the market power issues set for hearing in the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and Public Service Commission of Wisconsin (PSCW) merger dockets.  The MPUC also declined to hold hearings to investigate merger-related impacts on the environment, low income consumers and state regulatory effectiveness -- all of which were included in hearings before the PSCW.<p>
	MPUC Chairman Jacobs chaired the Commission's June 6th meeting and Commissioner Johnson participated actively in the discussions and votes at that meeting.   Neither Commissioner publicly disclosed their  ex parte contact with  NSP prior to voting -- at the meeting or previously, pursuant to Minn. Rules  7845.7300.   Their May 15th ex parte meeting with NSP representatives did not come to light until late June, when Commissioner  Don Storm received a phone call from an anonymous NSP employee stating:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>that the caller overheard a conversation involving Commissioner Jacobs and Merle Anderson during which the pending NSP merger was discussed.  The caller told Commissioner Storm that Merle Anderson was trying to convey information relating to a Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) staff report that was critical of the merger.  The caller said Anderson was attempting to persuade Jacobs that one doesn't need to put a lot of stock in the report.  Further, the caller said that Anderson purportedly stated that the report is not a big deal, and the merger can continue without emphasis on the report. </BLOCKQUOTE> <CITE>AG Summary, at 3.</CITE><P>

	Chairman Jacobs and Commissioner Johnson recused themselves from the merger proceedings after their meeting with NSP officials became public.  The remaining two Commissioners, with assistance from the Office of Attorney General, conducted an investigation of NSP's contact with Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson.   As these two Commissioners prepared to meet to consider the results of their investigation, several parties filed comments suggesting the absence of a quorum.  Consequently,  on September 16, 1996 the Governor announced his appointment of Commissioner Mac McCollar, assuring a quorum in the merger docket.<P>

<H3>IV.	THE ORDER FINDING NO PROHIBITED EX PARTE COMMUNICATION WAS BACKED BY A TWO PERSON MAJORITY -- CONSISTING OF ONE COMMISSIONER WHO WAS SOMEWHAT EQUIVOCAL AND ANOTHER WHO WAS INEXPERIENCED</H3><P>
	On September 27th Commissioners Knaak, Storm and McCollar met to hear oral argument and to determine whether NSP's contact with Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson constituted an illegal ex parte communication, contrary to Minn. Rules, Part 7845.7000, subpt. 4.  Commissioner Storm announced that, after weighing the evidence, he was convinced that illegal ex parte contact had indeed occurred.  Commissioner Knaak, who chaired the meeting, emphasized how difficult it was to decide the ex parte matter.  She indicated that she was not prepared to find prohibited ex parte contact, but would, nonetheless, vote to require NSP to demonstrate that its "policies regarding communications with decision-makers relating to contested matters"  apply to its registered lobbyists and independent consultants.   Commissioner McCollar,  who was in only his tenth day of service on the Commission, concurred with Chair Knaak.<P>

<H3>V.	ALL OF THE TESTIMONY SUBMITTED BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL/
CONSUMER COALITION HAS BEEN STRICKEN BECAUSE IT IS BEYOND THE SCOPE OF THE NARROWLY DEFINED ISSUES SET FOR HEARING BY THE COMMISSION -- INCLUDING THE TWO COMMISSIONERS WITH WHOM NSP HAD EX PARTE CONTACT</H3>	<P>
	In mid-October, intervenors filed testimony.  Much of this testimony, like NSP's application and testimony in the MPUC merger docket, is similar to testimony filed in the FERC and PSCW merger dockets.   NSP immediately moved to strike all of the testimony filed by the Environmental Coalition and Energy CENTS Coalition in this proceeding.  As grounds, NSP asserted that the testimony  is beyond the scope of the hearing, as narrowly defined in the June 25, 1996 Order Establishing Procedural Framework issued by Chairman Jacobs and Commissioner Johnson (both have since recused themselves), Commissioner Storm (who has since been convinced that NSP engaged in illegal ex parte communication prior to the Commission's scoping decision) and Commissioner Knaak .   On November 7, 1996 the ALJ issued a preliminary decision granting NSP's Motions to Strike all of the testimony submitted by the Environmental Coalition and Energy CENTS Coalition in this proceeding. <P>

<H3>VI.	THE COMMISSION SHOULD RECONSIDER ITS ORDER FINDING NO PROHIBITED EX PARTE COMMUNICATION AND SET THE MATTER FOR REHEARING BECAUSE ITS DECISION IS NOT SUPPORTED BY SUBSTANTIAL EVIDENCE IN THE RECORD.</H3><P>

	"Ex parte communication" is defined under Minn. Rules, Part 7845.7000, subp. 4, which states in relevant part:<BR>
	"Ex parte communication" means an oral or written, off-the record communication made to or by commissioners. . . without notice to parties, that is directed to the merits or outcome of an on-the-record proceeding.  This term does not include procedural, scheduling, and status inquiries or other inquiries or requests for information that have no bearing on the merits or the outcome of he proceeding.  <P>

	In its Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication, the Commission held that the NSP's off-the record contact with the Commission on May 15, 1996 "was in the nature of a modest information clarification regarding the authorship or the procedural status of the report" and was, therefore, "excepted from the definition of ex parte communication under Minn. Rules, part 7845.7000, subpt. 4."    Order, at 5.   The Order states that "the Commission does not believe that the parties involved in the disputed conversation directed their remarks to the merits or outcome' of the NSP merger proceeding."  Order, at 5.    Ultimately, the Commission found that the conversation consisted of  "tangential, glancing references not addressing the merits of the FERC staff report -- incidental, casual talk of fleeting duration and slight interest to the conversers and ultimately of insubstantial relevance to the merits and outcome NSP's proposed merger application."  Order, at 5.<P>

	The Commission's findings are completely at odds with the evidence provided by MPUC staff analyst Betsy Engelking, who told investigators that during a briefing with Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson, on the afternoon of May 15, 1996, Chairman Jacobs made a statement that concerned her:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Specifically, Ms. Engelking said that Commissioner Johnson asked her about a newspaper article that appeared in the paper that day (May 15, 1996).  The article discussed a FERC staff report which had negative comments about the proposed NSP/Wisconsin Energy merger.  Ms. Engelking reported that after Mr. Johnson made his comment to her regarding the newspaper article, Commissioner Jacobs interjected that he had lunch with Merle Anderson that day (May 15, 1996), and that Anderson had told Jacobs, "it's just one economist's opinion."   AG Summary, at 3.</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

	The account which Ms Engelking provided investigators from the Office of the Attorney General is highly credible.  It is consistent with the account which she provided to her supervisor, Janet Gonzales, and to Dave Sparby of NSP on the very day which the ex parte discussions occurred.   Ms. Engelking's decision to report the conversation to her supervisor is clear evidence that she thought that Mr. Anderson's comments concerned a material issue directed to the merits or the outcome of the pending merger proceeding -- that she was concerned about possible evidence of prohibited ex parte communications.<P>
	Ms. Engleking's account of the situation is the most credible evidence available to the Commission to assess NSP's contact with the Commissioners.  Ms. Engelking is experienced with Commission procedure and, as lead analyst in the merger docket, she is intimately acquainted with the issues in case.   And, unlike the NSP employees and Commissioners involved in the incident, Ms. Engelking's account is not tainted by self-interest.<P>

	Incredibly, Ms. Engelking's testimony was virtually ignored by the two Commissioners who found that no prohibited ex parte communication had occurred.  Instead, these two Commissioners relied on the testimony of Merle Anderson -- despite his obvious self-interest and the absence of any contemporaneous statements that he made corroborating the account he provided investigators over two months after the events in question.  When confronted by  investigators from the Office of Attorney General, Mr. Anderson admitted that he told Chairman Jacobs that "he saw the article," but claims that he noted only "that it was a staff report not a commission report."   AG Investigation Summary, at 2.  <P>
	The two Commissioners who found no prohibited ex parte communication treat this matter as though Mr. Anderson said something factual and inconsequential (e.g., the witness testified in the morning, not the afternoon)  rather than something subjective, in an attempt to persuade a Commissioner or Commissioners on a material issue in a contested case proceeding.   Ms. Engelking's account of Commissioner Jacobs' comments clearly capture this distinction.  The Commission's attempt to blur this distinction, by suggesting that Mr. Anderson's account "is consistent with the information provided by Commission staff member Engelking" is not supported by substantial evidence in the record.<P>


<H3>VII.	THE COMMISSION SHOULD RECONSIDER ITS ORDER FINDING NO PROHIBITED EX PARTE COMMUNICATION AND SET THE MATTER FOR REHEARING IN LIGHT OF NEW EVIDENCE SUGGESTING THAT NSP'S CONTACT WITH MPUC COMMISSIONERS MAY BE PART OF A PATTERN OF EX PARTE CONTACTS BY THE MERGER PARTNERS.</H3><P>

	The Commission concluded that NSP's ex parte contact with Commissioners Jacobs and Johnson was an isolated incident and that there was no need for further investigation of additional ex parte contacts.   Order, at 6.   There is, however, new evidence indicating that NSP's merger partner, WEC,  has had ex parte contact with a PSCW Commissioner on at least three occasions since filing its merger application with the PSCW in August of 1995.  See, Attachment One: "Regulator's Meetings with Utility Revealed: Propriety Questioned While Big Merger Looms,"  Capital Times, November 8, 1996.   The MPUC should reconsider its decision regarding the need for further investigation, in light of this new evidence suggests that NSP's contact with MPUC Commissioners may be  part of a pattern of ex parte contacts by the merger partners.<P>

<H3>VII.	THE COMMISSION SHOULD RECONSIDER ITS ORDER FINDING NO PROHIBITED EX PARTE COMMUNICATION AND SET THE MATTER FOR REHEARING BECAUSE THE COMMISSION'S DECISION VIOLATES THE ENVIRONMENTAL/LOW INCOME CONSUMER COALITION PARTIES' FUNDAMENTAL DUE PROCESS RIGHTS IN THIS PROCEEDING.</H3><P>

	Almost a decade ago, in a case involving improper ex parte contact between a MPUC Commissioner and Northern States Power Company, the Minnesota Supreme Court held:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>	. . .failure to disclose and disqualify must be viewed as irrevocably tainting at least a portion of these proceedings.  While the record contains no direct evidence that [the MPUC Commissioner] unduly influenced the decision, his mere presence creates the obvious appearance of impropriety and undermines the public confidence in the system.  We are incredulous that these sophisticated governmental and utility officials could have assumed otherwise.  In the Matter of the Petition of Northern State Power Company, 414 N.W.2d 383 (1987)</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

Nonetheless, in the instant case, two Commissioners made important decisions regarding the scope of this proceeding without disclosing ex parte contacts with NSP.   Although these two Commissioners have since recused themselves from this docket, their participation in the scoping decision "creates an obvious appearance of impropriety and undermines the public confidence in the system."  Id.<P>
	The scope of this proceeding, which is more restrictive than either the FERC or PSCW merger dockets, is so narrow that all of the testimony submitted by the Environmental Coalition and Low Income Intervenors has been stricken.   Members of the public who have testified about merger-related impacts on the environment and low income consumers have also been told that their testimony is beyond the scope of the public hearings in this docket.  As a result, the Environmental/Low Income Consumers's fundamental due process right to be heard in this proceeding has been violated.   <P>
	Indeed, the entire chronology of events set forth in Sections I-V, supra, suggest a progression of steadily eroding process that has produced an outcome that is fundamentally unfair to the Environmental/Low Income Consumer parties in this proceeding.  The Commission (and the merger partners) should heed the words of the U.S. Supreme Court on this issue, when reconsidering its findings on ex parte contacts in this docket and the impact on the Environmental/Low Income Coaction in this docket:<BR>
 	<BLOCKQUOTE>surreptitious efforts to influence an official charged with the duty of deciding contested cases upon an open record in accord with basic principle of our jurisprudence, eat at the very heart of our system of government -- due process, fair play, open proceedings, unbiased, uninfluenced decision.  He who engages in such efforts in a contest before an administrative agency is fortunate if he loses no more than the matter involved in that proceeding.  WKAT, Inc. v. Federal Communications Commission, 111 U.S. App. D.C. 253, 296 F.2d 375, 383 (D.C. Cir. 1961), cert. denied 368 U.S. 81 (1961)</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<H3>VIII.	CONCLUSION</H3><P>

Wherefore, for all of the reasons stated herein and our previous Comments regarding allegations of Ex Parte contact by NSP , the Environmental/Low Income Consumer Coalition requests that the Commission reconsider its Order Finding No Prohibited Ex Parte Communication and requests that the Commission set the matter for rehearing: (1) because the Commission's decision is not supported by substantial evidence in the record; and (2) in light of new evidence suggesting that NSP's contact with MPUC Commissioners was part of a pattern of  ex parte contact by the merger partners; and (3) because the Commission's decision produces a result that violates the Environmental/Low Income Consumer Coalition's fundamental due process rights in this proceeding.<P>
Date:   November 18, 1996<P>

Respectfully submitted,<P>


Susan Hedman<BR>					
Environmental Law & Policy Center	<BR>		
203 North LaSalle; Suite 1390<BR>			
Chicago, Illinois 60601<BR>				
(312) 759-3400		<BR>
ATTORNEY FOR THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION AND ENERGY CENTS COALITION<P>	
		
Margaret Becker<BR>
Cullen, Weston, Pines & Bach<BR>
20 North Carroll Street<BR>
Madison, Wisconsin 53703<BR>
(608) 251-0101<P>
ATTORNEY FOR THE CITIZENS' UTILITY BOARD, INC.<BR>


