<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF STEPHEN G. BRICK</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<P>
<CENTER><H3>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF STEPHEN G. BRICK</H3><P>


STATE OF MINNESOTA<BR>
OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE HEARINGS<BR>
FOR THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<P>

<P>

In the Matter of Northern States Power Company's<BR>
Petition for approval to Merge with Wisconsin Energy Corporation<BR>
MPUC Docket No. E,G-002/PA-95-500<BR>
OAH Docket No. 6-2500-10601-2<BR></CENTER>


<P>

<B>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF STEPHEN G. BRICK</B><P>

<B>Q.	Please state your name, qualifications and for whom you appear.</B><BR>
A.	My name is Stephen G. Brick.  I am appearing on behalf of the Environmental  Coalition, which is comprised of the Izaak Walton League of America,  Minnesotans for an Energy Efficient Economy, and the Environmental Law &  Policy Center of the Midwest.  My qualifications are attached as Exhibit _____  (SGB-1).<P>

<B>Q.	What is the purpose of this testimony?</B><BR>
A.	I describe some of the environmental costs associated with the proposed merger,  which must be taken into account to determine the net savings, if any, that the  proposed merger can be expected to produce.   I also identify two mitigation  measures which the Commission should require the merged companies to  implement, if this merger is approved.  These conditions would ensure that:  (1)  air pollution emissions do not rise above present levels as a result of the merger,  and, (2) the merged company does not perpetually enjoy a market advantage due  to the less stringent environmental standards (relative to new competitors) that  apply to existing plants on the WEPCO-NSP system.<P>

<B>Q.	Is there a risk that the merger will cause emissions to increase above otherwise- expected levels?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  The companies themselves state that the merger will create conditions  favorable for increased off-system sales.  Such increases will cause air pollution  levels to rise, harming individuals and ecosystems in Minnesota, Wisconsin and  Michigan.  Such environmental costs are undesirable side-effects of the proposed  merger, and to the extent that remedies are available that eliminate or limit the  damages, they should be applied in order to protect the public interest.<P>

<B>Q.	Have you analyzed where increases are likely to occur?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  In my testimony in this case before the FERC, I presented the results of  modeling that suggested that increases were more likely to occur on the NSP  system, due to the marginally-better economics of the NSP plants.  In fact, on an  integrated system basis, emissions decreased at the WEPCO plants, and increased  at NSP plants.  It is likely that even without increased off-system sales, Minnesota  rate payers will bear a disproportionate share of the environmental costs of this  merger.<P>

<B>Q.	Do you have a proposal that would remedy this problem?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  As a condition of approving the merger, this Commission should require the  companies to limit their emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen oxides (NOx)  and carbon dioxide (CO2) to 1995 levels.  The official US EPA emission data for  1995 -- as measured by continuous emission monitors (CEMs) and reported to the  EPA -- should serve as the basis for these caps.  Preliminary 1995 data indicate  the following emission levels:<P>

<CENTER><!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD><B>Company</B></TD><TD><B>NOx tons</B></TD><TD><B>SO2 tons</B></TD><TD><B>CO2 tons</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>NSP</TD><TD>62,000</TD><TD>54,000</TD><TD>19 million</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>WEPCO</TD><TD>57,000</TD><TD>111,000</TD><TD>20 million</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>TOTAL</TD><TD>119,000</TD><TD>165,000</TD><TD>39 million</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<BR>
<P>

<B>Q.	What would a system-wide cap on these pollutants accomplish?</B> <BR>
A.	It would insure that air pollution does not rise above 1995 levels as a result of  increased sales arising from the merger. <P>

<B>Q.	Do the companies enjoy an economic advantage arising from differential  environmental standards?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.   This issue was discussed in my testimony before the FERC.<P>

<B>Q.	What do you propose as a remedy to this inequity?</B><BR>
A.	Emissions from existing fossil-fueled power plants larger than 25 MW on the  combined WEPCO-NSP system should be limited to levels that would be met by  equivalent new sources.   The facilities affected by this proposal are listed in <!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#SGB-2"> Exhibit _____ (SGB-2)</A>.  <P>

<B>Q.	What measures could be used to achieve the proposed emission reductions?</B><BR>
A.	Any combination of fuel switching, pollution control retrofit, unit retirement,  energy efficiency or renewable energy could be used to meet the aggregate limits. <P>

<BR>
<B>Q.	How would New Source-equivalent emission limits be calculated for the  WEPCO-NSP system?</B><BR>
A.	First, typical New Source emission rates would be determined by reviewing data  contained in the BACT/LAER clearinghouse, which is maintained by the US  EPA.<P>

<B>Q.	What is the BACT/LAER clearinghouse?</B><BR>
A.	This is a database that reports permitted emission rates for new facilities  constructed throughout the US.<P>

<B>Q.	What rates have generally been applied to new coal facilities?</B><BR>
A.	These rates vary from location to location and over time.  For SO2, I have assumed  that a new unit would be required to have a  scrubber that was at least 90 percent  efficient, and that coal averaging approximately 3.00 pounds of SO2 per MMBtu  would be permitted to be burned.  This combination yields an emission rate of  0.30 pounds of SO2 per MMBtu.  For NOx, I assumed that selective catalytic  reduction (SCR)  would be required, and that  0.15 pounds of NOx per MMBtu is  typical for new coal plants fitted with SCR.<P>

<B>Q.	How were these emission rates translated into overall system limits?</B><BR>
A.	For each affected unit, I multiplied the appropriate emission rate by a historic  output level and a uniform heat rate and then added the unit-specific allocations to  arrive at a system cap.<P>

<B>Q.	What output level did you use?</B><BR>
A.	I used 1995 net generation from the affected  facilities, based upon data provided  by the companies to the US Energy Information Administration.  <P>

<B>Q.	Why did you use 1995 output levels?</B><BR>
A.	Because this was the most recent year for which data were available.<P>

<B>Q.	 Why was net output used instead of gross output?</B><BR>
A.	This creates an incentive to ensure that in-plant efficiency is maximized.<P>

<B>Q.	Why did you select a 10,000 Btu/kWh heat rate?</B><BR>
A.	This heat rate was calculated to avoid rewarding inefficient units and penalizing  efficient ones.  The allocation scheme used in the acid rain provisions of the 1990  Clean Air Act Amendments simply used historical heat input figures averaged  over the 1985-1987 period as a means of determining emission allowance  allocation.  This means that an inefficient unit -- say, operating at 12,000  Btu/kWh -- was rewarded with more allowances for being inefficient.   Using a  uniform heat rate avoids this problem and rewards efficient units.<P>

<B>Q.	Based on this analysis, what total emission limits do you recommend?</B><BR>
A.	If this merger were approved, subject to the new source-equivalent condition I've  described, total SO2 emissions would be limited to approximately 60,000 tons per  year and NOx emissions would be limited to approximately 30,000 tons per year.   The reductions needed to met these limits could be completed  within five years  of  approval.  The data used to arrive at these figures are listed in <!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#SGB-3">Exhibit _____  (SGB-3)</A>.<P>

<B>Q.	Why do you recommend a five year period for making reductions?</B><BR>
A.	It would be highly desirable to have these limits apply at once as a means of  insuring equity and limiting market power.  However, it is not technically possible  to make all the physical changes necessary to achieve the proposed reductions  instantaneously.  A five-year window provides the needed time frame to plan and  implement measures for reducing emissions. <P>

<B>Q.	Why do you recommend a system-wide cap for these pollutants rather than unit- specific limits?</B><BR>
A.	System-wide caps are more economic to achieve and can yield equivalent overall  levels of pollution reduction.<P>

<B>Q.	What will be accomplished if these system limits are imposed?</B><BR>
A.	First, any market power deriving from differential environmental standards will  be eliminated.  Second, instead of increasing environmental costs, this merger will  yield a substantial improvement.  Third, to the extent that unit retirements are  used as a means of complying with this requirement, the concentration of  generation resources created by the proposed merger will be lessened.<P>

<B>Q.	Who should pay the cost of making these reductions?</B><BR>
A.	The shareholders of the newly-merged company should pay these costs.<P>

<B>Q.	Why?</B><BR>
A.	I assume that deregulation of the power generation segment of this industry will  continue quickly.  Making the shareholders alone responsible for how the  proposed clean-up is achieved increases the likelihood that it will be done in a  cost-effective fashion without unfair ratepayer subsidies.  It is also consistent with  a market structure in which cost-of-service, rate-of-return regulation is replaced  by competition.<P>

<B>Q.	Have any other utilities agreed to make such environmental improvements?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  In connection with the introduction of retail access in Massachusetts  and  Rhode Island, the New England Power Company has agreed to clean-up its fossil  stations to the equivalent of NSR standards by 2010.<P>

<B>Q.	Why have you proposed a shorter time-frame here?</B><BR>
A.	Because the proposed merger poses market power problems not present in the  Massachusetts case.  The Wisconsin Commission should act more swiftly to  address the market power impacts associated with the proposed merger.<P>

<B>Q.	Does this conclude your testimony?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.<P>

<HR>

