<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF JERRY E. MENDL:  Part I
</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<P>
<CENTER><H3>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF JERRY E. MENDL:  Part I
</H3><P>


STATE OF MINNESOTA<BR>
OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE HEARINGS<BR>
FOR THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<P>

<P>

In the Matter of Northern States Power Company's<BR>
Petition for approval to Merge with Wisconsin Energy Corporation<BR>
MPUC Docket No. E,G-002/PA-95-500<BR>
OAH Docket No. 6-2500-10601-2<BR></CENTER>


<P>
<B>Note:</B>  This document is in two parts.  The Part I is the web page that you are now viewing.<P>
<B>Part I.</B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="mendl.html">The potential reduction of the MPUC's regulatory authority in Minnesota, both through possible loss of control to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) and through the increased complexities of coordinating the regulation of multi-state utilities and generation and transmission planning.</A><P>

<B>Part II.</B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="mendl2.html">Increased barriers to the development of demand-side and renewable energy resources and a summary of recommendations</A><P>

<HR>
<B>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF JERRY E. MENDL:  Part I</B><P>
<B>Q.	Please state your name, business address.</B><BR>
A.	I am Jerry E. Mendl.  I am President of MSB Energy Associates, Inc., 7507 Hubbard  Avenue, Suite 200, Middleton, Wisconsin, 53562.<P>

<B>Q.	Have you previously testified before the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (MPUC)?</B><BR>
A.	No.  I have testified before other state utility regulatory commissions including Wisconsin, Michigan, Georgia, Hawaii, District of Columbia, South Carolina, Vermont, Texas, Connecticut, Massachusetts and Maryland. <P>
<B>Q.	What is the purpose of your testimony today?</B><BR>
A.	My testimony demonstrates that the proposed Primergy merger will significantly and adversely affect the public interest in Minnesota.  My testimony should be read in conjunction with that of other witnesses offered by the Environmental Coalition.  The issues I am addressing in my testimony pertain to determining Minnesota jurisdictional merger-related net savings.  Specifically, I am addressing:<P>

<B>I.</B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="mendl.html">The potential reduction of the MPUC's regulatory authority in Minnesota, both through possible loss of control to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) and through the increased complexities of coordinating the regulation of multi-state utilities and generation and transmission planning.</A><P>

<B>II.</B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="mendl2.html">Increased barriers to the development of demand-side and renewable energy resources.</A><P>


<B>Q.	On whose behalf are you testifying?</B><BR>
A.	I am testifying on behalf of the Environmental Coalition, which consists of the Izaak Walton League of America, Minnesotans for an Energy Efficient Economy, and the Environmental Law & Policy Center of the Midwest.<P>

<HR>

<CENTER><H3>Impact of Proposed Merger on State Regulatory Authority</H3><P></CENTER>

<B>Q.	Please summarize your testimony regarding the impact of the proposed merger on the regulatory authority of the MPUC.</B><BR>
A.	The Primergy merger carries an enormous risk that the MPUC's ability to exercise regulatory control over utility matters will be severely compromised.  This means that some of the cost controls which currently exist may not be available after the merger.  Cost increases that result from decreased state regulatory control will reduce the net savings.  Operating cost savings which accrue to utilities are of no net benefit to Minnesota ratepayers if the merger also enables the utilities to pass through excessive costs to the ratepayers.  The MPUC is rightly concerned that the post-merger net savings must be determined in this case, and should consider the risk of its reduced ability to control costs in determining the net savings.<P>

If the MPUC approves the proposed merger, some actions can be taken to mitigate some of the concerns.  However, these actions by no means eliminate all of the risk that the MPUC and the marketplace will be unable to protect the public interest.  Denial of the proposed merger offers the best protection.  <P>
	Many of the power supply functions currently regulated at the retail level by state commissions would be governed by federally-approved wholesale power interchange agreements and service agreements after the merger.  In addition, much closer coordination among state regulatory commissions would be needed to mitigate the loss of individual regulatory oversight and to avoid requests to resolve disputes which could invoke federal pre-emption.<P>

<B>Q.	How does the Interchange Agreement result in an erosion of Minnesota's state regulatory authority?</B><BR>
A.	Under the Interchange Agreement, more costs will fall under authority of the FERC.  The Interchange Agreement establishes a formula for wholesale rates for buying and selling energy and capacity between the Minnesota and Wisconsin portions of Primergy.  Once the formula is in place, traditional state regulatory flexibility and authority are diminished.  After the Primergy merger, the fraction of the revenue requirement of Northern States Power Company (NSP) that may be subject to FERC authority under the interchange agreement will increase dramatically over current conditions.<P>

<B>Q.	How much regulatory authority could Minnesota lose if the proposed Primergy merger takes place?</B><BR>
A.	Using the change in the amount of revenue subject to the MPUC's sole authority as a measure of the change in regulatory authority, I have estimated the potential effect of the proposed merger.  Minnesota's regulatory authority over the NSP-M electric utility drops from 90% of the revenues pre-merger to as little as 28% post-merger.  In contrast, FERC's regulatory authority over the multi-state NSP-M/NSP-W/WEPCo electric systems would increase from 13% of the operating revenues pre-merger to as much as 68% post-merger.<P>

<B>Q.	How did you determine these percentages of revenues subject to regulatory control?</B><BR>
A.	The NSP-M pre-merger percentage was determined by comparing the 1994 payments received under the Interchange Agreement and revenues from wholesale sales with the 1994 NSP-M total electric revenues.  The post-merger percentage was developed by estimating the 1994 revenue which could fall under FERC authority (the Interchange Agreement and wholesale revenues) and comparing it to NSP-M's 1994 total electric revenues.  The derivation of these percentages is shown in Exhibit ___ (JEM-1), Schedule 2.<P>

<B>Q.	What aspects of the Interchange Agreement result in the erosion of state regulatory authority to the FERC?</B><BR>
A.	The Interchange Agreement is designed to equalize the costs of generation and transmission between Primergy's Wisconsin and Minnesota subsidiaries.  The cost allocation formula and payments effectively represent wholesale power exchanges subject to FERC regulations and rates.  In addition, fixed charges, fixed costs and variable costs associated with production and transmission serve both wholesale and retail functions.  At least one-half of the costs of production and transmission will flow directly through the Interchange Agreement.  <P>
	Because the same facilities serve both wholesale and retail load, I have assumed that all production and transmission costs could become subject to FERC authority.  Conflicting regulation with respect to the appropriateness of certain expenses, facilities, etc., could lead to further erosion of state regulatory authority through pre-emption by FERC.  Article XVI of the Interchange Agreement addresses the relationship of affiliated wholesale (equalization purchases between WEC and NSP under the Interchange Agreement) and retail or non-affiliated wholesale proceedings.  <P>
<B>Q.	What are the provisions of Article XVI that lead to further erosion of state regulatory authority?</B><BR>
A.	Article 16.1 states that only three categories of issues can be raised collaterally in the retail or non-affiliated wholesale cases.  These are: i) prudence of costs used to derive charges under the Interchange agreement; ii) the details of the derivation of charges under the Interchange Agreement to the extent that they are not explicitly derived in the Agreement; and iii) the reasonableness of monthly peak demands filed annually to determine the allocation fractions.  Point ii does not appear to permit questioning of the method of calculation if it is set forth explicitly in the Agreement, i.e., a state could not disallow the costs if it believed a different formula should be used to allocate costs than is set out in the Agreement.<P>


<B>Q.	Article 16.1 appears to allow the state regulatory commissions to consider a limited number of significant retail generation and transmission issues.  How does that give rise to further erosion of state regulatory authority to FERC?</B><BR>
A.	Article 16.2 states that if a collateral challenge is brought in a retail proceeding, either NSP or WEC (or any other person with an interest in the matter) may remove it from the retail proceeding and place it before FERC in a proceeding under the Primergy Interchange Agreement.  Article 16.2 provides that "Upon making a filing with the Commission [FERC] to remove an issue to the Commission, the appropriate Primergy Company will take whatever action is necessary to terminate further consideration of the matter in the retail or wholesale proceeding and allow the matter to be determined by the Commission in a proceeding under the Primergy Interchange Agreement."  In other words, it appears that NSP or WEC could invoke pre-emption over retail regulation of the already limited issues identified in Article 16.1.<P>

	Article 16.3 goes on to clarify that any Primergy Interchange Agreement matter (Article 16.1) in a retail proceeding would only affect the retail rates in that proceeding, but would not affect the charges among the Primergy Companies under the Interchange Agreement.  This would probably limit the ability of any state regulatory commission to impose requirements or approve disallowances which impact decisions at the multi-state system level.  <P>

Finally, Article 16.4 clarifies that any matters under the Primergy Interchange Agreement other than those identified in Article 16.1 cannot be raised in a retail proceeding.  <P>
	Taken together, Article XVI limits the issues the state can consider in setting retail rates, limits the effect of those issues only to the state case at hand, and gives the utilities the discretion to remove remaining issues from consideration in a state proceeding to be instead decided in a FERC proceeding.  This is a significant infringement of the current regulatory authority of the MPUC, which is directly attributable to the proposed merger.<P>

<B>Q.	In addition to the risk of reduced state regulatory control over the prudence and allocation of costs already incurred, could the merger also affect planning and construction authorities?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  I believe the proposed merger could also lead to an irrevocable loss of control over energy resource investment and procurement decisions.  This could effectively hamstring the MPUC's and the public's ability to review and revise utility energy resource plans and facilities to assure that the public interest is served.<P>

<B>Q.	Why do you believe that the proposed merger will lead to an irrevocable loss of control over energy resource investment and procurement decisions?</B><BR>
A.	Because NSP, the regulated company, may not be the one making investment and procurement decisions.  The applicants have been inexplicably vague as to where and how decisions would be made.  In response to Data Request Nos. EC-12, EC-13, and EC-14, which asked whether the utility, the Service Company, or another Primergy company would plan for, build, secure or provide generation resources to the utility, the applicants responded that the roles have not yet been determined.  The responses to Data Request Nos. EC-12, EC-13 and EC-14 are attached as Exhibit ___ (JEM-1), Schedule 3.<P>

	I find it incredible that in asking approval for a six billion dollar merger, the applicants have not determined who will be responsible for securing the electricity supplies.  That is a particularly critical issue in this merger application because the degree of regulatory authority able to be exercised by the Commission may vary greatly with the Primergy companies' post-merger structure and functions.<P>

<B>Q.	Why does it matter whether NSP makes its own investment and procurement decisions?</B><BR>
A.	Being the regulated public utility serving retail loads, this arrangement most closely parallels the pre-merger regulatory authority.  If a company not regulated in Minnesota calls the shots regarding investment and procurement of electricity supplies, and the Interchange Agreement allocates costs which must be passed through to NSP ratepayers, the Minnesota regulators are effectively removed from their historic role of approving, rejecting or modifying utility plans and facilities. <P>
	Even if NSP is the decision maker in Minnesota, and WEC is the decision maker in Wisconsin, the Interchange Agreement calls for an allocation of costs to NSP for generation secured by WEC in Wisconsin, which again reduces the effectiveness of the MPUC's ability to control NSP's costs.  At best, this independent utility paradigm requires much coordination between NSP and WEC to assure that planning and securing energy supplies are done efficiently, especially because NSP and WEC would be subject to parallel but equal regulation by Minnesota and Wisconsin.<P>

<B>Q.	Is there any reason to believe that NSP will not be the entity responsible for planning, building, securing or providing its own generation resources?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  Aside from NSP's statement that its role in the resource procurement process has not been determined, the Service Agreement identifies a role for the Service Company which suggests that the Service Company would have a key role.<P>

<B>Q.	What is the Service Agreement?</B><BR>
A.	The Service Agreement is an integral part of the merger which sets forth a financial and service relationship between the Service Company, NSP and WEC, all subsidiaries of Primergy.  <P>
<B>Q.	What kinds of services will the Service Company provide to NSP and WEC?</B><BR>
A.	The Service Company will be able to provide a variety of services to NSP and WEC according to the Service Agreement.  Notably, these include i) coordinating the planning, procurement, optimization and support for the generation, transmission and distribution systems, and ii) provision of energy services including market product and program development and demand-side management administration, and marketing strategic planning and research.  Coupled with the other services provided, it appears that the Service Company staff will consist of much of the technical professional staff formerly housed at NSP-M, NSP-W and WEPCo.  The Service Company is likely to be a key player in Primergy's investment and procurement decisions.  <P>
	This will reduce the MPUC's ability to control costs (before they are incurred).  When coupled with the MPUC's reduced ability to disallow costs after they are incurred, the likely long-term impact of the merger is to decrease regulatory controls at the same time the utilities are increasing their market power.  This is a recipe for higher customer costs, and is not in the public interest.<P>
<B>Q.	What can be done to minimize the loss of state regulatory authority?</B><BR>
A.	The MPUC could:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Deny the proposed merger application, or<P>

<LI>Condition the approval of the merger application on the formation of a single regulated multi-state utility rather than two subsidiary utilities.  This would mimic WEPCo's current structure, with service territory in Michigan and Wisconsin rather than the current NSP-M/NSP-W relationship.  This corporate structure would eliminate the Interchange Agreement and not risk invoking FERC regulatory authority as there would simply be allocations of costs within the single corporate entity rather than wholesale sales between two affiliated entities, and<P>

<LI>Require Primergy to obtain MPUC approval of all agreements prior to the filing of any such agreement at FERC and obtain SEC approval for this general requirement.<P>
</OL>

<B>Q.	Could the loss of state regulatory authority be minimized by conditioning the approval of the merger application on the revision or elimination of Article XVI to give the states more regulatory authority?</B><BR>
A.	I do not believe this to be a viable approach because the underlying corporate structure might provide a basis for FERC authority to pre-empt state regulation.<P>

<B>Q.	In addition to the erosion of state regulatory authority to FERC, are there other state regulatory issues which the MPUC should address its consideration of the proposed merger application?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  There are several other ways in which the merger could confound state regulation and the ability of state commissions to apply traditional regulatory approaches, including at least the following:<P>
<OL>
<LI>The merged utility is a much larger entity, increasing the amount of resources available to advance its positions and the amount of political influence it can muster.<P>

<LI>The merged utility extends across state boundaries, necessitating improved coordination between regulatory commissions in different jurisdictions regarding planning and day-to-day operations.<P>

<LI>Equity and cross subsidization issues between jurisdictions may arise, and should be coordinated between regulatory commissions.  These apply to the rates charged to the same customer class in different jurisdictions, relative rate differentials between customer classes between jurisdictions, and the relative availability of programs for low-income customers and demand-side measures among jurisdictions.<P>
</OL>
<B>Q.	Why would the merged utility's size be a factor in the effectiveness of continued state level regulation?</B><BR>
A.	There are two reasons.  First, the merged utility will have increased size, increased revenues, and increased influence at the commissions and the legislatures.  The amount of resources available to a utility to present a case before the commission dwarfs that available to any intervenors or the commission staff, even prior to the merger.  The merger will only magnify the disparity.  <P>
	Second, as a further complication, while the utility is speaking with a single voice throughout all jurisdictions, intervenors and regulatory staffs in different jurisdictions may hold different, and even contradictory, positions.   While the merger consolidates the utility positions and increases available resources to win them, the regulatory staffs and intervenors will probably remain fragmented because of the expense and difficulty of coordinating independent and distantly located groups.  One can easily imagine such situations -- Minnesota regulators may support a utility proposed transmission improvement in Wisconsin because it is the cheapest way to increase transfer capacity needed for off-system sales, Wisconsin regulatory staff may oppose it because there is a more expensive proposal that better balances environmental concerns with economics, Wisconsin landowners may oppose both proposals because the project is not needed for local needs but benefits wholesale customers outside Wisconsin, while Minnesota environmental intervenors may not get involved because of inadequate budgets to deal with out-of-state issues.  <P>
<B>Q.	Turning now to your concern about state regulatory coordination, what kind of planning issues will confront the MPUC as a result of the proposed merger?</B><BR>
A.	The merger will require increased regulatory coordination of generation and transmission planning and facility approval issues, especially between Minnesota and Wisconsin.  The vast majority of the load served by Primergy is in Minnesota and Wisconsin, and it is likely that regulatory interests and concerns in those states will dominate.  Michigan, North Dakota, and South Dakota are likely to play a lesser, though possibly significant role.  <P>
	Failing to coordinate among all of the jurisdictions, but especially Minnesota and Wisconsin, could result in conflicting plans, stalemated projects, and possibly FERC pre-emption through the Interchange Agreement.  A similar situation occurred in connection with the denial of the application for the proposed Tyrone Nuclear Power Plant by the Public Service Commission of Wisconsin (PSCW).  In that case, Minnesota regulators wanted Wisconsin ratepayers to bear the design, application and other costs associated with the PSCW-terminated project.  FERC, and ultimately the courts ruled in favor of the allocation under the Interchange Agreement.  <P>
	The opportunity for conflict among the state regulatory agencies is greatly enhanced by the merger because the merger increases the interest in actions taken in the other state.  After the merger, Minnesota ratepayers will be strongly affected by actions taken in Wisconsin and vice versa because Primergy's Minnesota and Wisconsin subsidiaries are of equal size and costs will be equalized under the Interchange Agreement.<P>

<B>Q.	Is there an increased need for coordination among state regulators from an operational perspective as well?</B><BR>
A.	Yes, from an operational perspective, the merger will create the opportunity to jointly dispatch generating units that were previously separately dispatched.  It will also create a single transmission entity which can transport power from North Dakota to Illinois and allow a more direct access to power from Manitoba Hydro.  All of these operational opportunities are dependent on the existence of adequate transmission capacity, and thus have transmission planning implications as well.<P>


<B>Q.	What state regulatory issues may arise from the operation of the merged utilities?</B> <BR>
A.	There are many possible state regulatory issues regarding opportunities for operational changes resulting from the merger.  First, each state commission must determine whether the utility is making use of all its opportunities to reduce retail customer costs in its jurisdiction.  For example, state regulatory commissions will have to determine whether the merged company is economically dispatching the combined power plants, and if not, whether there are transmission or other physical limitations preventing economic dispatch.  There may be planning or operational guides that improve the opportunities, and those would have to be addressed by each jurisdiction.  Ultimately, there will be cost and siting/location issues that need to be coordinated -- e.g., who pays for the less-than-economic dispatch, who benefits from improved dispatch, who pays for the physical improvements, and how are environmental impacts mitigated?  Mitigation of environmental impacts is potentially very difficult because situations could arise in which the jurisdiction in which construction was planned could determine that the economic benefits of the project were inadequate to offset the environmental impacts; while other jurisdictions would only receive the economic benefits.  Additionally, environmental authority and siting standards vary from state to state, which may make it difficult for a state with lower standards to pay more to build a facility in another state to meet higher standards than it would itself require.  Finally, controversial issues such as nuclear plant relicensing, regional and on-site spent fuel storage, spent fuel transportation, and decommissioning may also trigger conflict among regulators from different states.<P>
<B>Q.	What potential equity and cross subsidization issues should state regulators, including the MPUC anticipate as a result of the merger?</B><BR>
A.	Equity and cross subsidy issues between jurisdictions may arise at two levels.  The first may involve disputes over the allocation of costs under the Interchange Agreement between the Wisconsin company (including Wisconsin and Michigan) and the Minnesota company (including Minnesota, North Dakota and South Dakota).  The Interchange Agreement would be subject to FERC approval, and cost allocations subject to the agreement would be pre-empted by the FERC.  Nonetheless, cost allocation issues would need to be addressed by the states before FERC at the time the new interchange agreement was being considered by FERC and at any time thereafter that a request is made to modify the agreement.  The states could coordinate to achieve mutual regulatory objectives, or may initiate a petition to FERC to resolve disputes among the states.<P>

<B>Q.	What is the second level at which equity and cross subsidy issues may arise?</B><BR>
A.	The second level pertains to real and perceived differences in rates and services offered by Primergy in each of the jurisdictions.  Once the costs are allocated under the Interchange Agreement, and any other jurisdiction-specific adjustments to revenue requirement made, the rates will be set in each jurisdiction.  To the extent that rate levels differ for a given customer class from jurisdiction to jurisdiction, that may result in demands by customers for modifying the rates.  Similarly, one state adopting innovative new rate designs would put the pressure on other states to modify their rate designs as well.  Even if rates overall are reduced as a result of the merger, certain customer groups in some jurisdictions may experience rate increases.<P>

	Equity in regards to customer programs could also become an issue.  If the utility offered different energy efficiency or load control programs in different states, there could be an adverse reaction by those not receiving the programs.  The same could hold true for low-income programs, economic development programs, customer assistance (e.g., budget billing) and the like. <P>
	The inverse situation could also occur, in which a state might find that certain programs should be implemented by the utility to save system costs.  To the extent that other jurisdictions do not require those programs, system costs will be higher.  To the extent that all jurisdictions share in the system costs, the state implementing the programs will have a basis to argue that other states are unfairly burdening its ratepayers by not requiring the programs.  In essence, system costs are higher than they should and could be as a result of the inaction by other states.<P>

<B>Q.	If the MPUC is inclined to approve the merger application, have you any recommendations for it to consider?</B><BR>
A.	It is evident that coordination among the state regulatory agencies will need to be substantially expanded in the event of the Primergy merger.  To achieve that coordination, I recommend that:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Prior to deciding the merger, the MPUC initiate discussions with other affected jurisdictions to determine the possibility for effective multi-state coordinated regulation.  The discussions should include:<P>
<UL>
<LI>The statutory requirements for each jurisdiction.  Of particular interest will be statutes regarding facility (generation, transmission, distribution) planning, facility construction approval (pre-approval) requirements, environmental impact, consumer impact/protection, and automatic fuel cost adjustment clauses.<P>

<LI>Regulatory roles and practices of the commission, energy office, environmental agency, and other agencies in each jurisdiction.<P>

<LI>Statutory and procedural conflicts among the agencies be identified, and a revised process be defined which eliminates or mitigates the conflicts be developed.  This may require legislative action.<P>

<LI>Relevant agency objectives (e.g., rate design principles) and precedents established by past regulatory decisions.  Compare among jurisdictions and flag potential conflicts.<P>

<LI>Mechanism for sharing information, identifying potential conflicts and solutions, and coordinating decisions (including schedules and substantive issues).<P>

<LI>The establishment of a single multi-state integrated resource plan process.<P>
</UL>
<LI>If the MPUC approves the proposed merger, the order should be conditioned to require Primergy to provide intervenor funding to assist affected intervenor groups in various jurisdictions to coordinate amongst themselves and to participate in relevant regulatory proceedings.<BR>
</OL>
<HR>
