<html><head><title>Coal Plants in the Neighborhood:  Stopping Increased Air Pollution From the NSP Merger</title></head><body BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><p>
<p>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Coal Plants in the Neighborhood:<BR>  Stopping Increased Air Pollution From the NSP Merger</H2>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>By Kevin P. Bengston, Michael Noble, and J. Drake Hamilton</H4>
<H5 ALIGN=CENTER>September 1996</H5><p>

<b>Preface</b><p>
	How will the proposed merger between Northern States Power (NSP) and Wisconsin Energy Corporation (WEC) affect air pollution in Minnesota's Metropolitan area?
In NSP's view, "There is no indication that the proposed merger will lead to
increased harmful emissions from applicants' coal-fired facilities."<a
href="coalreportfn.html#fn0">[1]</a>  Most utility experts, however,
would disagree.  According to an analysis conducted for the National
Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners, "Industry restructuring will
likely result in competitive pressures to increase the operation of currently
underutilized coal facilities with relatively high emissions, and to extend the
operation lives of these facilities."<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn1">[2]</a>  Is NSP right, or is their proposal apt to result
in increased operations and increased pollution from power plants in and around
the Twin Cities?  This paper answers those questions by presenting the reasons
why the NSP/WEC merger, if it is approved, will almost inevitably result in
increased pollution from coal plants in the seven-county metropolitan area.  In
addition, simple mitigation strategies will be suggested that can be ordered by
the Minnesota Public Utility Commission or the legislature as a condition of
the merger.<p>


<b>I.  Merger Background and Potential for Increased Pollution</b><p>

<i>The Announcement of the Merger</i><p>
	On July 10, 1995, NSP announced that it would merge with WEC to form a new
entity:  Primergy Corporation.  The merger has already been approved by
regulators in North Dakota and Michigan, but it still must be approved by the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC), the Minnesota Public Utility
Commission (MPUC) and the Public Service Commission of Wisconsin.  Approval
relies on the ability of NSP and WEC to prove that the merger is "consistent
with the public interest."<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn2">[3]</a><p>




<i>Stimulus for the Merger</i><p>
	What brought about the proposal for the merger?  In the past year, thirteen
large utilities have proposed mergers, and rumors abound for many more.<a
href="coalreportfn.html#fn3">[4]</a>  The primary stimulus for mergers
comes from increasing competition in the electric industry.  At present,
proposals exist in a number of states that would allow large electricity
consumers to choose their electricity providers.<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn4">[5]</a>  Although deregulation has not yet occurred,
utilities are preparing for competition by following the very first step they
learned in Business 101--cutting costs.  NSP projects that it will save almost
$2 billion between 1997 and 2006.<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn5">[6]</a><p>
	The merger will also allow the company to expand its influence over the
market.  Currently, NSP and WEC are the largest utilities in Minnesota and
Wisconsin, respectively.  If joined, Primergy would serve 2.3 million customers
and would be the 10th largest investor-owned utility in the nation.<a
href="coalreportfn.html#fn6">[7]</a>  The new company would control a
majority of generation, transmission, and local distribution of electricity in
two states.  Perry Brown, senior economist for FERC, opposes the merger unless
steps are taken to prevent Primergy from having too much power and control in
the Upper Midwest.<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn7">[8]</a>  NSP states
that the merger will not inhibit competition.  According to NSP and WEC, the
merger will give the new company "the ability to take advantage of synergistic
opportunities related to the creation of Primergy."<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn8">[9]</a> <p>

<i>A Synergy of Factors will Increase Coal Emissions</i><p>
	Contrary to the private benefits of the synergy hailed by NSP, Minnesotans for
an Energy-Efficient Economy believes that there will be significant damage to
the public from the synergy of other factors.  Three factors will combine to
have a negative impact on pollution emissions in metropolitan Minnesota:  the
merger; rate differentials between Primergy's rates and those charged in
surrounding states; and increasing competition in the utility industry.  Of
these, the only factor within Minnesota's control is whether to approve the
Primergy merger and, if so, under what conditions.<p>
	NSP's main argument for the merger is that Minnesotans will enjoy low rates,<a
href="coalreportfn.html#fn9">[10]</a> but potentially the greatest
savings will go to new customers outside the combined NSP/WEC system.  The
Minnesota public, especially urban dwellers, will be stuck with costly
increases in harmful air emissions as a result of Primergy sales in new
off-system markets.<p>




<b>II.  NSP's Metropolitan Coal Plants:  Capacity Factors</b><p>

	NSP has four coal plants in the metro area that have significant potential to
increase generation.  The plants have several common characteristics, the most
important being that they are all aging, coal-burning generators operating in
densely-populated areas.  Table 1, "Metropolitan Coal Plants," identifies the
key features of the plants.<p>

<b>Table 1:  Metropolitan Coal Plants</b>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD>Plant</TD><TD>Location</TD><TD>Year*</TD><TD>Capacity (MW)</TD><TD>Main Fuel (type of coal)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>High Bridge</TD><TD>St. Paul (Ramsey Co.)</TD><TD>1944</TD><TD>325</TD><TD>Sub-bituminous</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Riverside</TD><TD>Minneapolis (Hennepin County)</TD><TD>1964</TD><TD>370</TD><TD>Sub-bituminous</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Black Dog </TD><TD>Burnsville (Dakota Co.) </TD><TD>1952</TD><TD> 524</TD><TD>Sub-bituminous</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Allen S. King</TD><TD>Bayport (Washington Co.)</TD><TD>1968</TD><TD>550</TD><TD>Sub-bituminous</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

* Denotes the year that the oldest operating generating unit was installed.<p>

	The most common indicator used to show operating characteristics is the
capacity factor.  The capacity factor expresses how much electricity a plant is
actually generating as a percentage of its total capability.  The equation to
calculate the capacity factor is shown below:<p>

<b>Capacity Factor (%) =	Annual Generation (Megawatt-hours)/
Rated Capacity (Megawatts) X 8760 (Hours per Year)</b><p>

	A graph of capacity factors can be found in Figure 1, "NSP Metro Coal Plant
Capacity Factors versus National Average."  This graph clearly shows that the
High Bridge, Black Dog and Riverside facilities are being operated at levels
consistently below the national average.<p>


<b>Figure 1:  NSP Metro Coal Plant Capacity Factors versus National
Average</b><BR>
(Expressed as a %)<p>
<IMG SRC="coalfig1.GIF"><p>
	Capacity factors can be found in Table 2, "NSP Coal Plant Capacity Factors."
The operating characteristics of NSP's coal plants are atypical of the modern
coal plant.  Modern coal plants are used to provide baseload electricity and
have high capacity factors--70% to 80%.  With the exception of the Allen S.
King and Sherburne County plants, none of NSP's coal plants are presently used
as baseload plants.  The Black Dog and High Bridge plants have particularly low
capacity factors, not even reaching 50%.  While these plants are not currently
being used to provide baseload electricity, past performance does not preclude
NSP from operating these plants at 70%-80% of capacity.<p>
<p>

<b>Table 2:  NSP Coal Plant Capacity Factors</b><a href="coalreportfn.html#fn10">[11]</a><BR>
(Expressed as a %)
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
