<TR><TD>Avg.</TD><TD>28.0</TD><TD>34.3</TD><TD>56.7</TD><TD>65.9</TD><TD>60.9</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<p>
	These numbers clearly indicate an enormous potential to produce and sell more
electricity from these plants.  NSP Chief Executive Officer Jim Howard does not
deny that increased output could occur from these plants, and has stated, "If
increased output occurs, it will be a result of increased demand, not the
merger."<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn11">[12]</a> <p>
	The question is not, "Will demand increase?"  The question is, "With the
merger and its `synergistic opportunities', how much will demand increase?"
Since the main function of an investor-owned utility is to provide a return to
its shareholders, NSP will have every incentive to build demand in order to
increase the profitability of the company.  Shareholders have a right to expect
nothing less than maximum operations of old plants if the electricity is
competitive in new markets.<p>
<p>

<b>III.  Primergy's Incentive to Produce More Electricity</b><p>

	Will NSP's coal plants be competitive in new out-of-state markets?  The
opportunities presented by the merger, regional rate differences and increased
competition would encourage Primergy to produce and sell more electricity.
Figure 2, "New Territories and Markets," shows possible avenues for how power
will flow between regional power networks in a deregulated environment.  The
flows are based on the market clearing prices, excess generation capacity, and
demand for electricity.  As can be seen in the chart, electricity from the
Mid-Continent Area Power Pool (MAPP) is cheaper to produce and will therefore
be sold to utility customers in the Mid-America Interconnected Network (MAIN)
and the Southwest Power Pool (SPP) even though excess capacity exists in those
markets.<p>
<p>
	Table 3, "Rate Differentials--NSP and WEC Compared to Average Rates in
Adjacent States," looks more closely at several states in the MAPP, MAIN and
SPP areas.  The table shows that Primergy would have a significant cost
advantage over the average utility in eight states.  This advantage will
continue, inasmuch as NSP has already stated that it proposes to reduce
customer electric rates by 1.5% and freeze these rates for 4 years.  Adding to
the rate advantage would be a merged transmission system that could facilitate
the delivery of electricity into new markets.<p>
<b>Table 3</b><p>
<b>"Rate Differentials :  NSP and WEC Compared to Average Rates in Adjacent States."</b><a href="coalreportfn.html#fn12">[13]</a>
(1993)

<pre>
  Primergy      (Cents/KWH)           Adjacent States    (Cents/KWH)    
NSP - MN            5.6               Illinois               7.8        
NSP - WI            5.8               Michigan               7.1        
WEC                 5.7               Kansas                 6.6        
                                      Missouri               6.3        
                                      South Dakota           6.2        
                                      Ohio                   6.2        
                                      Iowa                   6.0        
                                      North Dakota           5.8        

</pre>

<b>Figure 2, "New Territories and Markets"</b><a href="coalreportfn.html#fn13">[14]</a><p>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=2>Due to issues related to formatting Figure 2 is not yet available electronically, sorry.</FONT><p>

	Some observers may predict that increased demand will be met by
relatively clean new gas-fired combined-cycle turbines.  Indeed, the
availability of these low-cost new technologies drives industrial customers
demand for cheaper energy and creates pressure for a more competitive
electricity industry.  However, Figure 3, "Operating Cost Comparison:  NSP's
Coal Plants Versus New Gas Plants," shows that NSP's existing plants are
cheaper to operate than new gas-fired combined-cycle power plants.<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn14">[15]</a>  The two curves on the graph represent
estimates of the cost of these new gas plants at different capacities.  Even at
the lowest cost, both General Electric (GE) and the Electric Power Research
Institute (EPRI) agree that new gas turbines cannot compete with NSP's old coal
plants.  Thus, if NSP did face a scenario of increased demand, it would be
cheaper to increase the output from existing coal units rather than build gas
combined cycle plants.<p>

<b>Figure 3, "Operating Cost Comparison: NSP's Coal Plants Versus New Gas Plants"</b><a href="coalreportfn.html#fn15">[16]</a><BR>
(1994 Fuel and O&amp;M in Cents/KWH)<p>
<IMG SRC="coalfig3.GIF"><p>



<b>IV.  Pollution Emissions from NSP's Coal Plants</b><p>
<p>
	Emissions from NSP's metropolitan coal plants are extraordinarily high
compared to current standards governing new power plants.  Old plants do not
need to meet the pollution control standards of new plants.  Figure 4, "NSP
Coal Plant Emissions per Net Generation," compares the four older NSP coal
plants to a newer NSP coal plant in Sherburne County, the "SherCo plant",
installed from 1976 to 1987.  The graph shows the significant pollution
reduction of new technologies and new emission standards.  If the older coal
plants reach the high utilization of SherCo (71.6% capacity), pollution
increases would be dramatic.  According to Mike Hernandez, plant manager at
High Bridge, "If the output (of the plant) were to increase...emission
quantities would increase in
proportion to the increase in output."<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn16">[17]</a><i>  </i>Incredibly, in its argument before the Minnesota Public Utility Commission, NSP defies this logic.<p>


<b>Figure 4, "NSP Coal Plant Emissions per Net Generation"</b>
(Tons/GWH)<P>
<P>

<IMG SRC="coalfig4.GIF"><p>

In its response to intervenor comments on the merger, NSP states, "Even if the
Commission (MPUC) were to assume the merged entity will increase output at its
coal-fired facilities, the [environmental] coalition<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn17">[18]</a> gives no reason to conclude an increase in net
emissions would result."<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn18">[19]</a>
Arguably, what NSP means by this is that if generation does increase at the
metro plants, the power generated will displace some other power plant's
generation--for instance, a Commonwealth Edison plant--thus, there would be no
net increase in pollution.  However, even if no net increase in pollution
occurs, this scenario creates a tradeoff of pollution between one geographical
region and another.  The Twin Cities Metro area would experience a net increase
in emissions while the Chicago area would experience a net decrease.  Such a
tradeoff is not compatible with Minnesotans' interest in clean air.<p>

	Table 4, "NSP Coal Plant Emissions, 1990-1995,"<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn19">[20]</a> shows the total annual plant emissions by
pollutant, and the method used to derive that number.<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn20">[21]</a>  An immediately noticeable feature of Table 4 is
the yearly variation in emissions.  Several factors can explain the cause of
such variation.  First, the capacity factor strongly influences plant
emissions.  Simply put, the more often a plant runs, the more pollution it will
emit.  Second, the method used to calculate emissions can cause wide variation,
especially if the same method is not used annually.<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn21">[22]</a>  Finally, emissions vary due to changes in
control equipment or changes in the type of coal used.  According to the
Minnesota Pollution Control Agency, the only significant change in control
equipment on metro plants was an improvement at Black Dog during 1995.  The
type of coal used, low-sulfur sub-bituminous, has not significantly changed
over the past five years.  Despite these explanations, there remain serious
unexplained anomalies in the data record, especially as it relates to
particulates less than 10 microns in size.  A 1996 study of 239 metropolitan
areas by the Natural Resources Defense Council estimates 64,000 people may die
prematurely from heart and lung disease each year due to particulates.<a
href="coalreportfn.html#fn22">[23]</a><p>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1><caption><h3>Table 4, "NSP Coal Plant Emissions, 1990-1995" (Tons)</h3></caption>

