<B>Key:</B><P>
<B>Pollutants</B><BR>
NOx-Oxides of Nitrogen (Leads to visibility impairment and regional haze problems)<BR>
PB-Lead (Contaminates soil and lakes--if ingested could lead to health problems for humans)<BR>
PM10-Particulate Matter smaller than 10 Microns (Leads to visibility problems, health problems for humans, premature mortality)<BR>
SOx-Oxides of Sulfur  (Causes acid rain and leads to visibility problems)<BR>
VOC-Volatile Organic Compounds (Contaminates soil and lakes--if ingested could lead to health problems for humans)<BR><BR>

**Greenhouse Gases and Mercury emissions are not tracked by the PCA since they are not criteria pollutants under the Clean Air Act<P>
<B>Methods </B><BR>
Test-Stack Test<BR>
AP-42  Environmental Protection Agency calculation method<BR>
CEM - Continuous Emissions Monitoring<P>


<b>V.  Mitigating Increased Emissions </b><p>

	Regional rate differences, aging coal plants and the availability of capacity
are key factors that could lead to increased pollution emissions for the metro
area and neighborhoods that host coal plants.  When paired with the synergistic opportunities of the merger and competitive pressures, the increase in emissions appears inevitable.  Therefore, the merger as proposed is not compatible with the public interest and according to Minnesota statute should be denied by the Minnesota Public Utility Commission.  Steps must be taken before the merger is approved to eliminate potential increased emissions from coal power plants in Minnesota's metropolitan area.<p>
	The Minnesota Public Utility Commission, or the Minnesota legislature could
require that no increase in emissions result from the merger by placing an
"emissions cap" on NSP for several years.  This would require NSP/Primergy to
refrain from "ramping up" its old metro coal plants, and seek to free up
capacity to serve new markets by increased conservation in Minnesota.
Alternatively, NSP/Primergy could develop additional renewables and
low-emission sources such as cogeneration if it seeks new-supply sources to
serve out-of-state markets.  Both wind-power development and NSP's cogeneration
agreement with Rosemount's Koch Refining offer ample examples of opportunities
to build low-cost power without negative local impacts from pollution.<p>
	An alternate strategy is to require that all the old Primergy coal power
plants be refurbished to reach New Source Review standards (NSR).<a href="coalreportfn.html#fn23">[24]</a>  In other words, if the merger is
approved, the metro power plants might run full tilt, but at least they would
be as efficient and clean as the newer technology at SherCo.<p>
	Each of these options is fully available to Minnesota regulators and
lawmakers.  They should exercise their authority to protect the public interest
by stopping the risk of increased pollution from coal plants in our metro
neighborhoods.<p>

<HR>
ME3 would like to thank Carol Andrews and Dana Abbott Vanderbosch, MN Pollution Control Agency;  Susan Hedman, Environmental Law and Policy Center;  Bill Grant, Izaak Walton League of America;  Gayle Betcher and Nancy Stafki, Northern States Power Company;  Lee Olson, West St. Paul Neighborhood Environmental Committee;  Carol Neuman, NOSHAMS;  Steve Corneli, MN Office of Attorney General;  and Ray Warner for their input and perspective in developing the paper.  ME3 is solely responsible for the final product.  <P>
