<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<P>
<CENTER><H3>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF JERRY E. MENDL:  Part II
</H3><P>


STATE OF MINNESOTA<BR>
OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE HEARINGS<BR>
FOR THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<P>

<P>

In the Matter of Northern States Power Company's<BR>
Petition for approval to Merge with Wisconsin Energy Corporation<BR>
MPUC Docket No. E,G-002/PA-95-500<BR>
OAH Docket No. 6-2500-10601-2<BR></CENTER>


<P>
<B>Note:</B>  This document is in two parts.  The Part II is the web page that you are now viewing.<P>
<B>Part I.</B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="mendl.html">The potential reduction of the MPUC's regulatory authority in Minnesota, both through possible loss of control to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) and through the increased complexities of coordinating the regulation of multi-state utilities and generation and transmission planning.</A><P>

<B>Part II.</B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="mendl2.html">Increased barriers to the development of demand-side and renewable energy resources and a summary of recommendations</A><P>

<HR>
<B>DIRECT TESTIMONY OF JERRY E. MENDL: Part II</B><P>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Impact of Proposed Merger on Demand-Side and Renewable Resources</H3><P>

<B>Q.	Please explain the relationship between the impact of the proposed merger on demand-side and renewable resources and the MPUC's issue regarding the net-savings associated with the proposed merger.</B><BR>
A.	The proposed merger can increase the barriers to demand-side and renewable resources.  By increasing barriers, fewer demand-side and renewable resources are likely to be implemented, which will increase the cost for electric energy services to utility customers and reduce the net savings of the proposed merger.  The MPUC should consider the risk that the merger will result in less installation of demand side and renewable resources when determining the net savings associated with the merger.<P>

<B>Q.	In what ways could the proposed merger create barriers to demand-side and renewable resources?</B><BR>
A.	Barriers to demand-side and renewable resources can result from the merger because:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Primergy would have more ability to control access by or to these resources.  For renewables, a prime concern would be the control of transmission access which would prevent, or make less dependable, the provision of energy by renewable suppliers on the wholesale market.<BR>
  	For demand-side resources, a major barrier to non-affiliated demand-side resource providers results if affiliated providers have access to customer information and coordinated billing services (e.g., shared savings) which is denied to non-affiliated providers.  This is a concern given the proposed structure in which the Service Company may provide metering, billing and research services to NSP and WEC.  In addition, customers learn about demand-side resources by word of mouth from friends and neighbors.  A larger entity will insulate more customers from the competitive pressures that often occur at the edges of service territories where customers see other approaches being used.<P>

<LI>Primergy would have more ability to control prices.  The proposed merger consolidates two potential competitors which in itself has the potential to result in increased prices.  Other witnesses are addressing the full spectrum of market power issues which may increase the price of electricity.  The ability to control prices will cause a chilling effect on demand-side and renewable resource providers because the merged utility can undercut prices to thwart competition.  The so-called "cogeneration rates" adopted in many locations are a good example of a utility deeply discounting its rates to prevent cogenerators from locating in the service area.  Allowing non-utility developers to expend significant money and time to design projects/resources with utility customers only to have the utility offer the customer a deeply discounted rate when the "threat of competition" from the non-utility resource is credible has a powerful adverse effect on the climate for implementing non-utility resources.  This is especially true if the utility is able to recover all or part of the revenue lost associated with the discount from other customers, or if the lost revenue is collected through monopoly above-market prices.<P>

	As I addressed earlier, the role of the Service Company is not precisely defined, but may include the procurement of power supplies and demand-side resources for NSP and WEC.  If the procurement processes were not subject to regulatory oversight, it is possible that the processes could be biased against non-affiliated renewable energy and demand-side resource providers.  The MPUC should assure that a fair and equitable bidding process is employed, especially if the Service Company procures energy resources for WEC and NSP.<P>

<LI>Primergy would require a complex multi-state regulatory approach as discussed earlier in my testimony.  Demand-side and renewable resource activities in a multi-state utility affect electric system costs, allocations of costs among the jurisdictions, and benefits from demand-side and renewable sources.  The need to coordinate and develop consistent approaches to demand-side and renewable resource policy over a multi-state area complicates regulatory actions and creates barriers to regulator-induced utility demand-side and renewable programs.  <P>

	Because renewable resources would be planned and procured on a Primergy systemwide basis, the MPUC could have reduced ability to order additional renewable resources to be implemented.  This could apply to both expanding  reliance on current technologies and to taking advantage of evolving technologies.  <P>
<B>Q.	Would the proposed rate freeze mitigate your concerns about the ability of Primergy to control electricity prices to increase their profitability and undercut competitors?</B><BR>
A.	No.  The rate freeze extends through the year 2000.  At that time, if the merger is approved as proposed, the MPUC could have much less regulatory authority, and less ability to protect ratepayer interests, than it currently has.  Long-term prices well in excess of reasonable cost could result. <BR>
	In addition, the rate freeze proposal actually heightens my concerns because it creates incentives for the utility to not engage in implementing demand-side and renewable resource programs.   The promise of a rate freeze should not buy the MPUC's approval of the merger.  <P>
<B>Q.	Why does a rate freeze result in utility incentives adverse to demand-side and renewable resources?</B><BR>
A.	A rate freeze can easily result in increased average customer bills, and increased utility revenues beyond those necessary to recover costs.  By terminating demand-side resource programs and promoting sales growth, Primergy can increase its revenues and net short-term profits during the freeze period.  <P>
	A rate freeze implies at least frozen demand-side and renewable resource programs, since new money will not be available during the course of the freeze period to initiate and expand programs.  Second, a rate freeze creates an incentive to curtail programs because this creates an opportunity to increase revenues.  With rates frozen, revenues can be increased over the entire freeze period by promoting sales growth, or eliminating programs which reduce sales.  The utility will not spend money to reduce sales and reduce revenues over the next four-year freeze period if it can increase sales to increase short term revenues.  Third, the rate freeze shelters the utility from public scrutiny, as WEPCo and NSP-W have already successfully done in Michigan.  If the merger savings are greater than anticipated, or if the cost trends were decreasing without the merger, the rate freeze would overcollect without detection.  The extra revenues could be used to thwart non-utility competitors as discussed above.  Finally, the focus on rates is much more limited than the multi-faceted long-term public interest perspective (e.g., considering customer bills, reliability, environmental effects, etc.) embodied in Minnesota's resource planning and conservation improvement planning processes. <P>
<B>Q.	What are the intentions of the applicants regarding the continuation and expansion of demand-side resource programs after the merger?</B><BR>
A.	The applicants have not decided what level of demand-side resources they will implement after the merger.  In response to Data Request No. EC-1, the applicants state:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>No final decisions have been made about energy efficiency programs WEC and NSP will operate in the period 1997-2000.  However, it is anticipated that WEC will continue to offer the programs Wisconsin Electric and NSP-W plan to offer in their service territories in 1997.  It is also anticipated that NSP will offer the programs NSP-M plans to offer in its service territory in 1997.  <B>No decisions have been made for subsequent years.</B> (Emphasis added)<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

	In response to Data Request Nos. EC-6 and EC-7, NSP-M indicated that the most recently approved energy efficiency programs in Minnesota for the post-merger period were in the 1993 Resource Plan.  NSP-M is seeking approval for its 1995 Resource Plan, which shows scaled back energy efficiency programs.  A comparison of the 1993 and 1995 Resource Plan levels of projected DSM impacts is shown in Exhibit ___ (JEM-1), Schedule 4.  NSP-M has no energy efficiency programs planned in North or South Dakota.  <P>
<B>Q.	Is it a serious concern that the applicants have not decided on the post-merger levels of demand-side resources they intend to implement?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  NSP-M has an approved resource plan containing demand-side resources, and it has a proposed resource plan with about a 60% reduction in energy savings from demand-side resources.  NSP-M's apparent unwillingness to commit itself to any level of demand-side resources, either the approved level or even the lower requested level, after the merger is of great concern.  <P>
<B>Q.	Is this a merger issue?  Or would the applicants have been similarly non-committal regarding demand-side resources in the 1997-2006 time period without the proposed merger?</B><BR>
A.	This is clearly a merger issue.  While applicants may have proposed modifying, curtailing or eliminating their demand-side resource programs in the absence of the proposed merger, the potential loss of state regulatory authority resulting from the merger will make it much more difficult for the Department of Public Service, the MPUC and interested parties to assure that appropriate levels of demand-side resources continue to be implemented.  One should not assume that NSP-M will not take advantage of any softening of state regulatory authority to require implementation of demand-side resources.  Where not mandated (in North and South Dakota), NSP-M has no programs to implement demand-side resources.  If the MPUC does approve the proposed merger, I believe that the order should be conditioned in a binding enforceable manner to require the applicants to implement demand-side resources in at least the amounts in the most-recently approved (1993) resource plan.<P>

<B>Q.	What constitutes an enforceable provision?</B><BR>
A.	To be enforceable the order provision must:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Define a measurable performance standard.  This could be the number of customers served by the utility's demand-side program, the number of MW and MWH of electric power saved, the budget, etc.<P>

<LI>Define an appropriate penalty for failure to perform up to the standard.  The penalty could be graduated, or it could involve a threshold.  The penalty should be large enough to be meaningful, as the stakes are high in a six billion dollar merger that potentially compromises the ability of state regulators to discharge their protection of the public interest.  Serious performance failures should lead to revocation of the merger approval for failure to meet the standards upon which it was granted.<P>
</OL>

<B>Q.	Should special demand-side programs be implemented to assist low-income customers fulfill their energy needs?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  Assisting low-income customers reduce bills through reducing energy use is an important way to assure that low-income customers are not disproportionally affected by the proposed merger.  Earlier in my testimony I identified ways in which the rates or bills could increase as a result of the merger.  Low-income customers are unique in that they spend a higher proportion of their income on energy than the average American household.  Despite the high percentage of income spent on energy, low-income households have little discretionary income available to them to make energy-efficiency improvements.<P>

<B>Q.	If the proposed merger is approved, do you believe the MPUC should require a condition in the order requiring the accelerated implementation by the applicants of energy efficiency programs targeted to low-income customers?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  Low-income customers are more at risk from unnecessarily high bills than customers in general.  One way to mitigate the impact on low-income customers is to implement energy efficiency programs which overcome the lack of discretionary income.  Programs requiring the customer to come up with up-front capital, or to incur additional expenses, will be of little use to customers who are trying to come up with money for food and shelter.<P>

<B>Q.	What is your recommendation to the Commission?</B><BR>
A.	I propose that the MPUC, in consultation with the Commissioner of the Department of Public Service, require NSP to implement a low-income energy efficiency program designed to reach at least two-thirds of its low-income customers in its service territory in the next ten years.  The order provision should be enforceable, with defined performance standards.  This would be the applicant's commitment to resolving low-income issues as quickly as possible.<P>

<B>Q.	What are the intentions of the applicants regarding the continuation of renewables programs after the merger?</B><BR>
A.	In Minnesota, NSP expects to procure 425 MW of wind and 125 MW of biomass by 2002.  This is a result of a legislatively mandated renewable resource portfolio.  There does not appear to be any intent on the part of NSP to expand renewable energy beyond the mandated levels.<P>

	 WEPCO has no defined renewable resource portfolio, but has initiated the Energy For Tomorrow Renewable Energy Program which allows customers the option of purchasing, at a higher price, energy from renewable resources.  The future quantity of renewable resources is undefined, and will depend on customer response and opportunities to buy or build renewable resources.  The higher price will be a barrier to development of renewable resources in Wisconsin which will not be cost-justified in many instances.<P>
<B>Q.	Will Wisconsin ratepayers be paying for part of the cost of the renewable resources procured in Minnesota?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  In response to Data Request No. EC-9, the applicants stated, "A portion of these power purchases will be charged to NSP-W's customers, since resources are planned and implemented by NSP on a system-wide basis."  In fact, post-merger, it appears that the Interchange Agreement would allocate about one-half of these costs to WEC customers.<P>

<B>Q.	If WEC is mandated to secure renewable resources, will Minnesota ratepayers be charged part of its cost?</B><BR>
A.	Yes, Minnesota ratepayers would be required to pay about one-half the cost of the resources secured in Wisconsin, whether voluntarily or in response to Wisconsin mandate.  Similarly, to the extent that WEC secures energy resources which are more costly than renewable energy sources, Minnesota ratepayers would pay one-half of those costs as well.<P>

<B>Q.	If the MPUC approves the proposed merger, should it adopt a systemwide renewable resource portfolio requirement as an enforceable condition of the order?</B><BR>
A.	Yes.  Without a set portfolio requirement, WEC has no renewable resource targets.  This is likely to result in an under-utilization of renewable resources in Wisconsin.  The added price for a customer to participate in WEPCo's Energy For Tomorrow Renewable Energy Program will be a deterrent for many customers, and will simply not be cost-justified for some renewable resources.  The renewable resource would be cost-effective to the utility without charging a price premium from customers.  The added price for renewable energy is particularly not cost-justified if the renewable resources are sited in an area where transmission and distribution benefits can be derived, and when the environmental benefits of renewable resources (especially non-combustion renewable resources) are considered.  By underutilizing renewable energy sources in Wisconsin, Minnesota ratepayers will be paying a share of the higher-cost nonrenewable energy sources used instead.<P>

	Additionally, the renewable resource portfolio will stimulate the manufacture and installation of renewable resource equipment to reduce long run costs and gain working experience.  The renewable resource portfolio could be fulfilled through the construction of utility-owned facilities, or could be bid to non-utility providers.  The portfolio would stimulate competition with the utility, help mitigate market power concerns with the merger, and overcome some of the market barriers (such as the chilling effect of utility pricing to thwart competition) faced by non-utility providers.<P>

<B>Q.	What would be a reasonable level of renewable resources to be required for the Primergy system?</B><BR>
A.	To be equitable, an amount of renewable resources in Wisconsin, similar to that in Minnesota, about 550 MW, would be reasonable.  It would be appropriate to extend the time frame for procuring this amount of renewable resources to 2005.<P>
	The MPUC should include in any order approving the merger, a binding enforceable condition that Primergy implement 550 MW of renewable energy resources in Minnesota by 2002, and an additional 550 MW of renewable energy resources in Wisconsin by 2005.<P>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Summary</H3><P>

<B>Q.	Please summarize your major recommendations regarding the first issue discussed in your testimony, the erosion of regulatory authority and the ability of the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission to protect Minnesota's ratepayers and environment.</B><BR>
A.	The MPUC should:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Not approve the proposed merger, or<P>
<LI>Condition merger approval on a revised corporate structure -- one single utility serving multiple states to avoid FERC involvement under the Interchange Agreement.  Resource decisions must not be made by unregulated non-utility subsidiaries.  The single utility should have the responsibility and accountability, and<P>
<LI>Require Primergy to obtain MPUC approval of all agreements prior to filing any such agreement at FERC, and obtain SEC approval for this general requirement, and<P>

<LI>Initiate discussions with other affected jurisdictions to develop effective multi-state coordinated regulation, and <P>
<LI>Condition merger approval on Primergy's agreement to provide intervenor funding to assist affected intervenor groups in various jurisdictions to coordinate amongst themselves and to participate in relevant regulatory proceedings, and<P>

<LI>Require that NSP meet or exceed the 1993 resource plan approved levels of demand-side resources for each year through 2006, and<P>

<LI>Require that NSP accelerate programs for low-income customers, especially weatherization and energy efficiency programs, to assist two-thirds of NSP's low-income customers within ten years, and<P>

<LI>Require that NSP secure 550 MW of renewable resources by the year 2002. <P>
<LI>Require that WEC secure 550 MW of renewable resources by the year 2005. <P>

<B>Q.	Does that complete your testimony?</B><BR>
A.	Yes, it does.<BR>

<HR>
