Attractive Avenue for Growth in 	Certain Instances," Developed by Leslie
Buttorff for Presentation at the Edison Electric 	Institute 64th Annual
Convention and Exposition, July 9-12, 1996.<p>
<a name="fn14">[15]</a>	Plots of NSP power plant costs against Combined-cycle
natural gas cost curves were 	constructed using data presented by Bruce Biewald
of Synapse Energy Economics, Inc.  	The curves are based on EPRI and GE
estimates of combined-cycle gas costs for the year 	2000 levelized over 30
years.  Data for the four NSP plants is also provided by Bruce 	Biewald, taken
from the Utility Data Institute's, "1994 SteamPlant Production Costs."<p>
<a name="fn15">[16]</a>	Biewald, Bruce, "Can the Existing Fleet Compete?:
Operating Costs of Power Plants in 	the U.S.," Tellus Institute:  Boston, April
11, 1996.<p>
<a name="fn16">[17]</a>	Correspondence between Michael P. Hernandez, Plant
Manager of NSP's High Bridge 	Facility and Carol M. Neuman, member of Westside
St. Paul NO SHAMS organization.  	Correspondence was a response to written
questions posed by the NO SHAMS 	organization.<p>
<a name="fn17">[18]</a>	The Environmental Coalition consists of the following
parties:  The Izaak Walton League 	of America, Energy CENTS Coalition,
Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy, 	RENEW Wisconsin, Wisconsin's
Environmental Decade, and the Environmental Law and 	Policy Center of the
Midwest.<p>
<a name="fn18">[19]</a>	Lawrence, David A. and Jeffrey C. Paulson, "Answer of
Applicants," <u>Docket No. E, G-</u>	<u>002/PA-95-500</u>, In the Matter of
NSP's Petition for Approval to Merge with WEC, March 	1, 1996, p. 35.<p>
<a name="fn19">[20]</a>	Data for this table were taken from the Title V Permit
Applications for each of the plants 	and emissions inventory data reported
annually to the Minnesota Pollution Control 	Agency (MPCA) by NSP.  Emissions
data is verified by the MPCA and is available to the 	public.<p>
<a name="fn20">[21]</a>	Two of the most serious emissions, mercury and carbon
dioxide, are not criteria 	pollutants according to the Clean Air Act, and
therefore not on the table.  Carbon dioxide 	is the major greenhouse gas
contributing to global climate change.  Mercury 	contaminates lakes and rivers,
upsetting the fragile ecosystem and threatening the health 	of humans who eat
fish from those lakes.<p>
<a name="fn21">[22]</a>	The three methods used when reporting emissions to the
Minnesota Pollution Control 	Agency (MPCA) are Continuous Emissions Monitoring
(CEM), AP-42, and stack tests.  	Each method has its own strengths and
weaknesses.  CEM is by far the best method 	because emissions are tracked
continuously throughout the day.  This provides the best 	information possible
because an accurate, overall picture of emissions is developed.  The 	weakness
of CEM is that it is not used to track all kinds of pollutants.  NSP has used
CEM 	to track SOx and NOx during the past two years.  AP-42 is a calculation
method designed 	by the scientists at the Environmental Protection Agency.
Using this method, emissions 	are calculated using specific information about
the plant (type of coal burned, type of 	boiler used, etc...).  The good thing
about the AP-42 method is that it gives regulators a 	"working number" for
pollutants that are difficult to track.  Unfortunately, the calculation 	is an
estimate of emissions and does have a margin of error.  Stack tests do
basically what 	their name implies--tests the plant's gases to determine the
amount of emissions.  These 	tests are usually contracted out and could vary in
timing from once every five years to 	twice a year.  Stack tests can accurately
measure plant emissions; however, the 	measurement is only a snapshot of the
pollution being emitted during the test and does 	not give an overall picture.
Stack tests are also expensive to perform.<p>
<a name="fn22">[23]</a>	Natural Resources Defense Council, <u>Breath Taking:
Premature Mortality due to </u>	<u>Particulate Air Pollution in 239 Cities</u>,
May 1996.<p>
<p>
	Harvard Medical School, "Six City Study," <u>The New England Journal of
Medicine</u>, 	December 1993.<p>
<a name="fn23">[24]</a>	NSP and WEC's coal plants are mostly pre-1980's, and
therefore are not subject to strict 	New Source Review standards which control
emissions of SOx, NOx and Particulates.
