<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Part One: Staff Report to EQB On The Siting Of A Dry Cask Storage Facility</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Staff Report to the Minnesota Environmental Quality Board On The Siting Of A Dry Cask Storage Facility In Goodhue County</H1><BR>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>June 1996</H2><BR>
<HR>
This report is presented electronically in three parts. Find links to the other two sections on the bottom of this page.
<HR>
<CENTER>TABLE OF CONTENTS<P>

I.	Introduction<BR>
II.	History of the Prairie Island Generating Plant<BR>
III.	Federal Policy<BR>
IV.	Term-of-Storage<BR>
V.	The 1991 EIS on the Prairie Island ISFSI<BR>
VI.	Present Siting Process<BR>
VII.	Options<P>
Appendices-Not included in Electronic Version<BR>
<P></CENTER>
<HR>

<B>Acronyms</B><P>

<B>ALJ</B>-Administrative Law Judge<BR>
<B>CON</B>-Certificate of Need<BR>
<B>DOE</B>-US Department of Energy<BR>
<B>(F)EIS</B>-(Final) Environmental Impact Statement<BR>
<B>ISFSI</B>-Independent Spent Fuel Storage Installation<BR>
<B>MEQB</B>-Minnesota Environmental Quality Board<BR>
<B>MDH</B>-Minnesota Department of Health<BR>
<B>MDPS</B>-Minnesota Department of Public Service<BR>
<B>MPUC</B>-Minnesota Public Utilities Commission<BR>
<B>NRC</B>-US Nuclear Regulatory Commission<BR>
<B>NSP</B>-Northern States Power Company<BR>
<B>PI</B>-Prairie Island<BR>
<HR>
<H3>I.	Introduction</H3>

The Prairie Island Nuclear Generating Plant is located in Red Wing, Minnesota.  The plant began operation in 1973 with a  holding pool designed for spent fuel storage for only a limited period of time because in the early 1970&#146;s it was anticipated that the federal government would build a facility to reprocess spent nuclear fuel from all nuclear power plants in the country.  <P>

In June 1989,  NSP, needing additional  room to store spent fuel in the pools at Prairie Island, announced that it would seek approval to construct an above-ground dry cask storage facility, called an Independent Spent Fuel Storage Installation (ISFSI), at the Prairie Island Plant site.  The MEQB prepared an Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) in 1990-91.  NSP filed an application with the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (MPUC) for a mandatory Certificate of Need in 1991.  After extensive public hearings, the MPUC issued a Certificate of Need authorizing the construction of a storage facility to hold up to 17 casks.  This decision was challenged by a number of opponents to the above-ground storage, and the Minnesota Court of Appeals held that approval from the Legislature was required to construct the ISFSI.  See In the Matter of Prairie Island Dry Cask Storage, 501 N.W.2d 638 (Minn. Ct. App. June 8, 1993), review denied by Supreme Court (July 15, 1993).  <P>

The matter came before the Minnesota Legislature during the 1994 Session.  The Legislature passed what is referred to as the &#1471994 Prairie Island Legislation.&#148;  Minn. Laws 1994, ch. 641 (codified at Minn. Stat.  116C.77 to 116C.80, 216B.2423 to 216B.244, and 216C.051).  The Legislature authorized NSP to store nuclear wastes at Prairie Island in a certain number of casks and under certain conditions.  <P>

One of the conditions for storage was that NSP had to search for a second above-ground site located in Goodhue County.  The Legislature required NSP to obtain a Certificate of Site Comparability from the MEQB before it could construct another dry cask storage facility at a second site.  This process must include the opportunity for broad public review and comment.  <P>

NSP applied for a Certificate of Site Comparability in August 1995.  NSP identified two possible sites for dry cask storage, both located in Florence Township in Goodhue County.  The MEQB appointed a Site Advisory Task Force, comprised of residents of Goodhue County, to consider possible alternative sites.  The Site Advisory Task Force submitted its report in January 1996, concluding that there were no alternate sites in Goodhue County for spent nuclear fuel storage.  The MEQB is presently in the process of reviewing NSP&#146;s application.  <P>

Recently, legislative initiatives and other discussion have centered on the possibility of NSP and the Prairie Island Dakota Community entering into an agreement that would provide monetary and land compensation to the Tribe and a revocation of the requirement to find a second storage site in Goodhue County for NSP.  In response to these initiatives and discussion, and in response to the Site Advisory Task Force report, the MEQB determined in March 1996 to consider the appropriateness of going forward with the alternative siting process.  The Board directed its staff to prepare this Report summarizing the past history of environmental review of the Prairie island Plant, the major health and environmental issues associated with the storage of spent nuclear fuel, and the options available to the Board in carrying out its legislative mandate to consider an application by NSP for a second dry cask storage facility in Goodhue County.  <P>

<H3>II.  History of the Prairie Island Nuclear Generating Plant</H3><P>
<DL>
	<DT><B>A.  The Plant.</B><P>

The Prairie Island Plant consists of two independently controlled nuclear reactors, each with a nominal generating capacity of 530 megawatts.  These reactors were manufactured by Westinghouse.  Prairie Island provides approximately 20% of NSP&#146;s current system needs.  <P>

The Prairie Island Plant lies within the city limits of Red Wing, Minnesota, in Goodhue County.  The Plant abuts the Prairie Island Dakota Community Reservation.  <P>

NSP began construction of the Prairie Island Plant in 1968.  The Prairie Island Plant went into commercial operation in 1973 and 1974.  NSP&#146;s license from the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) for the Prairie Island Plant expires in the year 2014.  <P>

NSP operates one other nuclear power plant in Minnesota.  That plant is located at Monticello, Minnesota.  The Monticello reactor is a General Electric design.  NSP&#146;s federal operating license for the Monticello Plant expires in the year 2010.  The Monticello Plant has enough storage capacity in its spent fuel pools to allow operation through the year 2010 without storage expansion.  <P>

A chronology of developments at Minnesota&#146;s two nuclear reactors is included in Appendix A.<P>

<DT><B>B.  Spent Fuel Storage.</B>  <P>

<DD><B>1.  Background.</B><P>

A nuclear reactor core contains a number of fuel assemblies, bundles of thin tubes containing pellets of enriched uranium.  These tubes are usually referred to as fuel rods.  Over time, the buildup of neutron-absorbing poisons resulting from the chain reaction reduces the ability of the fuel to sustain an efficient chain reaction, and the rods must be replaced.  <P>

The Prairie Island Plant&#146;s two nuclear reactor units each hold 121 fuel assemblies.  On an approximate sixteen month cycle, NSP refuels each unit by replacing 48 spent fuel assemblies with new assemblies.  The Prairie Island Plant began operation with a holding pool designed to hold 198 fuel assemblies.  Subsequent reracking of spent fuel rods in the pools has resulted in a pool capacity of 1386 assemblies.  Operation of the Prairie Island reactors for 50 years (at approximately 70 assemblies per year) would produce a total of 3546 spent fuel assemblies.  (This would require a total of 90 casks of the type being installed at Prairie Island, each with 40 assemblies.)<BR>
At the time the Prairie Island Plant began construction (1968), there were no requirements for environmental review or power plant siting.  The U.S. Atomic Energy Commission prepared an Environmental Statement in 1973, when the Plant was 95% constructed, which stated that &#147spent fuel will normally be shipped from the reactor site about four months after it is discharged from the reactor&#148; and &#147will be shipped between the Prairie Island Plant and the Nuclear Fuel Services Reprocessing Plant at West Valley, New York by truck.&#148;  <P>

At the time of the Plant construction and early operation, NSP anticipated that the spent fuel rods would be shipped off-site for reprocessing.  However, when it later became clear that reprocessing would not be a viable option, NSP undertook action to increase the capacity in the spent fuel pool.  <P>

<DD><B>2.  Reracking.</B><P>

	<B>a.  1977 Authorization.</B><P>

In 1975 NSP applied to the NRC for approval to store more spent fuel rods in the pools.  This request was not to actually build a larger pool, but only to allow NSP to store the fuel rods closer together in the existing pool.  As most nuclear utilities did at that time, NSP acted in response to a shift away from reprocessing and toward more storage in pools.  NSP was anticipating at that time that a national repository would be available by 1985.  <P>

The MPCA prepared an Environmental Assessment Worksheet, on order by the Minnesota Environmental Quality Council (the former MEQB), and concluded that a state EIS should be prepared.  The MEQC agreed that it was a significant action, but determined that there was no state authority involved and that no EIS must be prepared (April 11, 1977 EQC Minutes, p. 5).  No Certificate of Need was required by the state in 1975.<P>

The Minnesota Pollution Control Agency intervened in the proceeding before the Nuclear Regulatory Commission and sought more state control over nuclear power plants, challenged federal preemption arguments, and pushed the NRC to develop a permanent storage solution.  In contentions filed with the NRC, the MPCA sought further environmental review on the basis, among several, that pool storage was not temporary and the reracking did not address long-term needs, and that certain and incremental future expansions should be anticipated and analyzed.  In 1977 the NRC amended NSP&#146;s operating license to allow NSP to expand the pool capacity to store 687 spent fuel assemblies.  The State appealed the NRC licensing decision.  See State of Minnesota v. U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission, 602 F.2d 412 (D.C. Cir. 1979).  The U.S. Court of Appeals upheld the NRC&#146;s determination to allow the reracking.  <P>

<BR>
	<B>b.  1981 Authorization.</B><P>

At the time of the 1977 license amendment authorizing expanded storage in the pools, it was anticipated by the nuclear industry and NSP and the NRC that a federal repository would be available by 1985.  By 1979, however, after continuing federal delays in siting a national repository, NSP was facing pool storage limits that could shut down the Plant by 1985, and so NSP sought again for approval to store more spent fuel rods in the pools.  This time, because of changes in Minnesota law, NSP had to apply for a Certificate of Need (CON) from the Minnesota Energy Agency to conduct a second reracking of fuel rods in the pools.  <P>

As the Energy Agency was beginning its Certificate of Need proceedings, citizens petitioned the MEQB for an EIS.  The MEQB held public hearings on the EIS question, concluding in 1980 that &#147NSP&#146;s proposed modification of the spent fuel storage pool at Prairie Island does not have the potential for significant environmental effects and that no state environmental impact statement need be prepared for that action&#148; (September 18, 1980 EQB Resolution).  The MEQB adopted the findings of the Hearing Examiner that an EIS was not required.<P>

The Hearing Examiner made his recommendation based on a finding that the federal record of review on reracking was comprehensive and addressed all concerns raised in the hearings.  However, in a memorandum to the findings, the Examiner observed that, <P>

The most troublesome aspect of the testimony in this proceeding is the federal government&#146;s lack of decisive leadership (or at least lack of any concrete progress) in its exercise of its preempted authority to develop permanent spent fuel disposal facilities.  If federal progress in this area continues at the rate of the last three years, NSP will be forced to return in 5 to 10 years seeking a CON for construction of some kind of new at-reactor spent fuel storage facility.....that proceeding should require construction design based on the potential that at-reactor storage facilities may become permanent disposal sites.  (July 18, 1980 EQB Report of the Hearing Examiner).  <P>

Thus, the CON process continued without a state EIS, and, after further hearings, a CON was approved by order of the Minnesota Energy Agency on February 3,1981.  It permitted expansion of pool storage capacity to 1582 assemblies, but limited actual pool storage to 1386 assemblies &#147to ensure that the spent fuel can be removed from the pools and that the pools do not become a permanent facility...&#148; (1981 Second Rerack CON).  The NRC approved the second storage expansion amendment to the plant&#146;s operating license, and the reracking proceeded.  The MPCA argued in this second reracking proceeding that the pool should be treated as &#147de facto&#148; permanent storage.<P>

<BR>
	<DT><B>3.  Independent Spent Fuel Storage Installation</B><P>

In 1987, NSP determined that additional storage was again necessary in the absence of a federal repository for spent fuel, or the plant would face shutdown in 1994.  Rod consolidation was proposed as a means of further condensing pool storage, and a pilot demonstration project was undertaken in the fall of 1987.  No state or NRC regulatory permits were required for this demonstration project.  <BR>
At this point, NSP opted to pursue dry cask storage over rod consolidation, citing concerns about cost efficiencies and continuing uncertainty about federal acceptance schedules.  NSP made initial public disclosure of the company&#146;s dry cask initiative in mid 1989.  NSP acknowledged that a third  reracking of the rods in the pools was an option, but was limited to 20% additional space (about 250 assemblies).<P>

Though there was some initial posturing over the level of environmental review of the dry cask proposal, NSP volunteered to pay for the preparation of an EIS as the MEQB prepared to order one, and in December 1989, the MEQB began preparation of an EIS on the Prairie Island Independent Spent Fuel Storage Installation.<P>

An important fact about the environmental review conducted by the MEQB in 1989-91 regarding the proposed Independent Spent Fuel Storage Installation is that while the MEQB prepared the Environmental Impact Statement, the MEQB had no siting authority over the facility, unlike the MEQB&#146;s authority over the siting of a second storage site in Goodhue County.<P>

The MEQB staff began the &#147scoping&#148; of environmental issues and alternatives in December 1989 to establish the contents of an EIS.  The initial documentation was provided by NSP in the form of a description of the proposed ISFSI.  NSP was asked to provide a summary of each of the alternatives it had considered and would ultimately submit in its Certificate of Need (CON) application to the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (MPUC).  An off-site (in Minnesota built by NSP) storage facility was not an alternative considered feasible by NSP.  (The term &#147off-site&#148; is used to mean off the PI plant site and is distinguished from &#147away-from-reactor,&#148; which in federal usage can mean on the plant site but not in the reactor building.)<P>

MEQB convened a technical review committee of state agency staff to assist in preliminary scoping.  In addition to MEQB member agencies, the MPUC and the Minnesota Department of Public Safety were participants.  Among a range of alternatives identified in early discussions was a &#147similar facility at another site.&#148;  In all references this offsite facility was treated as a new and independent, but generic, off-site concept with no geographic or political parameters other than presumably in Minnesota.  It was a logical extension of a series of other alternatives that included shipment off-site to existing non-PI storage pools (including NSP&#146;s Monticello Plant and a private facility in Morris, Illinois) and to the promised federal facilities wherever located.  <P>

The off-site alternative was included in the March 1990 Draft Scoping Decision Document as one of 11 alternatives.  During the subsequent public meeting and comment period, only NSP spoke to the off-site alternative.  In an April 26, 1990 comment letter, NSP stated:<P>

This alternative will be demonstrated to be unreasonable in part because there are no adverse environmental consequences of locating a dry cask storage facility at the current site.  Use of an alternative site will merely increase costs and decrease operating efficiency.  Use of a site other than Prairie Island could require land acquisition, new site licensing by the NRC, transportation for the storage site, and construction of a fuel handling and cask loading facility at the storage site to transfer spent fuel from transport casks to storage casks.<P>

The last point in NSP&#146;s comment letter recognized that at that time there were no dual-purpose (transport\storage) casks available.  Federal spent fuel management policy  and cask development by vendors were concentrated on on-site storage-only design and implementation.  Today the NRC has approved one dual purposed cask.<P>

No public comments were received on the off-site alternative.  The level of public and local government participation was minimal during the scoping period, and staff elected to recommend to the MEQB that all alternatives be retained to allow further analysis, with the expectation, as stated in the approved Scoping Decision Document, that one or more of the alternatives could be determined to be unreasonable and not included in the EIS.<P>

Further consideration by the interagency technical review committee in mid-1990 concluded that there was insufficient basis for carrying forward the off-site alternative.  There was no support from any agency for analyzing it in the EIS.  Ten other alternatives were considered reasonable in a feasibility context, and represented a range of federal and state options.  The US Department of Energy (DOE) had determined that utilities could and would store waste at reactor sites until a federal storage or disposal facility was available (See discussion of Waste Confidence Decision on page 9).  At the state level, there was no recorded public or agency interest in considering a new, off-<BR>
site spent fuel storage site.<P>

As provided in the MEQB&#146;s rules for EIS contents (Minn. Rules 4410.2300, subp.G), the draft EIS (page 3.3) identified the off-site option as an alternative that was considered but eliminated, and provided a brief discussion and the reasons for elimination.  Transportation and increased waste handling at an off-site facility wherever it was located were noted as significant issues.<P>

Four alternative sites within the PI plant boundary, or on-site, were identified in the draft EIS.<P>

During the public comment period on the Draft EIS, again there were no comments supporting consideration of an off-site alternative.  In its final order determining the EIS adequate, the MEQB included a finding (Finding 11G, May 16, 1991) that &#147The alternative of a similar facility (dry cask) at another site (away-from-reactor site in Minnesota) was not included....and was considered unreasonable and infeasible.&#148;<P>

About a month before the EIS was finalized, NSP applied to the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission for a Certificate of Need.  The EIS became part of the MPUC record.  Additionally, NSP sought a site-specific NRC license for an independent (not pool but at-reactor) storage facility.<P>

Subsequently, the MPUC&#146;s CON process did not reevaluate the off-site alternative.  The ALJ&#146;s report and the Commission&#146;s findings are silent on this alternative.  It was also not an issue addressed by the Court of Appeals in 1993.<P>

The EIS was made a part of the record before the Public Utilities Commission.  The Administrative Law Judge found, &#147These FEIS analyses and findings support the conclusion that the ISFSI will not cause environmental pollution, impairment, or destruction as defined by statute&#148; (MPUC ALJ Report, April 10, 1992, Finding 124).  Further, the MPUC Order approving the limited (to 17 casks) Certificate of Need found that, &#147The Commission....gives the Environmental Impact Statement significant weight in finding that the proposed facility will not materially adversely affect the environment.&#148;  (MPUC CON Order, p.19).<P>

The Minnesota Court of Appeals was not asked to address directly any issues relating to the EIS, but in determining that the ISFSI must be classified as a radioactive waste management facility under state law because the nuclear waste would be &#147permanent&#148; storage at the site, the Court acknowledged, as stated in the EIS, that the EIS was based on a temporary facility and that a determination that it was permanent may require a supplemental EIS.  In the Matter of Prairie Island Dry Cask Storage, 501 N.W.2d 638,648  (Minn. Ct. App. 1993).  Subsequently, there was no request by the MPUC for a supplemental EIS.<P>

As legislative hearings began prior to the 1994 legislative session, EQB staff provided background testimony on the EIS preparation process and content (October 20, 1993 Testimony of Michael Sullivan).  That testimony noted that the alternative of a similar facility at another site had been narrowed to consideration of four alternate sites at the reactor (on-site).  Addressing the issue of the temporary assumption as a basis for the EIS, the testimony clarified that the analysis assumed 48 casks would be placed in service, the last one in 2020, and that at the end of the 20-year NRC license period environmental review would again be required.<P>

In the 1994 PI legislation, the legislature recognized that, &#147the Minnesota environmental quality board on May 16, 1991, reviewed and found adequate a final environmental impact statement on the proposal to construct and operate a dry cask storage facility for the temporary storage of spent nuclear fuel from the Prairie Island nuclear generating plant;&#148; and &#147ratifies and approves the EIS.....and authorizes the use of casks at Prairie Island ...as modified by this act and without further environmental review under chapter 116D...&#148; (Minn. Stat.  116C.77 (1994).<P>

		<DT><B>4.  Monticello Spent Fuel</B><P>

	The Monticello Plant is a single reactor plant using a General Electric design reactor.  While none of the reactor manufacturers ever did provide reprocessing facilities for the nuclear industry, General Electric did develop a private pool storage facility (not at a reactor) at its Morris, Illinois site, to which NSP shipped 1058 Monticello spent fuel assemblies between 1984 and 1987 under an agreement with GE when the Monticello plant was built.  Thirty dedicated rail shipments were made, generating controversy, particularly in Wisconsin.  The shipments created space in the Monticello storage pool which NSP reports will allow operation of the reactor through its current license (2010) without storage expansion.<BR>
</DL>
<HR>
