<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Part Two: Staff Report to EQB On The Siting Of A Dry Cask Storage Facility</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2>Staff Report to the Minnesota Environmental Quality Board On The Siting Of A Dry Cask Storage Facility In Goodhue County-Part Two</H2>
<HR> 
<H3>III.  Federal Policy.</H3>
	
<DL><DT><B>A.  Nuclear Waste Policy Act. </B> <P>

When the first large, commercial, nuclear plant began operation in 1960 near Morris, Illinois, the then Atomic Energy Commission (AEC) assumed that nuclear waste would ultimately be disposed of by deep geologic burial, probably in salt domes, but also researched diverse alternatives.  Under congressional inquiry, the AEC first acknowledged in 1971 that if problems arose with the deep disposal plan, that the spent fuel assemblies would have to remain at nuclear power plants or as reprocessed waste at reprocessing facilities.  An interim, centralized storage concept was proposed by the AEC in 1972 when repository planning was delayed, and then abandoned in 1975 when the US Environmental Protection Agency and state and local governments expressed concern about the possibility that economic factors could later dictate utilization of the facility as a permanent repository, contrary to the stated interim intent.  Nuclear utilities already having to expand pool storage were reassured by federal agencies that the repository would be developed.<P>

The first congressional efforts to adopt a comprehensive nuclear waste policy failed in 1980.  In early 1983, the United States Congress passed the Nuclear Waste Policy Act of 1982 (NWPA).  P.L. 97-<BR>
425, now codified at 42 U.S.C.  10101-10270.  The purpose of NWPA was to establish a process by which the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) would select two sites in the United States where high-level radioactive wastes from nuclear power plants could be permanently stored deep within the earth.  The NWPA required the DOE to site one repository by 1987, with operation by 1995, and a second repository a few years later.  <P>

In 1983, the DOE had already been focusing on nine sites in six states as possible sites for the first repository.  The states were Nevada, Utah, Washington, Louisiana, Texas, and Mississippi.  For the second repository, DOE was looking for certain crystalline rock formations around the midwest and east and had determined that Minnesota and ten other states had areas with the requisite geologic characteristics DOE was looking for.  Several sites in Minnesota were included on the list as a possible location for the second repository.  These locations were primarily in the northern parts of the state; none were in Goodhue County.  <P>

At this point (August 1984), the NRC released its &#147Waste Confidence Decision&#148;, after having spent five years reviewing alternatives to storage issues.  This position found that a repository would be available within 25 years and that spent fuel could be safely stored in reactor pools or ISFSI&#146;s for up to 30 years beyond the licensed life of reactors.<P>

On December 14, 1984, the Secretary of the DOE, in accordance with NWPA, issued draft environmental assessments for the nine potentially acceptable sites in the six states that were on the list for the first repository.  49 Fed. Reg. 49540-41 (Dec. 20, 1984).  No environmental assessment was ever prepared by DOE for any potential site in Minnesota.  <P>

On May 28, 1986, the Secretary nominated five sites for site characterization, one each in Mississippi, Texas, Utah, Nevada, and Washington.  51 Fed. Reg. 19783-84 (June 2, 1986).  See State of Nevada v. Watkins, 914 F.2d 1545, 1550 (9th Cir.), a case brought by the State of Nevada challenging the DOE&#146;s decision.  At the same time the DOE announced that it had postponed indefinitely site-specific work for a second repository.<BR>
  <BR>
On December 22, 1987, Congress amended NWPA to designate the Yucca Mountain site in Nevada as the sole site to be characterized for possible development as a repository site.  P.L. 100-203, 42 U.S.C.  10172 (1993 Supp.).  Moreover, the DOE was told by Congress to call off all activities to search for a second site.  42 U.S.C.  10172(a).  Today, all efforts by the federal government to find a national repository are directed to the Yucca Mountain site in Nevada.  <P>

		<DT><B>B.  Minnesota Response.</B><P>

In 1984, the Minnesota Legislature, concerned about Minnesota becoming a national repository for nuclear wastes, responded to Congress and the DOE by passing its own law providing for state involvement in the siting process and over the transportation of high-level radioactive wastes.  Minn. Law 1984, ch. 453.  That law is known as the Radioactive Waste Management Act and is codified at Minn. Stat.  116C.705 to 116C.76 (1994).  <P>

One provision of the Radioactive Waste Management Act created the Governor&#146;s Nuclear Waste Council.  Minn. Stat.  116C.711 (1994).  Through the involvement of the Governor&#146;s Nuclear Waste Council, Minnesota participated in siting activities by the Department of Energy.  Minnesota submitted extensive comments to DOE on the proposed Minnesota sites in 1986.  <P>

Shortly after DOE announced on May 28, 1986, that it was abandoning its efforts to site a second repository (and that therefore Minnesota was no longer in the running for the repository), the Chair of the Nuclear Waste Council issued a memorandum to the Council members stating that future efforts by the Council would be held in abeyance.  The Governor&#146;s Nuclear Waste Council has not functioned in any capacity since then, although the legislation is still on the books.  <P>
</DL>
<H3>IV.  Term-of-Storage</H3> <P>

The dilemma facing Minnesota decision makers, and NSP, and an issue of crucial importance to the public, is that it is uncertain how long nuclear waste would be stored in a dry cask storage facility.  (This same issue was a matter of concern in the 1977 and 1980 reracking debates.)  Two fundamental but opposite assumptions -- whether dry cask storage is a temporary or a permanent  solution to what to do with spent nuclear fuel -- have become central to planning and regulating nuclear spent fuel management.  Utilities, regulators, politicians and the general public all make their own assumption on whether dry cask storage is a temporary or a permanent resolution of the spent fuel issue.  Definitions are loosely implied, which makes the issue even more elusive, and one can hear of projected periods of storage ranging between two years and thousands of years.  <P>

NSP has steadfastly maintained that spent fuel storage at PI is temporary, meaning that once the federal government builds a national repository, the waste will be moved to that facility.  All utilities in the country with nuclear power plants have made this assumption, and a huge investment has been made with an expectation that the federal government could and would deliver on its commitment to accept spent nuclear fuel.  <P>

The Administrative Law Judge who presided over the MPUC&#146;s 1992 CON hearings observed:<P>

NSP is caught in a quagmire that is not of its own making--the inability of the Federal government to meet deadlines.  The past two decades have been one missed deadline after another, and the future does not appear to be substantially different&#148; (MPUC ALJ Report, p.19).  <P>

The Administrative Law Judge expressed concern that the ISFSI could become a permanent storage solution and stated, &#147In all likelihood, DOE will not take spent fuel away from Prairie Island in the predictable future.&#148; (MPUC ALJ Report, p. 19).<P>

The MEQB&#146;s Site Advisory Task Force identified the permanent-temporary issue as one of particular concern that required further analysis and careful deliberation.  Citizens, too, have focused on this issue.  The Chair of the Florence Township Board of Supervisors, Joan Marshman, commented, &#147The permanency issue is a major concern for many residents of Florence Township as it should be for the rest of the state of Minnesota.&#148;  (Testimony before MEQB, Jan. 18, 1996)<P>

Minnesota regulators have generally assumed that dry cask storage would be temporary and that the federal government would indeed locate a national repository.  The MEQB&#146;s 1991 PI EIS assumed that storage would be temporary, and concluded as noted earlier that up to 48 casks stored through 2020, and built and operated under NRC standards and as described by NSP, would comply with state environmental policy.  Beyond that volume, time and operational context, the state has conducted no environmental review.  <P>

A major confounding factor over this issue is that the definition of temporary has lengthened since 1973, when the federal government began promising that it would be responsible for spent nuclear fuel, at the same time that confidence in the federal government finding a solution has eroded.  The 1994 legislative debate reflected a growing discomfort with extending the temporary characterization beyond the NRC license term (20 years) for the Prairie IslandI ISFSI due to federal inaction.  Though NSP and the industry emphasize that the cask design life is longer (25 years) and the operational life perhaps much longer (50+ years) than the license period, the continuing federal inability to provide for interim storage or permanent disposal will at some point require NSP and the state to consider longer-than-temporary storage facilities.<P>

In 1995, 17 states, including Minnesota, 22 state utility regulatory commissions, and several municipal utilities filed a petition in the US Court of Appeals seeking a court order to force DOE to begin accepting and storing spent fuel from commercial nuclear power plants in January 1998.  The case is Michigan vs. DOE, court file no. 95-1321(D.C. Cir. 1995).  The petitioners contend, among other things, that because DOE has collected $11 billion in fees from ratepayers, the agency must accept spent fuel and store it somewhere, preferably within the DOE nuclear weapons production complex.<P>

Led by the Minnesota Department of Public Service, most of the parties to the lawsuit and other state regulatory bodies and utilities formed the Nuclear Waste Strategy Coalition in 1995.  The coalition consists of 38 members from 20 states, including, in addition to the Minnesota Department of Public Service, the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission and NSP. <P>

In November 1995 the Minnesota Department of Public Service commenced an investigation into payments made by the ratepayers of Northern States Power Company into the federal Nuclear Waste Fund.  This fund is supported by a tax on electricity generated from nuclear power plants around the country to be used by the U. S. Department of Energy in its work to develop a national repository for spent nuclear fuel.  On June 12, 1996, the Department of Public Service filed a report with the MPUC on the result of its investigation.  The DPS reported that the federal government&#146;s nuclear waste disposal program is unlikely to result in the timely, cost-effective disposal of NSP s on-site nuclear waste.  The DPS report recommends that the MPUC act to divert the Minnesota ratepayer assessments from the federal fund to an independently administered escrow account in order to maintain discretion over the future use of Minnesota ratepayers&#146; contribution to the Fund.  The Department&#146;s report is included as Attachment F.  The MPUC has opened docket no. E-002/DI-95-<BR>
1137 to receive comments on the report through July 31, 1996.<P>

The 1994 PI legislation specifically anticipated that ultimately the term-of-storage issue may be unavoidable.  In creating the Legislative Electric Energy Task Force, &#147The legislature finds that<BR>
it needs more information on the future management of high-level radioactive waste, the costs of that management, and the technical and economic feasibility of utilizing alternative energy resources.  Before any legislative determinations may be reasonably made that are more specific that the determinations made in this act, the legislature needs detailed, credible, and reliable information on these issues.&#148; Minn. Stat.  216C.051, subd.1 1994.  Comprising 16 legislators, the Electric Energy Task Force was directed to, in addition to reviewing broad electric energy policy: &#147....analyze the future of and the economic effects of the continued generation of electric power and radioactive waste at the Prairie Island nuclear power plant.  The task force shall include in its report under subdivision 5, a specific discussion of:(in part)<P>

(7) if the waste is unlikely to be removed from the state or if waste will need to be indefinitely stored outside the power plants after decommissioning, whether sites for storage of the waste outside the structure of the Prairie Island power plant potentially can be found that minimize economic and social disruption, maximize environmental, health, and safety protection, minimize transportation distance, and place the burden of storage of the waste on those communities that enjoy the immediate economic benefits of the existence and operation of the power plants; if potential sites exist, what process should be used to identify and utilize them if necessary; the entity that is searching for an alternative site within the state for the disposal of spent nuclear fuel from the Prairie Island nuclear generating plant, is seeking permits for the site, or is constructing the site shall report progress on those activities every six months to the task force commencing January 1, 1995; (Minn. Stat.  216C.051, subd 4(7)(1994).<P>

The Legislative Electric Energy Task Force has not yet undertaken these assigned tasks.  <P>

The term-of-storage uncertainty will become more controversial and more difficult to address as time progresses.  This issue will be a crucial issue in future state review of any proposal to deal with spent nuclear fuel, including the ongoing application by NSP for a Certificate of Site Comparability for a site in Florence Township.  Ultimately, assessments may have to be made of even larger issues such as plant and storage pool decommissioning.  The MEQB&#146;s Site Advisory Task Force identified this scenario as a particular concern and recommended further analysis in the EIA (Task Force Report, p. 115).<BR>
<HR>
