<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>BEFORE THE MINNESOTA OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE
HEARINGS</title></head><body>
<CENTER>BEFORE THE MINNESOTA OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE
HEARINGS<BR>
	100 Washington Square, Suite 1700<BR>
	Minneapolis, Minnesota 55401-2138<BR>
<p>
	FOR THE MINNESOTA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<BR>
	121 Seventh Place East, Suite 350<BR>
	St. Paul, Minnesota 55105-2147<BR>
<p>
	MPUC Docket No. E-999/CI-93-583<BR>
	OAH Docket No. 6-2500-8632-2<p>
<p>
	In the Matter of the<BR>
	Quantification of Environmental Costs<BR>
	Pursuant to Laws of Minnesota 1993,<BR>
	Chapter 356, Section 3<BR></CENTER>

<p>
<p>
<b>INITIAL BRIEF OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION<BR>
ON SUBSTANTIVE ISSUES</b><p>
<p>
<b></b>The Environmental Coalition<a href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a> submits
this Initial Brief on Substantive Issues to summarize the evidence submitted in
this docket supporting Commission adoption of final environmental cost values
for carbon dioxide, methane, particulate matter (PM-10) and mercury emissions
associated with electric power production.   The Commission is required by
statute to "quantify and establish a range of environmental costs associated
with each method of electricity generation."   <i>Minn. Stat.
[[section]]216B.2422.</i>  <b>  </b>Based on the evidence presented, the
Environmental Coalition recommends that the Commission adopt a final
environmental cost value of  $25 per ton for carbon dioxide emissions, $550 per
ton for methane emissions, $7800 per ton for PM-10 emissions and $50 million
per ton for mercury emissions.<b></b><p>
<b>I.	THE COMMISSION SHOULD SET THE FINAL ENVIRONMENTAL COST VALUE AT $25 PER
TON FOR CARBON DIOXIDE EMISSIONS ASSOCIATED <u>WITH ELECTRIC POWER
GENERATION</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Emissions of carbon dioxide from electric generating facilities have
significantly contributed to increased atmospheric concentrations of
carbon dioxide.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Electric utilities produce over one-third of the carbon dioxide emitted
from anthropogenic sources in the United States.  <i>Tr. 15,  at 179, lns.
14-17.</i>   Eighty percent of those emissions come from coal-fired power
plants. <i> Id.</i>  The volume of carbon dioxide emissions associated with
fossil fuel combustion is several orders of magnitude greater than emissions of
other pollutants, such as oxides of sulfur and nitrogen.  <i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at
15.)</i><p>
<i></i>In 1987, the United Nations Environment Program and the World
Meteorological Organization created the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate
Change ("IPCC') to evaluate the environmental impacts associated with
anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide.  <i>Ex.
113, at 1-2.</i>   Carbon dioxide is often characterized as a "greenhouse gas"
because it acts to trap heat in the troposphere.<i>  </i>The concentration of
carbon dioxide in the atmosphere is now about 350 parts per million and is
increasing at a rate of 0.5 percent annually.<p>
<i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 15.)</i><p>
<b>B. 	Increased atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide are associated
with <u>potentially catastrophic increases in global temperatures</u>.</b><p>
<b></b>   <p>
The IPCC's 1992 Supplement to its  <u>Scientific Assessment of Climate
Change</u>  states unequivocally that:  ". . .emissions resulting from human
activities are substantially increasing the atmospheric concentrations of the
greenhouse gases . . . [that] will enhance the greenhouse effect, resulting on
average in an additional warming of the Earth's surface."  <i>Ex. 111, at 3,
citing </i><cite>1992 IPCC Supplement:  Scientific Assessment of Climate
Change</cite><i>, at XI.  </i> The magnitude of additional warming is somewhat
less certain.  According to the IPCC, doubling carbon dioxide concentrations in
the atmosphere would lead to an increase in the global average temperature that
"is unlikely to lie outside the range of 2.7 to 8.1 degrees Fahrenheit."
<i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 16, citing the </i><cite>1992 Supplement: Scientific
Assessment</cite><i>, at 5.)  </i> At an IPCC meeting in Geneva in 1994,  IPCC
Chairman Bert Bolin noted that the risk of more severe and damaging climate
change is as great as the risk of less severe impacts.  <i>Ex. 111, at 3.</i>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>Climate change, due to increased atmospheric loading of greenhouse
gases, could involve a number of potentially catastrophic impacts -- including
a rise in sea level, heightened climatic variability and, consequently, changes
in vegetation.  <i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 16.)   </i>At this point, it is difficult
to draw conclusions about shifts in the distribution of precipitation,
agricultural output, and frequency and severity of extreme weather events for a
specific location, such as Minnesota.<i>  </i>However, some climate change
models have been developed that show the "grain belts" of the Northern
hemisphere shifting north by hundreds of kilometers and  predict significant
die-back of Boreal forests -- the spruce/pine/fir forests found in the Boundary
Waters Canoe Area, Superior National Forest and other parts of northern
Minnesota. <i>Id., at 16 and Ex. 69, at 4-5.</i> <i>    </i>Laboratory studies
also show that certain plants, including a type of  pine which grows in boreal
forests, is very adversely  affected by increased exposure to carbon dioxide.
<i>Tr. 10, at  82, lns. 19-25 through 83, lns. 1-12.</i>   <i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><b>C.	Uncertainty about the magnitude, distribution and timing of the
potentially serious global warming effects associated with fossil fuel
combustion should <u>not be a basis for inaction</u>.</b><i></i><p>
<i></i><b></b><p>
<b></b>IPCC reports are the most authoritative sources available for
information on climate change issues.  The IPCC research and peer review
process evaluates all available scientific information on factors affecting
climate change, including greenhouse gas emissions, and assesses the
atmosphere-ocean-land-ice system responses to these factors.  <i>Ex. 113, at 2,
lns. 5-7.  </i>Prior to publication, IPCC research reports are developed by
technical committees composed of experts from throughout the international
scientific community and are subjected to a rigorous multi-level peer review
process that ultimately involves most scientists working in relevant
disciplines.   "The design and execution of the IPCC research and peer review
process is a unique example of international cooperation of the scientific
community on a matter of global importance."   <i>Ex. 113, at 1, lns.
13-15.</i><p>
<i></i>Despite the IPCC's exhaustive research efforts, there is still
uncertainty about the magnitude, distribution, and timing of  climate change
and climate change-related impacts.  This uncertainty, which decreases with
each new IPCC report,  should not be a basis for inaction. <i>  </i> <i></i><p>
<i></i>Instead, Environmental Coalition witness Dr. Stephen Bernow recommends
using a "Pascal's wager" approach to address the global warming problem.
<i>Ex. 111, at 7, ln 9</i>.  He notes:<p>
If we act to prevent global warming and later discover that the impact is
relatively benign, our costs will be limited to some potentially unnecessary
emission reduction expenses.  If, instead, we choose not to act and
unprecedented climate change occurs, we could incur catastrophic. . .
ecological losses.  <i>Ex. 111, at 7, lns. 7-13.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
The appropriate policy response to address the risk of climate change is
adoption of policies that will defer commitments to resources that contribute
to the problem.  <i>Ex. 112, at 6, lns. 17 -20.  </i>  <i></i><p>
<i></i><b></b><p>
<b>D.	There is an international scientific and political consensus that carbon
dioxide emissions must be reduced to 1990 levels by 2000, and must be reduced
by fifty percent by the middle of the next century in order to <u>stabilize the
earth's climate</u>.</b><p>
<p>
"Concern over the impact of carbon emissions on climate change has led to a
growing international consensus on the need to reduce emissions."  <i>Ex. 111
(SB-2, at 14.)</i>  The Framework Convention On Climate Change ("FCCC"), to
which the U.S. is a signatory, requires the U.S. to reduce anthropogenic
emissions of carbon dioxide to 1990 levels by the end of the decade.  <i>Ex.
112, at  3, lns 1-5.</i>  This international treaty was ratified by the U.S.
Senate in 1992 and establishes legal obligations that bind the United States.
<i>Id.</i>  In order for the U.S. to meet its obligations under the Framework
Convention, electric utilities will have to implement measures to substantially
reduce carbon dioxide emissions by the end of this decade. <i>Ex. 111, at
5,</i><p>
<i>lns. 10-12.</i><p>
<i></i>The FCCC commitment, to merely stabilize carbon dioxide
<cite>emissions</cite> at current levels, represents only a modest first step
to reach stabilization of carbon dioxide <cite>concentrations</cite> in the
atmosphere.   <i> </i>In order to stabilize the earth's climate, the IPCC and
the Advisory Group on Greenhouse Gases<a href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a>
estimate that carbon dioxide emission levels will need to be reduced by at
least fifty percent below 1990 levels by the middle of the next century.
<i>Tr. 15, at 75, lns. 7-20. </i>   	FCCC signatories have already concluded
that further greenhouse gas emission reductions will be necessary to protect
the earth's climate.  <i>Exhibit 113, at 4, lns. 18-19.  </i>  During the
Spring of 1995, at a Conference of  the Parties in Berlin, the United States
and other developed country FCCC parties initiated a "process of strengthening
commitments" that would "set quantified limitations and reduction objectives. .
. for their anthropogenic emissions."   <i>Exhibit 113 (SB-4.)  </i>This work
will be completed "as early as possible in 1997."  <i>Id.    </i><b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>E.	The people of Minnesota support state-level action to reduce the risk  of global warming and  public hearing testimony in this docket favored
Commission adoption of  externality values to achieve that goal.
</b><p>
<b></b><p>
A recent statewide public opinion survey shows that  an overwhelming majority
of Minnesota residents -- 82 percent -- believe that the State of Minnesota
should make at least <u>some</u> changes to reduce the potential for global
warming.  <i>Ex. 112 (SB-3, University of  Minnesota Center for Survey Research
1994 Minnesota State Survey, at 33.)   </i>According to Environmental Coalition
witness Dr. Julia Brody, "[t]hese results indicate that Minnesota residents
overwhelmingly support state action to protect natural resources from air
pollution, <u>and they support action despite uncertainty</u>." <i>Ex. 238, at
9, lns. 14-16. </i> Many of the citizens who testified during the public
hearings held in this docket identified adoption of externality values for
greenhouse gas emissions as an important step that should be taken to reduce
the risk of climate change.<a href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a><b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>F.	The Commission should adopt an externality value for greenhouse gas
emissions which reflects the costs of implementing the emission reductions
<u>needed to achieve climate stabilization</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Environmental Coalition witness  Dr. Stephen Bernow, who is involved in
the IPCC process as a reviewer, premises his testimony in this docket on the
IPCC's conclusions regarding:  (1) the extent to which anthropogenic emissions
of greenhouse gases are associated with an increase in mean global temperature,
(2) the nature and extent of various environmental impacts associated with
increased temperatures, and (3)  the extent to which greenhouse gas emissions
must be reduced to achieve climate stabilization.   Starting with the IPCC's
findings on these three key points, Dr. Bernow uses a two-step analytical
process to determine an appropriate externality value for greenhouse gas
emissions associated with electric power generation.<p>
Dr. Bernow's analysis -- which he refers to as an environmental target approach
-- is a hybrid of the damage cost and risk of regulation methodologies
sometimes used to determine environmental externality values.  <i>Ex. 111
(SB-2, at 21.)  </i>The two steps to this approach consist of :   (1)
determining a target that, at a minimum, prevents irreversible damage to the
environment, and (2) assessing the marginal cost of  achieving the target.<p>
The first step in Dr. Bernow's analysis, like damage cost methodologies,
focuses on the physical impacts associated with emission of a pollutant -- in
this case, greenhouse gases.  He starts by noting that irreversible damage to
the environment will occur unless the earth's climate is stabilized.  In order
to achieve climate stabilization, greenhouse gas emissions must be reduced to
fifty percent of 1990 levels by the middle of the next century.  This fifty
percent emission reduction is the relevant "environmental target."<p>
<p>
The second step in Dr. Bernow's approach is to assess the marginal cost of
achieving the environmental target identified in the first step of the
analysis.   The process of determining the marginal cost of a specific emission
reduction is the same type of analysis carried out when environmental
externality values are developed using a risk of regulation approach.  The
similarity is particularly striking in this case, because the fifty percent
reduction target has already been recommended by the IPCC and is under active
consideration in the FCCC amendment process.   To determine the marginal cost
of  reducing U.S. greenhouse gas  emissions to 1990 levels by 2050,  Dr. Bernow
reviewed eleven recent studies<a href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a> that examine
greenhouse gas abatement costs.  <i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 24-37.) </i>  After
evaluating the various modelling techniques and the wide-range of assumptions
about baseline and future conditions used in each of these studies, Dr. Bernow
developed his own estimate of the marginal cost associated with reducing
greenhouse gas emissions to levels that would stabilize the earth's climate by
the middle of the next century.  <i>Id., at 37-38. </i><p>
Based on this analysis, Dr. Bernow recommends that the Commission adopt an
environmental cost value of $25 per ton for carbon dioxide emissions associated
with electric power generation.  <i>Ex. 111, at 7, lns. 18-22.</i>   Dr. Bernow
also recommends that the Commission adopt an environmental cost value of $550
per ton for methane.<a href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn4">[5]</a>  <i>Id.  </i> These
externality  values are "based on the best possible evidence at hand. . . the
IPCC reports and a critical review of . . . [recent greenhouse gas abatement
cost] studies." <i>  Tr. 15, at 167, lns. 6-8.</i>  <b>	</b><i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><b>II.	THE COMMISSION SHOULD SET THE FINAL ENVIRONMENTAL COST VALUE AT
$7800 PER TON FOR PM-10 EMISSIONS ASSOCIATED WITH<u> ELECTRIC POWER
GENERATION</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Emissions of particulate matter from coal-fired electric generating
facilities <u>contribute to increased ambient concentrations of
PM-10</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Particulate emissions from coal-fired generating facilities are made up
of particles that are generally divided into three categories, on the basis of
size:  (1) nonrespirable matter that has an aerodynamic diameter greater than
10 micrometers;  (2) smaller, inhalable particles that are less than 10
micrometers in diameter ("PM-10"), and  (3) fine particles that are no more
than 2.5 micrometers in diameter ("PM-2.5"). <i>Ex. 234, at 9, lns. 4-7.  </i>
The Environmental Coalition's witnesses focused their analysis on small
particle emissions -- those that are less than ten micrometers in diameter --
because they pose the greatest risk to human health. <i>Id.   </i>Using a model
developed for the Bonneville Power Administration,<a
href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn5">[6]</a> they estimated the effect on ambient air
quality associated with the emission of one ton of PM-10 from a generic coal
fired-power plant.<b>  </b> Based on their analysis, it is reasonable to
conclude that one ton of PM-10 emitted from a generic coal-fired power plant
would, on average, increase ambient concentrations of PM-10 by 0.000083
micrograms per cubic meter over 53.6 percent of the state of Minnesota.<a
href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn6">[7]</a><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>B.	Exposure to ambient concentrations of PM-10 at or above National Ambient
Air Quality Standard ("NAAQS") levels is associated with increased<u> morbidity
and mortality rates</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Small particle emissions from coal-fired generating facilities present a
very grave threat to human health.<b>  </b>Inhalation of  fine particles,
especially fine sulfate particles, increases the risk of mortality (shortening
life by several years) and morbidity -- even in areas <u>in</u>
<u>attainment</u> with NAAQS standards for particulate and sulfur dioxide
emissions.<a href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn7">[8]</a>   "Hospital admissions for the
elderly in Minneapolis-St. Paul are significantly associated with PM-10. . . at
concentrations below the NAAQS."  <i>Ex. 132, at 2, lns. 15-17, citing
Schwartz, J. "PM-10, and Hospital Admissions for the Elderly in Minneapolis-St.
Paul, Minnesota," </i><cite>Archives of Environmental Health</cite><i>, 49:
366-375 (1994).   </i>The U.S. EPA is currently under court order<a
href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn8">[9]</a>  to promulgate stricter NAAQS for PM-10
because existing standards are not sufficiently protective of human health.<p>
The Environmental Coalition's witnesses note that a recent meta-analysis of
studies of increased mortality associated with increased ambient concentrations
of PM-10 shows "[a] striking consistency in the results. . .after the different
studies were converted into a common metric."  <i>Ex. 234, at 9, lns. 19-21,
citing Ostro, 1993.  "The Association of Air Pollution and Mortality:
Examining the Case for Inference."  </i><cite>Archives of Environmental
Health</cite><i>  48 (5):  336-342.  </i> The meta-analysis compares the
results of numerous time-series studies to determine the level of increased
mortality in the general population associated with a 10 microgram per cubic
meter increase in ambient concentration of PM-10.  <i>Ex. 236, at 6, lns.
7-13.</i> <b> </b>The mean effect of a 10 microgram per cubic meter change in
PM-10 implied by these studies was a  mean increased mortality of 1.04 percent.
<i>Ex. 234, at 9, ln. 21 - 10, lns.1-2. </i>Using the dose-response
relationship derived from this meta-analysis, in combination with the BPA
model, the <p>
Environmental Coalition's witnesses estimate that one ton of  PM-10 emitted
from a Minnesota coal-fired power plant increases the state's death rate<a
href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn9">[10]</a> by  0.0016 persons per year<b>. </b><i> Ex.
234, at 10, lns. 11-19.</i><b></b><p>
<b></b>Increased ambient concentrations of PM-10 also produce morbidity
effects, which are typically measured in restricted activity days ("RADs.")
The Environmental Coalition's witnesses employed the following relationship
between PM-10 and RADs, which they defined as days missed from work, spent in
bed, or otherwise measurably constrained:  "PM-10 related RADs per person
equals 0.0556 times the annual average PM-10 concentration."  <i>Ex. 234, at
11, lns. 6-7, citing Hall, et al. 1992. "Valuing the Health Benefits of Clean
Air."  </i><cite>Science</cite><i> 255 (14 February): 812-817.  </i>  Using the
dose-response relationship derived from Hall's analysis, in combination with
the BPA emission model, the Environmental Coalition's witnesses estimate that
one ton of  PM-10 emitted from a Minnesota coal-fired facility is associated
with an increase of approximately 10.8 restricted activity days in the state.
<i>Id., lns.  11-12.</i><p>
<i></i><b></b><p>
<b>C.	In economic terms, the human health risks associated with one ton of
PM-10 <u>emissions can be valued at $7800</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
After using steps commonly employed in scientific risk assessment to determine
the human health risks associated with PM-10 emissions, the Environmental
Coalition's witnesses employ a damage cost approach to value these adverse
health effects in economic terms.  <i>Ex. 236, at 4, lns. 11-13.</i>
Increased emissions of PM-10 increase the risk of death or illness for the
entire exposed population.<b>  </b>It is this risk, which applies to all
persons exposed to the hazards of increased particulate levels, that is
valued.  <i>Ex. 234, at 5, lns. 8-10.</i><b></b><p>
<b></b>Based on a survey of the environmental economics literature,<a
href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn10">[11]</a> the Environmental Coalition's witnesses
identified $4.5 million as the appropriate estimated value for human mortality.
<i>Ex. 234, at 12, lns. 12-13.</i>   Restricted activity days associated with
airborne particulates are valued at approximately $60.<a
href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn11">[12]</a>   Using these values, they were able to
estimate the economic value of the human mortality and morbidity risks
associated with the emission of one ton of PM-10 from coal-fired generators in
Minnesota.<p>
Ultimately, the Environmental Coalition's witnesses conclude that the economic
value of human mortality risks associated with one ton of PM-10 emissions,
which increase the death rate by about  0.0016 persons per year, should be set
at approximately $7,200.  They conclude that the economic value of  human
morbidity risks associated with the emission of one ton of PM-10, which
increases the total number of PM-10-related restricted activity days by about
10.8, is approximately $648.  The Environmental  Coalition, therefore,
recommends that the Commission <p>
<p>
adopt an environmental cost value of $7800 per ton to reflect the human health
risks associated with the emission of one ton of PM-10.<b></b><p>
<b></b>While there are uncertainties associated with these values, the
estimates recommended by the Environmental Coalition most certainly
<u>underestimate</u> the total environmental cost associated with the emissions
of particulate matter from power plants.  The recommended value does not
reflect <i>any</i> of the costs associated with adverse effects on the natural
environment, such as decreased visibility.  Environmental Coalition witness,
Karen Shapiro, notes:<p>
While regulating under uncertainty may pose some risk of overestimating adverse
health effects, the fact that many NAAQS have become <u>more</u> stringent over
time indicates that many health effects may be <u>underestimated</u>.  In the
case of particulates. . .in Minnesota, there is clear evidence of significant
damage to health and an adequate basis for quantification and valuation of that
damage.  <i>Ex. </i>236<i>, at 7, lns.3-7.</i><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>III.	THE COMMISSION SHOULD SET THE FINAL ENVIRONMENTAL COST VALUE AT $50
MILLION PER TON FOR MERCURY EMISSIONS <u>ASSOCIATED WITH ELECTRIC POWER
GENERATION</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Mercury emissions from coal-fired electric generating facilities
accumulate <u>in the atmosphere, soil, water, and the bodies of  humans and
other animals</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Three quarters of all mercury deposition is from an anthropogenic
source.  <i>Ex. 234, at 18, ln. 10.</i>  A typical 500-MW  coal-fired generator
emits approximately 500 pounds of mercury per year, some of which may be
removed by existing emission-control technologies.  <i>Ex. 234, at 17, lns.
19-21, citing Moore. 1994. "Hazardous Air Pollutants:  Measuring in
Micrograms."  EPRI Journal (January/February): 7-15.  </i>Once emitted into the
environment, mercury will persist in the environment  (in the air, water and
soils) and will bioaccumulate, posing increased risks for <p>
<p>
<p>
future generations.<i>  </i>According to the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency
and the Minnesota <p>
Department of Health, mercury contamination is pervasive in Minnesota lakes.
<i>Ex. 234, at 18, lns. 7-9. </i> <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>B.	Exposure to mercury is associated with risks to human health and the
<u>environment</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Mercury is a neurotoxin and can bioaccumulate in the aquatic food chain.
The MPCA Mercury  Task Force has concluded that it is harmful to the
regeneration of some fish, and consumption of contaminated fish is hazardous to
birds and mammals -- including loons, osprey, mink, otters and humans.  <i>Ex.
234, at 18, lns. 3-6.</i>  Bioaccumulation of mercury poses increasing risks
for future generations.<p>
The Minnesota Department of Health has issued fish consumption advisories for
ninety-four percent of the lakes in Minnesota that have been surveyed.  <i>Ex.
234, at 18, lns. 7-9.</i> <i> </i>This advisory places stringent standards on
fish consumption by young children, pregnant women and women who may become
pregnant.  <i>Ex. 238, at 7, lns. 3-6.   </i>These groups require greater
protection from mercury exposure because it has neurologically damaging effects
on fetuses and children.  <i>Tr. 26, at 180, lns. 14-16.</i><b></b><p>
<b></b>The impacts of mercury emissions are ubiquitous and difficult to
trace.<i>  All Minnesotans </i>(as well as some people in other states) are
placed at risk, however, as a result of continued emission of mercury from
coal-fired generating facilities in Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 234, at 5, lns. 14-18.
</i>It is this increased risk that should be valued in this
proceeding.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>C.	Minnesotans have expressed a willingness to pay to reduce mercury
<u>emissions associated with coal-fired electric power generation.</u></b><p>
<b><u></u></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Changes in human health or other environmental risks can be valued in
terms of what society would be willing to exchange for them. <b> </b>From the
buyer's perspective, in a typical market transaction, the value of an item is
the amount the buyer is willing to pay (WTP) for it.  From the seller's
perspective, the value of an item is the amount the seller is willing to accept
(WTA) to relinquish it.  Recent empirical studies have shown that WTA values
frequently are larger that WTP values.  <i>Ex. 234, at 7, lns 1-2.</i><p>
<i></i>In a 1994 survey of 805 randomly selected Minnesota households,
Minnesota residents overwhelmingly expressed a willingness to pay to avoid
mercury emissions.  <i>Ex. 238 (JB-2.) </i>  Seventy-seven percent of the
survey respondents said they would be "willing to pay more for electricity
generated by sources that emit less mercury than coal-fired power plants."
<i>Id.</i>  Environmental Coalition witness Dr. Brody points out that:<p>
Willingness to pay more for lower mercury emissions is very broad-based across
the Minnesota population. . .a substantial majority of men and women, and all
subgroups defined by age, income, education . . . and political party
affiliation stated that they would be willing to pay more for electricity
generated by sources that emit less mercury than coal-fired power plants.
<i>Ex. 238, at 9, lns. 17-20 and at 10, lns.1-3.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>William Desvousges, a NSP witness in this proceeding, testified under
cross-examination that he recently co-authored a willingness to pay study<a
href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn12">[13]</a> that found that electric utility customers
in Wisconsin -- from all customer classes -- also indicated that they were
willing to pay higher monthly utility bills to reduce the number of fish
consumption bans on contaminated lakes.<p>
<i>Tr. 17, 112-113:</i><p>
<i></i>Q.	So I believe we would establish then that your study shows that
residential customers stated that they would be willing to pay 1.17 percent on
average more in their monthly electric bill to decrease the number of fish
consumption bans; is that correct?<p>
A.	Yes.<p>
Q.	And I believe that the same study showed that small commercial customers
were willing to -- stated a willingness to pay a .67 percent increase in their
average monthly electric bill to decrease fish consumption bans, is that
correct?<p>
A.	Yes.<p>
Q.	And farm customers were willing to pay a .11 percent increase in their
monthly electric bill; is that correct?<p>
A.	Yes.	<p>
Q.	And industrial customers were willing to pay a .9 percent? <p>
A.	Yes.<p>
Q.	Increase?<p>
A.	Yes.<p>
Q.	And large commercial customers were in fact willing to pay the largest
increase in their electric bill, a 1.44 percent increase in their average
monthly  electric bill to decrease the number of fish consumption bans; isn't
that correct?<p>
A.	Yes.<p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>Dr. Desvousges' findings are consistent with the Minnesota survey
results.  These data clearly establish that <u>people do indeed recognize the
environmental costs associated with mercury emissions and are willing to pay to
reduce those risks</u>.   The Wisconsin willingness-to-pay study, which was
partially funded by NSP and co-authored by NSP's witness, is
<u>inconsistent</u> with NSP's stated position in this case -- that mercury
should be assigned an externality  value of zero until uncertainties can be
resolved.<p>
The state of uncertainty regarding data on mercury emissions and values "should
not restrict us from valuing mercury," in the opinion of environmental health
expert, Karen Shapiro.  <i>Tr.. 26, at 155, lns 19-21.  </i>Her  colleague, Dr.
Brody, suggests the following perspective on uncertainty -- which contrasts
sharply with NSP's ostrich-like approach :<p>
[T]he best policy approach given uncertainty will depend upon the nature of the
costs, the risks, and the extent to which actions are irreversible or difficult
to mitigate once commitments have been made.  Both the construction of a new
coal-fired power plant and the release of mercury to the environment have
characteristics of irreversibility.  In this situation, I believe that it is
appropriate to adopt a preventive policy.  Based on the survey responses, I
conclude that the people of Minnesota agree.  <i>Ex. 238, at 10, </i><p>
<i>lns. 14-20.</i><b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b> <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>D.	In economic terms, the environmental risks associated with one ton of
<u>mercury emissions should be valued at </u><cite>at least</cite><u> $50
million</u>.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Public information about the potential health hazards associated with
consumption of mercury-contaminated fish is widely available.  As sport-fishing
enthusiasts acquire this information, mercury-contaminated fish could become
stigmatized, reducing the value of the fish in Minnesota waters. <i>Ex. 124, at
20, lns. 6-8.  </i> Evidence indicates that the oil spill from the wreck of the
Exxon Valdez, for example, stigmatized the salmon fishery and reduced its value
by approximately 20-40 percent.  <i>Ex. 234, at 20 , lns. 12-14, citing R.
Mendelsohn, "The Effect of the Valdez Oil Spill on Alaskan Salmon Prices,"
unpublished monograph, 10 February 1993.</i>   Environmental Coalition witness
Dr. Julia Brody notes that it is highly likely that stigmatization associated
with mercury contamination will occur in Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 234, at 20, ln
17.</i><p>
<i></i>Potential reductions in the value of the state's fish as the result of
mercury contamination are likely to be extensive.    <i>Ex. 234, at 20, ln. 11.
</i>The current value of the fish can be estimated based on expenditures on
recreational fishing in Minnesota -- what people are <u>willing to pay</u> to
catch fish.  <i>Id.</i>   According to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service,
expenditures on recreational fishing in Minnesota totalled $850 million in
1992.  <i>Ex. 124, at 20, lns. 8-10, citing U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
1992.  </i><cite>National Survey of Fishing, Hunting and Wildlife-Associated
Recreation, State Overview</cite><i>.</i><p>
<i></i>If mercury stigmatizes Minnesota's recreational fishery in the same way
that the Exxon Valdez oil spill stigmatized the Alaskan salmon fishery, the
reduction in value will be approximately $225 million per year.  <i>Ex. 234, at
20 lns. 14-16.    </i>Since air emissions of mercury from coal combustion are
one ton per year, or 19 percent of the state total, this suggests that the
environmental impact associated with these mercury emissions -- on recreational
fishing, alone<p>
 <p>
-- is roughly $50 million per year.  <i>Ex. 234, at 20, lns. 17-20. </i>  The
Environmental Coalition, therefore, recommends that the Commission adopt an
environmental cost value for mercury of <b>at least</b> $50 million per ton.
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Because the value recommended by the Environmental Coaction is based on
a measure of willingness-to-pay, rather than willingness to accept, it probably
underestimates mercury-related damage to recreational fishing.  Environmental
Coalition witness Dr. Julia Brody notes that:   "Empirical studies assessing
the magnitude of WTA have produced estimates that exceed  WTP by a factor of
four<i>  [and] . . .</i>Willingness to pay estimates are further limited by
income constraints."  <i>Ex. 238, at 4, lns. 10-19.</i><p>
An environmental cost value for mercury that is  based solely on recreational
fishing impacts is, of course, an extremely incomplete measure of the
environmental costs associated with mercury emissions from electric power
plants. <b>  </b>It does not, for instance, begin to reflect the economic
consequences of mercury's persistence in the environment -- even though impacts
associated with air emissions of mercury may persist several years, decades, or
even centuries.  <i>Ex. 234, at 21, lns.18-20.  </i> Nor  does this value
recognize the most disturbing <a href="ecbrf1_fn.html#fn13">[14]</a> problem
associated with mercury emissions, which Environmental Coalition witness summed
up as follows: <b></b><p>
<b></b>. . . <cite>the</cite> concern about mercury is that it is a neurotoxin,
that it has neurologically damaging effects to fetuses and to children.. .
putting a dollar value on <cite>that</cite> effect would be more appropriate. .
. And presumably the dollar value for such an adverse health effect as that
would be significantly greater . . .  <i>Tr. 26, at 180, lns.
14-22.</i><b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>IV.	<u>CONCLUSION</u></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Based on the evidence presented, the Environmental Coalition recommends
that the Commission adopt a final environmental cost value of $25 per ton for
carbon dioxide emissions, $550 per ton for methane emissions, $7800 per ton for
PM-10 emissions, and $50 million per ton for mercury emissions associated with
electric power generation. <b> </b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>DATE:  January 12, 1996<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
