<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>REPLY BRIEF OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION</title></head><body>	<CENTER>BEFORE THE MINNESOTA OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE
HEARINGS<BR>
	100 Washington Square, Suite 1700<BR>
	Minneapolis, Minnesota 55401-2138<BR>
<p>
	FOR THE MINNESOTA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<BR>
	121 Seventh Place East, Suite 350<BR>
	St. Paul, Minnesota 55105-2147<BR>
<p>
	MPUC Docket No. E-999/CI-93-583<BR>
	OAH Docket No. 6-2500-8632-2<p>
<p>
	In the Matter of the<BR>
	Quantification of Environmental Costs<BR>
	Pursuant to Laws of Minnesota 1993,<BR>
	Chapter 356, Section 3<BR></CENTER>
<p>
<p>
	<b>REPLY BRIEF OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION<BR>
ON SUBSTANTIVE ISSUES</b><p>
<p>
The Environmental Coalition submits this Reply Brief to respond to several
issues raised in the last round of briefs submitted by Western Fuels
Association ("WFA"), the Center for Energy &amp; Economic Development ("CEED"),
the Lignite Energy Council ("LEC"), Otter Tail Power Company ("Otter Tail"),
Minnesota Power ("MP"), Northern States Power Company ("NSP"), Minnegasco and
People's Natural Gas ("the Natural Gas Utilities"), and Cooperative Power
Association, Minnkota Power Cooperative and United Power Association ("the
Coops").  Like a herd of proverbial ostriches<a
href="ecbrf2_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a>, these parties urge the Commission to ignore
many significant environmental costs associated with electric power production
-- a position which defies both common sense and Minnesota law.  Their attempts
to use "uncertainty" as a pretext 
for ignoring the risks associated with carbon dioxide, fine particulate and
mercury emissions should be rejected.<p>
Environmental and human health impacts associated with these harmful emissions
will not conveniently disappear until scientists and economists develop a
perfect tool to measure them with complete certainty.  Recognizing this,
Minnesota's externality statute requires the Commission to be practical,
<i>not</i> perfectionist, as it fulfills its mandate to "quantify and establish
a range of environmental costs associated with each method of electricity
generation."  <i>Minn. Stat. [[section]] 216B.2422, subd. 3.</i>  The record in
this proceeding demonstrates that it <i>is</i> practicable to quantify the
environmental costs associated with the emission of criteria pollutants, carbon
dioxide and mercury.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>I.	THE RECORD CONTAINS "SUBSTANTIAL EVIDENCE" THAT SUPPORTS COMMISSION
ADOPTION OF ENVIRONMENTAL COST VALUES FOR <u>CRITERIA POLLUTANTS.
</u></b><u>
       </u><p>
<p>
A number of parties argue, unsuccessfully, that it is inappropriate to
establish environmental cost values for emissions designated as criteria
pollutants under the Clean Air Act.  <i>See, e.g., MP, at 10 and the Coops, at
12.</i>  They erroneously assume that National Ambient Air Quality Standards
("NAAQS") completely "internalize" all environmental costs associated with
emissions of pollutants such as sulfur dioxide, particulate matter and oxides
of nitrogen.  <i>Id.</i>  Some of these parties admit, however, that
"[i]nternalizing cost does not mean that the costs are eliminated."  <i>CEED,
at 4.</i>  Indeed, an expert witness appearing on behalf of Minnesota Power,
Ottertail and the electric cooperatives conceded under cross examination that
"there may be some environmental impacts at [the] point. . . [when
environmental costs are internalized because] . . . [e]liminating the
externality doesn't eliminate all the costs."  <i>Anderson, Tr. V. 24, at 191,
Ins. 11-13.</i><p>
Contrary to Ottertail Power's assertions, current air quality standards do
<u>not</u> "fully protect the public health and welfare."  <i>Otter Tail, at
12.</i>  In fact, Ottertail's own witness submitted testimony that identifies
several portions of Minnesota that are not in attainment with health-based
NAAQS:<p>
In Minnesota as a whole, the designated nonattainment areas are:  Duluth for
CO, the Minneapolis/St. Paul metro area for CO, SO2, PM-10 and lead; and
Olmstead County for SO2 and PM-10 due to violations in the Rochester metro
area.  <b><i>Roth Direct, Ex. 159, p. 25, Ins. 6-10.</i></b><i></i><p>
<i></i>In order to "fully protect" public health and welfare, Minnesota will,
at a minimum, have to go beyond existing NAAQS to meet new, more stringent
standards that the U.S. EPA is promulgating for some criteria pollutants.
<cite>American Lung Association v. Browner</cite>, <i>DC Ariz, No.
CIV-93-643-TUC-ACM.</i>  For instance, as noted in the Environmental
Coalition's Substantive Brief, exposure to fine particulates (PM-10) at levels
that meet <u>existing</u> NAAQS is associated with increased morbidity and
mortality rates.  <i>Ex. 131, at 4, Ins. 4-9.</i>  These negative impacts,
which occur despite regulatory controls, are precisely the type of
environmental costs that the Commission is required to quantify and value.<a
href="ecbrf2_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a>  <p>
<b>A.	The Environmental Coalition's PM-10 analysis is sound and its recommended
value for the environmental costs associated with PM-10 <u>emissions, $7800 per
ton, is supported by substantial evidence in the record</u>.</b><p>
After raising a general objection to the valuation of criteria pollutants, the
Initial Briefs filed by Minnesota Power and the electric cooperatives take
issue with specific aspects of the Environmental Coalition's PM-10 analysis.
<i>See, e.g., MP, at 26-31; and Coops, at 17.</i><p>
Although most of these criticisms have been addressed in the Environmental
Coalition's previous filings, this section briefly reiterates responses to the
points that they raise.  Neither party has suggested anything to alter the
Environmental Coalition's recommendation that the Commission adopt $7800 per
ton as an environmental cost value for PM-10.<p>
First, Minnesota Power criticizes the Environmental Coalition's PM-10 analysis
because it allegedly relies on a willingness-to-pay methodology.  This
assertion is simply wrong.  The Environmental Coalition's recommended PM-10
value, which focuses only on human health impacts, is based on values drawn
from a comprehensive survey of the environmental economics literature for
changes in risk of human death and morbidity (measured in restricted activity
days) from environmental facts -- not a willingness-to-pay methodology.  <i>Ex.
236, at 4, Ins. 11-13 and Ex. 234, at 5, Ins. 8-13.</i>  This is not to imply,
as attempted by Minnesota Power, that there is anything wrong with using a
willingness-to-pay approach.   The willingness-to-pay methodology is a valid
tool, used widely by economists to value changes in human health and other
environmental risks "in terms of what society would be willing to exchange for
them."  <i>Ex. 234, at 6, Ins. 8-9.</i><p>
The electric cooperatives and Minnesota Power, both, are also apparently
distressed that the Environmental Coalition's PM-10 analysis does not include a
Minnesota-specific study.  <i>Coops, at 17 and MP, at 26-29.</i>  While it is
true that the Environmental Coalition was not able to conduct its own
Minnesota-specific study for this proceeding, the Environmental Coalition used
existing data on power plan emissions of PM-10 and dispersion models which, as
the Environmental Coalition's experts explained, are appropriate to use when
estimating emission rates and dispersion patterns in Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 234, at
8 and Ex. 236 at 4, Ins. 14-20</i>.  Similarly, the Environmental Coalition's
decision to assume uniform dispersion of PM-10 and uniform population
distribution is not inappropriate for a generic planning model, where the
specific location of future electric generating facilities is unknown.  <i>Ex.
236, at 5, Ins. 1-12.</i><p>
Finally, the electric cooperatives claim that the Environmental Coalition
testimony "admits that economists are unable to estimate the value of many
environmental risks given the current data but then proceeds to do so anyway."
<i>Coops, at 18.</i>  This grossly mischaracterizes the Environmental
Coalition's testimony, which notes that economists are unable to estimate the
value of "the potential impacts on endangered species, or, more generally, on
biodiversity and ecosystem integrity."  <i>Ex. 235, at 17, Ins. 8-10.</i>  The
Environmental Coalition's witness does not attempt to value impacts of this
type.<p>
<p>
<b>II.	THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION'S CARBON DIOXIDE ANALYSIS IS SOUND AND ITS
RECOMMENDED VALUE FOR THE ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH CARBON EMISSIONS,
$25 PER TON, IS <u>SUPPORTED BY SUBSTANTIAL EVIDENCE IN THE RECORD.
       </u></b><p>
<p>
Several parties that oppose adoption of an environmental cost value for carbon
dioxide, including WFA, LEC, ND, NSP, CEED and the cooperatives, allege that
there is a lack of scientific consensus regarding the environmental impacts
associated with carbon emissions.  NSP, for instance, repeatedly asserts
that:<p>
. . . the issue of global warming, including the relationship between warming
and human activity, remains a hotly debated issue. . . there is considerable
debate and uncertainty over the presence of global warming as well as the
relationship between anthropogenic greenhouse emissions and the existence of
global warming . . . scientists continue to debate whether a global warming
trend is occurring.  <i>NSP, at 20 and 21.</i><p>
<p>
These parties repeat their concerns about uncertainty like a mantra that, if
repeated often enough, will ward off global warming.<p>
In point of fact, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has established
that there <u>is</u> a clear consensus, among the vast majority of scientists
working in relevant disciplines throughout the world, that anthropogenic
emissions of greenhouse gases (such as carbon dioxide emissions from electric
generating facilities) are increasing atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse
gases and, consequently, increasing mean global temperature by 2.7 - 8.1
degrees Fahrenheit (1.5 - 4.5 degrees Centigrade.)  <i>See EC, at 2-3, citing
the </i><cite>1992 UPCC Supplement:  Scientific Assessment of Climate
Change</cite><i>.</i>  Only a few scientists "hotly debate" this link between
anthropogenic emissions and climate change -- and many (if not most) of those
scientists appeared as witnesses in this proceeding on behalf of one of the
parties that seeks to avoid adoption of an environmental cost value for carbon.
WFA witnesses Balling, Lindzen, Michaels, Seitz and Idso represent a small, but
vocal, minority in the scientific community.  NSP witnesses Desvousges and
Harrison, who are not natural scientists and were not involved in the IPCC
process, are irrelevant to the scientific debate over global warming.<p>
Urging the Commission to set the environmental cost value for carbon dioxide at
zero, because a small minority of scientists are not convinced that there is a
relationship between anthropogenic carbon emissions and global warming, flies
in the face of reason.  A reasonable person who has gotten a second, third and
"nth" opinion confirming the need for life-saving surgery would not suddenly
reject this course of treatment if one physician is discovered who questions
this treatment option.  Nor would it be reasonable for the Commission to ignore
the great weight of scientific evidence collected by the IPCC, which clearly
establishes a relationship between anthropogenic emissions and potentially
catastrophic global warming, 
because a few scientists outside of the international consensus came to
Minnesota to appear in this proceeding.<p>
The parties that raise questions about the link between carbon emissions and
global warming also attack the Environmental Coalition's "targeted emissions
approach" to establishing an environmental cost value for carbon dioxide.  NSP
and the electric cooperatives repeat their unsupported contention that only
damage cost methodologies are acceptable.  <i>NSP, at 4 and Coops, at 11.</i>
WFA appears to recognize the validity of methodologies from which the target
emissions approach is derived -- such as risk of future regulation and
regulators' revealed preference -- but asserts that there is no "revealed
preference of regulators as to the environmental cost of carbon dioxide."
<i>WFA, at 49.</i>  Although WFA mentions the Rio Treaty and concedes that
parties to the Framework Convention on Climate Change have met to discuss
further emissions reductions <i>(WFA, at 52)</i>, this statement ignores U.S.
treaty obligations requiring greenhouse gas emissions reductions to 1990 levels
by the year 2000 and the emerging consensus favoring reductions to fifty
percent of 1990 levels by the middle of the next century -- a key predictor of
the cost of future regulation.  <i>EC, at 5, citing the IPCC and the Advisory
Group on Greenhouse Gases</i>.<p>
In a related criticism, LEC erroneously asserts that "the targeted emissions
approach requires that the Commission make general policy as to what
international levels of CO2 are desirable."  <i>LEC, at 33.</i>  WFA, CEED and
NSP similarly misconstrue the Environmental Coalition's testimony on this
point.  <i>WFA, at 49-51; CEED, at 5; and NSP at 20-21 and 28.</i>  These
criticisms miss the point.  The Environmental Coalition merely asks the
Commission to recognize the reductions in greenhouse gas emissions that,
according to the IPCC, will be necessary to achieve sustainability and to
assume that commensurate controls on carbon dioxide emissions will be a
rational regulatory response in the future.  It is not "beyond the authority
and power delegated to the Commission" to consider the cost of future
regulations in the process of establishing environmental cost values.  <i>LEC,
at 34.</i>  NSP's suggestion that sustainability may not be a "wise policy
objective" is contrary to the IPCC's stated position -- which is the best guide
as to where the future of carbon dioxide regulation lies -- and totally
disregards the rights of future generations.<p>
Finally, WFA focuses on numerous uncertainties and variable assumptions in the
eleven carbon dioxide abatement studies<a href="ecbrf2_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a>
that Environmental Coalition witness Dr. Stephen Bernow used to arrive at his
recommendation of $25 per ton as an environmental cost value for carbon dioxide
emissions.  <i>WFA, 56-63.</i>  The criticisms that WFA raises are no more
accurate than its initial assertion that Dr. Bernow appeared in this proceeding
"on behalf of the MPCA."  <i>WFA, at 45.</i>  WFA insists that Dr. Bernow's
recommended value of $25 per ton, with a range of $10 to $40 per ton, should be
rejected because Dr. Bernow cites studies which estimated marginal cost of
abatement for carbon dioxide emissions as high as $279 per ton and as low as $2
per ton.  <i>WFA, at 60.</i>  As Dr. Bernow explains in this testimony, he
developed a <u>conservative</u> estimate for this proceeding, which focused on
near-term abatement costs at the lower end of the marginal cost curve.  If Dr.
Bernow had, instead, emphasized the higher marginal costs (i.e. $279 per ton)
that will quite likely be associated with emissions reductions to fifty percent
of 1990 levels by <p>
the middle of the next century, WFA would undoubtedly find a reason to complain
about that, as well.  Dr. Bernow's $25 per ton estimate is a conservative one,
and is appropriate for the Commission's use in planning proceedings for at
least the next several years.<p>
The comments contained in the Initial Briefs of parties opposed to the adoption
of environmental cost values for carbon dioxide have not provided any basis to
reject the Environmental Coalition's recommendation that the Commission adopt
$25 per ton as the environmental cost value for carbon dioxide emissions.
Uncertainty about certain aspects of carbon dioxide-related impacts should not
be a bar to adoption of a value, despite self-serving arguments to the contrary
that have been made by several parties in this proceeding.  <i>See, e.g., LEC,
at 5-8 and WFA, at 2-3.</i>  There is nothing unusual about assessing and
managing risks that are uncertain.  People do it every day when they purchase
insurance policies, even though they don't know if or when they may get sick,
their house will catch fire or an accident will occur on the roadway.  The
people of Minnesota expect nothing less as the Public Utilities Commission
decides whether to account for carbon dioxide-related risks in the resource
planning process.  <i>EC, at 6.</i><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>III.	THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION'S MERCURY ANALYSIS IS SOUND AND ITS
RECOMMENDED VALUE FOR THE ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH MERCURY
EMISSIONS, $50 MILLION PER TON, IS <u>SUPPORTED BY SUBSTANTIAL EVIDENCE IN THE
RECORD.                     </u></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
Minnesota Power flippantly asserts that "...[a]ny value selected for mercury,
based on the record before us, could only be characterized as 'picking a number
out of a hat,'" <i>(MP, at 33-34)</i> and suggests that the Commission is
somehow being asked "to close its eyes to the uncertainties associated with the
science of mercury."  <i>(MP, at 37)</i>   This grossly mischaracterizes the
record and the position of those parties, including the Environmental
Coalition, that have made a case for Commission adoption of an environmental
cost value for mercury.  It would be far more accurate to say that Minnesota
Power and other parties advocating that no value be adopted for mercury are
asking the Commission to close its eyes to the substantial evidence in this
record that mercury emissions from electric generating facilities pose a
significant risk.  <i>(See MPCA Brief, at 43-48 and EC Brief, at 14-15 for a
summary of the scientific evidence of mercury-related risks contained in the
records.)</i><p>
The exaggerated caution that Minnesota Power, CEED, NSP and others display when
pointing out the uncertainties involved with quantifying and valuing mercury is
completely misplaced.  Genuine caution would properly be directed toward the
risks associated with mercury emissions.  This is simply common sense -- the
type of common sense that people use to survive every day.  For instance, a
cautious driver who sees something in the road ahead will immediately start to
slow down or take other action to avoid it, even though s/he may not be certain
what it is.  The consequences of waiting could be deadly.  Similarly, a
cautious regulator who sees that there is mounting evidence that mercury
emissions pose significant risks will take immediate steps to account for those
risks in resource planning, even though there are uncertainties.<p>
CEED, Minnesota Power and NSP recognize that many uncertainties about the
impacts of mercury emissions will likely be cleared up in the near future.  All
three parties note that two major studies, sponsored by the federal government
and mandated by the 1990 Amendments to the Clean Air Act, are about to be
released.  <i>(CEED, at 22; MP, at 35-6; and NSP, at 18.)</i>  Minnesota Power
also points out that the Legislative Commission on Minnesota Resources has
approved a damage cost study and a contingent valuation study of mercury.
<i>(MP, at 40.)</i>  In <p>
light of these upcoming developments, these parties should, at a minimum,
advocate that the Commission adopt a "place-holder" for mercury and re-open
this proceeding when the new studies are completed.  Instead, they ask the
Commission to adopt a zero value for mercury -- a position that is unreasonable
and that suggests these parties are blinded by short-term self-interest.<p>
NSP at least concedes that mercury is a neurotoxin that poses very real risks
to human health, but claims that its witness William Desvousges "concluded
that, given the data constraints, it was not possible to develop reliable
estimates of the potential damages from mercury."  <i>NSP, at 16, citing Ex.
135, page 5, lines 10-13.</i>  This claim is simply not credible because, as
pointed out in the Environmental Coalition's Initial Brief, Dr. Desvousges
<u>has</u> developed environmental cost values for mercury using a
willingness-to-pay methodology -- in a study that was partially funded by NSP.
<i>EC, at 17-18.</i>  CEED and Minnesota Power are even more unreasonable than
NSP.  They claim that they are unconvinced that mercury emissions cause harm,
at least not mercury emissions from Minnesota power plants and certainly not
anywhere in Minnesota.  <i>(CEED, at 13-222 and MP, at 34.)</i>  These claims
rest on the unreasonable supposition that mercury emissions from Minnesota
power plants are all magically transported beyond state borders.  This
supposition is not supported by the record.<p>
Finally, it seems worth noting (because it is so bizarre) Minnesota Power's
suggestion that mercury contamination of fish is an avoidable hazard that can
be easily eliminated:  "just don't eat the fish." <i>(MP, at 50)</i><a
href="ecbrf2_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a>  The Environmental Coalition has a better
idea.  Just don't use coal-fired power -- invest in DSM and renewable energy
sources, instead.<p>
None of the points that CEED, Minnesota Power and NSP raised in their Initial
Briefs provide any basis for rejecting the Environmental Coalition's
recommendation that the Commission adopt $50 million per ton as an
environmental cost value for mercury emissions.  Uncertainty should not be used
as an excuse for inaction.  Waiting would undoubtedly bring more certainty, but
it would also pose risks to human health and the environment that are
unacceptable to the people of Minnesota.  <i>See discussion of survey data in
EC, at 16.</i><p>
<p>
<b>IV.	<u>CONCLUSION</u></b><p>
<b><u></u></b><p>
<b><u></u></b><p>
Based on the evidence presented, as well as the reasons stated herein and in
our previous filings, the Environmental Coalition recommends that the
Commission adopt a final environmental cost value of $25 per ton for carbon
dioxide emissions, $550 per ton for methane emissions, $7800 per ton for PM-10
emissions, and $50 million per ton for mercury emissions associated with
electric power generation.<p>
<p>
DATE:	February 15, 1996<p>
<p>
<p>
