<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>PROPOSED FINDINGS AND CONCLUSIONS
OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION</title></head><body><CENTER>BEFORE THE MINNESOTA OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE
HEARINGS<BR>
	100 Washington Square, Suite 1700<BR>
	Minneapolis, Minnesota 55401-2138<BR>
<p>
	FOR THE MINNESOTA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<BR>
	121 Seventh Place East, Suite 350<BR>
	St. Paul, Minnesota 55105-2147<BR>
<p>
	MPUC Docket No. E-999/CI-93-583<BR>
	OAH Docket No. 6-2500-8632-2<p>
<p>
	In the Matter of the<BR>
	Quantification of Environmental Costs<BR>
	Pursuant to Laws of Minnesota 1993,<BR>
	Chapter 356, Section 3<BR></CENTER>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>PROPOSED FINDINGS AND CONCLUSIONS<BR>
OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION</b><p>
<p>
The Environmental Coalition proposes that the Administrative Law Judge
adopt the following findings of fact and conclusions, based on the proceedings
in this docket.  The Coalition also endorses the findings and conclusions
proposed by the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency which relate to adoption of
a value for sulfur dioxide emissions.  The Environmental Coalition does not
object to the Department of Public Service's proposed findings and conclusions
which relate to carbon monoxide, lead and nitrogen oxides.<b></b><p>
<b><u>Issues and Procedure</u></b><p>
<b><u></u></b>1.	The purpose of this proceeding is to "quantify and establish a
range of environmental costs associated with each method of electricity
generation," pursuant to Minn. Stat. ' 216B.2422, subd. 4(a).  The
environmental cost values established in this docket are to be used by
utilities "when evaluating and selecting resource options in all proceedings
before the commission, including resource plan and certificate of need
proceedings."  <i>Id.</i><b><u></u></b><p>
<b><u></u></b>2.	On March 3, 1994 the Commission issued its Notice and Order
for Hearing in this docket, which initiated a contested case proceeding to
establish final environmental cost values,  pursuant to Minn. Stat. '
216B.2422, subd. 4(a), to replace the interim environmental cost values
adopted by the Commission on March 1, 1994.<p>
3.	A prehearing conference was held in St. Paul on June 28, 1994 to address
issues related to the scope of the hearing.<p>
4.	Evidentiary hearings commenced in St. Paul on May 8, 1995 and continued
through June 28, 1995.  Their were 27 days of evidentiary hearings.<p>
5. 	Public hearings were held in Duluth on April 18, 1995; in Minneapolis on
April 18, 1995; in Fergus Falls on April 20, 1995; in Rochester on April 25,
1995; in St. Paul on April 26, 1995; and by teleconference in Bemidji, Brainerd
and Windom on April 27, 1995.    <p>
<b><u>Findings of Fact</u></b><p>
<b><u></u>Carbon Dioxide Emissions</b><p>
<b></b>6.	Electric utilities produce over one-third of the carbon dioxide
emitted from anthropogenic sources in the United States, and eighty percent of
those emissions come from coal-fired power plants.  <i>Tr. 15, at 179, lns.
14-17.</i><p>
<i></i>7.	Carbon dioxide is often characterized as a "greenhouse gas" because
it acts to trap heat in the troposphere.<p>
8.	The concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere is now about 350 parts
per million and is increasing at a rate of  0.5 percent annually.  <i>Ex. 111
(SB-2, at 15.)</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><b></b><p>
<b></b>9.	In 1987, the United Nations Environment Program and the World
Meteorological Organization created the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate
Change ("IPCC") to evaluate the environmental impacts associated with
anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide.  <i>Ex.
113, at 1-2.</i> <b></b><p>
<b></b>10.	The IPCC's 1992 Supplement to its <u>Scientific Assessment of
Climate Change</u> states that "emissions resulting from human activities are
substantially increasing the atmospheric concentrations of the greenhouse
gases. . . [which] will enhance the greenhouse effect, resulting on average in
an additional warming of the Earth's surface."  <i>Ex. 111, at 3, citing
</i><cite>1992 IPCC Supplement: Scientific Assessment of Climate
Change</cite><i>, at XI.</i><p>
<i></i>11.	According to the IPCC, doubling carbon dioxide concentrations in the
atmosphere would lead to an increase in global average temperature that is
unlikely to lie outside the range of 2.7 to 8.1 degrees Fahrenheit (1.5 - 4.5
degrees Celsius.)  <i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 16, citing the </i><cite>1992
Supplement: Scientific Assessment</cite><i>, at 5.)  </i> IPCC Chairman Bert
Bolin notes that the risk of more severe and damaging climate change is as
great as the risk of less severe impacts.   <i>Ex. 111, at 3.</i><p>
12.	IPCC reports are the most authoritative sources available for information
on climate change issues because the IPCC research and peer review process
evaluates all available scientific information on factors affecting climate
change, including greenhouse gas emissions, and assesses the
atmosphere-ocean-land-ice system responses to these factors.  <i>Ex. 113, at 2,
lns. 5-7.  </i>Prior to publication, IPCC research reports are developed by
technical committees composed of experts from throughout the international
scientific community and are subjected to a rigorous multi-level peer review
process that ultimately involves most scientists working in relevant
disciplines.<p>
13.	Western Fuels Association witnesses Balling Lindzen, Michaels, Seitz and
Idso represent a small, but vocal minority that takes issue with the IPCC's
conclusions on climate change issues.  Their views should be accorded very
little weight because they are not representative of the international
scientific consensus on climate change issues and are, therefore, unlikely to
affect the development of future regulation in this area.<p>
14.	Climate change, due to increased atmospheric loading of greenhouse gases,
could involve a number of potentially catastrophic impacts -- including a rise
in sea level, heightened climatic variability and, consequently, changes in
vegetation.  <i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 16.)</i><p>
<i></i>15.	Although it is difficult to draw conclusions about shifts in the
distribution of precipitation, agricultural output, and frequency and severity
of extreme weather events for a specific location, such as Minnesota, some
climate change models have been developed that show the "grain belts" of the
Northern hemisphere shifting north by hundreds of kilometers and predict
significant die-back of Boreal forests -- the spruce/pine/fir forests found in
the Boundary Waters Canoe Area, Superior National Forest and other parts of
northern Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 69, at 4-5 and Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 16.)
</i>Laboratory studies also show that certain plants, including a type of pine
which grows in Boreal forests, is very adversely affected by increased exposure
to carbon dioxide.  <i>Tr. 10, at 82, lns. 19-25 through 83, lns. 1-12.</i><p>
<i></i>16.	The U. S. is obligated to reduce anthropogenic emissions of carbon
dioxide to 1990 levels by the end of the decade under the terms of an
international treaty, known as the Framework Convention on Climate Change
("FCCC"), which was ratified by the U.S. Senate in 1992.  <i>Ex. 112, at 3,
lns. 1-5.   </i>Utilities will have to implement measures to substantially
reduce carbon dioxide emissions if the U.S. is to meet its treaty obligations.
<i>Ex. 111, at 5, lns. 10-12.  </i><p>
<i></i>17	The FCCC commitment to stabilize carbon dioxide emissions at current
levels, represents only a modest first step to reach stabilization of carbon
dioxide concentrations in the atmosphere.  In order to stabilize the earth's
climate, the IPCC and the Advisory Group on<p>
Greenhouse Gases estimate that carbon dioxide emission levels will need to be
reduced by at least fifty percent below 1990 levels by the middle of the next
century.<p>
18.	FCCC signatories have already concluded that further greenhouse gas
emission reductions will be necessary to protect the earth's climate.
<i>Exhibit 113, at 4, lns. 18-19.  </i> During the Spring of 1995, at a
Conference of the Parties in Berlin, the U.S. and other developed country  FCCC
parties initiated a "process of strengthening commitments" that would "set
quantified limitations and reduction objectives. . .for their anthropogenic
emissions."  <i>Ex. 113 (SB-4.)</i><p>
<i></i>19.	The international scientific and political consensus regarding the
level of carbon dioxide emission reductions that will be necessary to stabilize
the earth's climate, has developed despite uncertainty about the magnitude,
distribution, and timing of climate change and climate change-related impacts.
<i></i><p>
<i></i>20.	A recent statewide public opinion survey prepared for this
proceeding shows that an overwhelming majority of Minnesota residents -- 82
percent -- believe that the State of Minnesota should make at least some
changes to reduce the potential for global warming.  <i>Ex. 112 (SB-3,
University of Minnesota Center for Survey Research 1994 Minnesota State Survey,
at 33.)</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>21.	Many of the citizens who testified during the public hearings held
in this docket identified adoption of externality values for greenhouse gas
emissions as an important step that should be taken to reduce the risk of
climate change.  <i>(See, for example, the testimony of  University of
Minnesota Professor Dean Abrahamson at the St. Paul public hearing on April 26,
1995, and the testimony of dairy farmer Ken Tschumper at the Rochester public
hearing on April 25, 1995.)</i><p>
<i></i>22.	Adoption of an environmental cost value for carbon dioxide emissions
is a reasonable and appropriate policy response to address the risk of climate
change because it will help to defer irreversible commitments to resources that
may contribute to the global warming problem.  <i>Ex. 112, at 6, lns.
17-20.</i><p>
<B>Discussion</B><p>
Environmental Coalition witness Dr. Stephen Bernow recommended that the
Commission use a "Pascal's wager" approach to determine whether to establish an
externality value for  carbon dioxide:<p>
If we act to prevent global warming and later discover that the impact is
relatively benign, our costs will be limited to some potentially unnecessary
emission reduction expenses.  If, instead, we choose not to act and
unprecedented climate change occurs, we could incur catastrophic. . .ecological
losses.  <i>Ex. 112, at 6, lns. 7-13.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>23.	Environmental Coalition witness Dr. Stephen Bernow, who is involved
in the IPCC process as a reviewer, premised his testimony in this docket on the
IPCC's conclusions regarding:  (1) the extent to which anthropogenic emissions
of greenhouse gases are associated with an increase in mean global temperature,
(2) the nature and extent of various environmental impacts associated with
increased temperatures, and (3) the extent to which greenhouse gas emissions
must be reduced to achieve climate stabilization.<i>  Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 21 et
seq.)</i>   Starting with the IPCC's findings on these three key points, Dr.
Bernow uses a two-step analytical process to determine an appropriate
externality value for greenhouse gas emissions associated with electric power
generation.<p>
24.	Dr. Bernow's analysis -- which he refers to as an environmental target
approach -- is a hybrid of the damage cost and risk of regulation methodologies
sometimes used to determine environmental externality values. <i>Ex. 111 (SB-2,
at 21 et. seq.)</i>  This approach consists of two steps:  (1) determining a
target that, at a minimum, prevents irreversible damage to the environment, and
(2) assessing the marginal cost of achieving the target.    <i></i><p>
<i></i>25.	Determining a target that prevents irreversible damage to the
environment, like a damage cost methodology, focuses on the physical impacts
associated with the emission of greenhouse gases.  Since a greenhouse gas
emission reduction to fifty percent of 1990 levels by the middle of the next
century is needed to stabilize the earth's climate (see, <i>supra</i>, Findings
17 and 18) this is the environmental target that prevents irreversible damage
to the environment.<p>
26.	To determine the marginal cost of reducing U.S. greenhouse gas emissions to
1990 levels by 2050, Dr. Bernow reviewed eleven recent studies that examine
greenhouse gas abatement costs.  <i>Ex. 111 (SB-2, at 24-37.)  </i>After
evaluating the various modelling techniques and the range of assumptions about
baseline and future conditions used in each study, Dr. Bernow developed his own
estimate of the marginal cost associated with reducing greenhouse gas emissions
to levels that would stabilize the earth's climate by the middle of the next
century.  Based on this analysis, Dr. Bernow recommends an environmental cost
value of $25 per ton for carbon dioxide emissions associated with electric
power generation.  <i>Ex. 111, at 7, lns. 18-22.</i> <b></b><p>
<b></b>27.	Dr. Bernow recommends an environmental cost value of $550 per ton
for methane.  <i>Ex. 111, at 7, lns. 18-22.  </i>The recommended value for
methane is derived directly <p>
from the value for carbon dioxide.  Methane has a 100-year Global Warming
Potential that is twenty-two times greater than carbon dioxide.  <i>Ex. 111
(SB-2, at 38.)</i><p>
<i></i>28.	The environmental cost values that Dr. Bernow recommends, $25 per
ton of carbon dioxide and $550 per ton of methane, are based on the IPCC
reports and a critical review of recent greenhouse gas abatement cost studies
-- the best available evidence.  It is both reasonable and appropriate that the
Commission adopt these values for use in resource planning processes.<b></b><p>
<b>Particulate Matter (PM-10) Emissions</b><p>
<b></b>29.	Particulate emissions from coal-fired generating facilities are made
up of particles that are generally divided into three categories on the basis
of size:  (1) nonrespirable matter that has an aerodynamic diameter greater
than 10 micrometers; (2) smaller, inhalable particles that are less than 10
micrometers in diameter ("PM-10"); and (3) fine particles that are no more than
2.5 micrometers in diameter ("PM-2.5").  <i>Ex. 234, at 9, lns. 4-7.  </i>Small
particle emissions, those that are less than ten micrometers in diameter, pose
the greatest risk to human health.  <i>Id.</i><p>
<i></i>30.	The Environmental Coalition's witnesses used a model developed for
the Bonneville Power Administration to estimate the effect on ambient air
quality associated with the emission of one ton of PM-10 from a generic
coal-fired power plant.  <i>Ex.  234, at 8.</i>  Because the BPA study used a
screening model that does not rely upon site-specific geographical and
climatological data, it is applicable to Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 236, at 4.</i><p>
<p>
31.	Based on the Environmental Coalition's analysis, it is reasonable to
conclude that one ton of PM-10 emitted from a generic coal-fired power plant
would, on average, increase <p>
ambient concentrations of PM-10 by 0.000083 micrograms per cubic meter over
53.6 percent of the state of  Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 236, at 8. </i> <i></i><p>
<i></i>32.	Small particle emissions from coal-fired generating facilities
present a very grave threat to human health.  Inhalation of fine particles,
especially fine sulfate particle, increases the risk of mortality (shortening
life by several years) and morbidity -- even in areas <u>in attainment</u> with
National Ambient Air Quality Standards ("NAAQS") for particulate and sulfur
dioxide emissions.  <i>See, Ex. 131, at 4, lns. 4-9.</i><p>
<i></i>33.	Hospital admissions for the elderly in Minneapolis-St. Paul are
significantly associated with PM-10 . . .at concentrations below the NAAQS."
<i>Ex. 132, at, 2, lns. 15-17.</i><p>
<i></i>34.	The U.S. EPA is currently under court order to promulgate stricter
NAAQS for PM-10 because existing standards are not sufficiently protective of
human health.  <cite>American Lung Association v. Browner</cite><i>, DC Ariz.,
No. CIV-93-643-TUC-ACM, 10/6/94.</i><p>
<i></i>35.	Existing NAAQS do not internalize the environmental costs associated
with emissions of particulate matter from electric generating facilities.  The
negative impacts which occur despite these regulatory controls, are precisely
the type of environmental costs that the Commission is required to quantify and
value in this proceedings. <i>	</i><p>
<i></i>36.	The Environmental Coalition's witnesses estimated that one ton of
PM-10 emitted from a Minnesota coal-fired power plant increases the state's
death rate  by 0.0016 persons per year.  <i>Ex. 234, at 10, Lns. 11-19.
</i>This dose-response relationship was derived by using the BPA model
(described, <i>supra,</i> in Findings 30 and 31) in combination with a
meta-analysis, which examined the results of numerous time-series studies to
determine the level of increased mortality in the general population associated
with a 10 microgram per cubic meter increase in ambient concentrations of
PM-10.<i>  Ex. 236, at 6, lns. 7-13, citing Ostro, 1993, "The Association of
Air Pollution and Mortality:  Examining the Case for Inference,"
</i><cite>Archives of Environmental Health</cite><i>  48 (5):  336-342.
</i>The mean effect of a 10 microgram per cubic meter change in PM-10 implied
by these studies was a mean increased mortality of 1.04 percent.  <i>Ex. 234,
at 9, ln. 21 and at 10, lns. 1-2.</i><b></b><p>
<b></b>37.	Increased ambient concentrations of PM-10 also produce morbidity
effects, which are typically measured in restricted activity days ("RADs").
The Environmental Coalition's witnesses employed the following relationship
between PM-10 and RAD, which they defined as days missed from work, spent in
bed, or otherwise measurably constrained:  "PM-10 related RADs per person
equals 0.0556 times the annual average PM-10 concentration."  <i>Ex. 234, at
11, lns. 6-7, citing Hall, et al., 1992, "Valuing the Health Benefits of Clean
Air,"  </i><cite>Science</cite><i>  255 (14 February): 812-817.  </i>Using this
dose-response relationship, in combination with the BPA emission model, the
Environmental Coalition's witnesses estimate that one ton of PM-10 emitted from
a Minnesota coal-fired facility is associated with an increase of approximately
10.8 RAD in the state.  <i>Id., lns. 11-12.</i><p>
<i></i>38.	The Environmental Coalition's witnesses use a damage cost approach
to value the adverse health effects associated with PM-10 emissions.  <i>Ex.
236, at 4, lns. 11-13.  </i>Based on a survey of the environmental economics
literature, the Environmental Coalition's witnesses <p>
<p>
<p>
identified $4.5 million as the appropriate estimated value for human mortality.
  <i>Ex. 234, at 12, lns 12-13.  </i>Restricted activity days associated with
airborne particulates are valued at approximately $60 per day.  <i>Ex. 234, at
13. </i><p>
<i></i>39.	Ultimately, the Environmental Coalition's witnesses concluded that
the human health risks associated with the emission of one ton of PM-10 should
be valued at $7800 per ton. <i>Ex. 234, at 13.</i>  This value consists of
mortality and morbidity components.   The economic value of the human mortality
risks associated with one ton of PM-10 emissions, which increases the state
death rate by about 0.0016 persons per year, is approximately $7200.   The
economic value of human morbidity risks associated with the emission of one ton
of PM-10, which increases the total number of PM-10 related restricted activity
days in Minnesota by about 10.8, is approximately $648.<p>
40.	The Environmental Coalition's recommended value of $7800 per ton of PM-10
is reasonable and appropriate for use in resource planning proceedings.  This
value does not, of course, reflect any of the costs associated with adverse
effect of the natural environment, such as decreased visibility.  As such, this
value most certainly underestimates the total environmental costs associated
with the emission of particulate matter from power plants.   <b></b><p>
<b>Mercury Emissions</b><p>
<b></b>41.	Three-quarters of all mercury deposition is from an anthropogenic
source.  <i>Ex. 234, at 18, ln. 10.  </i>A typical 500-MW coal-fired generator
emits approximately 500 pounds of mercury per year, some of which may be
removed by existing emission-control technologies.  <i>Ex. 234, at 17, lns.
19-21, citing Moore, 1994, "Hazardous Air Pollutants: Measuring in Micrograms,"
</i><cite>EPRI Journal</cite><i> (January/February): 7-15.</i><p>
<i></i>42.	Once emitted into the biosphere, mercury persists in the environment
(in the air, water and soil.)   According to the Minnesota Pollution Control
Agency and the Minnesota Department of Health, mercury contamination is
pervasive in Minnesota lakes.  <i>Ex. 234, at 18, </i><p>
<i>Lns. 7-9.  </i>Impacts associated with mercury emissions may persist several
years, decades, or even centuries.  <i>Ex. 234, at 21, lns. 18-20.</i><p>
<i></i>43.	Mercury is a neurotoxin and can bioaccumulate in the aquatic food
chain.  <i>Tr. 26, at 180.  </i>The MPCA Mercury Task Force has concluded that
mercury contamination is harmful to the regeneration of some fish, and
consumption of contaminated fish is hazardous to birds and mammals -- including
loons, osprey, mink, otter and humans.  <i>Ex. 234, at 18, lns. 3-6.</i><p>
<i></i>44.	All Minnesotans (as well as some people in other states) are placed
at risk as a result of continued emission of mercury from coal-fired generating
facilities in Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 234, at 5, lns. 14-18.  </i>Bioaccumulation of
mercury poses increasing risks for future generations.  <i>Tr. 26, at
180.</i><p>
<i></i>45.	According to a 1994 state-wide survey conducted for this proceeding,
Minnesota residents overwhelmingly expressed a willingness to pay to avoid
mercury emissions.  <i>Ex. 238 (JB-2.)  </i>Seventy-seven percent of the survey
respondents said they would be "willing to pay more for electricity generated
by sources that emit less mercury than coal-fired power plants."  <i>Id.
</i>Willingness to pay more for lower mercury emissions is very broad-based --
across all demographic subgroups in Minnesota, as defined by  age, income,
education, gender and political affiliation.  <i>Ex. 238, at 9 -10.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<p>
46.	Wisconsin electric utility customers also say that they are willing to pay
higher electric bills to reduce fish consumption bans on lakes, according to a
recent study co-authored by NSP witness Dr. William Desvousges.  <i>Tr. 17, at
112-113.   </i>This Wisconsin willingness-to-pay study, which was partially
funded by NSP,  is inconsistent with NSP's stated position in this case -- that
mercury should be assigned an externality value of zero until uncertainties can
be resolved.    NSP's recommendations relating to mercury in this docket are
not supported by the record and are, therefore, rejected.<p>
47.	The Minnesota and Wisconsin willingness-to-pay survey data clearly
establish that people recognize the environmental costs associated with mercury
emissions and are willing to pay to reduce those risks, even though there are
uncertainties regarding impacts associated with mercury emissions.  <p>
<B>Discussion</B><p>
<p>
Environmental Coalition witness Dr. Julia Brody suggests the following
perspective on 
uncertainty:<p>

[T]he best policy approach given uncertainty will depend upon the nature of the
costs, the risks, and the extent to which actions are irreversible or difficult
to mitigate once commitments have been made.  Both the construction of a new
coal-fired power plant and the release of mercury to the environment have
characteristics of irreversibility.  In this situation. . . it is appropriate
to adopt a preventive policy.  Based on the survey responses, I conclude that
the people of  Minnesota agree.  <i>Ex. 238, at 10, lns. 14-20.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>48.	Public information about the potential health hazards associated
with consumption of  mercury-contaminated fish is widely available.  As
sport-fishing enthusiasts acquire this information, mercury-contaminated fish
could become stigmatized, reducing the value of the fish in Minnesota waters.
<i>Ex. 124, at 20, lns. 6-8.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>49.	The current value of the fish in Minnesota waters can be estimated
based on expenditures on recreational fishing in Minnesota -- what people are
willing to pay to catch fish.  <i>Ex. 234, at 20, ln. 11.  </i>According to the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, expenditures on recreational fishing in
Minnesota totalled $850 million in 1992.  <i>Ex. 124, at 20, lns. 8-10, citing
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, 1992, </i><cite>National survey of Fishing,
Hunting and Wildlife-Associated Recreation, State Overview</cite><i>.</i><p>
50.	Environmental Coalition witness Dr. Brody notes that it is highly likely
that stigmatization associated with mercury  contamination will occur in
Minnesota.  <i>Ex. 234, at 20, ln. 17.  </i>  Potential reductions in the value
of the state's fish as the result of mercury contamination and stigmatization
are likely to be extensive.  <i>Ex. 234, at 20, ln. 11.  </i> For instance, the
oil spill from the wreck of the Exxon Valdez stigmatized the Alaskan salmon
fishery and reduced its value by approximately 20-40 percent.  <i>Ex. 234, at
20, lns 12-14.</i><p>
<i></i>51.	If mercury stigmatizes Minnesota's recreational fishery to the same
extent that the Exxon<i> </i>Valdez spill stigmatized the Alaskan salmon
fishery, the reduction in value would be approximately $255 million per year.
<i>Ex. 234, at 20, lns. 14-16.  </i>Since air emissions of mercury from coal
combustion are one ton per year, or 19 percent of the state total, this
suggests that the environmental impact associated with these mercury emissions
-- on recreational fishing, alone   -- may be roughly $50 million per year.
<i>Ex. 234, at 20, lns. 17-20.</i><p>
52.	The Environmental Coalition's recommended value of $50 million per ton of
mercury is reasonable and appropriate for use in resource planning proceedings.
An environmental cost value for mercury that is based solely on recreational
fishing impacts is, of course, an extremely incomplete measure of the
environmental costs associated with mercury emissions from electric power
plants.  It does not, for instance, begin to reflect the most disturbing
problem associated with mercury emissions -- that mercury is a neurotoxin, that
has neurologically damaging effects to fetuses and to children -- a problem
that is extremely difficult to value in economic terms.<i></i><p>
<i></i><b><u>Conclusions</u></b><p>
<b></b>1.	The purpose of this proceeding is to "quantify and establish a range
of environmental costs associated with each method of electricity generation,"
pursuant to Minn. Stat. ' 216B.2422, subd. 4(a).  The environmental cost values
established in this docket are to be used by utilities "when evaluating and
selecting resource options in all proceedings before the commission, including
resource plan and certificate of need proceedings."  <i>Id.</i> <p>
2.	Utilities are required to value carbon dioxide emissions associated with
electric power generation at $25 per ton when evaluating and selecting resource
options in all proceedings before the commission, including resource planning
and certificate of need proceedings.<p>
3.	Utilities are required to value methane emissions associated with electric
power generation at $550 per ton when evaluating and selecting resource options
in all proceedings before the commission, including resource planning and
certificate of need proceedings.<p>
4.	Utilities are required to value fine particulate matter (PM-10) emissions
associated with electric power generation at $7800 per ton when evaluating and
selecting resource options in all proceedings before the commission, including
resource planning and certificate of need proceedings.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>5.	Utilities are required to value mercury emissions associated with
electric power generation at $50 million per ton when evaluating and selecting
resource options in all proceedings before the commission, including resource
planning and certificate of need proceedings.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>DATE:  February 23, 1996<p>
<p>
<p>
