<tt><b>BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</b></tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Joel Jacobs				Chair    </tt><p>
<tt>Dee Knaak				Commissioner</tt><p>
<tt>Thomas Burton			Commissioner</tt><p>
<tt>R. Marshall Johnson			Commissioner</tt><p>
<tt>Don Storm				Commissioner</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>MPUC Docket No. E-999/CI-93-583</tt><p>
<tt>OAH File No. 6-2500-8632-2</tt><p>

<tt>---------------------------------------------------</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt><b>In the Matter of Quantification of Environmental Costs</b></tt><p>
<tt><b>Pursuant to Laws of Minnesota 1993, Chapter 356, Section 3</b></tt><p>
<tt><b></b></tt><p>
<tt><b>------------------------------------------------------</b><P>



<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>EXCEPTIONS OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION TO THE FINDINGS OF FACT, CONCLUSIONS AND RECOMMENDATION OF THE ADMINISTRATIVE LAW JUDGE</H3>

<tt>Having reviewed the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="kleinfof.html">Findings of Fact, Conclusions of Law and
Recommendations</A> filed by the Administrative Law Judge ("ALJ")  on March 25,
1996, the Environmental Coalition</tt><a
href="ecexcept_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a><tt> hereby submits its exceptions.  The
Environmental Coalition also requests that the Commission hold oral argument on
the issues raised in these exceptions.</tt><p>
<tt><b><u>CRITERIA POLLUTANTS</u></b></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition agrees with the ALJ's findings rejecting the
notion that environmental costs are eliminated when ambient concentrations of
criteria pollutants are below National Ambient Air Quality Standards ("NAAQS.")
<i>See Findings No. 44 - 47.  </i>However, the Environmental Coalition proposes
changes  to several other findings relating to criteria pollutants.
Specifically, the Environmental Coalition proposes that the Commission amend
the ALJ's Finding No. 49 by deleting the final fifteen words, which suggest
that previous studies show that criteria pollutants account for most of the
environmental damage associated with electric power generation. This portion of
Finding No. 49 is not supported by the record and quite clearly conflicts with
the ALJ's Findings relating to the damage associated with  carbon dioxide and
mercury emissions.  <i>See, Findings Nos. 80 - 94  and Findings Nos. 120 -124,
respectively.   </i>The amended Finding No. 49 would, therefore, read as
follows:</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 49	The TER Study examined the effects of the six criteria
pollutants because they have been the focus of air quality regulations and data
on these pollutants generally are sufficient to implement a damage costs
approach.</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition also recommends that the Commission insert two
additional words in the first sentence of the next finding, to more accurately
reflect the record and to make Finding  No. 50 consistent with Finding No.
55:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 50	The TER Study developed environmental costs for three
planning scenarios in order to capture <u>some of</u> the relevant effects and
the magnitude and location of potential damages.  These planning scenarios
included a rural scenario, a metropolitan fringe scenario and an urban
scenario.  Each planning scenario includes existing NSP resources as well as
new resources located in specific areas throughout the study area in order to
identify the effect of location on study results. <i> Ex. 136, Executive
Summary, pp. 2-4.</i> </tt><p>
<tt>As noted in Finding No. 55, the TER Study examined <i>only</i> three main
categories of  potential effects:  "human health effects in the form of
morbidity and mortality risks, agricultural effects in the form of reduced crop
yields, and material damages in the form of stone and metal corrosion and
surface soiling."  <i>Finding No. 55, citing Ex. 135, pp. 5-6.  </i>The study
failed to examine other significant effects, including the acidification of
lakes associated with emissions of sulfur and nitrogen oxides -- even in NAAQS
attainment areas.</tt><p>

<tt><b><u>Sulfur Dioxide</u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b>The Environmental Coalition recommends that the Commission
reject the ALJ's findings relating to use of a zero value for sulfur dioxide
emissions after the year 2000.  <i>See Findings Nos.  77-79. </i> The ALJ's
recommendation presumes that the annual cap on sulfur dioxide emissions,
established in the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, will result in elimination
of all environmental impacts associated with sulfur dioxide emissions.  He
expressly rejected this type of assumption with respect to NAAQS</tt><a
href="ecexcept_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a><tt> and should do so here. The record does
not support a finding that the sulfur dioxide emission cap will end sulfur
dioxide-related damage to human health and the environment.</tt><p>
<tt>After the turn of the century, even though the cap will be in place,
approximately nine million tons of sulfur dioxide can be emitted each year.
That means that people who live near coal-fired power plants will continue to
be exposed to potentially lethal sulfate particles.   Long range transport of
sulfur dioxide emissions from coal-fired power plants will also continue to
contribute to acid precipitation -- despite the cap.</tt><p>
<tt>Absent a showing that the sulfur dioxide emissions cap is "necessarily set
at no-cost levels"  (<i>see note 2)</i>, each ton of sulfur dioxide emitted
after the year 2000 should be valued at the same level as a ton of sulfur
dioxide emitted before the year 2000.  As noted above, there has been no such
showing in this case.  Use of a zero value for  post-2000 sulfur emissions
would leave the Commission without a means of comparing the obvious difference
in environmental costs associated with two identical coal-fired generating
facilities, when one is proposed for a rural area and the other is proposed for
a metropolitan area where significant populations could be exposed to sulfate
emissions up to NAAQS levels.  The Commission would, of course, also be unable
to compare the difference in environmental costs associated with the latter
coal-fired facility and a gas turbine or wind generator.  A resource planning
process which arbitrarily avoids evaluation of the environmental costs
associated with sulfur dioxide emissions after the turn of the century could,
therefore, easily result in suboptimal resource selection.</tt><p>
<tt>To properly account for sulfur dioxide-related environmental damage after
the year 2000, the Environmental Coalition recommends that the Commission
revise Finding No. 77 by deleting the last four sentences and adding the
underlined language:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 77	A number of parties testified that SO2 should be treated
differently than other air pollutants because of the regulatory requirements
affecting utility emissions of SO2.  Sulfur dioxide emissions are subject to
federal regulation under the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments ("CAAA").  The 1990
Clean Air Act Amendments established a nationwide cap on utility emissions of
SO2 as well as a national SO2 allowance trading program.  The nationwide cap
starting in the year 2000 is approximately 8.9 million tons annually.  The
trading program allocates each existing source a fixed number of allowances,
but allows sources to trade the allowances freely.  Each allowance represents
one ton of emissions.  The owner of each source must submit sufficient
allowances at the end of each year to cover its emissions.  If a source emits
more than its allocation, its owner must obtain allowances from within its
system or buy them from another firm with excess allowances.  Ex. 8, p. 47, Ex.
37, p. 25.  The allowance trading program has been implemented in phases.  In
Phase I, beginning in 1995, some sources are covered.  At least one existing
facility in Minnesota, NSP's High Bridge Unit 6 facility, is covered by the
Phase I allowance program.  Ex. 8, p. 46.  In Phase II, beginning in 2000,
virtually all resources that emit SO2 in Minnesota and the rest of the country
will be included in the emission allowance trading program.  <i>Id.</i>
<u>While</u> the effect of an emissions cap enforced through tradable
allowances should be to reduce the amount of net new emissions (nationally) to
zero, <u>annual sulfur dioxide emissions totalling approximately nine million
tons will be allowed to continue, with all of the attendant impacts on human
health and the environment.  It is, therefore, impossible to conclude that the
SO2 allowance trading program internalizes damages related to SO2.</u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition also recommends that the Commission delete the
ALJ's </tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 79 and substitute the following language:</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finding  No. 79<u>	The sulfur dioxide emission cap imposed under the 1990
Clean Air Act Amendments allows nine million tons of sulfur dioxide emissions
to continue each year after the turn of the century.  This cap will not
necessarily eliminate sulfur-dioxide related damage to human health and the
environment.  The Commission's planning processes must, therefore, account for
any damage associated with post-2000 sulfur dioxide emissions by resource
additions proposed by Minnesota utilities.  The pre-2000 environmental cost
values for SO2 developed in the TER study, as modified in response to Dr.
Thayer,  should also be used to account for post-2000 sulfur dioxide
emissions.</u></tt><p>

<tt><b><u>Carbon Dioxide</u></b></tt><p>

<tt>The Environmental Coalition agrees with the ALJ's findings adopting the
conclusions of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change ("IPCC") regarding
the environmental impacts associated with carbon dioxide emissions.  <i>See
Findings Nos. 80 - 94. </i> We disagree, however, with the ALJ's
characterization of the "emissions target" approach used by Environmental
Coalition witness Dr. Stephen Bernow to determine the environmental cost of
carbon dioxide emissions.  The Environmental Coalition, therefore, proposes
several changes to the ALJ's findings regarding the emissions target
methodology to more accurately reflect the record.</tt><p>
<tt>First, the Environmental Coalition recommends that the Commission delete
the third line of  Finding No. 96.  As revised, Finding No. 96 would read as
follows:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 96	This approach involves a two-step process:  (1) selecting an
environmental target; and (2) determining the marginal cost of achieving this
target.  This methodology attempts to determine the cost of meeting particular
environmental goals to stabilize the earth's climate.  <i>Ex. 111, Attachment
SB-2 at 21.</i></tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Secondly, the Environmental Coalition proposes that the Commission replace
Finding No. 98</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>with the following language, which relates the emissions target approach to
the analysis of</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>environmental cost methodolgies (<i>Findings, at 19)</i> contained in the
ALJ's Discussion of Policy</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Issues:</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 98<u>	The emissions target approach is conceptually related to
cost of control and risk of regulation methodologies.  This approach assumes
that regulators will impose controls on greenhouse gas emissions to stabilize
climate and that the cost of required abatement measures will be approximately
equal to the environmental costs avoided by controlling emissions.</u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition also recommends that the Commission add the
following sentence to Finding No. 99, to demonstrate that is reasonable to
expect that regulators will adopt the target selected by Dr. Bernow -- a carbon
dioxide emission reduction to fifty percent of 1985 levels by the middle of
the next century: </tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 99	The target selected by Dr. Bernow has not been adopted by
any country or by signatories to any convention or treaty, <u>but has been
identified as the emission reduction level necessary to stabilize the earth's
climate by the IPCC and the Advisory Group on Greenhouse Gasses (formed by the
World Meteorological Organization, the International Council of Scientific
Unions, and the United Nations Environment Program.)</u><i>Ex. 111, SB-2.</i>
</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finally, the Environmental Coalition recommends that the Commission replace
the ALJ's</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 101 with the following language:</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 101<u>	Although, in most cases, damage cost methodologies are
superior to cost-of-control methodologies such as the emissions target
approach, the latter may be useful as an independent check when it is difficult
to measure actual damages.  This is certainly true when assessing damage
associated with greenhouse gas emissions.    Dr. Bernow's recommendation,
setting the environmental cost associated with carbon dioxide emissions at $25
per ton is, therefore, useful as an independent check on damage cost estimates
proposed by other witnesses.   In this case, $25 per ton is very close to the
upper bound of the damage cost estimate proposed by MPCA witness Peter
Ciborowski.</u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition generally endorses the environmental cost value
for greenhouse gas emissions developed by MPCA witness Peter Ciborowski and,
therefore, generally agrees with the ALJ's findings recommending Commission
adoption of at least some of the MPCA values for carbon dioxide.  However, the
Environmental Coalition believes, contrary to Finding No. 106, that the record
<u>does</u> support use of a "higher damage function"  (two percent of global
GDP) to establish the upper end of the range of environmental cost values for
carbon dioxide.  Despite this disagreement, the Environmental Coalition's
remaining exceptions relating to carbon dioxide focus primarily on discount
rates.</tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition agrees with the ALJ's statement, in Finding No.
111, that "selection of a discount rate largely controls the ultimate cost
figure."   The Environmental Coalition disagrees, however, with the ALJ's
recommended discount rates of 3% to 5%.  <i>Finding No. 114.  </i> A  5%
discount rate may be appropriate when evaluating the economic efficiency of
relatively short term (compared to the long term effects of  global climate
change) investments and projects.    A much lower discount rate should be used
when impacts are long term (<i>e.g., </i>global climate change would impact
future generations) and, consequently, intergenerational equity is an
issue.</tt><p>
<tt>The 1.5% discount rate proposed by  MPCA witness Ciborowski, based on
studies by Cline, is much more appropriate for  assessing the long term,
irreversible impacts associated with global warming  than the discount rates
recommended by the ALJ.   Of course, Mr. Ciborowski is not the only witness to
recommend use of a lower discount rate when evaluating impacts which have
intergenerational implications.   The Environmental Coalition's direct
testimony recommends that "a smaller discount rate should be used, perhaps zero
or close to zero, for significant intergenerational effects. . .[such as] risk
of serious modification of the natural ecosystem that threatens its biological
diversity and overall integrity."  <i>Ex. 234, at 23.</i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>In support of  this recommendation, the Environmental Coalition
cites the following comments by Nobel Laureate, Robert Solow  regarding
selection of an appropriate discount rate:</tt><p>
<tt>[T]he idea is that each generation is allowed to favor itself over the
future, but not too much.  Each generation can, in turn, discount the welfare
of  all future generations, and each successive generation applies the same
discount rate to the welfare of its successors.  To make [resource]conservation
an interesting proposition at all, the common discount rate should not be too
large.  You may wonder why I allow discounting at all.  I wonder too:  no
generation "should" be favored over  any other.  <i>Ex. 234, at 22-
23.</i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>There is ample evidence in the record to support adoption of a range
of  environmental costs associated with carbon dioxide emissions that includes
values calculated using a discount rates as low as one percent or zero.
Findings 113 and 114 should be revised accordingly.  The Environmental
Coalition, therefore, proposes that the Commission delete the first sentence in
the ALJ's Finding No. 113 and adopt the following language:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 113<u>	The record supports use of a range of  discount rates
(1% to 3%) to convert environmental damage estimates to present value. </u>
<i>Ex. 234  (zero or near zero recommended by Environmental Coalition witness);
Ex. 70 (1 -1.5% rate used by MPCA witness Ciborowski and Cline);  Ex. 13 (3%
rate used by the New York State Environmental Cost Study in valuing
environmental externalities);  Ex. 83 (DICE model uses 6% rate then declines to
about 3% as growth slows.  Lind model recommends 4.6 % discount rates);  Tr. 12
at 74 (Nordhaus contends rates of 4% to 5% are appropriate); Tr. 11 at 196
(National Academy of Sciences  used discount rates of 3%, 6% and 10% without
recommending any single rate as being most appropriate.)</i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>The Environmental Coalition also recommends that the Commission
amend the ALJ's Finding </tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>No. 114 to reflect the lower discount rate:<i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>Finding No. 114.	The range of costs for CO2 emissions, when using
Ciborowski's lower damage function (1% of global GDP) discounted at rates of
<u>1% </u> to 3% is <u> $14.29</u> to $2.92 per ton.  Based on the available
evidence, this range represents a reasonable estimate of costs.  It is also
consistent with the policy goal of using conservative values in the face of
uncertainty.<i> </i><b></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u>Mercury</u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b></b></tt><p>
<tt><b></b>The Environmental Coalition generally agrees with the ALJ's
conclusions regarding damage to human health and the environment associated
with mercury emissions from electric generating facilities.   <i>Findings
120-125.  </i> The ALJ notes that:</tt><p>
<tt>(1)	Coal burning has become the leading source of mercury emissions to the
air in Minnesota. <i>Finding No. 124</i>;</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>(2)	Mercury is a contaminant found in even the most remote lakes of the
Upper Midwest and virtually all mercury in these lakes is believed to have
reached them by atmospheric transport,  <i>Finding No.  121; </i>and</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>(3)	Fish [consumption] advisories have been posted [by the Minnesota
Department of Health] because consumption of fish with high mercury
concentrations poses risks of nervous system damage, especially for pregnant
women and young children.  Wildlife which eat contaminated fish are also at
risk,"  <i>Id.</i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt>Although the ALJ finds that "[n]o knowledgeable witness either denied or
disputes that mercury causes damage to the environment or has consequences that
people care about," he ultimately concludes that there is insufficient evidence
to recommend a value for mercury.  <i>Findings Nos. 120 and 143; ALJ
Discussion, at 41.  </i>This tentative conclusion is less significant, however,
than his observation that "[t]wo years from now, [the] information [necessary
to establish a reliable value] will be available . . .[t]wo years from now, the
state studies</tt><a href="ecexcept_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a><tt>, as well as some
of the federal studies</tt><a href="ecexcept_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a><tt>, should
be completed."  <i>ALJ Discussion, at 42</i>.  The ALJ clearly expects the
Commission to be in a position to adopt a final environmental cost value for
mercury in the near future, but recommends that "until the Commission has
adopted a numerical value, it require utilities to explain, in their filings,
subject to the statute, how they considered mercury."  <i>Finding No.
145.</i></tt><p>
<tt>In light of the uncontroverted evidence in this case showing that mercury
poses significant risks to human health and the environment, the Environmental
Coalition recommends that the Commission revise the ALJ's Finding No. 145 as
follows:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 145.<u>	The Commission shall establish a final environmental
cost value for mercury within two years of  issuing a final order in this
docket.</u>  Until the Commission has adopted a <u>final</u> numerical value,
<u>utilities will be required, at a minimum, to use the range recommended by
the MPCA and revised by the OAG, as an interim value:  $1,429 to $4,359 per
ton.</u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u></tt><p>
<tt>Use of this interim value is reasonable, in light of the ALJ's finding that
the environmental cost values for mercury developed by the MPCA and modified by
the OAG (a range of $1,426 to $4,359 per ton) provide a "rough estimate of the
magnitude of damages caused by mercury."   <i>Finding No. 142.  </i>Although a
rough estimate, the MPCA/OAG range is certainly less arbitrary and represents a
more systematic alternative than simply allowing "utilities to explain...how
they considered mercury," as suggested by the ALJ as an interim measure. <i>
Finding No. 145.</i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>This same rationale provides the basis for an  amendment to Finding
No. 145.  The Environmental Coalition, therefore, recommends that the
Commission revise the ALJ's Finding No. 143 by deleting the last sentence and
amending the Finding as follows:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 143	The MPCA's or OAG's recommendations of environmental cost
values for mercury based on the MPCA's methodology, <u>although adequate as a
basis for interim values, are not sufficiently  reliable as a basis for a final
value, for the for the following reasons:</u>  MPCA readily admits that the
analysis does not comport with the damage cost approach.  Instead, it is an
attempt to estimate damages from mercury by mercury's position on the air
toxics index vis-a-vis other pollutants whose damages are known, such as SO2,
N0x and PM-10.  The damages from mercury are dependent on a number of functions
that do not occur . . . with SO2, N0x, or PM-10.<b></b></tt><p>
<tt><b></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u>Methane</u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition proposes that the Commission adopt a value for
methane that is consistent with the findings for carbon dioxide discussed
<i>supra</i>.  Methane's 100 year Global Warming Potential is 22 times greater
than for CO2.  The range of environmental costs for carbon dioxide ($2.92 to
$14.29) need only be multiplied by 22 to obtain an appropriate value for
methane.  The Environmental Coalition, therefore, recommends that the
Commission strike portions of Finding No. 146 and revise it as follows:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 146.<u>	The Environmental Coalition's Stephen Bernow notes that
methane's 100 year Global Warming Potential is twenty-two times greater than
the Global Warming Potential for carbon dioxide.  </u><cite>Ex. 111, Attachment
SB-2, page 38.</cite><i>  </i>This value of 22 also includes the indirect
effects of methane and is consistent with the value adopted during the Ninth
Sessions of the INC (U.S. Climate Action Report, 1994).</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition also recommends that the Commission delete
Findings 147, 148 and 149 in their entirety and adopt the following finding
regarding the environmental cost associated with methane emissions:</tt><p>
<tt>Finding No. 147<u>	The appropriate range of environmental cost values for
methane is $64.24 to $314.38, which is derived by multiplying the range of
environmental cost values for carbon dioxide by 22, the ratio of the Global
Warming Potential for methane relative to carbon dioxide.</u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u></tt><p>
<tt><u><b></b></u></tt><p>
<tt><u><b>RECOMMENDATIONS</b></u></tt><p>
<tt><u><b></b></u></tt><p>
<tt><u><b></b></u>The Environmental Coalition proposes that the Commission
adopt the ALJ's Recommendations subject to the following changes, which are
consistent with the exceptions noted <i>supra</i>.  First, the Environmental
Coalition proposes that the Commission adopt all of  the ALJ's recommendations
for the criteria pollutants except one:  a zero value for SO2 after the turn of
the century.  The Environmental Coalition also recommends that the Commission
revise the range of values for carbon dioxide emissions, to include a lower
discount rate, and establish an environmental cost value for methane based on
the revised carbon dioxide values.    Finally, the Environmental Coalition
recommends that the Commission specify a date certain by which mercury values
will be established and adopt interim values to be used until a final value is
established.  Based on these points, the Environmental Coalition proposes the
following changes to the ALJ's Recommendations:</tt><p>
<tt>1.	That the Commission establish the following ranges of environmental
costs for criteria pollutants, to be used in proceedings subject to Minn. Stat.
[[section]] 216B.2422 (1994):</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<center>(1993 $ Per Ton)</center><p>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>Rural</TD><TD>Metropolitan<BR>Fringe</TD><TD>Urban</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Particulates Smaller than<BR>10 Microns</TD><TD>$530-$806              </TD><TD>$1873-$2720</TD><TD>$4206-$6054</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Nitrogen Oxides with Ozone</TD><TD>$17-$96                         </TD><TD>$132-$251</TD><TD>$350-$922</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Lead</TD><TD>$379-$422             </TD><TD>$1557-$1881</TD><TD>$2951-$3653</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Carbon Monoxide</TD><TD>$0.20-$0.39                     </TD><TD>$0.72-$1.26</TD><TD>$1.00-$2.14</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Sulfur Dioxide</TD><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Before year 2000</TD><TD>  $9-$24  </TD><TD>$43-$104</TD><TD>$106-$178</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>

<tt>2.	That the Commission  establish a range of  <u>$2.92 to $14.29</u>  per
ton as the environmental cost of carbon dioxide.</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt><u>3.	That the Commission establish a range of  $64.24 to $314.38 per ton
as the environmental cost of methane.</u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u></tt><p>
<tt><u>4.	That the Commission establish a final environmental cost value for
mercury within two years of  issuing a final order in this docket.</u>  Until
the Commission has adopted a <u>final</u>  numerical value, <u>utilities will
be required, at a minimum, to use the following range as an interim value:
$1,429 to $4,359 per ton.</u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u></tt><p>
<tt><u></u>5.	That the Commission specify what escalator should be used to
escalate the above figures from 1993 dollars to current dollars at the time of
filings under the statute.</tt><p>
<tt></tt><p>
<tt><b>Dated:  April 15, 1996</b></tt><p>
