<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>REPLY BRIEF OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION ON EXCEPTIONS</title></head><body><tt><b>STATE OF
MINNESOTA</b></tt><p>

<tt><b>BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</b></tt><p>


<tt>Joel Jacobs	Chair</tt><p>
<tt>Dee Knaak	Commissioner</tt><p>
<tt>Thomas Burton	Commissioner</tt><p>
<tt>R. Marshall Johnson	Commissioner</tt><p>
<tt>Don Storm	Commissioner</tt><p>




<tt>MPUC Docket No. E-999/CI-93-583</tt><p>
<tt>OAH File No. 6-2500-8632-2</tt><p>


<tt>---------------------------------------------------</tt><p>

<tt>In the Matter of Quantification of Environmental Costs</tt><p>
<tt>Pursuant to Laws of Minnesota 1993, Chapter 356, Section 3</tt><p>

<tt><b>------------------------------------------------------</b></tt><p>


<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>REPLY BRIEF OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL COALITION ON EXCEPTIONS</H3>

<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b>The Environmental Coalition files this Reply Brief in
response to the Briefs on Exceptions submitted by the Western Fuels Association
(WFA), the Lignite Energy Council (LEC), the Center for Energy and the Economic
Development (CEED), the State of North Dakota, Otter Tail Power Company (Otter
Tail), Northern States Power Company (NSP), Minnesota Power Company (Minnesota
Power), Dairyland Power Cooperative (Dairyland) and the Natural Gas Utilities.
As set forth more fully below, nothing in these briefs should alter any of the
recommendations in the Environmental Coalition's initial Brief on Exceptions
regarding Commission adoption of environmental cost values for carbon dioxide,
methane, mercury and the criteria pollutants. </tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u>Carbon Dioxide</u></b></tt><p>
<tt>WFA, LEC, CEED, North Dakota, Otter Tail, NSP, Minnesota Power, Dairyland
and the Natural Gas Utilities argue unconvincingly that the Commission should
reject many of the ALJ's most significant conclusions relating to the
environmental costs associated with carbon emissions from electric power
plants.   Despite overwhelming evidence of the potentially catastrophic risks
posed by increasing atmospheric loading of carbon from anthropogenic sources,
these parties oppose adoption of an environmental cost value for carbon
dioxide.   This position flies in the face of the great weight of evidence in
the record and is contrary to the Commission's clear statutory mandate to value
environmental damage associated with electric power generation.  <i>Minn. Stat.
[[section]] 216B.2422.</i>  The Commission should adopt, without amendment, the
ALJ's Findings Nos. 80-94 relating to carbon dioxide-related damage.</tt><p>

<tt>The ALJ's findings regarding the environmental costs associated with carbon
dioxide emissions are based on conclusions developed by the Intergovernmental
Panel on Climate Change (IPCC).   The ALJ found that:</tt><p>
<tt>IPCC reports are the most authoritative sources available for information
on climate change issues.  The IPCC research and peer review process evaluates
all available scientific information on factors affecting climate change.
Before publication, IPCC research reports are developed by technical committees
composed of experts throughout the international scientific community and are
subjected to a rigorous multi-level peer review process.  <i>ALJ Finding No.
87.</i> </tt><p>

<tt>By asking the Commission to reject the ALJ's well-founded conclusions
regarding climate change issues, WFA <i>et al. </i>effectively ask the
Commission  to reject the collective judgment of the international scientific
community.  These parties ask that the Commission, instead, accept a minority
viewpoint advocated by several "expert witnesses" who regularly serve as paid
spokesmen for the coal industry.   These witnesses variously contest the IPCC's
conclusions by emphasizing uncertainties regarding:  (1) the extent to which
anthropogenic emissions  cause increased atmospheric concentrations of  carbon
dioxide;  (2) the range of climate sensitivity associated with increased
concentrations of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere; and (3) the environmental
impacts likely to occur as a consequence of climate change within the predicted
range.    The record in this case, which includes the IPCC 1990 Report (<i>Ex.
72</i>) and the 1992 IPCC Supplement (<i>Ex. 70</i>), clearly supports the
ALJ's conclusion that "climate change in the predicted range could involve a
number of potentially catastrophic impacts, including a rise in sea level,
heightened climatic variability, and changes in vegetation."  <i>ALJ Finding
No. 33. </i></tt><p>
<tt>The ALJ's findings are also consistent with the most recent IPCC
reports</tt><a href="ecexreply_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a><tt> which state, in
relevant part:</tt><p>
<tt>During the past few decades, two important factors regarding the
relationship between humans and the Earth's climate have become apparent.
First, human activities, including the burning of fossil fuels. . . are
increasing the atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases (which tend to
warm the atmosphere) and, in some regions, aerosols (microscopic airborne
particles, which tend to cool the atmosphere).  These changes in greenhouse
gases and aerosols, taken together are projected to change regional and global
climate and climate-related parameters such as temperature, precipitation, soil
moisture and sea level.  Second, some human communities have become more
vulnerable to hazards such as storms, floods and droughts as a result of
increasing population density in sensitive areas such as river basins and
coastal plains.  <u>Potentially serious changes have been identified, including
an increase in some regions in the incidence of extreme </u></tt><p>
<tt><u>high-temperature events, floods and droughts, with resultant
consequences for fires, pest outbreaks, and ecosystem composition, structure
and functioning, including primary productivity</u>.  <i>IPCC Second Assessment
Report Synthesis, [[section]] 1.2, emphasis added.</i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt>The Environmental Coalition requests that the Commission take official
notice of the IPCC Second Assessment Report Synthesis, pursuant to Minn. Stat.
[[section]] 14.60, subd. 4, as an acknowledgement that the ALJ's findings are
consistent with the IPCC's most recent conclusions regarding the increasingly
certain link between anthropogenic carbon emissions and potentially
catastrophic climate change.  A copy of the Synthesis is attached in Appendix
One.</tt><p>
<tt>Ignoring the considerable risks associated with a build-up of greenhouse
gases, as WFA <i>et al.</i> suggest, will not diminish the probability or
magnitude of significant damage.  Indeed, the IPCC's Second Assessment serves
to reinforce the Environmental Coalition's view that the Commission should use
a "higher damage function" (two percent of  global GDP) to establish an
environmental cost value for carbon dioxide emissions.  <i>See, Environmental
Coalition Brief on Exceptions, at 7.  </i>If, instead, the Commission decides
to use the "lower damage function" that was selected by the ALJ, it is all the
more important that the Commission use a  discount rate that does not "zero
out" the costs imposed on future generations due to climate change-related
damage from carbon dioxide emissions.  The Environmental Coalition, therefore,
recommends that the Commission use discount rates of no higher than 1-3 percent
to establish a range of $2.92 to  $14.29 per ton as the environmental cost of
carbon dioxide.</tt><a href="ecexreply_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a><tt>  <i>See,
Environmental Coalition Brief on Exceptions, at 12-13.</i><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u>Mercury</u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b>The Environmental Coalition endorses the MPCA's proposed
Finding No. 145a, which would require Commission staff  to:</tt><p>
<tt>...form an advisory group drawn from all interested parties to the
contested case with responsibility  of reporting to the Commission on progress
in federal and state mercury studies and assisting the Commission in deciding
when to reconvene mercury values consideration.  <i>MPCA Brief on Exceptions,
at 12.</i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>A mercury advisory group of this sort is a logical solution to the
"timing issues peculiar to this proceeding" that the ALJ cites as a basis for
delaying adoption of a final environmental cost value for mercury.  <i>ALJ
Findings, at 42.   </i>Timely and systematic assessment of the significant
mercury-related research studies now nearing completion is needed to enable the
Commission to carry out its statutory mandate to establish final environmental
cost values, pursuant to Minn. Stat. [[section]] 216B.2422. <i>  </i>An
advisory group could ably perform this important function.<i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>Significantly, <u>no</u> exceptions were filed to the ALJ's Finding
No. 120, which notes that "no knowledgeable witness either denied or disputed
that mercury causes damage to the environment or has consequences that people
care about."   Nonetheless, some parties inexplicably continue to claim that
there is no need to account for the mercury-related impacts associated with
electric power generation.  <i>NSP Brief on Exceptions, at 16; CEED Brief on
Exceptions, at 24-30.  </i>By  asking the Commission to ignore undisputed
evidence of mercury damage, these parties are asking the Commission to ignore
its unambiguous statutory mandate.   The provisions of Minn. Stat. [[section]]
216B.2422 quite clearly require the Commission to reject these parties'
exceptions to the ALJ's findings relating to mercury (<i>specifically, Findings
Nos. 136, 139, 140, 142, 144 and 145.) </i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i></tt><p>
<tt><i></i>For all of the reasons discussed in the initial Briefs on Exceptions
filed by the OAG, MPCA and Environmental Coalition, the Commission should
accept, subject to the recommendations below, the ALJ's findings on mercury --
as the <u>first</u> <u>step</u> to establishing a final environmental cost
value for mercury.   The Commission should also adopt the MPCA's advisory group
proposal, discussed <i>supra</i>, and the two-year deadline for adopting a
final mercury value proposed by the Environmental Coalition.  <i>Environmental
Coalition Brief on Exceptions, at 10- 11.  </i>Until a final value is
established, the Commission should use the interim value ($1,429 to $4,359 per
ton of mercury) originally developed by the OAG (<i>Brief, at 7) </i>and
subsequently supported by the MPCA (<i>Brief, at 10) </i>and Environmental
Coalition (<i>Brief, at 11)</i>. <b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u>Criteria Pollutants</u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b>The parties which filed exceptions relating to the ALJ's
findings on criteria pollutants advocate a zero value (<i>e.g., </i>Otter Tail)
or a range bounded at the lower end by zero (<i>e.g., </i>NSP) for all criteria
pollutants. <b>  </b>Their positions are not supported by the record.</tt><a
href="ecexreply_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a><tt>  Perhaps that is the reason that NSP
uses evidence relating to economic issues, <u>that the ALJ and Commission have
expressly excluded from the record</u></tt><a
href="ecexreply_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a><tt>, in a failed attempt to make its case
with respect to criteria pollutants.  The Commission should unequivocally
reject these parties' exceptions to the ALJ's findings on criteria pollutants
and, in doing so, denounce NSP's open defiance of the evidentiary rulings in
this docket.<b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u>Conclusion</u></b></tt><p>
<tt><b><u></u></b>Nothing in the Briefs on Exceptions filed by other parties
significantly  alters any of the Recommendations set forth in the Environmental
Coalition's initial Brief on Exceptions, which proposes that the Commission
adopt the ALJ's Recommendations subject to the following changes.  First, the
Environmental Coalition proposes that the Commission adopt all of  the ALJ's
recommendations for the criteria pollutants except one:  a zero value for SO2
after the turn of the century.  The Environmental Coalition also recommends
that the Commission revise the range of values for carbon dioxide emissions to
include a lower discount rate, and establish an environmental cost value for
methane based on the revised carbon dioxide values.  Finally, the Environmental
Coalition recommends that the Commission specify a date certain by which
mercury values will be established and adopt interim values to be used until a
final value is established.  Based on these points, the Environmental Coalition
proposes the following changes to the ALJ's Recommendations:</tt><p>

<tt>1.	That the Commission establish the following ranges of environmental
costs for criteria pollutants, to be used in proceedings subject to Minn. Stat.
[[section]] 216B.2422 (1994):</tt><p>

<center>(1993 $ Per Ton)</center><p>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>Rural</TD><TD>Metropolitan<BR>Fringe</TD><TD>Urban</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Particulates Smaller than<BR>10 Microns</TD><TD>$530-$806              </TD><TD>$1873-$2720</TD><TD>$4206-$6054</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Nitrogen Oxides with Ozone</TD><TD>$17-$96                         </TD><TD>$132-$251</TD><TD>$350-$922</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Lead</TD><TD>$379-$422             </TD><TD>$1557-$1881</TD><TD>$2951-$3653</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Carbon Monoxide</TD><TD>$0.20-$0.39                     </TD><TD>$0.72-$1.26</TD><TD>$1.00-$2.14</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Sulfur Dioxide</TD><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Before year 2000</TD><TD>  $9-$24  </TD><TD>$43-$104</TD><TD>$106-$178</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>


<tt>2.  That the Commission  establish a range of  $2.92 to $14.29  per ton as
the environmental cost of carbon dioxide.</tt><p>
<tt>3. That the Commission establish a range of  $64.24 to $314.38 per ton as
the environmental cost of methane.</tt><p>

<tt>4.  That the Commission establish a final environmental cost value for
mercury within two years of  issuing a final order in this docket.  Until the
Commission has adopted a final  numerical value, utilities will be required, at
a minimum, to use the following range as an interim value:  $1,429 to $4,359
per ton.</tt><p>

<tt>5.  That the Commission specify what escalator should be used to escalate
the above figures from 1993 dollars to current dollars at the time of filings
under the statute.</tt><p>

<tt><b>Dated:  April 25, 1996</b></tt><p>


<tt><b>Respectfully submitted,</b></tt><p>


<tt><b>_____________________</b></tt><p>
<tt><b>Susan Hedman</b></tt><p>
