<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>ME3 Press Release-September 13: Costs of Global Climate Change to Be Considered in Minnesota:  New Report Focuses on Minnesota Impacts</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> <!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=10>
<TR><TD><B>For Immediate Release<BR>		September 13, 1996</B></TD><TD><B>Contacts:</B><BR> <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:me3noble@me3.org">Michael Noble</A>, Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy, 612/225-1133  or pager 612/649-7262<BR> <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:dmorris@ilsr.org">David Morris</A>, Institute for Local Self-Reliance 612/ 379-3815 </TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#0000FF"><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Costs of Global Climate Change to Be Considered in Minnesota:  New Report Focuses on Minnesota Impacts</H2></FONT><P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR SIZE=5>



<B>St. Paul, Minnesota </B>- Now that Hurricane Hortense has come ashore on the heels of Hurricane Fran&#146;s billions of dollars of damages, insurance companies and eastern coastal states continue to look closely at scientific inquiry from the United Nation&#146;s Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) as to whether global warming may be a root cause of more frequent and severe storms. These costs seem removed from most Minnesotans, although they are of course reflected in the costs we pay for property and casualty insurance.<P>

	Will there be more direct costs to Minnesota from global climate change and other environmental effects of electricity? Beginning Monday September 16 the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (PUC) will spend its whole week finalizing a multi-year process to put a price tag on the actual pocketbook costs of environmental damages from electric power including global climate change, mercury poisoning, and traditional smokestack pollution. <BR>
	<BR>
	A report released today by Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy (<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="me3mercury1.html">Global Climate Change and Mercury Pollution:  Issues in Minnesota&#146;s Environmental Externalities Decision</A>) highlights the most relevant concerns to Minnesotans raised by the most current report of theworld&#146;s assembled climate experts,  the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change or IPCC.<BR>
&#147Resources which are the backbone of Minnesota&#146;s ecology and regional economies are at risk from global climate change.&#148; This is the consensus view of the most rigorous peer-reviewed scientific investigations into climate ever conducted, according to ME3 Executive Director and co-author of the report, Michael Noble.<P>

 	Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy (ME3) is joined by the Izaak Walton League of America, the American Wind Energy Association, the Clean Water Action Alliance,  the Institute for Local Self Reliance, the Minnesota Center for Environmental Advocacy calling upon citizens to attend the proceedings next week, and calling upon the media to air the issues on television, radio and in the print media. &#147Minnesotans must realize that these are environmental issues which are central to who we are as Minnesotans, &#147 according to Diane Jensen of Clean Water Action.<P>

	The report asks Minnesotans to imagine, for a minute that  northern boreal forests and related wildlife habitat will suffer serious decimation from drought or ravaging forest fires. According to Pollution Control Agency  briefing papers on climate change, &#147virtually all of the ecological modeling shows that these systems will be lost with sustained warming.&#148; EPA research cited in the report suggest that temperature increases could reduce population of cool-water fish like trout and walleye by 50-100% in as many as 26 states.  Within a year of an enormous Minnesota policy debate on the protection of wetlands, the report suggests that all sides might consider the finding of the IPCC  that &#147the geographical distribution of wetlands is likely to shift with changes in temperature.&#148; According to rural economic development expert David Morris of the Institute for Local Self-Reliance, &#147Weather is often the nemesis Minnesota&#146;s farmers. Imagine that drought, pests, floods repeatedly reduce yields of the agriculture sector in coming years, as it did in 1988 when crops yield fell by 30% nationwide, costing $40 billion.&#148;  In terms of human lives, the report notes that Minnesotans need not  expect the inundation and dislocation that will befall island nations and up to 70 million residents of the delta of Bangla Desh, but the upper Midwest is most vulnerable to the kind of heat wave which killed over 700 residents of Chicago in 1995.<P>

	 These potential losses which are raised in <A HREF="http://www.unep.ch/ipcc/ipcc-0.html">IPCC&#146;s most current scientific consensus  report on climate change</A>. However the document may not be recognized by the PUC in their deliberations, because it issued shortly after the end of formal evidentiary hearing in 1995.  But according to Minnesota administrative law, the Commission may take administrative notice of the document if it is essential for a fair determination in the case. The coal industry, represented by the Western Fuels Association,  the Lignite Energy Council and the Center for Energy and Economic Development  strenuously objected to the recommendation of environmental advocates that the Commission consider the facts in the report of the IPCC. According to Bill Grant of the Isaak Walton League of America, &#147Listening to big coal crying &#147foul&#148; is laughable. The coal lawyers have vigorously sought to suppress a report which has been peer reviewed by nearly every credible climate scientist in the world, citing absurd claims that they would not have an opportunity to cross-examine the IPCC experts .&#148;<P>

	The new report from ME3 clearly shows that scientific opinion is not significantly conflicted on the basics of global climate change; rather, the body of world climate scientists agrees that warming is already &#147discernible&#148;. The report shows that the public remains confused because the coal industry and their sprinkling of allies in the science community are working hard to make sure that they stay confused.  According to co-author Michael Noble, &#147Next week&#146;s  debate in Minnesota about global climate change may be regarded as a modern-day Scopes&#146; Monkey Trial, pitting the breadth of scientific judgment against passionate defenders of an anti-scientific view.&#148; <P>

<BR>
	Because the IPCC report may or may not be formally accepted as evidence by the Public utilities Commission, ME3 feels that it is important that the public hear directly about the findings of the IPCC. For that reason, we are making copies available to the media, and we are issuing a report today that highlights where the IPCC report differs from the summary of evidence and recommendations that have been forwarded to the Commission from the Administrative Law Judge Allan W. Klein who presided over the evidentiary proceedingespecially on the critical question of how to apply economic discount rates to future global warming damages to estimate costs in present value.<P>

	In its report, ME3 praises  the law judge for what it considers exhaustive and thorough analysis of thousands of pages of evidence offered by more than thirty parties; ME3 praises the Judge&#146;s findings and recommendations  regarding the costs of smog, acid rain, small particulates and all of the other smokestack emissions traditionally regulated by the Clean Air Act and Minnesota&#146;s Pollution Control Agency. <P>

	In addition, the release report  praises the judge&#146;s report for its complete dismissal of the views of the professional global warming skeptics who testified in Minnesota as expert witnesses for the coal industry.  Rather, the judge agreed with  the experts sponsored by the Pollution Control Agency that the real costs to Minnesotans from global warming are very large indeed. Broadly speaking, the judges recommendation acknowledges that the damages caused by global warming, from a doubling of carbon dioxide levels by 2030 will be staggering losses - a minimum one percent of the world&#146;s economic output.<P>

	In its report, ME3 highlighted  the views of the IPCC, as well as Nobel Laureate economists on the subject of social discount rates, which will probably be the most hotly-contested issue before the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission next week. According to the report, the heart of the multi-year proceeding comes down to discount rates, and whether the commission will consider the costs of global climate change to be the responsibility of this current society, or whether it will pass them on to future generations. <P>

	In its new report, ME3  explains  the importance of  a  choosing a common sense  discount rate for damages from global climate change. Lastly, the report raises concerns about the failure of the proceeding to arrive at an estimate of the cost of mercury, and calls upon the commission to adopt a reasonable interim value until a final value is adopted when scientific research currently in progress is completed.<BR>
<HR>
