<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>Initial Brief of the MN Pollution Control Agency</title></head><body>

<CENTER>BEFORE THE MINNESOTA OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE
HEARINGS<BR>
	100 Washington Square, Suite 1700<BR>
	Minneapolis, Minnesota 55401-2138<BR>
<p>
	FOR THE MINNESOTA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<BR>
	121 Seventh Place East, Suite 350<BR>
	St. Paul, Minnesota 55105-2147<BR>
<p>
	MPUC Docket No. E-999/CI-93-583<BR>
	OAH Docket No. 6-2500-8632-2<p>
<p>
	In the Matter of the<BR>
	Quantification of Environmental Costs<BR>
	Pursuant to Laws of Minnesota 1993,<BR>
	Chapter 356, Section 3<BR></CENTER>

<p>
<B>INITIAL BRIEF OF THE MINNESOTA POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY<BR>
ON SUBSTANTIVE ISSUES</B>
<P>

<b>I.	THE COMMISSION
SHOULD ESTABLISH VALUES THAT REPRESENT ITS BEST ESTIMATE OF ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS
BASED ON THE EVIDENCE BEFORE IT.</b><p>
<b>	</b>This proceeding is unusual in several respects.  It is driven not by a
request for action by one of the parties, but by a specific statutory mandate
to the Commission to adopt environmental cost values. That mandate requires the
ALJ and the Commission to make decisions in an area inherently fraught with
uncertainty.  The law also requires the Commission to make factual
determinations and policy choices in an area outside its traditional area of
expertise.  Finally, the values adopted in this proceeding will have no
automatic <i>regulatory</i> consequence,  but rather will be considered in
future <i>planning</i> proceedings and balanced against other issues to
determine the public interest.  This section of the brief is devoted to issues
that arise from the unusual nature of this proceeding. <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A. 	The Statute Mandates The Adoption Of Cost Values To The Extent They Can
Be Practicably Quantified, Overriding The Proof Requirements Of Minnesota Rule
1400.7300, Subpart 5.</b><p>
<b>	</b> The statute underlying this proceeding mandates the adoption of
values:  "[t]he Commission <i>shall</i>, to the extent practicable, quantify
and establish a range of environmental costs associated with each method of
electricity generation."  Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 3
(1994) (emphasis supplied).  This mandate -- qualified only by the
much-contested issue of practicability which is discussed below -- renders
inapplicable the proof requirements that would otherwise apply under the OAH
rule at Minn. R. 1400.7300, subp. 5.   The OAH rule states that the "party
proposing that certain action be taken must prove the facts at issue by a
preponderance of the evidence, unless the substantive law provides a different
burden or standard."  <u>Id.</u>   In this case, section 216B.2422, subd. 3 is
the substantive law, and by mandating the adoption of values to the extent
practicable, it has fundamentally changed the issue before the ALJ and the
Commission.  Thus, the customary burden of proof for contested cases has no
application. <p>
	Unlike the typical contested case to which Minn. R. 1400.7300, subp. 5 would
ordinarily apply, the Commission is subject to an <i>explicit statutory
requirement </i>to take the action that is the subject of the proceeding:
namely, to establish cost values.  Typically, an administrative agency has the
authority to take a particular action, but is not required to do so.  In such a
situation, it is logical to subject the proponent of action to the burden of
proof, and if that burden is not met, the agency could lawfully refuse to act.
In this case, the Commission does not have the legal option of refusing to act,
except where the quantification is simply impracticable.  The Commission's
decision to use a contested case hearing as the procedural vehicle to develop a
record on which to base the values does not change the fact that the underlying
substantive law requires the establishment of values.  The contention by some
parties that Minn. R. 1400.7300, subp.&nbsp;5 imposes on the proponents of
values the burden of proving not just practicability but something more,
ignores the requirements of the underlying statute.  The OAH rule itself
acknowledges the possibility of being overridden by conflicting substantive
law.  Even without such acknowledgement in the rule itself, the statute's
placement of a burden to act on the Commission would preempt the rule's
inconsistent placement of a burden of proof on the proponents of action.  Put
otherwise, the "proponent" of action is not just the parties proposing values,
but rather the law itself; and indeed, it does not just propose action, it
requires it.   <p>
	  Given that this proceeding is being held to help the Commission comply with
its statutory obligation, it is more appropriate to discuss the evidentiary
burden that falls on the Commission than to discuss the evidentiary burden that
falls on the parties.  In other words, how much evidence must the record
contain before the Commission is justified, and in fact required, to quantify a
value?  In the words of section 216B.2422, subd. 3, the Commission's
quantification must be "practicable."  The question remains whether the
Commission would be required to adopt values if the record is "tied" on the
issue of practicability.  In other words, if the record neither establishes
practicability nor impracticability, would the Commission still be required to
adopt cost values?<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a>  While the statute does
not directly address this issue, we note that the Commission would in any event
be required to show that any action it takes is based on "substantial evidence"
and/or is not "arbitrary and capricious" in order to be upheld on judicial
review. Minn. Stat. [[section]] 14.69 (1994).<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a>   If a value can be established that is
based on substantial evidence and it is not arbitrary and capricious, then it
is also "practicable" to quantify it.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a>
Therefore, while the overall burden of proving facts at issue by a
preponderance of the evidence has clearly been replaced by section 216B.2422,
subd. 3, the MPCA does not object to proceeding under the assumption that the
Commission must be able to show upon this record that quantification is
practicable, since such a showing is comparable to what would be necessary to
support any agency action.  <p>
<b>B.	An Environmental Cost Can Be Practicably Quantified If The Commission Can
Make More Informed Planning Decisions With the Cost Value Than Without
It.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.	The goal of this proceeding is to provide information that will be
helpful in future planning proceedings; if values can be established that are
reliable enough to assist in the planning process, then their quantification is
practicable.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>	</b>In some respects, it could be said that it is "practicable" to quantify
any environmental cost, in that a number could always simply be assigned to it.
Presumably, though, all parties would agree that if the number is not supported
by evidence, it is meaningless and not informative to the Commission, and that
it was not the legislature's intent to require the Commission to establish
arbitrary values for consideration in its planning process.   Therefore, there
must be some minimum threshold of reliability associated with the value in
order to say it has been practicably quantified.   The location of that
reliability threshold is, of course, a disputed matter which the ALJ and the
Commission will have to determine.  In making that determination, it is
critical to keep in mind the goal of this proceeding:  namely, to provide
information to the Commission that will be useful in future planning
proceedings.  <p>
	As the Commission has already explicitly recognized in its Order Establishing
Interim Environmental Cost Values, with the adoption of section 216B.2422,
subd. 3, and the repeal of the pre-existing language, the legislature
consciously moved away from the so-called "adder" approach.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a>  Under the "adder" approach, the cost values
would have been given lives of their own, applied in an automatic and formulaic
fashion beyond the discretion of the Commission.  In contrast, as the Office of
the Attorney General discussed in detail in earlier briefing<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn4">[5]</a>, the values established in this proceeding
are not intended to be automatically applied.  Rather, they will be used by the
Commission as part of its <i>planning</i> process, becoming one of the factors
among others that the Commission must balance in determining the resource
decisions that are most in the public interest.  <p>
 	Therefore, in deciding whether a value is reliable enough to conclude it has
been practicably quantified, the ALJ and the Commission must ask, "reliable
enough for what?"  Given that these numbers are to be adopted to provide for a
more informed planning process in the future, the answer must be "reliable
enough to assist the Commission in its future planning process."  In other
words, is the resource planning process enhanced, made more informed, made more
complete by the value?  Can the Commission make better decisions considering
the environmental cost value, along with all the other considerations
necessarily before it, than it could in the absence of the information
represented by the value?  Does the value assist the Commission in predicting
which resource approach will be most in the long-term public interest? <p>
	While the record would support the quantification of the values proposed by
the MPCA even with a more rigorous definition of  "practicable," the
legislature's goal of expanding the  information available to the Commission in
making resource plans strongly supports the use of a somewhat more relaxed
standard of practicability.  Most government agencies, and most individuals,
would want to have at their disposal as much information as they could about
the possible consequences of their decisions at the time they make those
decisions, even if there is some uncertainty associated with those
consequences.  Having information about the consequences -- together with
information about the uncertainty of those consequences where necessary --
allows for more informed decisionmaking, and therefore better decisions.  This
is particularly important when the decisionmaking in question is of such
importance and has such long-term consequences.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn5">[6]</a> <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>2.	The values need not be adopted or used without explanation; the
Commission may formally or informally recognize any explanations that would
make the values of more use in future planning.</b><p>
<b>	</b>It is also important to keep in mind, when determining if a value is
reliable enough to be helpful in a planning process, that the value need not be
presented in a vacuum, without any explanation of how it was derived.  These
values are going to be considered by the same agency that is adopting them.
The Commission will be familiar with the record on which the values are based
and the disputes surrounding the values.  The parties in subsequent proceedings
will have the opportunity to remind the Commission of what the numbers include
and exclude when they are being considered in future proceedings and to bring
in more current economic and scientific information.  Moreover, to show that
its decisions are not arbitrary or capricious, and that they are based on
substantial evidence, the Commission would in any event want to explain how the
values in question were derived, the types of costs included and excluded, and
any other information that would be of use in future proceedings.  For example,
the MPCA would fully support accompanying a  value for CO2 with language
explaining that the costs are not all incurred in Minnesota in the immediate
future, but rather are spread out globally across the next century.<p>
	To the extent that a party has valid concerns that a value standing alone may
be misleading, and that therefore the Commission would actually be better off
not even having the value for  future proceedings, that concern is easily
rectified by attaching the necessary explanation to the value.  To include such
information would be fully consistent with the legislature's goal of improving
the planning process by making it a more-informed one.  In contrast, to exclude
values because they may be based on incomplete information or because further
studies are ongoing, would thwart the legislature's goal.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>C.	The Commission's Statutory Assignment To Quantify Environmental Costs
Inherently Involves Making Judgments About How To Resolve Scientific And
Economic Uncertainties; The Need To Do So Does Not Make The Task
Impracticable.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.	Agencies routinely adopt, and courts routinely uphold, environmental and
health regulations based on incomplete and conflicting scientific data,
particularly when the agencies regulate at the frontiers of science; agencies
are allowed to formulate solutions to the best of their abilities based on
available information, theoretical projections, and their own policy
judgments.</b><p>
<b>	</b>It has been suggested in this proceeding that the scientific
uncertainties surrounding the calculation of some of the cost values make the
calculation itself impracticable.  The MPCA strongly disputes this contention.
Of all the parties in this proceeding, as the state's environmental regulatory
agency, the MPCA is probably the most familiar with the difficulty of needing
to take action in the face of scientific uncertainty.  However any agency
charged with protecting the environment or public health is by necessity
routinely required to act based on scientific evidence that is incomplete or
even conflicting.  Waiting for what may be considered complete and undisputed
scientific certainty would often make it impossible for such agencies to
adequately protect public health and the environment.<p>
	Of course, the Commission is not an agency primarily charged with protecting
the environment or public health.  However, the Commission is required to make
energy resource choices consistent with  the public interest.   Minn. Stat.
[[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 2 (1994).  This necessarily requires it to
make long-term predictions in many areas where uncertainty abounds, such as
regarding economic growth, future regulations, technological advances, emerging
competition, fuel supply, fuel prices, energy reliability and other
socioeconomic factors.  Section 216B.2422, subd. 3, requires the Commission to
make judgments and predictions in the face of  environmental scientific
uncertainty as well.  Just as the agencies like the MPCA cannot properly
protect the environment and public health without accepting the reality of
scientific uncertainty and still acting on the most informed current judgment,
similarly the Commission cannot properly predict long-term public interest if
it excludes from its consideration environmental consequences about which
scientific uncertainty exists.  In neither case is uncertainty an excuse for
inaction.  The ALJ and the Commission should reject any arguments that such
uncertainties necessarily make action "impracticable."<p>
	The courts have long recognized the authority, and in some cases the
obligation, of agencies to act despite scientific uncertainties about the
health or environmental effects of a certain substance.  The leading case in
Minnesota discussing the authority of agencies to regulate despite scientific
uncertainties about the risks the regulations address is <u>Manufactured
Housing Institute v. Petterson,</u> 347 N.W. 238 (Minn. 1984).  In
<u>Manufactured Housing</u> the court reviewed a rule by the Department of
Health setting a maximum indoor air level of formaldehyde in newly constructed
housing units (formaldehyde is used in some construction materials).  While the
court struck down the Department's rule  as arbitrary and capricious given the
Commissioner of Health's utter lack of explanation for setting the level where
he did,<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn6">[7]</a> in so doing it endorsed the
following standard for agency behavior in the face of scientific uncertainty:<p>
<p>
[The Department of Health concedes] that the data is imperfect and also that
the Department may not adopt an arbitrary rule.  Nevertheless, they contend --
and we agree -- that in fulfilling their obligation to protect the public
health, it may be necessary, as here, to make judgments and draw conclusions
from "suspected, but not completely substantiated, relationships between facts,
from trends among facts, from theoretical projections from imperfect data, from
probative preliminary data not yet certifiable as `fact,' and the like."
<u>Ethyl Corp. v. EPA</u>, 541 F.2d 1, 28 (D.C. Cir.[1976]), <u>cert.
denied</u>, 426 U.S. 941, 96 S.Ct. 2662, 49 L.Ed.2d 394 (1976).  <u>See
also</u> <u>Amoco Oil Co. v. EPA</u>, 501 F.2d. 722, 739-41 (D.C.Cir. 1974).<p>
<p>
<u>Manufactured Housing</u>, 347 N.W.2d at 244.  <p>
	The D.C. Circuit cases cited by the Minnesota Supreme Court in <u>Manufactured
Housing,</u> and particularly the often-quoted <u>Ethyl</u> case, analyze
cogently and in depth the issues faced by agencies required to protect public
health and the environment despite imperfect evidence of risks.  In
<u>Ethyl</u>, the court considered <i>en banc </i>a challenge to EPA
regulations requiring annual reductions in the lead content of leaded gasoline.
The Clean Air Act had in 1970 authorized the EPA Administrator to regulate
gasoline additives whose emission products "will endanger the public health or
welfare."  42 U.S.C. [[section]]&nbsp;7545(c)(1)(A).  The Administrator had
found that emissions from lead in gasoline presented a "significant risk of
harm to public health" pursuant to that authority, and adopted rules requiring
the phased reduction of the lead content of gasoline.<p>
	Various manufacturers of lead additives and refiners of gasoline challenged
the regulations, primarily charging that the rule was without support in the
evidence and was arbitrary and capricious.  There were indeed many gaps and
weaknesses in the evidence on which the EPA relied to regulate lead additives.
Given the multiple sources of lead to which humans are exposed, it was
virtually impossible to isolate the effects on the body of airborne lead from
gasoline, and the extent to which airborne lead was absorbed into the body was
vigorously disputed. <u>Ethyl</u>, at 9.  The low levels of exposure from
automotive emissions meant that the feared effects would not materialize until
after a lifetime of exposure, and at the time the regulations were adopted, the
existing emission levels had only been present for 15 to 20 years.  <u>Id.</u>
at 25.  Lead exposure from the ambient air was so pervasive that adequate
control groups could not be found, and experiments on humans that would help
alleviate the scientific uncertainty could not be ethically conducted.
<u>Id.</u> at 25-26.  <p>
	After a division of the appellate court initially found in favor of the
petitioners, <u>Id</u>. at 11, the court reheard the case <i>en banc</i>
because of the importance of the issues involved, and vacated the earlier
judgment.  Despite the shortcomings in the data, the majority found that the
Administrator's lead rule had a rational basis in the evidence. <u>Id.</u> at
37,<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn7">[8]</a> and found for the EPA.  Its comments
respecting scientific uncertainty directly relate to the issues arising in this
case and are worth quoting at some length:<p>
<p>
Questions involving the environment are particularly prone to uncertainty.
Technological man has altered his world in ways never before experienced or
anticipated.  The health effects of such alterations are often unknown,
sometimes unknowable.  While a concerned Congress has passed legislation
providing for protection of the public health against gross environmental
modifications, the regulators entrusted with the enforcement of such laws have
not thereby been endowed with prescience that removes all doubt from their
decision-making.  Rather, speculation, conflicts in evidence, and theoretical
extrapolation typify their every action.<p>
<u>Id.</u> at 24 (footnote omitted).  Awaiting certainty, the court held, was
not required because "certainty in the complexities of environmental medicine
may be achievable only after the fact, when scientists have the opportunity for
leisurely and isolated scrutiny of an entire mechanism," and the court rejected
the contention by petitioners that agency action based on anything less than
certainty was irresponsible.  <u>Id.</u> at 25.  <p>
	In addition to the language quoted by the Minnesota Supreme Court in
<u>Manufactured Housing,</u> <u>supra</u>, the court offered the following
description of the Administrator's authority and responsibilities in the face
of scientific uncertainty:<p>
<p>
Where a statute is precautionary in nature [or, as with OSHA, mandatory in its
command to act], the evidence difficult to come by, uncertain, or conflicting
because it is on the frontiers of scientific knowledge, the regulations
designed to protect the public health, and the decision that of an expert
administrator, we will not demand rigorous step-by-step proof of cause and
effect.  Such proof may be impossible to obtain if the precautionary purpose of
the statute is to be served.  <p>
<p>
* * *<p>
All of this is not to say that Congress left the Administrator free to set
policy on his own terms. To the contrary, the policy guidelines are largely
set, both in the statutory term "will endanger" and in the relationship of that
term to other sections of the Clean Air Act.  These prescriptions direct the
Administrator's actions.  Operating within the prescribed guidelines, he must
consider all information available to him.  Some of the information will be
factual, but much of it will be more speculative -- scientific estimates and
"guesstimates" of probable harm, hypotheses based on still-developing data,
etc.  Ultimately, he must act, in part on "factual issues," but largely "on
choices of policy, on an assessment of risk, [and] on predictions dealing with
matters on the frontiers of scientific knowledge." <p>
<p>
<u>Ethyl</u>, at 28, 29 (citation omitted, text of footnote added in brackets
to first quote).    <p>
	Like the <u>Ethyl</u> case, other federal appellate decisions addressing
national issues of safety and health also recognize the need for agencies to
make decisions based on their own policy judgments when the underlying
evidence, drawn from the frontiers of scientific knowledge, is insufficient to
make a purely "factual determination."  <u>See</u> <u>Amoco Oil Co. V. EPA,</u>
501 F.2d 722 (D.C.Cir. 1974)(upholding against industry challenge EPA's rules
prohibiting the use of leaded gasoline in cars with catalytic converters);
<u>Industrial Union Department, AFL-CIO v. Hodgson</u>, 499 F.2d 467 (D.C.Cir.
1974) (upholding in part and remanding in part OSHA's asbestos dust rule
following challenge by union);  <u>Society of Plastics Indus., Inc., v.
OSHA,</u> 509 F.2d 1301 (2d Cir. 1975)(upholding against industry challenge
OSHA's vinyl chloride rule) <u>cert. denied</u>, 421 U.S. 992, 95 S.Ct. 1998;
<u>Public Citizen Health Research Group v. Tyson</u>, 796 F.2d 1479 (D.C.Cir.
1986)(upholding in part and remanding in part OSHA's ethylene oxide standard
following challenge by citizens group).  <u>See also</u> <u>Motor Vehicle Mfrs.
Ass'n v. State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Co.</u>, 463 U.S. 29, 52, 103
S.Ct. 2856, 2871 (1983) (holding as arbitrary and capricious the attempt of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to rescind its earlier rule
requiring cars to be built with passive restraints, while recognizing that
"[i]t is not infrequent that the available data do not settle a regulatory
issue, and the agency must then exercise its judgment in moving from facts and
probabilities on the record to a policy conclusion.").  <p>
	The courts recognize the need for agencies to make policy judgments along the
way, in particular, when dealing in new areas of regulation.  In <u>Industrial
Union,</u> <u>supra</u>, union members challenged rules adopted by OSHA
regulating their exposure to asbestos dust, seeking a more stringent regulation
in several respects.  The court upheld most of the agency's rule as
promulgated, but remanded on two points where the agency had failed to explain
its choice of less protective approaches than the union wanted.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn8">[9]</a>  In addition to recognizing the need for
agencies to make policy judgments when working with insufficient factual
information,  the court added:<p>
  <p>
Where existing methodology or research in a new area of regulation is
deficient, the agency necessarily enjoys broad discretion to attempt to
formulate a solution to the best of its ability on the basis of available
information.  <u>Permian Basin Area Rate Cases</u>, 390 U.S. 747, 811, 88 S.Ct.
1344, 20 L.Ed.2d 312 (1968).<p>
<p>
<u>Industrial Union</u>, 499 F.2d at 474-5, footnote 18.  <p>
	In order to quantify the environmental costs of energy generation, the
Commission must in some cases consider not yet conclusive scientific evidence
from the frontiers of science.  Agencies charged with protecting the nation's
health and environment are routinely in this position, and the courts have
recognized that they cannot fulfill their obligations without making judgments
and drawing conclusions based on such evidence.  In predicting the future, as
the Commission must do in order to make energy resource decisions most in line
with the public interest, the Commission must also be willing to make judgments
and draw conclusions based on still-developing scientific evidence.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>2.  	Quantifying environmental costs involves even more uncertainties than
traditional environmental regulation since it also depends on a developing area
of economic theory; the legislative history shows that the legislature was
aware of the methodology debate, and that it did not intend a definition of
"practicable" under which values could be quantified only if they meet a
particular set of stringent methodological criteria.</b><p>
<b>  	</b>In addition to the scientific uncertainties inherent in much of the
environmental evidence, there are significant economic uncertainties introduced
by the requirement to quantify costs, given that this is a controversial and
still-developing area of economic theory.  Some parties have suggested that
there is a single, widely-accepted, "correct" way to proceed to quantify costs,
and that other methodologies are theoretically unsound.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn9">[10]</a>  However, the record shows that there is
considerable debate among economists over quantification methodology.  The
Congressional Office of Technology Assessment (OTA) recently examined the
results, methods, and assumptions of several studies of the environmental costs
of electricity to determine "whether there are generally accepted approaches to
estimating environmental costs."  <u>Studies of the Environmental Costs of
Electricity</u>; Background Paper, Office of Technology Assessment, 1994
(hereafter "OTA Report") at 2, attached to McCarron Surrebuttal, Exh. 164.  As
a result of this review:<p>
<p>
OTA concludes that <i>no clear consensus exists on quantitative estimates of
environmental costs of electricity, or on methodologies for making those
estimates.</i>  The methods of these studies, and the estimates themselves,
vary widely.  The differing methods and results have produced a contentious
technical debate among analysts and policymakers who wish to use the results of
environmental cost studies.  Many of these differences can be addressed through
further research and analysis.  Some critical disagreements over methodology,
however, mask deeper disputes over values, basic policy goals, and the intended
role of environmental cost studies.  <p>
<u>Id</u>.  The report goes on to emphasize the importance for policymakers of
understanding the assumptions underlying each method in order to make the best
use of the information.  <u>Id</u>. at 3. <p>
	In assessing the legislative intent behind Minn. Stat.
[[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 3, and particularly the intended meaning of
"practicable," the ALJ and the Commission should keep in mind the wide variety
of methodologies that have been used by economists to quantify environmental
effects and the resulting debates among them.  The legislature in enacting
section 216B.2422, subd. 3 was aware of the ongoing debate in Minnesota over
how to quantify costs; indeed, the Senate sponsor referred in committee to the
debate and the resulting delays in quantifying costs as one of the reasons for
amending the law.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn10">[11]</a>  She reiterated this
point on the Senate floor and stated that the adoption of section 216B.2422,
subd. 3 "would make it <i>easier </i>for the Commission to quantify and
establish a range of environmental costs associated with each method of
generation."<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn11">[12]</a>     <p>
	Moreover, Senator Johnson notes that while Minnesota has been unable to act
because of debates over how to quantify, Massachusetts and Nevada have "led the
way" and Wisconsin and Iowa have followed suit.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn12">[13]</a>   While the record does not include a
great deal of data about the methodological approaches used by these other
states, it does show that Massachusetts, Nevada, and Wisconsin all established
CO2 values based on control costs.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn13">[14]</a>
<u>Valuation of Environmental and Human Health Risks Associated With Electric
Power Generation:  A Discussion of Methods and a Review of Greenhouse Gas
Studies</u> (hereafter, "Tellus Report"), Table 1, attached to Bernow Direct,
Exh. 111.  The control cost valuation methodology is one that economists who
have testified in this proceeding consider to be not well grounded in economic
principles, particularly in comparison to the damage-cost approach.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn14">[15]</a>  Nonetheless, it is apparently one
considered to be "practicable" by the Senate sponsor of the law.  <p>
 	In determining whether to quantify a value based on the record in this
proceeding, the ALJ and Commission should ask whether the quantification is
"practicable" as the legislature intended that term to be used.  This history
shows that the legislature did not intend a narrow definition of practicable,
under which a value should not be adopted unless it could meet a particular and
stringent valuation theory.  Nor could it have assumed that quantification
would proceed only in accordance with one or more methodologies endorsed by a
clear consensus among analysts, because there is no such consensus.  Rather,
the legislative history reveals a preference for a broader definition of
practicable, a receptiveness even to those methodological approaches rejected
by economists testifying in this hearing, and a desire to make it "easier" for
the Commission to quantify environmental values for future planning purposes.
<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>II.	BECAUSE CO2 EMISSIONS IMPOSE A SUBSTANTIAL COST ON THE ENVIRONMENT DUE
TO GLOBAL WARMING, AND BECAUSE IT IS PRACTICABLE TO QUANTIFY THAT COST, THE LAW
REQUIRES THE COMMISSION TO ADOPT A RANGE OF CO2 COST VALUES REFLECTING THAT
SUBSTANTIAL COST.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	CO2 Emissions Will Have A Substantial Environmental Cost.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.  	Global warming, due primarily to CO2  emissions, is likely to cause
dramatic climate changes and substantial harm to the environment, according to
the most authoritative scientific panels.</b><p>
<b>	</b>The record firmly establishes that CO2 emissions have a substantial
environmental cost.  The Commission cannot reasonably ignore costs of this
magnitude, which can be practicably quantified, and still comply with the
legislature's purpose of having the Commission consider environmental costs
when making resource planning decisions. <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>a.	CO2 contributes to the "greenhouse effect" by helping warm the Earth, and
the concentration of CO2 in the atmosphere is increasing dramatically.  </b><p>
	The basic theory underlying global warming is simple.  Greenhouse gases, of
which CO2 is the most important after water vapor, trap within the earth's
atmosphere heat which would otherwise radiate into space.  <u>Climate Change,
The IPCC Scientific Assessment (1990)</u>, attached to Ciborowski Surrebuttal,
Exh. 62 (hereafter IPCC 1990 Report) at 25-26.  This heat-trapping action, as
part of what is known as the natural greenhouse effect, keeps the earth's
surface about 33deg. C. warmer than it would be if the natural greenhouse
effect gases were not present. <u>Id.</u><p>
<u></u>	Concerns over global warming, or the enhanced greenhouse effect
attributable to human activities, arise because the amount of carbon dioxide in
the Earth's atmosphere has already risen from its preindustrial level of about
275 to 280 parts per million (ppm) to over 350 ppm, with majority of this
increase occuring just since 1950. IPCC 1990 Report at xvi, Figure 3.  The
concentrations of CO2 now in the atmosphere are already higher than they have
been in at least the last 160,000 years, as shown by ice core samples from
which historic concentrations of CO2 can be measured.  IPCC 1990 Report at xv.
Projections made in 1990 of increases in CO2 emissions, combined with increases
of other greenhouse gases, show that if current trends are sustained (the
so-called "business-as-usual" emissions forecast), human activities will cause
a doubling of the "equivalent CO2 concentration"<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn15">[16]</a> from preindustrial levels before the year
2030, with a quadrupling in the equivalent CO2 concentration before the end of
the next century. IPCC 1990 Report at xx, Figure 6.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn16">[17]</a>  <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>b.	Many scientific review panels around the world have studied the evidence,
and they predict significant amounts of global warming; the most authoritative
voice of the international scientific community is the Intergovernmental Panel
on Climate Change (IPCC).</b><p>
<b>	</b>Not surprisingly, concerns over global warming have attracted the
attention of hundreds of scientists throughout the world.  The MPCA was able to
identify nineteen scientific reviews of the issue just since 1979, including
reviews by the National Academy of Sciences, by the World Meteorological
Organization, by the U.S. Department of Energy, by scientific bodies in
Germany, the Netherlands, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and a joint US/USSR
Commission. Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 at 11, Table 2.  Of these, all but
three make projections of "climate sensitivity," -- (the average level of
global warming that will result from a doubling of atmospheric CO2<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn17">[18]</a>
-- resulting in substantial warming.  Most predictions fall within the range of
1.5 to 4.5deg. C.  Notably, none of these bodies predicted that there would
<i>not</i> be global warming, or that there would be no more than minimal
warming. <p>
	The most authoritative voice of the international scientific community on the
issue of global warming is that of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate
Change (IPCC).  The IPCC was established by the World Meteorological
Organization (WMO) and the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) in 1988
precisely for the purpose of assessing the scientific information relating to
climate change.  IPCC 1990 Report, preface.  Its first and most sweeping report
on the science, produced by Working Group I of the IPCC, came out in 1990 and
is included in the record in its entirety.  This report was written by 37 lead
authors and contributed to by 170 scientists from 25 different countries, with
further review by an additional 200 scientists, involving most of the active
scientists working in the field.  IPCC 1990 Report at v. The record shows that
the participating scientists are affiliated with many distinguished
universities and government laboratories from around the world.  IPCC 1990
Report, App. 3 and 4.  The lead officers of  WMO and UNEP commended the chair
of the IPCC Working Group I, Dr. John Houghton, and his Secretariat, for
having, with the 1990 Report, "succeeded beyond measure in mobilizing the
co-operation and enthusiasm of hundreds of scientists from all over the world.
They have produced a volume of remarkable depth and breadth, and a Policymakers
Summary which translates these complex scientific issues into language which is
understandable to the non-specialist."  IPCC 1990 Report, preface.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn17">[19]</a><b>  </b>In 1992, the IPCC prepared a
supplement to its 1990 report.  The 1992 supplement was prepared by 22 lead
authors, with 126 contributors and over 350 reviewers.  IPCC 1992 Report,
Appendices 2 and 3, attached to Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72.  The
introductory chapter of the 1992 supplement is also part of the record,
attached to Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70.  <p>
	As MPCA discusses more fully <u>infra,</u> the reports prepared by this
distinguished group of scientists provided the scientific foundation for the
international global warming treaty entered into by the United States and 127
other nations at the "Earth Summit" in 1992, and continue to be basis of
international negotiations over CO2 reductions.  <p>
<p>
<b>c.	Global warming due to doubled concentrations of CO2 is likely to be in
the range of 1.5 to 4.5 degrees C, with a best estimate of 2.5deg. C; at
current emission trends, this would result in climate change of an
extraordinary proportion in a century.</b><p>
<b>	</b>The IPCC predicts the following:<p>
<p>
the evidence from modelling studies, from observations and the sensitivity
analyses indicate that the sensitivity of global mean surface temperature to
doubling CO2 is <i>unlikely to lie outside the range 1.5 to 4.5deg. C</i>.<p>
IPCC 1992 Report at 5.  While the IPCC scientists were reluctant to judge where
within the range the correct value is likely to lie, based on the modeling
studies, sensitivity analyses done on the models, and observational evidence of
temperature change in the last century, the IPCC made a  "best estimate" of
climate sensitivity of 2.5deg. C.  IPCC 1990 Report at xxv and 139.  IPCC 1992
Report at 16.    <p>
	It is important to keep in mind that this estimate of climate sensitivity in
the range of 1.5 to 4.5deg. C. is tied to a doubling of CO2 concentrations, or
equivalent CO2 concentrations, above preindustrial levels.  In other words,
warming within the predicted range is what could be expected to eventually
result from the CO2 doubling.  If CO2 concentrations exceed the doubling level,
then additional warming would follow.  In its 1990 Report the IPCC's "business
as usual" scenario predicted a doubling of equivalent CO2 concentrations before
the year 2030, and a quadrupling by the end of the 21st century.  1990 IPCC
Report at xx, Figure 6.     <p>
	Using its business-as-usual scenario, and a best estimate of climate
sensitivity of 2.5deg. C., the IPCC projects warming of about 0.3deg. per
decade (with an uncertainty range of 0.2deg.C to 0.5deg.C per decade).  This
results in a likely increase in global mean temperature of about 1deg.C above
the present value (or 2deg.C above preindustrial temperatures) by 2025, and a
rise of 3deg.C above the present value (or 4deg.C above preindustrial) before
the end of the century. IPCC 1990 Report at xxii.  The high estimate of warming
by the year 2100 is over 6deg.C above the preindustrial level, and the low
estimate of warming by that year is nearly 3deg.C above the preindustrial
level.  <u>Id.</u>,<u> </u>Figure 8.  Moreover, the temperatures given above
are only the "realized" levels of warming likely to occur by the dates in
question.  Because there is a lag time between the increase in CO2 and when the
warming is actually felt, at any given time the Earth would be committed to
even greater levels of warming.  IPCC 1990 at xxii.<p>
	In other words, at current trends, the planet is heading toward a warming of 2
to 5 degrees C., with a best estimate of 3 degrees C., above current levels in
about a century.  While this may sound like an insignificant amount of warming
given the temperature fluctuations we all experience each day, it represents an
enormous change in the Earth's climate.  In its 1983 report, the National
Academy of Sciences revisited the findings of its 1979 report predicting a
climate sensitivity of 1.5 to 4.5 degrees C.  It confirmed its earlier
prediction, and concluded as follows:<p>
<p>
In summary, the conclusions of our study appear to remain valid.  Man-made
increases of CO2 and other trace gases in the atmosphere may be reasonably
expected to change climate significantly within the lifetimes of a large
fraction of the world's inhabitants who are alive today.  (According to Ausubel
and Stoto, 1981, 40% of the current population will still be alive 50 years
hence.)  <i>The change will be large and rapid; it will be greater in global
terms than any climate changes that civilized man has yet experienced.</i> <p>
<u>Id.</u> at 282, attached to Exh. 70 (emphasis supplied).  More recently the
NAS noted that:<p>
<p>
[d]espite the modest decline in average temperatures in the northern hemisphere
between about 1940 and 1975, we are still in an unusually warm period of
earth's history.  Thus the temperature increases of a few degrees projected for
the next century are not only large in recent historical terms, <i>but could
also carry the planet into largely unknown territory</i>.  <p>
Exh. 76 at 20 (emphasis supplied).  And the IPCC said this about its projected
rate of warming:<p>
<p>
The changes predicted to occur by about the <i>middle</i> <i>of the next
century</i> due to increases in greenhouse gas concentrations from the
Business-as-Usual emissions <i>will make global mean temperatures higher than
they have been in the last 150,000 years</i>.  The rate of change of global
temperatures predicted for Business-as-Usual emissions will be greater than
those which have occured naturally on Earth over the last 10,000 years.<p>
IPCC 1990 at xxviii (emphasis supplied). <p>
	To put the environmental effect such a warming could have in perspective, it
is comparable in magnitude to the difference between average global
temperatures during the ice ages and and the average global temperatures of
today.  IPCC 1990 Report at 202, Figure 7.1.  As Mr. Ciborowski stated in his
testimony:  <p>
<p>
Earth's climate has oscillated between conditions that have been either 4 to 5
degrees Celsius cooler or at about present levels of warmth for several
millions of years.  To find a time when it has been between 3 and 4 degrees
Celsius warmer, one would have to go far back into the geological past more
than 3 to 9 millions of years ago to the late Tertiary period, and to find a
period that was 5 to 6 degrees Celsius warmer, one would have to go back in
time 9 to 25 million years ago to the Miocene.<p>
Ciborowski Rebuttal at 15 (citations omitted).   <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>d.	General circulation models on which warming predictions are largely
based, are the best-developed tools available to predict climate change, and
their results are reliable enough to be the basis of policy decisions.</b><p>
<b>	</b>The primary, though not the only, tools scientists have for predicting
global climate change in response to increasing greenhouse gases are computer
models known as general circulation models (GCMs).  These models are based on
what scientists currently know about the physical laws and mechanisms that
control our climate.  IPCC 1990 Report at xxv.  According to the IPCC:<p>
<p>
To make a climate forecast, the climate model is first run for a few
(simulated) decades.  The statistics of the model's output is a description of
the model's simulated climate which, if the model is a good one, will bear a
close resemblance to the climate of the real atmosphere and ocean.  The above
exercise is then repeated with increasing concentrations of the greenhouse
gases in the model.  The differences between the statistics of the two
simulations (for example in mean temperature and interannual variability)
provide an estimate of the accompanying climate change.<p>
<u>Id.</u>  <p>
	The GCM's synthesize "our knowledge of the physical and dynamical processes in
the overall [climate] system and allow for complex interactions between various
components."  IPCC 1990 Report at xx.  The IPCC 1990 Report acknowledges that
the descriptions of many of the processes involved are comparatively crude.
<u>Id.</u>  Nonetheless, there can be little dispute that the GCMs remain the
best tools scientists have for predicting the effects of increasing greenhouse
gases.  <u>Id.</u>  The National Academy of Sciences<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn18">[20]</a> review of global warming in 1979 said the
following about the strengths and weaknesses of the models:<p>
<p>
.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;We have examined with care all known negative feedback
mechanisms, such as increase in low and middle cloud amount, and have concluded
that the oversimplification and inaccuracies in the models are not likely to
have vitiated the principal conclusion that there will be appreciable warming.
The known negative feedback mechanisms can reduce the warming, but they do not
appear to be so strong as the positive moisture feedback.  We estimate the most
probable global warming for a doubling of CO2 to be near 3 degrees C with a
probable error of +/- 1.5 degrees C.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;To summarize, we
have tried but have been unable to find any overlooked or underestimated
physical effects that could reduce the currently estimated global warming due
to a doubling of atmospheric CO2 to negligible proportions or reverse them
altogether.<p>
<u>Carbon Dioxide and Climate: A Scientific Assessment</u>, 1979, pages 2 - 3,
quoted in NAS' subsequent report, <u>Changing Climate: Report of the Carbon
Dioxide Assessment Commitee</u>, 1983, attached to Exh. 70.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn19">[21]</a>   <p>
	In the subsequent years scientists have still found no basis on which they
could dismiss the general warming predictions of the models.  On the contrary,
in 1990 the IPCC expressed "substantial confidence that models can predict at
least the broad-scale features of climate change."  IPCC Report at xxvii.  This
confidence is due in part to the fact that the models have successfully
predicted the broad features of current and past climates.  With respect to the
ability of computer models to simulate current climates,  the IPCC noted that
the models show "considerable skill in the simulation of the present day
climate by atmospheric general circulation models in the portrayal of the
large-scale distribution of the pressure, temperature, wind and precipitation
in both summer and winter."  IPCC 1990 Report at 126.  As for past climates,
the IPCC found that, "[i]n general, palaeo-climate modelling studies have found
encouraging agreement between simulations and observation on continental
scales,"  <u>Id.</u> at 125, and that "palaeo-climatic data have provided
encouraging evidence of the ability of climate models to simulate climates
different from the present."  <u>Id.</u> at 126.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn20">[22]</a>     <p>
	 The scientists who have reviewed in detail the strengths and weaknesses of
the GCMs consider them reliable enough to make predictions about what is likely
to happen to the planet in response to increasing greenhouse gases, recognizing
that those predictions will be the basis of  policy decisions.  One of the
major conclusions of the 1992 IPCC Report at 5 - consistent with the
predictions of the many review panels that preceded them - was that climate
sensitivity "is <i>unlikely to lie outside the range of 1.5 to 4.5deg. C</i>."
1992 IPCC Report at 5.  The IPCC reports are offered precisely for the purpose
of informing international policy decisions.  IPCC 1990 Report at vi and xiii.
<p>
	Moreover, as is discussed infra, 128 nations of the world including our own
have entered into a treaty setting CO2 emission reduction goals on the basis of
the IPCC's predictions, evidencing substantial confidence in the models on
which the predictions are largely based.  <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>e.	The dramatic climate change associated with levels of warming predicted
by the IPCC and the other scientific review panels  will greatly stress many of
the ecosystems of the planet, including Minnesota's forests.</b><p>
<b></b>	As we emphasize above, the warming expected by the end of the next
century if current trends continue would result in a global climate unknown in
human history.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn21">[23]</a>  This makes it difficult
to predict precisely what ecological conditions would result, and increases the
risks inherent in the projected climate change.  Nonetheless, there are ways to
predict how the climate will respond to predicted levels of warming.  One way
is to look at the climates of the distant past, or "paleoclimates,"  which has
been done by Dr. Margaret Davis and others.  Another way is through the use of
computer models that incorporate what we know about the tolerances of
ecosystems to changing conditions, such as the forest model used by Dr. John
Pastor.  Both of these scientists -- both internationally recognized experts in
the response of ecosystems to climate change whose work has been relied on by
the IPCC<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn22">[24]</a>-- testified to the dramatic
ecological changes that could be expected.<p>
	The paleoclimatic evidence establishes that widespread changes in ecosystems
have occurred in response to past changes in the climate comparable in
magnitude to those predicted for the next century.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn23">[25]</a>   Dr. Davis testified that fossil records
show that the climate changes of only 2 to 3 degrees C associated with the
so-called Younger-Dryas cold interval 10,000 to 11,000 years ago provoked
ecological disasters in various parts of the world, killing trees and replacing
them with bare ground and sparse tundra vegetation in the British Isles and
Scandinavia, disrupting soil profiles and causing massive erosion in parts of
Canada.  Davis Rebuttal, Exh. 79 at 2.  Sudden changes during the last glacial
cycle also caused the extinction of many tree species in Europe, replacing
temperate forests with a period of polar desert in Denmark, northern Germany,
and the Netherlands, and replacing the forests that existed in France with
cold, dry steppe.  <u>Id</u>.  The sudden warming at the end of the last
glaciation is associated with the extinction of the horse, camel, mammoth,
mastodon, and other large mammals in North America.  <u>Id.</u>  In short,
climate swings of the magnitude predicted have in the past been associated with
large scale ecological damage.<p>
	Similarly, large-scale ecological changes may be expected in response to the
climate change projected for the next century.  Forests are particularly
vulnerable:<p>
<p>
Climatic changes of the order of magnitude predicted by climate models for a
doubling of CO2 are <i>potentially sufficient to produce substantial immediate
and long-term changes in the composition, size, and locations of the forests of
the world.</i>&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;The natural forests of the high
latitudes and boreal forests in particular appear sensitive to predicted
temperature changes.  Warmer conditions could possibly lead to large reductions
in the areal extent of boreal forests and a poleward shift in their
boundaries.<p>
"The Greenhouse Effect, Climatic Change, and Ecosystems, Scientific Committee
on Problems of the Environment (SCOPE), quoted in Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.70
at 11.<p>
	The record also establishes that Minnesota's ecosystems are quite sensitive to
climate changes of the type predicted.  Dr. Davis testified:<p>
<p>
The state includes a steep gradient of climate, from dry and relatively warm in
the southwest to cool and more moist in the northeast, and a steep gradient of
vegetation reflects this.  Consequently climate changes across this gradient
will be accompanied by conspicuous changes in natural vegetation.   <p>
Davis Rebuttal, Exh. 77 at 7.  Dr. Davis notes that all of the GCMs predict
large temperature increases in the northern Great Plains. <u>Id.</u>  Moreover,
most of the GCMs project a dryer spring and summer climate here, particularly
less soil moisture.  Tr. 12 at 56, ln. 20 - p.&nbsp;57, ln. 2.  If Minnesota
indeed becomes both warmer and dryer, dramatic changes can be expected in the
distribution of trees, as illustrated by Figure 2 of Dr. Davis' Rebuttal
showing the range of the sugar maple shifting not just out of Minnesota, but
entirely out of the Great Lakes Region.  Exh. 77 at 8.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn24">[26]</a><p>
	The forest change computer models being used by Dr. Pastor and others
similarly predict drastic changes in the forests of the state.  Dr. Pastor
testified that of all the ecosystems of North America, those of Minnesota and
particularly the Lake Superior region, are likely to be the most sensitive to
climate change.  Pastor Rebuttal, Exh. 65 at 2.  This is because of the high
level of relative warming predicted for this region, and because "most of the
tree species are at the edges of their ranges here and are already stressed to
some degree by extreme climate."  Exh. 65 at 7.  Using a computer model that
incorporates current knowledge of forest ecology and various climate change
predictions from different GCMs,  Dr. Pastor expects ecological changes similar
to what one would see today traveling from the Boundary Waters to the Twin
Cities, with boreal forests of spruce and fir being replaced with oak and
prairie. <u>Id</u>.  In the words of Dr. Pastor:<p>
<p>
Thus, we simply have to warm the climate of northern Minnesota to reach that
now experienced in the Twin Cities to effect the simulated drastic changes in
vegetation that match those which are now observable.  Such a change is not
inconceivable; in fact, given the current rate of increase in CO2, it is a
conservative estimate.<p>
Exh. 65 at 8.  And this change follows from the relatively conservative
assumption of a 2deg. C rise in average global temperatures over 100 years.<p>
<b>	</b>These forecasts imply that the Minnesota landscape and ecological mix
will dramatically change in response to global warming.  The exact future shape
of the Minnesota landscape under changing climate will depend on the ability of
ecosystems to migrate and maintain the present mix of species.  Neither is
assured.  In fact, the ability of ecosystems to shift into new areas as the
climate changes is seriously threatened by two things:  the rate of projected
change, which is faster than most ecosystems can migrate, and the fact that
historic pathways of migration have been interrupted by human development.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn25">[27]</a>    <p>
	As Dr. Davis testifies, the ability of ecosystems to migrate to new areas
where they can thrive depends critically on the rate of climate change.  The
rate of climate change likely to result from a doubling of equivalent CO2
values by the year 2050 would be ten to a hundred times faster than climate
changes of the past, requiring trees to "migrate" much faster than the fossil
records show they have ever been able to migrate in the past.  Davis Rebuttal,
Exh. 77 at 9-10.  While commercially valuable trees might be assisted in their
migration by foresters, who could plant trees tolerant of the new climatic
conditions, the future is more threatening for the less commercially valuable
plants, and for biodiversity in general.  Dr. Davis testified:<p>
 <p>
These mono-specific plantations are not diverse habitats, they're very
different from a natural forest.  In Minnesota, most of our forests are not
managed this way, they are not plantations, they're really natural forests that
have just grown up after logging.  In old growth forests there is a wide
diversity of species, undergrowth, herbs and mosses and many small animals
which live in these thick humus layers, and I can't visualize loggers bothering
to move these species.  Now the Nature Conservancy might try to move them, but
it's notoriously difficult to grow things, plants like this, in cultivation.
And I know that there are some plant societies that are trying to get them
under cultivation, foreseeing the difficulty in preserving those species as the
climate changes and as the preserves become more and more limited in size.
It's certainly very expensive, so if society is willing to put enough money
into getting plants like that under cultivation and then willing to set up new
reserves and try to plant them northward, I think it's feasible we can save
some of these species in a kind of zoo-like environment for plants, but the
costs will be very high.<p>
<p>
Tr. 12 at 5, ln. 1 - p.&nbsp;24, ln 2.  <p>
	Similar concerns for biodiversity are expressed in a study published by Yale
University by Botkin and Nisbet, who project the effects of climate change on
biological diversity in forests using a computer model of forest growth similar
to that used by Dr. Pastor.  "Projecting the Effects of Climate Change on
Biological Diversity in Forests," 1992, attached to Ciborowski Direct, Exh. 69.
Their study found "surprisingly large" and "surprisingly rapid" changes in the
BWCA forests, with "a major change in forest composition" either by 2010 or
2040, depending on rate of warming assumed.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn26">[28]</a>  They note that "[t]hese changes are so
rapid that there may be transitional decades when dying and poorly growing
trees dominate the landscape&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.," and if climate
change continues beyond 2070, "large areas might remain treeless, dominated
instead by shorter-lived annual and perennial herbs and shrubs."  <u>Id.</u> at
290 and 291.<p>
	In summary, the dramatic climate changes predicted for the next century are
expected to result in widespread and costly ecological disruption, as changes
of similar magnitude have in the past.  Boreal forests such as those in
northern Minnesota are particularly sensitive to warming, and would be
profoundly changed by the predicted levels of warming.<p>
<b>			 </b><p>
<b>2.	The Commission, following the lead of the international political
community, should accept as authoritative and reliable the predictions of the
IPCC and reject the minority scientific viewpoints promoted by the coal
industry.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>a.	The predictions of the IPCC are considered to be so reliable and
authoritative by the international political community that it has negotiated
global CO2 reduction goals based on them; policymakers on the federal level
also take the evidence and threat of global warming seriously.</b><p>
<b></b>	The international political community considers the predictions of the
IPCC to be so serious and so reliable that it is negotiating major global
reductions in CO2 emissions in response.  The IPCC provided the scientific
basis for the global warming negotiations at the June 1992 "Earth Summit" in
Rio de Janeiro.  Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 at 3.  Those negotiations
resulted in the Framework Convention on Climate Change (Framework Convention),
signed by 128 countries including the United States and most of the
industrialized world.  <u>Id.</u>.  The Framework Convention commits signatory
countries to actions to limit global warming with the aim of reducing CO2
emissions to 1990 levels by the year 2000.  Bernow Direct, Exh. 111 at 4.  Last
spring the signatories to the Framework Convention met in Berlin to negotiate
changes to the Framework Convention, and during that meeting the tenure of the
IPCC as the scientific review body of the signatory group was extended.
Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 at 3.  <p>
	Pursuant to the Framework, the United States has launched a Climate Change
Action Plan designed to reduce U.S. emissions to 1990 levels by the year 2000.
NERA Report at 61, attached to Harrison Direct, Exh. 8.  According to the EPA
official charged with implementing the agency's programs to reduce greenhouse
gas emissions, establishing programs to reduce greenhouse gas emissions is one
of the highest environmental priorities of the Clinton administration.  Letter
from Paul Stolpman, Acting Director, Office of Atmospheric Programs, U.S. EPA,
submitted into public record by Sen. Janet Johnson, April 26, 1995.<p>
	In relying on the scientific expertise of the IPCC -- and in rejecting the
minority scientific viewpoints of the witnesses presented by the coal industry
--  the Commission will be acting consistently with the international political
community and the U.S. government.  Indeed, given that the U.S. government and
the other 127 signatory nations to the Framework Convention are proceeding in
reliance on the IPCC, it would be unreasonable not to accept the IPCC's
scientific predictions as authoritative.<p>
	Additional evidence that policymakers are taking seriously global warming
projections similar to those of the IPCC comes from the legislative history of
the Clean Air Amendments of 1990.  Congress adopted extensive provisions to
regulate chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs).  These gases destroy the ozone layer and
are also powerful greenhouse gases.  The CFC provisions were therefore adopted
not just to protect the ozone layer, but also to respond to the "related global
environmental crisis" of "massive, uncontrolled global climate change
associated with the intensification of the greenhouse effect."  Senate Comm. on
Env't &amp; Public Works, Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, S. Rep. No.
101-228, 101st Cong., 2nd Sess., reprinted in 1990 U.S.C.C.A.N., vol. 6, 3385,
3760.  With respect to scientific uncertainty, the Senate Report on the
Amendments, states: <p>
<p>
It is easy to overstate the uncertainty that surrounds this issue.  It is true
that scientists disagree about matters such as whether the greenhouse effect
has already begun.  Similarly, there is no scientific consensus about the
precise timing or magnitude of the predicted changes.<p>
<p>
Nevertheless, there is a remarkable degree of scientific consensus concerning
the threat of massive, uncontrolled global climate change.  Specifically, most
experts agree that if we do not change our pattern of polluting the atmosphere,
many of us, our children, and our grandchildren will experience devastating
climate changes of a magnitude and at a rate that will preclude natural
evolutionary responses.<p>
<p>
There appears to be consensus on another critical point.  That is:  by the time
there is scientific proof for every detail of the problem, it will be too late
to avoid the most devastating impacts of an intensified greenhouse effect and
global climate change.  We can ill afford to wait for 5 to 10 years of research
before we take action to (1) limit the rate and extent of future climate change
by reducing atmospheric emissions and concentrations of greenhouse gases, and
(2) implement adaptation strategies for coping with changes to which we are
already committed.<p>
<u></u><p>
<u>Id.</u> at 3762.  While the Senate Report was written before the IPCC 1990
report came out, it clearly demonstrates the seriousness with which national
policymakers view the scientific evidence of global warming, it represents an
illustration of taking policy action partially in response to that threat, and
it endorses the need to take additional policy actions now to minimize the
warming.<b></b><p>
<b>b.  	Criticisms of the IPCC process and findings by the scientific witnesses
for Western Fuels et al., are baseless and should be rejected.</b><p>
<b></b>	The coal industry has brought forward five scientific witnesses who
dispute the scientific findings of the IPCC.  In the last round of briefing,
the MPCA detailed at length the stark differences between the predictions of
the Western Fuels witnesses and those of the IPCC, as well as some of the
differences among the views of the Western Fuels witnesses themselves.
MPCA/Environmental Coalition Additional Evidentiary Motions and Memorandum, at
8 - 16, and appendices.  While MPCA expects to address the weaknesses of these
witnesses' testimony in its reply brief, at this point we will simply note that
it would be unwise for the ALJ and the Commission in this proceeding to
second-guess the scientific judgments of the IPCC based on the scientifically
complex criticisms presented by these witnesses.  The IPCC reports are based on
the contribution of scores of scientific experts from around the world,
reviewed by hundreds of other experts, as is discussed <u>supra</u> at 17.  The
IPCC's claim to present the authoritative statement of the views of the
international scientific community, IPCC 1990 Report, Foreword, are completely
justified, especially given their role as scientific advisory body to the 128
nations who are signatories to the international treaty on global warming,
discussed in the next section of this brief. <p>
	Perhaps because they recognize the implausability of expecting the
decisionmakers in this proceeding to second-guess the scientific judgment of
the IPCC, some witnesses for Western Fuels resort to attacking the credibility
of the IPCC by alleging that the predictions reflect not their honest
scientific judgment but rather a politicized process.  <u>See</u> <u>e.g.</u>
Lindzen Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;54 at 33 - 35; Michaels Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;57 at
21-22.  The MPCA showed in the last round of briefing that these subjective
characterizations of the IPCC process are entirely without foundation,
particularly given that none of the witnesses played a major role in the
development of the IPCC reports.  MPCA/Environmental Coalition Additional
Evidentiary Motions and Memorandum at 2-4 and App. A.  What these witnesses
seem truly uncomfortable with is the openness of the IPCC process -- the very
openness to many voices which we in government generally consider useful to
ensure fairness and to temper the biases of any single scientist.  Moreover, in
suggesting that the Commission should disregard the IPCC reports because they
reflect biases rather than scientific judgment, and that the Commission should
accept their own reassuring predictions instead, these witnesses ask the
Commission:  (1)&nbsp;to disregard the fact that the findings of the IPCC are
entirely consistent with the conclusions of many prior scientific review panels
that have found that increasing greenhouse gases will cause substantial changes
in climate<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn27">[29]</a> and (2)&nbsp;to assume that
while the many eminent scientists who have contributed to the IPCC and other
review panels since 1979 share a common bias due to politicization or funding
pressures, the scientific judgment of the Western Fuels' witnesses remain free
of any such influences.  If the ALJ or the Commission are in fact concerned
about bias, there is greater reason to worry about the witnesses for Western
Fuels than about the scores of scientists contributing to the IPCC.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn28">[30]</a><p>
<b>3.  	The law requires the Commission to quantify the environmental costs
associated with CO2 emissions, without regard to when or where the costs are
actually felt.</b><p>
<b>	</b>Global warming is a long-term, global problem.  The costs that will be
incurred as a result of it will inevitably be spread out over space and time.
However, section 216B.2422, subd. 3 requires that the Commission attempt to
calculate the costs of CO2 emissions, without respect to where or when they
occur.  CO2  emissions result in costs because they contribute to the rising
global CO2 concentration and resulting climate change.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn29">[31]</a>  Because of CO2's long atmospheric
lifetime, CO2 emissions contribute to global warming for centuries.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn30">[32]</a>  Necessarily, the Commission must take a
global and long-term perspective in order to estimate CO2's environmental cost.
The statute calls for nothing less.<p>
	NSP asserts through its witness Dr. Harrison that "the correct conceptual
rationale" for establishing CO2 values is to look solely at "damages to
Minnesota residents from Minnesota utility emissions."  Harrison Rebuttal, Exh.
9 at 2.  NSP raised this same issue in its first evidentiary brief, arguing
that consideration of environmental costs incurring outside of Minnesota was
inconsistent with the intent of the statute and even outside the Commission's
legal authority.  Initial Brief I of NSP Co., at 4 - 7.  As was pointed out in
our last round of briefing, the plain language of the statute requires
quantification of costs regardless of where they occur.  Joint Reply Brief of
MPCA and Environmental Coalition On Evidentiary Issues, at 7 (October 6, 1995).
That brief showed that such a narrow "Minnesota-only" reading of the statute is
inconsistent with the legislative history and with the environmental leadership
Minnesota has shown on other environmental problems of regional or global
scope, such as our mercury, acid rain and CFC statutes.  <u>Id.</u> at 7 -10.
Finally, it demonstrated that there is no constitutional or common law
limitation to the Commission's legal authority that prevents it from doing what
the statute plainly requires and the legislature intended.  <u>Id</u>., 11 -
21.  Those arguments are incorporated here.  In addition to the evidence of
legislative intent discussed in our last brief, the comments of Senate Janet
Johnson, the Senate author of section 216B.2422, subd. 3, at the St. Paul
public hearing, reflect her clear concern over Minnesota's contribution to the
larger global warming problem, testifying:  <p>
	<p>
Some people believe that Minnesota can do little in the face of a world-wide
problem and therefore, we should do nothing.  But every state contributes to
the condition of the country as a whole and as was noted in a letter to me from
the Federal EPA on behalf of Administrator Browner, the inclusion of carbon
dioxide values in utility planning in Minnesota would help facilitate
achievement of the President's greenhouse gas emission reduction goals.<p>
<p>
Public Hearing Tr., April 26, 1995, at 70, lns. 10 - 18.  While these comments
do not constitute official legislative history, they do clearly establish the
views of the Senate author on this critical point, supplementing the evidence
of legislative intent discussed in our last brief.<p>
	In short, there is no legal basis for limiting consideration of the costs of
CO2 to those costs that occur within the state and which can be attributed in
some fashion to the Minnesota-related emissions, and there is no rational
scientific basis for doing so given the global effects of the emissions.
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>B.	The Environmental Costs Caused By CO2 Emissions Can Be Practicably
Quantified; There Is Substantial Evidence Supporting A Cost Value in the Range
of $4.28 to $28.57.</b><p>
<b>	</b>Given that the best evidence available to science shows that dramatic
environmental consequences will result from global warming, it is clear that
the zero cost value advanced by other parties (or implied by the failure to
adopt a value at all) greatly understates the environmental costs attributable
to CO2 emissions.  Moreover, the record shows that, through a series of
supportable and reasonable assumptions, the Commission can indeed practicably
quantify the environmental cost of CO2.  While the resulting range of cost
estimates may not be the only defensible range, it is rationally based on the
best evidence and methods available.<p>
	The methodology recommended by the MPCA derives the from two fundamental
characteristics of CO2 emissions discussed <u>supra</u>:  (1) they have a
global consequence, and (2)&nbsp;they have long-term impacts.  They have a
global consequence because the atmosphere is well-mixed, so it cannot be said
that emissions here have only local effects, or that effects here are
particularly associated with local emissions.  What matters with CO2 are the
global concentrations; these are what lead to global warming.  Tr. 12 at 17,
lns. 9-10.  They have a long-term consequence because they persist for so long
in the environment.  The IPCC notes that "CO2 emitted into the atmosphere today
will influence the atmospheric concentration of CO2 for centuries into the
future."  IPCC 1990 Report at 5.   <p>
	Because CO2 emissions will have long-term global effects, it is necessary to
look at long term global costs per ton of pollutant.  The MPCA has employed a
methodology that does precisely this, estimating long-term discounted global
costs based on the existing economic literature, and dividing by long-term
global CO2 emissions to arrive at an average cost per ton of CO2.  The
resulting cost value could be equally applied to any CO2 emission on the
planet, and this is entirely appropriate since emissions from around the globe
contribute equally to the rising global CO2 concentration, and thus to global
warming.  This portion of the brief explains in more detail this method of
calculation, and the assumptions made along the way.  At each step, the MPCA
has attempted to identify the most likely scenario, or the "best estimate,"
given the available evidence.  The resulting range therefore reflects the best
estimate of the environmental costs of the emission of CO2. <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.  	There is substantial evidence supporting an estimate of long-term costs
of at least two percent global GDP due to a warming of 2.5deg.C.</b><p>
<b>	</b>A body of published economic literature has developed estimating  the
long-term costs that society will incur as a result of the levels of warming
predicted by the IPCC.  The work of four of these economists is summarized in
Table 3 of Mr. Ciborowski's Rebuttal Testimony, Exh. 70, at 24.  While the
studies vary in methodology and in the cost sectors they address, they arrive
at damage estimates for the United States for a warming of 2.5deg.C that are
relatively close together:  1.1% (Cline), 1.0% (Nordhaus), 1.3% (Fankhauser),
and 0.8% (Scheraga).  <u>Id.</u>  The low estimate of 0.8% from Scheraga is
based on a review of only three cost sectors, compared to the review of 12 cost
sectors by Fankhauser and 13 cost sectors by Cline.  In a study for the
Organization of Economic Development (OECD), Cline provides a damage cost
function that allows for the calculation of costs not just at an average global
warming of 2.5deg.C, but at other levels of temperature change as well.  Exh.
70 at 23-24.<p>
	Based on work by Nordhaus and Fankhauser, we can reasonably assume that costs
on the global level would be similar to those given for the United States.
Exh. 70 at 26.  Nordhaus estimates global GDP losses in 2050 of 1% of GDP, and
Fankhauser estimates global GDP losses in 2050 of 1.5%.  <u>Id.</u>  Losses in
developing countries are estimated to be about twice as large as a percent of
GDP as those in the developed world.  <u>Id.</u><b></b><p>
<b>	</b>These cost estimates are likely to underestimate, rather than
overestimate, the true level of costs associated with global warming.
Substantial evidence in the record shows that the true level of costs is likely
to be at least twice the the 1% range estimated above. Cline acknowledges that
his cost estimate of 1.1% of GDP does not include all costs of global warming
to unmanaged ecosystems, species diversity, and air pollution.  He concludes
that the inclusion of these costs <i>could easily raise the expected GDP loss
to about 2 percent of GDP</i>.  Exh. 70 at 25.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn31">[33]</a>  Indeed, the testimony of Drs. Davis and
Pastor and others discussed in section II.A.1.e. <u>supra</u> provides
compelling evidence of the grave threat to unmanaged ecosystems and the species
that they contain if warming proceeds to predicted levels at anything like the
rate expected by the business-as-usual scenario.  There are also other cost
sectors that are simply not included, such as the effects of warming on
infectious diseases or on livestock production.  Tr.13 at 92, ln. 5 to
p.&nbsp;93, ln. 10.<p>
	Moreover, there are additional reasons why Cline's projection of 2% GDP is
likely to be closer to true costs than 1%.  First, the 1% range cost estimates
all assume that the predicted midrange warming will occur in a gradual and
linear pattern, rather than in a step-like fashion.  Exh. 70 at 25; Tr. 13, p.
91, lns. 11- 13.  While disruption would be less if this is true, this
assumption does not have a firm scientific basis. Tr. 13, p. 91, lns. 13 - 18.
In fact, the IPCC notes that, because of other factors which influence climate
they "would not expect the rise [of temperatures] to be a steady one."  IPCC
1995 Report at xxii.  In fact, based on the earth's long-term climatic history,
there is reason to believe that the changes could be quite sudden.  Commenting
on ice-core records going back several hundred thousand years, one scientist
points out that "these records indicate that Earth's climate does not respond
to forcing in a smooth way.  Rather, it responds in sharp jumps which involve
large-scale reorganization of Earth's systems."  Broecker, W., "Unpleasant
Surprises in the Greenhouse?"  <u>Nature</u>, 329 (1987), cited in Ciborowski
Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 18.<p>
	Second, these estimates do not account for the effects of temperature change
on the rate of emissions of CO2 and other greenhouse gases from the biosphere
itself.  Rising levels of CO2 and the resultant warming could trigger large
emissions of greenhouse gases from the living organisms of the Earth.
Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70, at 25.  Carbon continuously cycles through
plants, soil, and atmosphere.  <u>Id</u>, at 13.   Much of carbon stored in the
biosphere is contained in global soils, and a substantial warming could result
in the release of massive amounts of carbon from soils. <u>Id.</u>  Similar
feedbacks exist for methane and other greenhouse gases.  Exh. 70, at 13 to 14.
See also testimony of M. Davis, Tr. 12 at 15, lns. 2 - 21.  Because these
amplifying feedbacks are not well understood, particularly with respect to CO2,
there is danger that rising temperatures and CO2 concentrations could trigger
one of them, leading to even greater warming than what has been predicted,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn32">[34]</a> and higher resulting costs.<p>
	Third, there is no valuation of the enormous risk inherent in changing the
existing, natural climate and replacing it with a fundamentally different
man-made climate.  Climate change of the scale predicted raises a host of
catastrophic possibilities -- which may be remote but which cannot be ruled out
-- like the melting of ice at the poles, or drastic changes in the path of the
Gulf Stream or other ocean currents.  Exh. 70, at 15-17.  In 1987 the National
Academy of Sciences concluded the following: <p>
<p>
Most important, we are reluctant to accept a reassuring forecast for a warmer
world because of imponderables.  <i>We know that major changes are likely to
produce major unforeseen consequences --</i> indeed the unforecasted Antarctic
ozone hole may be just such an example of an unforeseen consequences of changes
acting on a complex system.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;We are pushing our
climate and environment -- the surroundings in which we live, work, and play --
into a region literally unexperienced during the history of homo sapiens.  To
find a climate as warm on the average as that projected for a century hence, we
would have to go back many millions of years.  <p>
NAS (1987) at 20, cited in Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72, at 13.<p>
 	Given the multiple estimates of identifiable U.S. costs in the range of 1% of
GDP, given the studies supporting the likelihood that global costs are in the
same range, and given the foregoing reasons why the 1% range is likely to be
too low, 2% of GDP is a reasonable and even cautious estimate of global costs.
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>2.	Projected costs can be reasonably converted from percentage of GDP to
current value dollars.</b><p>
<b>	</b>In Table 4 of Mr. Ciborowski's Rebuttal, the MPCA sets forth a
practicable method for calculating a range of global CO2 costs derived from the
percentage of GDP estimates discussed above.  Exh. 70 at 40.  Calculations are
presented using both the 1% of GDP cost estimate and a 2% GDP cost estimate
suggested by Cline. <u>Id.</u>  The damage function was taken from Cline.
Exh.&nbsp;70 at 39.  Warming is projected using the IPCC midrange prediction of
a 4deg.C warming above preindustrial levels by the end of the next century,
which assumes a 2.5deg.C climate sensitivity and emission rates under the
business-as-usual scenario.  <u>Id.</u>  Costs are estimated as a percent of
GDP, and are converted to 1995 dollars for all dates out to the year 2100,
assuming global GDP growth rates recommended by the EPA.  <u>Id.</u> at 40.<p>
	The stream of damages is sensitive to the rate of forecasted GDP growth.
Although  projecting growth rates out that far cannot be done with certainty,
it is reasonable to assume that long-term growth rates will be within certain
ranges.  The growth rate projections used in Table 4 were taken from the
Environmental Protection Agency, which used them in their 1989 report to
Congress on policy options to slow the rate of warming.  Tr. 13 at 56, ln. 16
to 57, ln. 2.  One projection assumes what is considered a low rate of growth
at 2% per year between 1995 and 2015, and 1.5% per year between 2025 and 2100.
The other projection assumes what is considered a high rate of growth of  3.4
percent per year between 1995 and 2025, and 2.6% per year between 2025 and
2100.  Exh. 70, at 40-41.  These numbers represent the extremes of the most
likely ranges of growth.  Tr. 13 at 59, lns.2-11.  Not only are they derived
from the E.P.A. who used them to advise Congress on global warming issues, but
they are consistent with the range of projections made by the IPCC in their
1992 and 1994 reports.  <u>Id.</u>, IPCC 1992 at 11.  It is reasonable for the
Commission to rely on the same global growth estimates that are being relied on
in the federal and international arena.  <b></b><p>
<b>	</b>The stream of future damages assumed in Table 4 begins in the year 2010
and ends in the year 2100.  Costs are assumed to begin in the year 2010 based
on the conservative assumption that before that date warming might still be
indistinguishable from natural variability.  Tr. 11 at 116, lns. 1 - 9.
Moreover, despite the fact that the effects of these CO2 emissions will persist
long after the year 2100, costs incurred after that year have been excluded.
By simplifying the calculation in this way, the overall costs attributable to a
ton of CO2 are far lower than they would be if one attempted to calculate the
more long term costs physically associated with the ton of CO2.  Tr. 11 at 129,
ln. 22 - p.&nbsp;130, ln. 12. <b></b><p>
<b> 	</b>In order to convert the long-term stream of costs into present value,
an appropriate discount rate must be chosen.  Costs incurred in the future do
not have the same present value as costs incurred today.  Thus, in estimating
the present value of future effects, it is necessary to discount the dollar
value of those effects using a discount rate.  Tr. 2 at 53, lns. 6-10.  The
higher the discount rate, the lower value is placed on future costs, and vice
versa.  Tr. 12 at 71, ln. 22 - p.&nbsp;72, ln.8.  In general, the present value
of global warming costs, given that they will be incurred over the next
century, is very sensitive to the selection of a discount rate, as is apparent
from Table 4.  Exh. 70 at 40.<p>
	The selection of an appropriate discount rate is a matter of some dispute, and
particularly for costs that will be incurred over many generations, such as
global warming costs.  Tr. 12 at 73, ln. 23 -p.&nbsp;74, ln.3.  See also OTA
Report at 60-62.  Cline, in his 1992 publication, puts forward a discount rate
of approximately 1.5%.  This fairly low discount rate is composed of two parts,
described as follows by Mr. Ciborowski: <p>
<p>
One part would be essentially an investment discount rate.  Another one would
be the social rate of time preference. Since effects fall on GDP, that is total
production in some year, you must take the weighted average.  We must look to
the way in which GDP divides into, on the one hand, the investment budget, on
the other hand, consumption.  Roughly at present maybe 15% of GDP in the U.S.
goes to investment, the rest goes to consumption.  The analysis of Cline
suggests that we take the weighted average, then, of these two discount rates.
We know the rate of return on private capital, let's say 8 percent.  With
regard to the social rate of time preference, the analysis of Cline and others,
[say] that in cases where you have damages that span more than one generation,
and future generations do not have a voice in decision-making, they're simply
not around, it is necessary, it is only equitable that future generations'
interests be reflected in the choice of the discount rate you apply with regard
to consumption.  On that basis Cline recommends a fairly low social rate of
time preference, roughly one percent, and taking the weighted average of those
two, comes up with a discount rate, a total discount rate of about one and a
half percent.<p>
Tr. 13 at 95, ln. 2 - p.&nbsp;96, ln. 13.<p>
 	Table 4 uses four different discount rates to analyze future costs:  1, 2, 3,
and 5 percent.  Exh. 70 at 40.  However, as explained above, because of the
multi-generational nature of the costs, the MPCA believes it is most
appropriate to apply discount rates in the 1 to 2 percent range.  This validity
of this approach is also recognized and indirectly endorsed by the New York
State Environmental Cost Study, November 1994, which describes a review of the
discounting of environmental values by Freeman.  Exh. 13 at III-26 to III-27.
Based on his review, including the fact that the Congressional Budget Office
has specified 2 percent as the best estimate of the real discount rate:<p>
<p>
Freeman recommends using a rate of 2 to 3 percent, at least where the streams
of benefits and costs accrue to people in the same generation.  In part, this
is because both gainers and losers could (potentially) participate in the
decisions such that compensation between groups in the same generation can
explicitly or implicitly occur.  Freeman notes, however, that discounting
across generations is more controversial because future generations have no
voice in present decisions, and because it is difficult to determine meaningful
mechanisms and measures of compensation across generations.<p>
Exh. 13 at III-27.  The New York study adopts a discount rate of 3% because
"[m]ost damages considered in the model occur within a time period of about 40
years, which can be considered to be in the same generation."  <u>Id.</u>  In
contrast, the global warming costs being discounted here span more than a
century.  The costs resulting from the current generations fuel consumption
will be visited upon multiple future generations.  Many of these costs can be
seen as irreversible, such as the permanent loss of species likely to be driven
into extinction by changes in their habitat.<p>
	The choice of an appropriate discount rate reflects the value we place on
future generations relative to our own.  The MPCA urges the Commission to make
a policy choice that recognizes the multi-generational nature of global
warming, and that does not unduly discount the interests of future generations.
In other words, MPCA supports the use of a relatively low discount rate of 1 or
2 percent.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>3.	Total costs can be converted into a cost per ton of future emissions of
CO2 by subtracting out the percentage of total costs attributable to past
emissions of all greenhouse gases and future emissions of non-CO2 greenhouse
gases.</b><p>
<b></b>	The last step in the calculation of a cost per ton of CO2 is to divide
long-term global costs, as calculated above, by the long-term global emissions
of CO2 necessary to achieve the predicted warming.  As part of this step the
share of warming attributable to past emissions and the warming attributable to
future emissions of non-CO2 gases are subtracted.  Exh. 70 at 39.  In this way,
the MPCA isolates the warming that can fairly be attributed to future emissions
of CO2.  The MPCA has also assumed in this part of the calculation that of each
ton of CO2 emitted, between 0.5 and 0.6 tons are sequestered at the time of
emission in the deep oceans.  <u>Id.</u>  Table 4 of Mr. Ciborowski's Rebuttal,
presenting the results of all these calculations, is attached for convenience
to this brief as Attachment A.<p>
	As is stated in Mr. Ciborowski's Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 41, and as is discussed
is section II.B.1. above, the MPCA supports the use of the higher damage
function suggested by Cline, of 2% of global GDP.  Further, given the very
long-term, intergenerational nature of global warming costs, we support the use
of a discount rate in the range of one to two percent.  We therefore believe
the record best supports a range of costs per ton of CO2 of $4.28 to $28.57.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn33">[35]</a>  <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>III.</b>	<b>MINNESOTA HAS BEEN A LEADER IN IDENTIFYING THE PROBLEMS FROM
AIRBORNE MERCURY AND THE COMMISSION SHOULD ADVANCE THAT LEADERSHIP BY
ESTABLISHING ENVIRONMENTAL COST VALUES FOR MERCURY</b>.<p>
<p>
<b>A.	Atmospheric Deposition Of Mercury Is A Recently Discovered And Fast
Evolving Environmental Concern.  Coal Burning Is a Major Source Of Mercury In
The Atmosphere.</b><p>
<b></b>	Mercury contamination has been an environmental concern for decades.
However, it is only in recent years that the significance of mercury transport
through the air and its deposition to remote locales has been understood.  As
outlined in the direct testimony of MPCA research scientist Edward Swain, Exh.
213, environmental and natural resource management agencies have long been
concerned about direct discharges of mercury wastes into rivers and lakes.
Only in the late 1980's and early 1990's have researchers, most of whom focused
their investigations on the Upper Midwest and Canada, determined that mercury
deposited from the atmosphere is the cause of widespread mercury contamination
found in even the most remote lakes.  Because very small amounts of mercury in
lake water can become concentrated many thousand-fold ("bioaccumulate") up the
aquatic food chain, walleye, northern pike and other large fish at the top of
the food chain can build up so much mercury in their tissue that their
successful reproduction may be threatened, and wildlife and people who consume
these fish risk harm to their nervous systems. Swain Direct, Exh. 213 at 2-3,
11-12.  In recognition of this threat, the Minnesota Department of Health has
issued fish consumption advisories, the latest of which recommends that anglers
restrict their consumption of fish on about 95% of the Minnesota lakes
surveyed<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn34">[36]</a> and that particularly
susceptible groups such as young children and women of child-bearing age follow
even more limiting restrictions.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn35">[37]</a><p>
	It is generally estimated that fifty to seventy-five percent of the mercury in
the atmosphere is present as a result of human activity ("anthropogenic").  In
Minnesota the seventy-five percent figure is considered more accurate because
of field research performed by Dr.&nbsp;Swain.  Swain, Tr. 23 at 18-20, 78-79;
Swain Direct, Exh. 213 at 2, 5, 8.  An MPCA inventory of anthropogenic mercury
emissions in Minnesota for 1990 shows major sources in Minnesota to be
volatilization from painted surfaces (28%), coal combustion (19%), and
municipal solid waste combustion (14%).<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn36">[38]</a>
Although more recent information on unintended removal of mercury by utilities'
pollution control equipment might lower the actual amount attributable to coal
combustion, the relative percentage attributable to coal combustion stays about
the same because the 1991 federal prohibition on the addition of mercury to
paints will reduce and eventually eliminate the leading source, volatilization
from painted surfaces.  Swain, Tr. 23 at 21-24; Swain Direct Exh 213
at&nbsp;7-8.  With the ban on mercury in paints, and in fungicides as well,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn37">[39]</a>  and the promulgation of MPCA rules
limiting mercury emissions from waste incinerators,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn38">[40]</a> coal combustion stands out as the largest
single source of  anthropogenic mercury emissions in Minnesota.  The precise
percentage it contributes has no bearing on the cost/unit determinations to be
made in this proceeding; however, its top ranking underscores the urgency of
including a range of values for mercury.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>B.	Mercury's Unique Characteristics Of Persistence In The Environment And
Amenability To Transport Mean That Mercury Emissions To The Air Have Long-Term
Consequences On Local, Regional And Global Scales.</b><p>
<b></b>	Because mercury is an element it can never degrade.  While it can be
diluted, bioaccumulation through the aquatic food chain can reconcentrate it as
much as a million fold and thus negate the effects of dilution.  Mercury is
highly mobile and can be re-emitted to the atmosphere after initial deposition.
For example, 90% of the mercury deposited to the oceans is re-emitted to the
atmosphere.  Mercury has, to some extent, the characteristics of a global
pollutant such as carbon dioxide (CO2); but it also has important local and
regional impacts.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn39">[41]</a>  See Swain Direct,
Exh. 213 at 3-4 and Swain Surrebuttal, Exh. 215 at 6.<p>
	Unlike the elaborate pairing of emission sources and receptors needed for the
TER study (Exh. 136) of priority pollutant impacts, estimation of the
environmental costs of mercury does not require specific information on where
the mercury is emitted or where it is deposited.  Tr. 24 at 51, ln. 21 - p. 54,
ln. 8.  As Dr. Swain testified:<p>
<p>
Because of the extreme mobility of mercury in the environment, we're looking
at, our method looks at the average environmental impact of mercury in the
environment, not particularly elevated sites near emission sources.<p>
Tr. 24 at 54, lns. 10-14.<p>
While site-specific resource plan or certificate of need proceedings under
Minn. Stat. ch.&nbsp;216B would want to focus on both the 10% local impact and
90% regional/global impact of mercury emissions, this generic proceeding need
only recognize that "Minnesota's mercury emissions impose an environmental cost
not only in Minnesota, but inevitably, somewhere on the globe."  Swain Direct,
Exh. 213 at 4, lns. 4-6.<p>
	Mercury emissions have far-reaching consequences not only from the perspective
of the persistence of mercury once it is released to the environment but also
from the perspective that the mercury in coal would have remained locked up for
millennia were the coal not mined and burned.  Swain Direct, Exh. 213 at 16-17.
See also LCMR Work Program (Mercury), 1995, Exh. 221, sect. A.1.a.  The
introduction to the biosphere of additional amounts of a contaminant which
otherwise would have been securely buried further underscores the environmental
consequences of releasing mercury to the atmosphere through coal combustion.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>C.	Because Mercury Contamination Was Considered Until Recently A Problem
Only From Surface Water Discharges, Regulation Of Air Emissions Of Mercury Has
Lagged Behind.  Minnesota Is A Leader In The Field And Congress Has Directed
EPA To Address The Problem.</b><p>
<b></b>	As a problem found in surface waters, mercury contamination was first
addressed through regulation of direct discharges to those waters.  In
Minnesota, earlier site-specific water discharge permit determinations were
followed by MPCA adoption of surface water standards for mercury in Minn. R.
7050.0220, subp. 3.  The application of these stringent water quality standards
is discussed in Swain Direct, Exh. 213 at 13. <p>
	Spurred by the research of Dr. Swain and his colleagues showing the connection
between airborne mercury and the contamination of remote lakes,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn40">[42]</a>  Minnesota has quickly become a leader
nationally and internationally in investigating and addressing the atmospheric
mercury problem.  The most recent initiatives of the Minnesota Legislature are
discussed at length in the cross-examination of Dr. Swain, Tr. 23 at 54-71.
Minnesota regulations effective in 1994 limiting mercury emissions from waste
combustors, Minn. R. 7011.1201 - .1285,<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn41">[43]</a>
and recent state laws on consumer products restricting mercury content in
batteries, inks, paints, fungicides, toys and tennis shoes addressing disposal
and recycling of products with mercury are all further examples of the
importance of mercury reduction to Minnesota.  The State's legislative record
on reducing mercury, and the model Minnesota has become for other states, is
thoroughly covered in the public testimony of Representative Jean Wagenius, and
accompanying Public Exhibit 16.  Public Hearing Tr. at 155-164 (St. Paul
Hearing, April&nbsp;26, 1995).<b></b><p>
<b>	</b>Existing federal regulation of mercury<b> </b>air emissions are very
outdated and not applicable to coal-burning power plants.  Exh. 213 at 14.
However, Congress recognized the mercury problem in its massive rewriting of
the federal Clean Air Act at the start of the decade.  As discussed in Exhibit
213 at 15-16, the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 require U.S. EPA to
undertake two major studies:  (1) an overall review of mercury emissions to the
air, including public health and environmental impacts, and control
technologies;<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn42">[44]</a> and (2) a study on toxic
emissions from coal-fired electricity generation, which will include
consideration of mercury emissions.  In addition EPA has initiated a process to
establish national rules on municipal waste combustors, proposing more
stringent limitations on mercury emissions than those promulgated in 1994 by
Minnesota.  Exh. 213 at 15.<p>
	As Dr. Swain has testified, lack of sufficient data has been the reason U.S.
EPA and MPCA have not proposed mercury emission limits for coal-fired power
plants.  Tr.&nbsp;23 at 53, ln. 14 -p.&nbsp;54, ln. 4.  While the record here
does not show whether the studies currently underway at both federal and state
levels will provide necessary information to establish emission limits,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn43">[45]</a> they do underscore the important
environmental impacts of atmospheric emissions of mercury.<p>
<p>
<b>D.	In Light Of The Regional/Global Nature Of The Atmospheric Mercury
Problem, The Current Focus On Studies In The Regulatory Effort To Address
Mercury Emissions, And The Legislative Directive In Minn. Stat.
[[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422 To Quantify The Significant Environmental Costs Of
Electricity Generation, The MPCA "Benefit Transfer Procedure Offers A
Practicable Approach To Bring Mercury Emissions' Impact Into Planning For
Future Electric Generating Facilities.</b><p>
<b></b>	The historical background and current direction from the Legislature on
environmental considerations in the total resource planning process for
regulated electric utilities have been fully covered in an earlier brief in
this proceeding by the Office of the Attorney General (OAG).<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn44">[46]</a>  As noted by OAG, environmental impacts
are similar to cost and reliability factors, elements that utilities and
ultimately the Commission must forecast as best as present knowledge permits.
When the Commission reaches a decision point on new generation facilities, it
must exercise its informed judgment to strike the optimal balance among cost,
reliability, environmental and other<i> </i>factors.  This environmental costs
proceeding is part of the preparation for those important resource decisions.
<p>
	The State's principal environmental agency, the MPCA, is urging the Commission
to recognize that atmospheric mercury deposition is one of the State's most
important environmental issues today, and that coal-fired power plants are a
leading contributor of mercury emissions in the state.  As explained in the
MPCA testimony of Robert J. McCarron and Dr.&nbsp;Gregory C. Pratt and briefly
summarized below, the MPCA has employed the best information as of the time of
the hearing in this matter to calculate a range of environmental costs for
mercury emissions.  The Commission should fulfill the mandate given it by the
legislature, as discussed at pages 1-15, <u>supra</u>, and adopt the MPCA's
proposed mercury range.  To assume it has the benefit of the ongoing state and
federal studies mentioned above, the Commission should add narrative to its
order directing parties in any subsequent environmental costs proceedings and
resource planning and certificate of need proceedings to incorporate the latest
mercury findings from those studies into any consideration of future coal-fired
generation capacity coming before the Commission.<p>
	The two key elements of the MPCA approach to developing a range of
environmental costs for mercury emissions are the damage cost estimates for
priority pollutants performed for NSP by Triangle Economic Research (TER) and
the Indexing System developed by MPCA staff with the University of Toronto to
track substances emitted to the air for their potential hazard to humans and
other terrestrial and aquatic organisms.  Since the Indexing System was
intended as a comparative tool for directing air quality regulatory efforts, it
could not alone be sufficient for deriving a mercury cost range.  Fortunately,
TER's work provided damage costs for substances also covered by the Indexing
System, so that the Index's comparative weighting factors could be applied to
the TER cost estimates after adjustments to assure consistency to derive a
mercury cost range.  <p>
	The Indexing System is set forth in Exhibit 170, Pratt, Gregory C., et al, "An
Indexing System for Comparing Toxic Air Pollutants Based Upon Their Potential
Environmental Impacts," <u>Chemosphere</u>, Vol. 27, No.&nbsp;8, 1993 at
1359-1379.  As the paper explains, "[t]he Indexing System assesses and compares
the environmental fate and human and ecological toxicity potential of chemicals
emitted to the air in Minnesota, although the method could be applied at other
locations."  <u>Id.</u> at 1360.  Compared with earlier ranking systems, the
Indexing System "is more rigorous in that it processes the data in a meaningful
way by actually calculating concentrations in environmental compartments,
identifying exposure routes, and determining hazard."  <u>Id</u>.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn47">[47]</a>
The Indexing System utilizes a Level-3 fugacity model developed by University
of Toronto researchers to predict the movement and steady state distribution
(environmental fate) of  chemicals in the environment.  <u>Id.</u><a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn47">[48]</a>  All mechanisms of mercury transport are
considered by the fugacity model.  Tr. 20 at 40, ln. 18 - p.&nbsp;41, ln. 16.
Existing databases, primarily developed by U.S. EPA,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn49">[49]</a> are relied upon for human health and
ecological toxicity information.  Exh. 170 1360, 1364-71.  <p>
	Dr. Gregory C. Pratt, the principal author, was challenged on many aspects of
the Indexing System.  He testified that environmental fate information was
empirically derived through examination of real world data.  Tr. 20 at 27, lns.
16-25; at 38, lns. 4-7; at 44, ln. 11 - at 45, ln. 19; and, at 46, lns. 16-17.
He explained that although the Indexing System was not designed to model actual
emissions and predict actual amounts of a chemical to be found in a given
location, it did produce sound relative rankings of the chemicals studied.  Tr.
20 at 123, ln.&nbsp;15 - at 124, ln. 11; Tr. 22 at 53, ln. 25 - at 54, ln 16;
Tr. 22 at 49, lns. 10-16.  Also see Exh. 170, at 1373, 1378.  Those relative
rankings could be employed to "transfer" the dollar-based findings of the TER
work to mercury, a chemical studied in the Indexing System<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn46">[50]</a> but not assigned dollar values by TER.
Dr. Pratt  explained the value of such comparisons based on the quantitative
ranking in the Indexing System:<p>
<p>
[S]cientists and government regulators and others have been searching for some
time for a good quantitative way to compare the environmental hazard posed by
pollutants.  This indexing system method does provide such a quantitative
measure and can be very useful in a number of ways.  One way would be in the
setting of fees for pollutant emissions, and that's something that we are
actively working on now at the MPCA.  In a proceeding like this where we're
attempting to set environmental costs associated with pollutants, this
quantitative measure provided by the index is also very useful in achieving
that result.<p>
Tr. 22 at 50, lns. 2 - 14.<p>
  	Dr. Pratt also explained that the Indexing System is applicable to broad
geographic areas, such as "concentrations of different substances across the
state as a whole."  Tr. 20 at 34, lns. 6-14.  Since this is a generic
proceeding on environmental costs and 90% of mercury emissions impact on a
regional or global scale, Dr. Pratt  responded to cross-examination inquiry
about the uses for which the Indexing System was designed and the objectives of
the present hearing, by concluding:<p>
<p>
I believe that the current proceeding is a perfect example of how the indexing
system could be used.  It's a very good fit for this type of proceeding.<p>
<p>
Tr. 20 at 20, ln. 24 - p. 21, ln. 2.<p>
	Both the Indexing System and the TER Report are valuable contributions on
assessment of environmental impacts in Minnesota.  However, neither alone can
fulfill the mandate given the Commission of establishing environmental cost
ranges for each method of electricity generation.  The TER work has carefully
fashioned three representative scenarios; modeled priority pollutant emissions;
developed dose-response functions for receptors of those emissions; and
monetized the harmful consequences to human health, agriculture and materials
suffered by the receptors through willingness-to-pay and other economic
valuation tools.  The Indexing System has modeled not only the half-dozen
priority pollutants addressed by TER, but over 175 additional chemicals of
concern; it considers not only human health/agriculture effects but also a
broad range of impacts on terrestrial and aquatic life<b> </b>not considered by
TER.  Where there is long range transport and wide dispersion of pollutants, as
with the transformation products of SO2 and NOx, mercury, and CO2, the TER work
offers no direct help in fulfilling the Commission's mandate.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn51">[51]</a>
The Indexing System, while covering more pollutants through more pathways and
over greater distances, lacks any valuation element.  Only by combining the TER
valuation work with the Indexing System's broader coverage, in a manner that
assures the integrity and consistency of this combination process, could
mercury values be developed and, ultimately, the mandate of
[[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422 be fulfilled.<p>
	The mechanics of applying the Indexing System to the TER results to provide a
range of mercury values was performed by MPCA economist Robert J. McCarron in
consultation with Drs. Swain and Pratt and presented in McCarron Rebuttal, Exh.
163 at 28-43.  To utilize the Indexing System and achieve a fair
"apples-to-apples" comparison of mercury to some of the well-studied priority
pollutants evaluated by TER, Mr. McCarron had to make adjustments to the high
actual index value for mercury.  Most significantly, he disregarded the
ecological component and all non-inhalation human health components of the
mercury index value.  This reduction was necessary because the Indexing System
had developed toxicity ranking for all priority pollutants (except lead) solely
on the inhalation-induced health effects established in the U.S. EPA's
development of the National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS).  To compare
mercury to the priority pollutants, he selected the only pathway of harm
(inhalation) for which all of these substances had been evaluated.
Subsequently, he focused the comparison on mercury and three of the priority
pollutants, particulate matter (PM10), sulfur dioxide (SO2), and nitrogen
oxides (Nox).<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn47">[52]</a>  Carrying the comparison
across the three scenarios developed by TER led to the table of nine values set
forth at Exh. 163 at 35.  Recognizing that the PM comparison might lead to too
high a mercury value<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn48">[53]</a> and SO2/NOx
comparisons might lead to too low a mercury value,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn49">[54]</a> MPCA narrowed the proposed range to
encompass the highest of the low (SO2) and the lowest of the high (PM10)
derived values for mercury.  This range is from $4359/lb. to $9781/lb.  As
explained in McCarron Rebuttal, Exh. 163 at 40, this range likely
underestimates mercury values because it only takes into account inhalation
exposure to humans.  However, it is faithful to the "apples-to-apples"
comparison and, as Mr. McCarron has demonstrated, is the product of an
analytical process necessitated by circumstances and appropriate for the
purpose of this proceeding.<p>
	This two-step process of deriving mercury values though application of the
Indexing System to TER priority pollutant study results is called "benefit
transfer analysis" by economists.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn50">[55]</a>
Benefit transfer techniques are a useful option to inform decision-making when
a direct damage cost study is not available.  Even though the Commission's
Notice of Hearing raised the possibility of a Minnesota mercury survey<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn51">[56]</a> and the Minnesota Legislature shortly
thereafter approved funds for an independent study to be used in this
proceeding, a gubernatorial veto<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn52">[57]</a> and a
less-than-persuasive TER conclusion of "insufficient data" on mercury<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn53">[58]</a> resulted in no mercury damage cost study
being performed.  Confronted with this situation, and unable to find any damage
cost study for mercury emissions methodologically similar to the TER study,
Exh. 163, at 41, lns. 1 - 11, Mr. McCarron and colleagues applied the benefit
transfer techniques describe immediately above to derive mercury values.<p>
	Despite the differences in methodology recognized by Mr. McCarron, the MPCA
mercury values have sufficient reliability for the purposes of
[[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422.  Subdivision 5 of that section refers to the
environmental cost values as "environmental cost estimates" and, as argued
earlier in this brief, the test of  "practicability" means "reliable enough to
assist the Commission in its future planning process."  Moreover, as Mr.
McCarron has described, economics literature recognizes that benefit transfer
applications are to be tested along a continuum of required accuracy.  These
proceedings, as policy decisions, fall in the mid-range of that continuum.
McCarron Surrebuttal II, Exh. 165, at 8, ln. 14 - 10, ln. 10.  The ranges of
values to be established are best characterized as "benchmarks" from which the
Commission can begin analysis of specific applications.  <u>Id.</u> at 10, ln.
10, n. 4.  They do not represent immediate economic commitments, such as the
"adders" which have been legislatively repealed, but rather informed inputs for
subsequent resource decisions in which a variety of factors are to be balanced
to achieve a policy choice best serving the public interest.  Viewed in this
perspective, the range of values proposed by MPCA provide the Commission a
practicable approach for addressing the important concern over atmospheric
mercury emissions.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>IV.	MPCA ENDORSES THE VALUES PROPOSED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SERVICE
FOR CRITERIA POLLUTANTS PM10, CARBON MONOXIDE (CO), AND LEAD.  MPCA ENDORSES
THE DEPARTMENT'S VALUES FOR OXIDES OF NITROGEN (NOX) WITH ADJUSTMENT FOR
AGRICULTURAL EFFECTS.  MPCA CONTENDS THAT AGRICULTURAL EFFECTS ALSO JUSTIFY AN
$86/ TON VALUE FOR VOLATILE ORGANIC COMPOUNDS (VOC'S).</b><p>
<b></b>	Setting aside the proposal of a zero value for sulfur dioxide (SO2)
from the Department of Public Service, discussed in the following section of
this brief, the MPCA endorses the overall approach to other criteria pollutants
taken by the Department.  Most importantly, as explained by Dr. Morton
Lippmann,<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn54">[59]</a> and applied to the TER Report
and Thayer critique, there are no thresholds for criteria pollutants below
which damages do not occur.  Moreover, air quality that complies with National
Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) for criteria pollutants established under
the Clean Air Act provides no assurance that pollutants at concentrations below
NAAQS are not causing damages.  <p>
	The Department has utilized results of the TER study and obtained agreement
from TER principal author William Desvousges on certain upward adjustments to
TER results based on the critique of that study performed for the Department by
Thayer, et al.  As noted in the above discussion of mercury values and the
Indexing System, MPCA believes that the TER work underestimates near-field
exposures and ignores important transformation products from criteria
pollutants with a resulting underestimate of actual environmental costs.  MPCA
particularly urges the Commission to add explanation to its order in this
matter calling for consideration of transformation products in future
environmental cost proceedings and in site-specific planning proceedings
considering coal-fired power generation.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn55">[60]</a>
With these reservations, MPCA endorses the ranges of values proposed by the
Department for PM10, CO, and lead.  As will be explained, MPCA disagrees with
the Department/TER analysis of agricultural impacts of oxides of nitrogen (NOx)
and arrives at proposed values which are somewhat higher than the Department's
in the rural and fringe scenarios and somewhat lower in the urban scenario.
The same analysis for agricultural effects also leads the MPCA to propose a
value of $86/ ton for volatile organic compounds (VOCs) emitted by coal-fired
plants.<p>
	The Rebuttal Testimony of Dr. Gregory C. Pratt explains the basis for the
different PCA values for agricultural impacts.  Exhibit 176 at 6 - 9.  Dr.
Pratt's extensive experience in modeling the dispersion of air emissions can be
seen from his resume, Exh. 177, and from his testimony on cross-examination,
Tr. 20 at 8 <u>et</u> <u>seq</u>.  To summarize the position set out in Exhibit
176, Dr. Pratt takes issue with the TER conclusion, later utilized by the
Department, that power plant emissions of NOx may have agricultural benefits
and may be assigned negative environmental costs.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn56">[61]</a>  He believes that ozone formed from these
emissions results in crop damages and that environmental cost values should be
assigned to the precursors which lead to the formation of ozone.<p>
	Ozone (O3) is a photochemical oxidant formed by reactions of NOx and
hydrocarbons (i.e.,VOCs) in the presence of sunlight.  Ozone exposure has been
demonstrated to cause crop losses and nationwide crop impact studies have been
performed.  TER correctly noted that in the immediate vicinity of  power plants
high concentrations of NOx may react with ozone to reduce total ozone
concentrations ("ozone scavenging").  TER then argued that agricultural damages
due to ozone might be offset in part by in-plume scavenging of ozone.  As noted
by Dr. Pratt as well as in the critique of TER's work performed for the
Department by Thayer, et al.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn57">[62]</a>  TER
utilized flawed modeling of ozone ("oxidant modeling").  The better conclusion
is that there will be no agricultural benefits, only damages, from NOx
emissions:<p>
<p>
Although there may be some ozone scavenging within the power plant plume
itself, in the larger context extending state and regionwide, NOx and VOC
emissions from power plants will ultimately result in the formation, not
destruction. of ozone.<p>
<p>
TER has used these results to suggest that agricultural damages due to O3 may
in part be remediated due to in-plume scavenging of O3.  To the knowledge of
MPCA staff, such a remediation effect has never been documented in the
scientific literature.  The proposition by NSP and TER of agricultural benefits
due to power plant plume scavenging of O3 should be disregarded.<p>
<p>
Exh. 176 at 7.<p>
	After reaching this conclusion, Dr. Pratt then developed values for
agricultural damage from ozone formed because of power plant emissions.  He
attributed these damages equally to ozone precursors NOx and VOCs, ascribing a
value of $86.16 per ton of emission of each substance.  Even though only a
small fraction of ambient VOCs are attributable to coal--fired power plants,
Dr. Pratt thought it more appropriate to divide the damages between NOx and
VOCs, rather than attribute it all to NOx.  For this reason, MPCA is proposing
a VOC value of $86 per ton.<p>
	The MPCA refers the ALJ and the Commission to the summary table of values in
McCarron Surrebuttal II, Exh. 165 at 3 - 4 to see how the MPCA attribution of
half the ozone agricultural damages to NOx would affect total NOx environmental
cost ranges.  Since preparation of that table, the Department has raised its
range of values for NOx for reasons apparently unrelated to ozone.  Pending
further review of the explanation of those changes given in this round of
briefs, MPCA recommends the NOx values being proposed by the Department in its
brief with adjustments resulting from substitution of the MPCA $86 value for O3
(agr. effects) for the three Department ("DPS") ranges in the summary table.
Using the mean of the Department's range to facilitate comparison, the effect
of this substitution would be to raise the Department's rural NOx range by $75
and the Department's metro fringe ("S" in the table) by $60, and to lower the
Department's urban range by $90.  With those modifications and the addition of
the VOC value based on ozone,  MPCA endorses the NOx values presented by the
Department.  All MPCA recommended values are shown under Conclusion.<p>
<p>
<b>V.</b>	<b>ALTHOUGH ACTUAL TRADES MAY LATER BE TAKEN INTO ACCOUNT IN
SITE-SPECIFIC PLANNING PROCEEDINGS, NO ADJUSTMENT TO VALUES IS WARRANTED IN
THIS PROCEEDING BECAUSE A NATIONAL SO2 ALLOWANCE TRADING PROGRAM IS BEING
DEVELOPED.  THE MEDIAN SO2 DAMAGES FROM TER'S REPORT SHOULD BE THE LOW END OF
THE RANGE OF SO2 VALUES.</b><p>
<b></b>	While their damage assessment experts acknowledge that SO2 emissions
have serious environmental impacts,<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn58">[63]</a> the
Department of Public Service and NSP maintain that a zero value should be
assigned these impacts because of a federal program to cap national SO2
emissions known as  "allowance trading."  The Department/NSP argument should be
rejected because it is contrary to the legislative mandate for a resource
planning process that is fully informed on environmental cost issues; overlooks
real world damages by assuming that internalization of any fraction of residual
SO2 damages means there are no longer environmental costs; and ignores the
extensive record evidence that SO2 damages estimated in this proceeding are
highly localized and vary dramatically with proximity to population centers.<p>
	The emissions allowance trading program of Title IV of the federal Clean Air
Act Amendments of 1990 was created primarily to address acid rain concerns
voiced by Canada and impacted northeast and north central states (including
Minnesota) in the United States.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn59">[64]</a>  It
seeks to achieve reductions of large magnitude from coal-fired utilities, the
major source of acid rain precursor SO2.  Its establishment and economic basis
have been explained by Mr. McCarron:<p>
<p>
An emissions "cap," which takes effect in the year 2000, generates the demand
for newly created emission allowances.  Utility firms with the largest
generating plants have received (for free) SO2 emission allowances in amounts
determined by their historic emission rates.  Smaller SO2 emitters get their
allowances the year 2000.  In some cases extra allowances are given to utility
firms located in politically strategic regions.[<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn60">[65]</a> ]  The utility firms must collectively
reduce SO2 emissions within the next five years so that <u>total</u> emissions
are about 8.5 million tons below 1980 levels.  Emission control cost
differences, both within and among firms, make allowance purchases more
economic for some than installing emission control equipment.  If relatively
high cost firms can pay lower cost firms to add control equipment and sell
their unused allowance, then environmental protection is paid for at lower than
usual total cost.<p>
<p>
Exh. 163 at 2-3.<p>
Of course, with improved pollution control technology and emphasis on renewable
power generating sources<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn61">[66]</a>, the free
allowances distributed may prove adequate for a utility's expansion and no
money need be spent for allowance purchases.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn62">[67]</a>  Moreover, these same technological and
political trends also tend to reduce the demand for allowances and thus drive
their prices to low levels.  Exh. 163, at 7.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn63">[68]</a>  Finally, as confirmed by Drs. Sansom<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn64">[69]</a> and Nichols<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn65">[70]</a>, SO2 continues to be regulated nationwide
by EPA and the states under Title I of the Clean Air Act so that the collective
effect of state-imposed restrictions on SO2 levels could drive total national
emissions beneath the cap established by Title IV.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn66">[71]</a>  In those circumstances the cap could no
longer have any effect.<p>
	The MPCA contends that the existence of significant environmental damages from
SO2 emissions of coal-fired utilities, and related dollar costs, has been
established beyond dispute through testimony of witnesses such as Dr.
Desvousges, Dr. Pratt, and Dr.&nbsp;Thayer.  These residual damages, and the
risk of greater damages absent controls, are the reason SO2 has been regulated
as one of the priority pollutants under the federal Clean Air Act for a quarter
of a century.<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn67">[72]</a>   The imposition of a
national cap on utilities' SO2 emissions and the free distribution of tradable
allowances does not mean that continuing SO2 emissions allowed under that cap
will magically become harmless.  In fact, the goals of the national SO2 cap
have virtually nothing to do with the kind of SO2 damages calculated by TER.
As the legislative history of Title IV illustrates,<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn68">[73]</a> the concerns that led to the national cap
and trading program are long-range transport of transformation products (e.g.,
sulfate) which lead to acid deposition and resulting damages to lakes and other
ecosystems.  TER, as principal author William Desvousges acknowledged, did not
evaluate any of these damages from sulfate.  Tr. 17 at 259, ln. 6 -
p,&nbsp;260, ln. 23.  Its report only looked at the near-field effects of
untransformed emissions.  Therefore, there is no logic in ignoring the
undisputed damages noted by TER because of a program that has as its objective
amelioration of other damages never considered by TER.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn69">[74]</a><p>
	The broad mandate of section 216B.2422 can best be served by providing the
Commission the fullest possible information on SO2 impacts on public health and
ecology,<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn70">[75]</a> including the consequences from
long-range transport and transformation products not addressed by TER.  The
objectives of the law similarly require that the Commission be informed on the
allowance trading program and any offsetting reductions in environmental
damages that may follow from trades under that program.  As illustrated in
footnote 76 <u>infra</u>, there are many factors about allowance trading that
make it imprudent in this generic proceeding to jump to the proffered
conclusion that the significant impacts of SO2 emissions from Minnesota
electric utilities are fully internalized by the national allowance trading
scheme and should therefore be totally ignored by the Commission in all future
resource planning.  Accordingly, the Commission should adopt a SO2 range
starting with the median SO2 values from the TER Report as the lower end
(i.e.,$21/ton rural, $54/ton fringe, $126/ton urban), Exh. 136, vol. 7, Table 3
- 1, and should add a narrative to that range directing that future
environmental cost proceedings and/or site-specific planning proceedings also
consider the transformation product impacts and long range transport effects
resulting from SO2 emissions of electric power generation.<p>
	If the Commission were to follow the approach suggested by MPCA for SO2, it
may consider in specific applications whether allowance purchases, or other
kinds of offsets required of new sources in nonattainment areas, justify
adjustments to those SO2 values.  What a given adjustment might be for SO2
trading allowance purchases would vary with a number of factors.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn71">[76]</a>  The critical point for the present
proceeding is that the trading allowances do not reflect marginal damages.
Administrative Law Judge Klein obtained confirmation of this point from Dr.
Albert Nichols:<p>
<p>
Q[Judge Klein]:	So you can't talk about equating the market price of the
allowance with marginal damages?<p>
<p>
A[Dr. Nichols]: 	No.<p>
<p>
Tr. 27 at 120, lns. 13 - 15.<p>
	Parties on all sides of the matter agree.  Mr McCarron for MPCA testified that
"[T]radable permit systems are not designed to determine and internalize
environmental costs.  The relationship between the price for a tradable
emission permit and environmental cost is coincidental at best."  Exh. 163 at
5.  Dr. Sansom for LEC, when asked if Congress imposed the emissions cap on SO2
to reach an optimal level from a societal standpoint, replied:  "The question
of the optimization of the tonnage reduction goal in the 1990 amendments is
largely a question of political judgment&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;there was a
political judgment that we wanted to see that kind of tonnage reduction.  But I
don't think there was any monetized avoided damages associated with that
tonnage."  Tr. 7 at 128, ln. 19 - p.&nbsp;129, ln. 7.<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn72">[77]</a>  <p>
	The allowance trading program is a new concept in American environmental
regulation and addresses an acid deposition problem whose long-range transport
and distant impact features had stymied national efforts to address it for at
least a decade prior to enactment of Title IV in 1990.  <u>See, e.g.</u>,
<u>Her Majesty the Queen in Right of Ontario v. U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency</u>, 912 F.2d 1525 (D.C. Cir. 1990).  Perhaps because it addresses a
problem distinct from the near-field impacts more customarily assessed in
environmental regulation, its impact on environmental cost assessment can be
difficult to grasp.  Even a seasoned environmental cost economist such as Dr.
Thayer seemed at times confused on how to account for the trading program.  On
cross-examination, he explained that his adjustments to TER values in revised
Table 15<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn73">[78]</a> did not include secondary
particles from the emissions of SOX (i.e., sulfates) "because that's a
Department policy decision because of the emissions trading program."  Tr. 21
at 119, ln.&nbsp;19 - p.&nbsp;122, ln. 6.  A few moments later, on redirect
concerning the same issue of secondary particles, he appeared to have forgotten
entirely the Department policy which ruled out attributing secondary particles
to SOx:<p>
<p>
Q[Mr. Vanderlinden]:	Now, could you tell me why you originally allocated
secondary PM10 to the primary PM10 number?<p>
<p>
A[Dr. Thayer]:	Well, this is really an accounting issue.  You emit NOx or SOx,
and/or SOx, and [due] to the reactivity just generate secondary PM10.  But
individuals breathe PM10 so the health effects are related to PM10.  So what we
did is we allocated the damages to PM10 because that's what people are
breathing.  Or their soiling or visibility or whatever.  The alternative would
be to go back and allocate to the original pollutants.  NOx and SOx.  After
criticisms from TER and from, I think, a PCA witness, that our allocation to
PM10 was, in their words, not correct, we changed and allocated to the original
pollutants, NOx and SOx.<p>
<p>
Q:	So --<p>
<p>
A:	But again, this is just an accounting issue. The damages are the damages.
The dollar numbers are still there, it's just a matter of where you allocate
them.<p>
<p>
Q:	And I take it from your testimony you're saying that is would be fair to
allocate them either place?<p>
<p>
A:	It would be fair to allocate them either place.<p>
<p>
Tr. 21 at 141, ln. 1-25.<p>
Cleared from the "policy" restraints imposed on him by his sponsor, Dr. Thayer
recognized that secondary particles from SOX emissions have real effects:
"<i>The damages are the damages."</i>  As Dr.&nbsp;Thayer did inadvertently,
the Commission should do deliberately:  recognize the actual damages from
sulfur dioxide emissions in this proceeding and subsequently consider in
specific instances if and how allowance trading may call for adjustments.<p>
	The position urged by MPCA is expressed in Mr. McCarron's Rebuttal, Exh. 163
at 3 - 5.  It is to consider "environmental costs" without engaging in the
economists' debate over "internalization."<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn74">[79]</a>  However, if the Commission wishes to
examine allowance trading in relation to the internalization concept, it should
follow the analysis at pages 5 - 7 of the McCarron Rebuttal.  Since there is
only the chance possibility that prices of allowances and the damages resulting
from new SO2 sources will coincide, the best economic niche for the allowances
is the concept of "partial internalization."<a
href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn75">[80]</a>  Based on the recent creation of the
trading system and the lack of any information on its actual workings in the
record,<a href="pcabrf1_fn.html#fn76">[81]</a> the most that should be
concluded at this stage is that there may be partial internalization of some
portion of residual damages by allowance payments.  The Commission should go no
further at present.  It should defer to actual cases the application of any
allowance payment offsets to the SO2 values developed in this already
protracted proceeding.<p>
<b>VI.	CONCLUSION</b><p>
<b></b>	The table below summarizes the MPCA's recommendations for ranges of
environmental costs to be established by the Commission.  Also shown for
comparison are the Interim Values adopted by the Commission on March&nbsp;1,
1994.<b></b><p>
<b></b>

<pre>
Pollutant             LOCALE                MPCA VALUES           INTERIM VALUES        
                                            $/TON                 $/TON                 
                                                                                        
 SO2                   rural  fringe         &gt;21  &gt;54  &gt;126        0-300  0-300  0-300  
                      urban                                                             
 PM10                  rural  fringe         562-855  1987-2866    166.60-2380.00       
                      urban                 4462-6423             166.60-2380.00  166   
                                                                  60-2380.00            
