<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>REPLY BRIEF OF THE MN POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY</title></head><body>
<CENTER>BEFORE THE MINNESOTA OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE
HEARINGS<BR>
	100 Washington Square, Suite 1700<BR>
	Minneapolis, Minnesota 55401-2138<BR>
<p>
	FOR THE MINNESOTA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION<BR>
	121 Seventh Place East, Suite 350<BR>
	St. Paul, Minnesota 55105-2147<BR>
<p>
	MPUC Docket No. E-999/CI-93-583<BR>
	OAH Docket No. 6-2500-8632-2<p>
<p>
	In the Matter of the<BR>
	Quantification of Environmental Costs<BR>
	Pursuant to Laws of Minnesota 1993,<BR>
	Chapter 356, Section 3<BR></CENTER>

<p>
<B>REPLY BRIEF OF THE MINNESOTA POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY<BR>
ON SUBSTANTIVE ISSUES</B>
<P>

<b>I.	BURDEN OF
PROOF: THE COMMISSION IS NOT REQUIRED TO PROVE COSTS BY A PREPONDERANCE OF THE
EVIDENCE; THE COMMISSION SHOULD CHOOSE THE "BEST ESTIMATE" OF COSTS THAT CAN BE
PRACTICABLY MADE BASED ON THE RECORD.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Application of a Preponderance Of The Evidence Test To The Commission Is
Inconsistent With the Statutory Requirement To Establish Values To The Extent
Practicable.</b><p>
<b></b>	Several parties in their initial briefs argue that under the rules of
the Office of Administrative Hearings (OAH) the Public Utilities Commission
(Commission) cannot adopt values unless it (or the parties advocating values)
can prove those values by a preponderance of the evidence.  LEC Initial Brief
at 4;<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a> North Dakota (ND) Initial Brief at
24; CEED Initial Brief at 3.  As we have shown in our Initial Brief, such a
simplistic application of the OAH's burden and standard of proof requirements
overlooks the fact that the Commission is acting under a statutory mandate to
quantify costs.  MPCA Initial Brief at 1-3.  The fact that the Commission chose
to establish the necessary record using a contested case proceeding does not
change the underlying substantive law.  To apply the proof requirements of
Minn. R. 1400.7300, subp. 5 (1995) to the Commission's decision (or to the
parties advocating values), despite the clear language of the OAH rule limiting
its application where substantive law provides other burdens or standards,
would be to elevate form over function.  Despite its procedural footing, this
case is about the implementation of a legislative mandate by an administrative
agency.  As such, the Commission needs only to meet the standards of
reasonableness traditionally applied to administrative action, namely, that it
be based on substantial evidence and/or not be arbitrary and capricious.  And,
as we argued in our Initial Brief, if the Commission can adopt values that meet
these deferential standards of review, the values are by definition
"practicable" and must be adopted.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>B.	The Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) And The Commission Should Apply A
"Best Estimate" Approach To Estimating Environmental Costs, Consistent With The
Commission's Planning Function And The Treatment Of Direct Costs; The
"Zero-Default" Approach Advocated By Several Parties Creates A Built-In Bias In
Favor Of Underestimating Costs.</b><p>
<p>
<b>1.	The Commission should apply a best-estimate approach to the estimation of
environmental costs, consistent with its approach toward estimating uncertain
direct costs.</b><p>
	Explicitly, in their discussions of the burden of proof, and implicitly in
their criticisms of proposed values, some parties argue that unless each link
in a chain of cost valuation can be proven by a preponderance of the evidence,
the Commission should decline to quantify the cost and essentially assume it is
zero for planning purposes.  See e.g., Western Fuels Initial Brief at 1-3.  We
urge the ALJ and the Commission to recognize that this approach builds in a
substantial bias in favor of underestimating environmental costs, which is not
supported by the language of the law, by the legislative intent, or by economic
theory, and which is inconsistent with the way the Commission treats uncertain
direct costs in its resource planning process.  <p>
	Arguing that environmental costs should be assumed to be zero unless their
precise value can be proven by a preponderance of the evidence is similar to
arguing that since the Commission cannot be completely certain what the future
fuel costs or labor costs of a proposed power plant would be, it should assume
they will be zero and just ignore these costs in resource planning.  Such an
approach to planning, which might be called the "zero default" approach, would
of course be absurd and reckless. Even though we do not know what these direct
costs would be exactly, we do know they will probably exist within certain
ranges, that they will certainly not be zero, and that there are ways of
estimating them that will aid the planning process.  We know it does not serve
the public interest to ignore such costs just because they are hard to
estimate.  It makes far more sense to take what we have called the "best
estimate" approach:  that is, to look at all the evidence about what the costs
are likely to be, choose the most likely costs or range of costs based on that
evidence, and plan accordingly, with the ongoing recognition that assumptions
have been made in the planning process that could prove to be wrong.  <p>
	The same can be said for environmental costs.  When trying to predict the
resource choices most in the long-term public interest (broadly defined by the
legislature to include environmental and other considerations) the ALJ and
Commission should not take the "zero default" approach assuming costs to be
zero until their precise level can be proven.  Rather, the ALJ and Commission
should take the same "best estimate" approach taken in projecting uncertain
future direct costs:  look at all the evidence of costs in the record and make
their best estimate of environmental costs based on it.  To the extent those
environmental cost estimates reflect uncertainties, those uncertainties should
be kept in mind as the Commission applies the costs in future resource planning
proceedings and balances them against other costs which may involve similar
degrees of uncertainty.<p>
	The MPCA does not expect that environmental costs will ever be approached in
exactly the same way as uncertain direct costs.  We recognize that in many
cases the very existence of an environmental cost is more subtle and difficult
to identify than most categories of direct costs.  However, once there is
evidence that the environmental cost exists, the Commission should attempt to
arrive at the best estimate of where it lies. <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>2.	Economic theory supports the use of the best-estimate approach over the
zero-default approach.</b><p>
    <b>	</b>Not only is the "best estimate" approach more consistent with the
Commission's treatment of uncertain direct costs, it is supported by economic
theory.  In the paper by David Brookshire "Issues Regarding Benefits Transfer"
attached to the surrebuttal testimony of Mr.&nbsp;McCarron, Dr.&nbsp;Brookshire
rebuts "the argument that we cannot undertake a policy response without knowing
the exact nature of the functional relationship," by referencing studies
demonstrating that "in the absence of perfect information, correcting a
distortion will always improve social welfare in an expected value sense.
<u>Decisions based on even imperfect information, as from a benefits transfer,
are superior to no decisions</u>."  Attached to Exh. 165 at 6-7 (emphasis
added); also quoted in McCarron Surrebuttal, Exh. 165 at 9.  In other words, it
does not serve the interests of economic efficiency to sit back and refuse to
try to estimate costs, despite evidence showing they exist, until those
estimates can be made on perfect information.  Such an approach, based on an
excessive concern to avoid overestimating costs, establishes a pervasive bias
in favor of underestimating them.  McCarron Rebuttal, Exh. 163 at 22.  <p>
	It is also important to keep in mind that economists are more willing to make
estimates on the basis of imperfect information when the goal is to inform
policy decisions, as opposed to, for example, calculating compensable damages
such as in a litigation context.  McCarron Surrebuttal, Exh. 165 at 8-10.  Dr.
Desvousges himself authored a paper which summarized the conclusions reached by
members of a benefits transfer case study at a 1992 workshop of environmental
economists.  Despite the fact that "most members were reluctant to adopt the
transfer methodology when litigation was involved," the paper went on to say
that "none of our group members expressed serious concerns about using transfer
studies in a policy related context."  Tr. 17 at 14, ln. 22 to p. 15, ln. 10.
While the topic of Dr. Desvousges' paper and of the Brookshire paper discussed
above was benefits transfer, their findings support the larger point that
estimates based on imperfect information can be of use in policymaking.  As
Mr.&nbsp;McCarron testified and as we have argued in earlier briefing, the
values in this proceeding are to be used to inform subsequent policy choices;
they will not result in the sort of automatic and identifiable monetary
transfers which under the Brookshire and Desvousges papers would demand the
highest levels of certainty.  McCarron Surrebuttal, Exh. 165 at 9-10;  MPCA
Initial Brief at 4-5.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>3.	Nothing in the statute or the legislative history supports the use of the
zero-default approach.</b><p>
	Finally, we note that there is nothing in the statute or the legislative
history that would compel the use of the zero-default approach to estimating
environmental costs over the more sensible and economically sound best estimate
approach used for projecting direct costs.  We note that the legislature
clearly intended that the environmental cost values would be "estimates", and
referred to them as such in Minn. Stat. [[section]] 216B.2422, subd. 5 (1994)
(requiring utilities to use "the environmental cost estimates determined under
subdivision 3" in evaluating bids).  As we discuss more fully in our Initial
Brief at 13 to 15, one of the reasons that the Senate sponsor proposed this
legislation was because the Commission had been unable to quantify costs under
the previous law due to disputes over how it should be done.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a>  The purpose of the legislation was not to
increase the burden the Commission would have to meet before it could quantify
costs.  On the contrary, the Senate sponsor stated on the Senate floor that the
language of section 216B.2422, subd. 3 "would make it <i>easier </i>for the
Commission to quantify and establish a range of environmental costs associated
with each method of generation."<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a>  The ALJ
and the Commission should not now make it more difficult to quantify
environmental costs by adopting the zero-default approach advocated by some
parties to this proceeding.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>II.	THE ALJ AND THE COMMISSION SHOULD REJECT THE ADDITIONAL UNSUPPORTED
LEGAL REQUIREMENTS MANY PARTIES ARE CLAIMING APPLY TO THIS PROCEEDING. </b><p>
	As this proceeding approaches in magnitude of the record dimensions only
imagined by Charles Dickens, most counsel can recite in their sleep the brief
statutory directive from which all the testimony and argument spring: <p>
<p>
The Commission shall, to the extent practicable, quantify and establish a range
of environmental costs associated with each method of electricity generation.<p>
Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 3(a).  Early in the case a number
of parties, generally in disagreement with the legislative judgment underlying
the cited statute or at least opposed to establishment of any non-zero values,
focused on the word "practicable" in urging first the Administrative Law Judge
and then, after certification, the Commission to hear the litany of practical
difficulties that would follow from application of any positive values
developed here.  The ALJ and the Commission have made clear that future
possible applications of the environmental cost values which may be established
have no relevancy to the "practicability" of establishing values,<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a> and the ALJ has been extremely generous in
permitting such testimony into the record for the sole purpose of subsequent
appellate court consideration of constitutional challenges to the statute.<p>
	The initial briefs of these same parties include several additional legal
requirements they would like the ALJ and Commission to read into the statute,
all making it more difficult for the Commission to adopt values.  As we show
below, these additional requirements are as unsupported as the "practicability"
interpretation advanced earlier, and should similarly be rejected. <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Nothing In The Statute Excludes Costs That Occur Outside Of Minnesota
From the Requirement To Quantify Costs; Quantifying Costs Regardless of Where
They Occur Is Required By the Law And Is Fully Within The Commission's
Authority. </b><p>
	Several parties in their Initial Briefs continue to argue that the Commission
is not required, and is indeed not allowed, to quantify the costs of
electricity generation if they occur outside the boundaries of the state.
E.g., LEC Initial Brief at 26-32; NSP Initial Brief at 22-23; MP Initial Brief
at 37.  We addressed this issue in detail in the evidentiary round of briefing.
Joint Reply Brief of MPCA and Environmental Coalition on Evidentiary Issues
(Oct. 6, 1995) at 6-21.  We refer the ALJ and the Commission to that brief, in
which we show that consideration of the extraterritorial consequences of
electricity generated for Minnesotans is (1) required by the statute,
(2)&nbsp;supported by the legislative history, (3) entirely consistent with
Minnesota's approach to environmental harms in a variety of other contexts
(such as chlorofluorocarbons, acid rain, and mercury), (4) in no way prevented
by the Commerce Clause, and (5) well within the state's police powers.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.	Reading an exclusion of non-Minnesotan costs into the statute violates
the plain language of the law, is inconsistent with the legislative history,
and is inconsistent with the State's policy requiring recognition of the global
nature of environmental problems.</b><p>
	On the issue of whether an exclusion for out-of-state costs should be read
into section 216B.2422, subd. 3(a), we refer the ALJ and Commission to our
earlier brief where we show the completely unfounded nature of such an
exclusion.  Joint Reply Brief of MPCA and Environmental Coalition on
Evidentiary Issues (Oct. 6,1995) at 6-10.  LEC asserts that the general
legislative finding in Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;216B.01 somehow compels the
exclusion of out-of-state costs from this proceeding.  LEC Initial Brief at 27.
This assertion is not supported by the language of that section, which says
nothing about whether or not the legislature believes that Minnesota has a
legitimate interest in considering the extraterritorial environmental
consequences of its resource decisions before it makes them.<p>
	The provisions of the Environmental Policy Act, Minn. Stat. ch. 116D, provide
much more guidance on whether the statute should be read to require the
Commission to focus solely on in-state costs.  The Act requires that "to the
fullest extent practicable, the policies, rules and public laws of the state
shall be interpreted and administered according to the policies" expressed in
the Act.  Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;116D.03, subd. 1.  One of those policies
is: <p>
<p>
All departments and agencies of the state government shall:<p>
			. . .<p>
(e) Recognize the worldwide and long range character of environmental
problems<i> </i>and, where consistent with the policy of the state, lend
appropriate support to initiatives, resolutions, and programs designed to
maximize interstate, national and international cooperation in anticipating and
preventing a decline in the quality of the world environment.  <p>
Minn. Stat. [[section]] 116D.03, subd. 2.  Reading an unstated exclusion of
out-of-state costs into the quantification requirement would be to deny and
ignore the worldwide and long range character of energy related environmental
costs and would be flatly inconsistent with the Commission's obligation under
this provision of the Environmental Policy Act.  The Commission certainly would
not be lending "appropriate support" to programs designed to prevent a decline
in the quality of the world environment and would not be promoting interstate,
national and international cooperation by adopting a policy that would prevent
it from considering the out-of-state environmental consequences of Minnesota's
energy decisions.<p>
	Chapter 116D also requires the submission to the legislature of an "Energy and
Environmental Strategy Report" every two years.  Minn. Stat. [[section]]
116D.10.  The report must be sufficiently comprehensive to "assist the
legislature in allocating funds to support all of the policies, plans, and
programs of the state related to energy and the environment" and must include a
"concise, comprehensive discussion of state, and, as applicable, national and
global energy and environmental problems," specifically mentioning water
pollution and atmospheric changes among other listed environmental problems.
<u>Id.</u>, subitem (1).  While the elements of the "Energy and Environmental
Strategy Report" do not directly control the scope of this proceeding, they
make it clear that the legislature believes it can best legislate if it
understands the status of not just local but national and global environmental
problems.  It cannot reasonably be assumed that while the legislature feels
that understanding global environmental problems will improve its own
legislative policymaking, it intends that the Commission ignore global
environmental costs in its administrative policymaking.  <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>2.  	The Commission is not exceeding its authority by considering the
extraterritorial environmental consequences of it resource planning
decisions.</b><p>
	On the issue of whether Minnesota is legally prevented from considering the
extraterritorial environmental costs of its actions, we refer the ALJ and the
Commission to the case law discussed in earlier briefing,<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn4">[5]</a> demonstrating that not only may states
<i>consider</i> the environmental costs they impose on others, they may adopt
laws designed to minimize those costs.  <u>Proctor and Gamble Co. v. City of
Chicago</u>, 509 F.2d 69 (7th Cir. 1975), <i>cert. denied,</i> 421 U.S. 978, 95
S.Ct. 1980 (1975); <u>Cresenzi Bird Importers, Inc. v. State of N.Y.</u>, 658
F. Supp. 1441 (S.D.N.Y. 1987), <i>affirmed</i> 831 F.2d 410 (2d. Cir. 1987).
<u>Palladio v. Diamond</u>, 321 F. Supp. 630, 635 (S.D.N.Y. 1970),
<i>aff'd</i>, 440 F.2d 1319 (2d Cir. 1971), <i>cert. denied</i>, 404 U.S. 983,
92 S.Ct. 446 (1971); <u>A.E. Nettleton Co. v. Diamond</u>, 27 N.Y.2d 182, 264
N.E.2d 118, 315 N.Y.S.2d 625 (N.Y. 1970), <i>appeal dismissed sub nom.
</i><u>Reptile Products Assn. v. Diamond</u>, 401 U.S. 969, 91 S.Ct. 1201
(1970). <p>
	No party has been able to convincingly distinguish between these cases and the
current case.  North Dakota and LEC attempt to do so, but their arguments are
unpersuasive.  ND Initial Brief at 45-46; LEC Initial Brief at 49-51.  North
Dakota argues that while the birds and skins of endangered species regulated by
the New York line of cases can be regulated at the border, electrons cannot be
stopped at the border to see how they have been generated.  This argument fails
for two reasons.  First, it only applies to out-of-state generation, not
in-state generation.  As for in-state generation, there will be no difficulty
determining how the electrons were generated.  Second, it goes to the issue of
how the values will be applied, making specific assumptions about whether they
will be enforceable, and as such the argument is premature.  <p>
	Both North Dakota and LEC attempt to distinguish the electricity market from
the detergent market discussed in <u>Proctor and Gamble</u>.  Actually, the
plaintiff in <u>Proctor and Gamble</u> based its objections to the City of
Chicago's phosphate ban on arguments very similar to those raised by North
Dakota and LEC in this proceeding: namely, that the ban interfered with the
company's ability to supply a six-state area because of production limitations,
<u>Proctor and Gamble</u>, 509 F.2d at 77; that the industry might be subject
to conflicting regulations from other jurisdictions, <u>Id.</u>; and that the
industry's four-state warehousing system meant that the ban would have the
extraterritorial effect of depriving many people outside of Chicago of
phosphate detergent.  <u>Id.</u> at 78.  The court nonetheless held that
Chicago was acting within its authority in banning phosphates, and similarly,
the Commission would be acting within its authority in quantifying the
extraterritorial consequences of Minnesota's energy decisions.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn5">[6]</a> <p>
	 Reasonable minds may differ on how much extra money we Minnesotans should
someday spend for the purpose of  reducing the extraterritorial environmental
consequences of our electric resource decisions.  However, this is not the
issue in this proceeding.  When the Commission applies these values as part of
its consideration of actual resource options, it can and should consider that
question.  At this point, the MPCA is simply arguing that the Commission must
include in its quantification the extraterritorial environmental costs so that
the Commission is at least capable of considering them and balancing them
against other factors in those future proceedings.  Conversely, LEC, NSP and
others are not merely arguing that the Commission should never take action in
future proceedings to minimize extraterritorial costs, they are arguing that
the Commission should not even be able to <i>consider</i> those
extraterritorial costs.  Indeed, they are arguing that it would be illegal for
the Commission to do so.  As we have shown, this narrow construction of what
the Commission can consider in determining how best to serve the public
interest is completely without merit.  The Commission should not be forced to
make important long-term resource decisions while blinded to their
extraterritorial environmental consequences.  This is particularly true when
the extraterritorial effects are as great as the evidence shows they are for
mercury and carbon dioxide.<p>
<b>B.	The Statute Does Not Require A Showing That Costs Are Attributable Solely
To Electric Utilities, As Distinct From Other Pollution Sources.</b> <p>
	Several parties in their initial briefs tie their wagons to the statutory
phrase "associated with each method of electricity generation" to argue that an
environmental cost should be recognized only if (1) every inch of the path from
electric utility plant emission to the harmed receptor is defined in precise
detail and (2) the harm to the receptor is demonstrated to be wholly from the
utility plant emission, without regard to other natural or man-made sources of
the pollutant which also affect the receptor.  An example of this argument can
be found in Otter Tail Power's Initial Brief at 25-45, in which rejection of
all values for criteria pollutants proposed by MPCA and by Northern State Power
(NSP) is urged, <u>inter alia</u>, because those proponents have failed to
distinguish between emissions from all sources and those associated with
electrical generation.  Another example can be found in CEED's Initial Brief at
8-12, arguing against the mercury values proposed by MPCA and the Environmental
Coalition (EC) because those parties have <i>only</i> shown that coal-fired
plants emit mercury to the atmosphere; that most of the mercury emitted is
cycled on a regional or global scale; and that subsequent atmospheric
deposition of mercury leads to its bioaccumulation in living organisms and
resulting environmental damage.  This showing, according to CEED, is
statutorily lacking because  the costs are "not `associated with electricity
generation.'" <u>Id.</u><p>
	As discussed in our Initial Brief at 7-15, there is nothing in the statute,
the legislative history, or the case law establishing the kinds of proof
requirements advanced by these parties.  On the contrary, a long line of state
and federal case law makes it clear that agencies must, and routinely do, adopt
health and safety regulations that may address only one source of a problem or
that may be based on incomplete and conflicting scientific data.  These
agencies are allowed to formulate solutions to the best of their abilities
based on available information, theoretical projections, and their own policy
judgments.  MPCA Initial Brief at 7 - 12.  In the case of <u>Ethyl Corp. v.
EPA,</u> 541 F.2d 1 (D.C. Cir. 1976), <u>cert. denied</u>, 426 U.S. 941, 96
S.Ct. 2662 (1976), the court upheld the EPA's adoption of a rule requiring
annual reductions of the lead content of gasoline, despite acknowledging
industry's objection that given the multiple sources of lead to which humans
were exposed, it was virtually impossible to isolate the effects of lead from
gasoline.  <u>Ethyl</u>, 541 F.2d at 9. The Commission, as it develops tools to
use in future planning processes, surely has as much leeway in this regard as
agencies actually adopting regulations imposing immediate costs on industry and
consumers.  <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>C.	The Statute Does Not Impose An "All-Or-Nothing" Requirement To Either
Quantify At This Time All Costs Associated Will All Methods Of Electricity
Generation Or None Of Them.  Even If The Commission May Soon Need To Quantify
Costs For Other Methods Of Generation, That Need Does Not Justify Disregarding
The Values Developed Here.</b><p>
	Other "gloss" applied to the straightforward statutory mandate can be found in
the post-hearing briefs of the State of North Dakota and of LEC.  They
essentially argue that it is unfair in this proceeding to quantify values for
air pollution resulting from burning fossil fuels unless equal scrutiny is
given to all other methods of generation.  ND Initial Brief at 5-12; LEC
Initial Brief at 5-11.  The MPCA believes this argument to be meritless for the
reasons being set forth by the Office of the Attorney General in its reply
brief.  We simply emphasize here two important points.  First, it is quite
reasonable to quantify in this proceeding the most obvious costs (air
pollution) associated with the most common methods of electricity used in
Minnesota (burning of fossil fuels).  Second, if North Dakota and LEC correctly
predict that the Commission will soon have to quantify the costs of nuclear and
renewable energy sources, the remedy would not be to simply disregard the
progress toward quantification already made in this lengthy and expensive
proceeding; rather, the Commission would be required to take an additional look
at those other costs, either in a subsequent generic cost proceeding or in the
context of individual resource plans where site specific information would be
available. <p>
<p>
<b>III.	THE COMMISSION SHOULD ADOPT THE MPCA'S PROPOSED RANGE OF COSTS FOR
CARBON DIOXIDE.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A. 	The Carbon Dioxide Values Proposed By The MPCA Are Reasonable And Useful
Estimates Based On Substantial Evidence.</b><p>
<b></b>	In our Initial Brief at pages 35 to 43 we demonstrate that it is indeed
practicable to quantify the environmental costs associated with CO2, and we
propose values that are reasonable, supported by substantial evidence, and
useful to the Commission in its planning process.  Western Fuels raises many
objections to these values, to which we respond here.  In several respects,
Western Fuels blatantly mischaracterizes and/or misunderstands the MPCA's
calculation or the underlying evidence, and thus we urge the ALJ and the
Commission to keep an eye on the record when considering our proposed values
and Western Fuels' criticisms of them.  However, in certain other respects the
differences between Western Fuels' position and our own are simply reflections
of different underlying tolerances for uncertainty, and different assumptions
about what should be done in the face of that uncertainty.  <p>
	This different philosophical approach is illustrated by Western Fuels' point
that the seriousness of the resource decisions that will be affected by this
docket preclude the use of speculation in establishing values.  WFA Initial
Brief at 2.  However, as we have argued, resource planning <i>inherently</i>
involves making predictions about the future, and given the importance of both
the resource decisions and their environmental consequences, it would be
imprudent to undertake those predictions without first obtaining as much
information as possible about the consequences of the resource decisions.  In
other words, the Commission and the State of Minnesota do not have the luxury
of refraining from "guessing" in this context; failure to establish a value is
simply a "guess" that the value is zero, and if wrong, it may lead to
irretrievable resource commitments not in society's best interests.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn6">[7]</a> <p>
	Western Fuels points out that the Commission would be the first regulatory
agency to adopt values for CO2 using the methodology proposed.  WFA Initial
Brief at 5.  Ironically, Western Fuels references for this point the Table
appended to the testimony of Dr. Bernow, which shows that several states have
adopted values, largely in the range of those proposed by the MPCA, using the
"control cost" methodology.  Bernow Direct, Exh. 111, attached report at Table
1.  The control cost methodology used in these other states has been condemned
by economists in this proceeding as inferior to the damage cost methodology
that underlies the MPCA's CO2 calculations.  Harrison Direct, Exh. 8, attached
report at 22; Brocket Direct, Exh. 37 at 17.  Moreover, Oregon and perhaps
other states have used the inferior control cost methodology not just to inform
planning decisions, but to establish cost adders.  Bernow Direct, Exh. 111,
attached report at 18.  As mentioned in our "best estimate" and benefit
transfer discussions, when values are going to automatically result in the
actual transfer of dollars such as in an adder context -- as opposed to simply
being used to inform a policy-making process where the uncertainties underlying
the values can be appropriately considered -- economic theory would require an
even greater level of certainty.  In other words, other states have established
substantial CO2 values using methods inferior to the method relied on by MPCA
in this proceeding, and at least one has applied those values in a context that
calls for a greater level of certainty than what is called for in this
proceeding.  All in all, reviewing the actions of other states (which we note
were cited with approval in the legislative history<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn7">[8]</a>) strongly supports the reasonableness of
what the MPCA is asking the Commission to do.    <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.	The MPCA's CO2 values are based on the best estimate warming predictions
of the IPCC and the published estimates of economic costs expected to result
from that warming; Mr. Ciborowski is well-qualified to convey the findings of
the IPCC, which have also been included in the record.</b><p>
<b>	</b>Western Fuels alleges that the fundamental basis of the MPCA's carbon
dioxide values is Mr. Ciborowski's opinion that CO2 emissions are in fact
causing global climate change of a certain character and extent.  WFA Initial
Brief at 6-7.  The suggestion that MPCA's values depend entirely on Mr.
Ciborowski's viewpoint is nonsense.  The fundamental basis of the MPCA's CO2
values is the mid-range warming predictions of the Intergovernmental Panel on
Climate Change (IPCC), and the published cost estimates of economists who have
studied the costs to be expected from those predictions.     <p>
 	WFA also makes the point that the reports of the scientific review panels are
very complex, and so, apparently, the ALJ and Commission cannot learn anything
from them directly or rely in any way on Mr. Ciborowski's relaying of them, but
should instead rely solely on the interpretations of them by the WFA scientific
witnesses.  We have two responses.  First, the reports of the IPCC, while
complex, include summaries explicitly for non-expert policymakers.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn8">[9]</a>   (The MPCA has placed the summaries of the
1990 and 1992 reports, along with the entire 1990 report, into the record.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn9">[10]</a>)  The ALJ and the Commission are themselves
qualified to understand the views of the IPCC, and Mr.&nbsp;Ciborowski -- an
MPCA policy analyst with 13 years professional experience working almost
exclusively on the global warming issue<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn10">[11]</a>
-- is amply qualified to understand and convey the IPCC's findings.  Moreover,
no party in this highly adversarial proceeding has found any example where Mr.
Ciborowski misquoted or mischaracterized the views of the IPCC or any of the
other scientific review panels he cites.<p>
	Second, the scientists sponsored by WFA cannot reasonably be relied on to
interpret the views of the IPCC.  As we showed in our earlier evidentiary
brief, the WFA scientists disagree with the IPCC on most issues pertinent to
this proceeding.  MPCA/Environmental Coalition Additional Evidentiary Motions
and Memorandum (Sept. 8, 1995) at 8-17 and Appendices B-E.  If that were not
true -- if the international scientific community accepted the reassuring
forecasts of the WFA scientists -- global warming would not be an issue in this
case or such a serious concern in the national and international political
arenas.<p>
	  <b></b><p>
<b>2.	The dollar per ton costs are calculated in  straightforward,
well-reasoned manner by a well-qualified MPCA policy analyst.</b><p>
<b>	</b><p>
<b>a.	Mr. Ciborowski's years of training and experience in global warming
public policy make him amply qualified to undertake the calculation underlying
the MPCA's recommended values for carbon dioxide.</b><p>
<b></b>	In order to put the economic cost projections into dollar per ton terms
for this proceeding, the MPCA has undertaken a calculation which is described
in our Initial Brief at 39 and 40, and explained in Mr. Ciborowski's Rebuttal,
Exh. 70 at 39-41.  Western Fuels asserts that Mr.&nbsp;Ciborowski is not
qualified to perform such a calculation.  WFA Initial Brief at 17.  On the
contrary, Mr. Ciborowski's training and experience in global warming policy are
precisely suited to this calculation.  Mr. Ciborowski has an M.A. in public
policy from the Humphrey Institute of Public Affairs.  Mr. Ciborowski's C.V.,
Exh. 87 at 1.  As Mr. Ciborowski testified, part of the training of a policy
analyst is projecting the net present value of a stream of costs into the
future, exactly the task undertaken by Mr. Ciborowski in this proceeding.  Tr.
13 at 56.  We also note that the analysis presented in Table 4 of Mr.
Ciborowski's rebuttal was reviewed by Mr. McCarron, staff economist for the
MPCA.  Tr. 11 at 137, lns. 18-19.  Finally, other parties were able to
scrutinize Mr.&nbsp;Ciborowski's calculations and if they had found any
mathematical errors in the calculations to point them out in surrebuttal or
during cross-examination, and yet the calculations themselves remain
unrebutted.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn11">[12]</a>
	Mr. Ciborowski's specialization in global warming policy makes him
particularly well-qualified to perform this calculation.  His testimony and
publications vividly demonstrate that he has gained a broad understanding of
the science underlying global warming as a necessary part of his work on global
warming policy.  See Mr. Ciborowski's C.V., Exh. 87 and list of writings at
Exh. 86.  When asked to what extent his studies and work as a policy analyst on
the issue of global warming have required him to gain an understanding of the
underlying science, Mr.&nbsp;Ciborowski testified:<p>
<p>
I have worked on this question as a policy analyst, thinking about policy
analysis this question for roughly 13 years.  My work has covered a large
number of areas.  Some of those areas have included assessment of the nature of
the scientific information on the global warming question, the description in
the literature of levels of uncertainty in that information, and a
determination of whether those levels of uncertainty are sufficient to preclude
the treatment of this question in a policy context.  To do that requires, with
regard to the science, a substantial, fairly broad knowledge of the basic
responses of the climate system, the basic information on emissions, emission
sources, rates of accumulation of greenhouse gases, responses of natural
systems to various climate perturbations, and of course, consideration of
effects on humans and unmanaged systems.  That knowledge is, I think, fairly
broad, is not concentrated in any specific area.  As a policy analyst, what you
are interested in is not specific knowledge in any one area, but you're
interested in the general applicability of that information to the question of
the development of policy analysis, the development of information on policy
responses.
 Tr. 13 at 44-45.  In sum, Mr. Ciborowski's immersion in the subject of global
warming for over a decade, studying and tracking all the disciplines pertinent
to policymaking, make him precisely the sort of expert necessary to undertake
the cost calculation underlying the MPCA's proposed CO2 values.  <p>
<p>
<b>b.	The attribution of 1.97deg.C of predicted warming to future emissions of
CO</b>2<b> is a straightforward mathematical calculation based directly on the
findings of the IPCC. </b><p>
	In calculating the warming costs attributable to CO2, Mr. Ciborowski begins
with the IPCC's best-estimate prediction of 4deg.C warming over the next
century assuming business-as-usual emission rates.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn12">[13]</a>  However, this 4deg.C prediction is not
based solely on the warming expected from CO2; the number is a composite of
warming projections for CO2 and the other greenhouse gases.  Moreover, this
figure includes the warming that the IPCC calculates we are already committed
to based on past increases in CO2 concentrations.  Mr. Ciborowski therefore
subtracts from the 4<sup>o</sup>C. total both the warming that the IPCC states
would result from past emissions of CO2 and the warming that the IPCC expects
from past and future emissions of other greenhouse gases.  Thus, instead of
calculating costs based on the 4deg. C. warming predicted for 2100, he
calculates costs only for 1.97deg.C.  <p>
	Western Fuels makes much of this stage of the calculation, attempting to make
it appear to be something more complicated than the straightforward mathematics
that it is.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn13">[14]</a>  WFA Brief at 15-17.
Western Fuels goes so far as to call this step of the calculation an invention
of Mr.&nbsp;Ciborowski's that is "unsupported" by the literature, constituting
Mr. Ciborowski's own "prediction" of what the temperature of the earth would be
a century from now.  <u>Id.</u>  Western Fuels concerns are misplaced and
reflect, at best, a profound misunderstanding of the calculation.  It is in
fact nothing more than a straightforward application of the findings of the
IPCC. <p>
	Use of the 1.97deg.C figure is obviously not, as Western Fuels claims, Mr.
Ciborowski's "prediction" of warming in the future.  It is merely a calculation
of the CO2 portion of the warming projected by the IPCC mid-range
business-as-usual scenario.  In undertaking this step of the calculation, Mr.
Ciborowski did not need to make his own judgment about the relative warming
potentials of the various greenhouse gases, as Western Fuels implies.  He
merely had to separate the 4deg.C warming prediction for total greenhouse gases
into its component parts, using the IPCC's own presentation of the relative
warming it assumed would result from each pollutant. The IPCC (1990) Report
shows that over a period stretching from 1765 to the year 2100, assuming
business-as-usual emission trends, the IPCC assumes that warming attributable
to CO2 will represent 69.1% of warming attributable to all greenhouse gases
(expressed as 6.84 watts per square meter out of total radiative forcing of
9.90 watts per square meter), with the balance of 30.9% attributable to the
other gases.  IPCC 1990 Report, Table 2.7, Scenario A at 57.  To determine the
portion of projected warming expected by the IPCC to result from non-CO2
greenhouse gases, Mr. Ciborowski simply had to calculate approximately 30% of
the projected warming.  Mr. Ciborowski made it clear in his prefiled testimony
and in his cross-examination by Western Fuels that this calculation was based
directly on the IPCC report.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn14">[15]</a>  The
subtraction of warming attributable to past CO2 emissions is similarly
straightforward, and based on IPCC predictions of the warming that would
ultimately result from current concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere.  Tr. 11
at 117, lns. 2-6.  <p>
<b>	</b>Western Fuels also objects that the uncertainty surrounding the
relative warming potential of the various greenhouse gases is reason to abandon
the effort to calculate the costs of CO2.  WFA Initial Brief at 17.  Once
again, this objection is unwarranted, reflecting in this instance a serious
misunderstanding of the nature of the IPCC's warming projection and the
importance of the various greenhouse gases to MPCA's CO2 values.  Western
Fuels' objection would make some sense if the IPCC had somehow started with the
assumption that warming would be 4deg.C by the year 2100 and then worked
backwards to decide what share of the warming should be attributed to each
greenhouse gas.  But of course the IPCC did just the opposite.  It assumed
business-as-usual emissions of the various gases, calculated the warming
expected from each gas, and then aggregated those predictions.  See IPCC 1990
Report, Figure 2.4 and Table 2.7 and accompanying text, at 55-57.  Thus, if the
IPCC underestimated the warming potential of one of the non-CO2 gases, the
ultimate warming for all the gases -- CO2 plus non-CO2 gases -- by 2100 would
be more than 4deg.C.  Similarly, if the IPCC overestimated the warming effects
of the non-CO2 gas, the overall warming for CO2 plus non-CO2 gases by 2100
would be less than 4deg.C.  The important point is that, while the relative
percentage of warming associated with each gas would change, <i>the absolute
amount of warming attributable to carbon dioxide would not change.</i>  Thus,
any flaws that may exist in the IPCC's relative rankings of the various gases
are largely irrelevant to the costs attributable to carbon dioxide.  What
matters for purposes of this calculation is the warming caused by carbon
dioxide itself, and there is no reason to question the IPCC's judgment with
respect to the warming effects of CO2. <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>c.	Given the long-term costs attributable to carbon dioxide emissions, it is
both necessary and appropriate to make predictions about long-term economic
growth.</b><p>
	Finally, as Western Fuels points out, this calculation requires us to make
predictions about the long-term rate of future economic growth.  WFA Initial
Brief at 20.  While we agree with WFA that such projections cannot be made with
certainty, we do not agree that it is impossible to make any meaningful or
rational projections for planning purposes.  Rather, we think it reasonable and
practicable to project the high and low extremes within which growth is likely
to fall over the long run, and this view is shared by the  Environmental
Protection Agency who made these projections in its report to Congress on
global warming, and by the IPCC who makes very similar projections to define a
range of future scenarios.  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 39 and 40 (notes to
Table 4); Tr. 13 at 56, ln. 16 to p. 57, ln. 21; IPCC 1992 Report at 11, Table
1.  As we discussed in our Initial Brief at 29, the IPCC provides the basis for
international treaty negotiations on CO2 reduction policies.  Just as it is
reasonable to make such economic projections to inform policy on these federal
and international levels, it is reasonable to use them to inform state energy
policy.   <p>
	Ultimately, this issue is simply an example of the parties' differing views
toward uncertainty as discussed above.  Western Fuels has not challenged the
range of growth estimates used by the MPCA, the EPA, and the IPCC; they simply
object to making such estimates at all.  In our view, the long-term effects of
the CO2 resulting from today's resource decisions both necessitate and justify
making estimates about the most likely range of long-term economic growth.
Otherwise long-term costs can by definition never be properly scrutinized, even
though their long-term nature means they warrant even greater scrutiny than
short-term costs. <p>
	Finally, we note that making reasoned projections about long-term growth to
facilitate the estimation of long-term costs is consistent with the
responsibility of the entire state government to preserve the environment as
trustee for future generations.  This obligation is imposed on the Commission,
the MPCA, and all other state agencies under the state's Environmental Policy
Act, Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;116D.02, subd. 2, discussed in more detail in
our section on discount rates, below.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>3.  	A projection of global costs of 2% is a reasonable best estimate
supported by substantial evidence.</b><p>
<b>	</b>Western Fuels challenges several aspects of the MPCA's assumption of
global warming costs in the range of 2% of global GDP in its CO2 cost
calculations.  WFA Initial Brief at 21 to 30.  In fact, the record shows that
the MPCA's assumption of global costs of 2% of GDP is a reasonable best
estimate of future costs well-supported by substantial evidence.  Three
economists (Cline, Fankhauser, and Scheraga) have identified a variety of cost
sectors that in aggregate result in costs in the range of 1% of GDP.
Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 24, Table 3.  Economists Cline and Fankhauser
each looked at several costs sectors, and while their estimated costs per
sector vary, they arrived at aggregate estimates of 1.1% and 1.3% of GDP
respectively.  Economist Scheraga looked only at three cost sectors, but still
arrived at a cost estimate of 0.8% of GDP.  <u>Id.</u>  <p>
	Economist Nordhaus only attempted to quantify four cost sectors, but in
recognition of all the costs not addressed he too suggested that overall costs
could be in the range of 1.0% of GDP.  The record shows that Nordhaus has been
criticized for greatly <i>underestimating</i> the costs associated with global
warming.  He personally testified before the Massachusetts Department of Public
Utilities (DPU) in its hearing on carbon dioxide environmental costs, and the
DPU concluded that Nordhaus' method of estimating damages from CO2 was
insufficiently comprehensive.  Bernow Direct, Exh. 111, attached report at 18.
Moreover, Environmental Coalition witness Bernow discusses another published
critique of Nordhaus' work by Morgenstern which argues that reanalysis of an
EPA report relied on by Nordhaus and correction of a mistake in that report
could lead to identifiable costs of 1.5% of U.S. GNP, or six times the damages
in the identified categories estimated by Nordhaus.  <u>Id.</u> at 35.  And
yet, even Nordhaus, with his apparent tendency to underestimate costs, has
offered the estimate that consideration of factors he has not measured could
lead to a cost estimate of 1% (with a reluctantly-offered upper error bound of
2%).  <u>Id.</u><p>
	Because the MPCA's cost estimates are not based solely on Cline's estimates,
and particularly not on any one sector of Cline's estimates, the Western Fuels'
criticisms of particular cost sectors reviewed by Cline are of quite limited
significance.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn15">[16]</a>  Moreover, the criticisms
are misplaced.  For example, Western Fuels argues that we can make no
predictions about the costs of global warming on agriculture because of
uncertainties associated with climate predictions at the regional level.  WFA
Initial Brief at 23 - 27.  Climate predictions at the "regional" level are
indeed less certain than those made at the global level.  However, the larger
the area under consideration, the more reliable the models' predictions are,
and in assessing the impact of climate change on U.S. agriculture generally, as
opposed to for any particular state, we are looking for effects on a scale at
which the models are far more reliable.  When asked whether she agreed that
regional projections of GCMs were not sufficiently reliable, Dr. Margaret
Davis, University of Minnesota Regents Professor, testified:<p>
<p>
If you're talking about a regional scale as a county or maybe a half of
Minnesota, then I would say that the regional scale predictions are not very
accurate.  If you're talking about a region which is a quarter the size of the
United States, then I would say they're doing quite well.<p>
Tr. 12 at 45, lns. 8 -12.  Mr. Ciborowski similarly explained that while
predictions for specific regions are uncertain, we can be more confident about
predictions on the scale of broad latitudinal bands.  Tr. 13 at 151-152.<p>
	Mr. Ciborowski further explained that there are three factors of interest in
determining agricultural response to climate change:  temperature change,
precipitation change, and soil moisture.  Tr. 13 at 82 - 86.  With respect to
temperature change, he notes that based on the GCM results and the climates of
the past, we can be fairly certain that warming in the midlatitudes will be the
same or slightly higher than mean global warming.  Tr. 13 at 83.  Looking next
at precipitation change, the model results do vary in their predictions.  Tr.
13 at 83.  However, from the perspective of agricultural impact, what is most
of interest is not overall precipitation levels but spring and summer soil
moisture levels.  Because of earlier springtime snow-melt and increased
evaporation due to surface heating, even moderate <i>increases</i> in
precipitation lead to <i>decreases</i> in soil moisture.  Tr. 13 at 85.  He
concludes, "if you look at all of the GCM results you have this presumption
toward drying in the summer months and the mid-latitudes generally."  Tr. 13 at
85-86.  Thus, significant costs to the agricultural sector are more likely than
not, supporting the cost projections in this sector by Cline and others.<p>
	WFA has made much of the fact that agriculture in Minnesota may be benefitted
by global warming.  WFA Initial Brief at 26.  Mr. Ciborowski explains in his
testimony that Minnesota may or may not be benefitted depending on future soil
moisture, and explains why is it somewhat more likely that Minnesota
agriculture will be harmed.  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 26.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn16">[17]</a>  However, despite the fact that this is an
issue of obvious concern to Minnesotans, it is not relevant to the MPCA's cost
calculation, which relies on global, not state-only, costs.  Moreover, as WFA
points out, Cline's estimate of U.S. agriculture costs does not include any
costs to Minnesota agriculture because he assumes there would be none.  WFA
Initial Brief at 26, citing Tr. 11, p. 167.  If that assumption is incorrect
and Minnesota agriculture is indeed harmed, as seems more likely, Cline's U.S.
cost estimate for agriculture would of course prove to be somewhat low.<p>
	Finally, as to agriculture, we address the CO2 fertilization effect testified
about by Mr.&nbsp;Idso and emphasized by Western Fuels and North Dakota.  ND
Initial Brief at 41-42; WFA Initial Brief at 42.  The record shows that there
are reasons to be less optimistic about the overall long-term fertilization
effect than these parties are, particularly with respect to forests.  Pastor
Surrebuttal, Exh. 67 at 1-2.  As to agriculture, however, the record shows at
least as to Cline that the effects of CO2 fertilization have already been
assumed in the estimate of agricultural costs.  Tr. 13 at 81-82.  Western Fuels
assertion that the benefits of CO2 fertilization are not reflected in the
studies on which the MPCA relies is simply wrong.  WFA Initial Brief at 42.<p>
	Western Fuels has also criticized the MPCA's assumption that the level of
costs assumed for the United States can be applied to the globe.  However, the
assumption is supported by the work of economists Nordhaus and Fankhauser, who
made global cost estimates of 1 percent and 1.5% of GDP respectively.
Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 26.  Moreover, these cost levels were projected
for the year 2050, <u>id.</u>, before the more severe warming projected for the
latter half of the next century occurs.  IPCC 1990 Report at xxii, Figure 8.
Nordhaus and Fankhauser projected that losses in developing countries would be
about double those experienced in the developed world as a percent of GDP.
Exh. 70 at 27.  It is entirely reasonable for the ALJ and the Commission to
assume, consistent with these studies, that costs on the global level would be
at least equal as a percent of GDP to those identified for the U.S.<p>
	Western Fuels also objects to the MPCA's recommendation that costs be
calculated using Cline's higher damage function of 2% of GDP rather than 1%.
As we discuss above, the MPCA believes that the issue of cost estimation should
be approached using a "best estimate" approach, seeking to establish the values
best supported by the evidence.  Given all the evidence, the 2% damage function
is the more accurate damage projection.  We know that the 1% damage function
excludes many costs which cannot be easily calculated, and Cline himself
projects that inclusion of these costs would raise the estimate to 2% of GDP.
We know that the 1% assumes that warming will be gradual and linear, not in a
more costly pattern with sudden periods of warming.  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.
70 at 25.  However, the evidence shows not only that a non-linear pattern is
possible, it is more likely; the IPCC states that it would not expect the rise
in temperatures to be a steady one.  IPCC 1990 Report at xxii.  We know that
the 1% does not reflect the risk that positive feedbacks from the biosphere
could amplify the warming, a possibility testified to by Dr. Margaret Davis.
Tr. 12 at 58, ln. 15 - p. 59, ln. 5.   And we know that the 1% figure does not
reflect any of the larger risks inherent in making changes of the magnitude
projected to the climate of the world.  See Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at
15-17 and Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 at 13.  For all these reasons, more
fully explained in our Initial Brief at 36-39, it is more reasonable to rely on
Cline's higher damage function of 2% than on his lower damage function of 1%.
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>4.  	It is reasonable to base cost estimates on the "best-estimate" of
climate sensitivity predicted by the IPCC.</b><p>
<b></b>	Western Fuels points out, as we have acknowledged all along, that the
MPCA's range of cost estimates is based on economic estimates which assume the
IPCC mid-range warming scenario.  WFA Initial Brief at 8.  It is quite true
that in calculating costs on this basis, the range does not include the very
lowest possible costs nor very the highest ones.  However, unlike Western
Fuels, we believe it is entirely appropriate and practicable to focus on the
IPCC's best-estimate of warming under the circumstances.  The IPCC selects
2.5deg.C as its best estimate of climate sensitivity taking into account the
model results and the observational evidence of the last century.  IPCC 1990
Report at xxv.  In other words, in the judgment of this eminent group of
international experts, 2.5<sup>o</sup>C represents the most likely measure of
climate sensitivity, and as such it can be reasonably relied on to calculate
the most likely range of costs.<p>
	It is important to realize that in focusing just on the mid-range of climate
sensitivity, the MPCA's recommended values fall very much on the <i>low</i>
side of the larger range of potential costs.  First, even though it is called
the mid-range warming projection, 2.5deg. is obviously somewhat closer to the
low end of the range of 1.5deg.C. than to the high estimate of 4.5deg..  If
climate sensitivity does prove to be at the low end of the IPCC range, at
1.5deg.C., warming at the end of the next century will still be nearly 3deg.C.
warmer than preindustrial levels assuming business-as-usual emission rates,
almost as high as the best-estimate of 4deg.C. warming, assumed by the MPCA
calculation.  IPCC 1990 Report, Figure 8, at xxii.  But more importantly, if
climate sensitivity is at the <i>upper</i> end of the IPCC range, at 4.5deg.C.,
temperatures at the end of the next century would be over 6deg.C. warmer than
preindustrial levels.<i> </i> <u>Id.</u>  <p>
	Second, costs associated with each increment of warming are expected to
increase exponentially with temperature, instead of just according to a linear
function.  The damage function developed by Cline and used in the MPCA's costs
calculations assumes that the identified costs of a 2.5deg.C. warming (1.1% of
GDP) would approximately double with a 4deg.C. warming (to 2 to 3 % of GDP) and
triple with a 5.5deg.C. warming (to 3 to 4 % of GDP).  Ciborowski Rebuttal,
Exh. 70 at 23-24; Tr. 11 at 146.  In other words, if the planet warms by 6deg.C
instead of 4deg.C., we could expect a more than proportional increase in
resulting costs.  Thus, even though we have not calculated the full range of
costs, we know that costs based on the mid-range predictions underestimate
costs at the upper end of the range far more than they overestimate costs at
the low end of the range.<p>
	The fact that a range of costs based on the entire range of possible climate
sensitivities would be larger than the MPCA's proposed cost range does not
justify abandoning the effort to quantify CO2 costs.  Under the circumstances,
it is entirely reasonable for the Commission to adopt the cost range proposed
by the MPCA, which is based on the IPCC's best-estimate of climate sensitivity.
We note that there is nothing in the statute that requires that the Commission
adopt a range that reflects both the lowest and highest possible environmental
costs of an emission.  In this case, it is practicable to establish a range of
values which estimates the most likely costs and which would be informative to
the Commission in future resource planning. <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>5.	Use of a discount rate of 1 or 2 percent is consistent with state policy
to preserve the environment as trustee for future generations.</b><p>
<b></b>	Western Fuels has criticized the MPCA's recommendation of a 1 or 2
percent discount rate in calculating costs, accusing the agency of "feigning
conservatism" and simply picking the discount rate that results in the highest
values.  WFA Initial Brief at 33.  We strongly object to this
mischaracterization of the MPCA's motives and reasoning, and refer the ALJ and
the Commission to our Initial Brief, pages 40 - 42, which explains the true
basis of our choice of the 1 to 2 percent discount rate.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn17">[18]</a>  As we explained, the very long-term,
multi-generational nature of global warming costs makes them fundamentally
unlike other costs to which discount rates are typically applied, and makes the
use of low discount rates only equitable.  We simply add here that the MPCA's
recommended discount rates are entirely consistent with official state
environmental policy, as expressed in the Environmental Policy Act, which
emphasizes the importance of future generations.  The Environmental Policy Act
applies not just to the MPCA, but to the Commission.  It declares that:<p>
<p>
It is the continuing responsibility of the state government to use all
practicable means, consistent with other essential considerations of state
policy, to improve and coordinate state plans, functions, programs and
resources to the end that the state may: <p>
<p>
(a) Fulfill the responsibilities of each generation as trustee of the
environment for succeeding generations;<p>
<p>
Minn. Stat. [[section]] 116D.02, subd. 2 (1994).  <u>See also</u> [[section]]
116D.02, subd. 1.  The Environmental Policy Act goes on to require that to the
fullest extent practicable policies, rules, and laws of the state be
interpreted and administered in accordance with the policies it expresses,
including the obligation to future generations established by the language
quoted above.  Minn. Stat. [[section]] 116D.03, subd. 1.  We urge the ALJ to
recommend, and the Commission to adopt, discount rates in the 1 to 2 percent
range; we believe that higher discount rates would unduly minimize future costs
and be inconsistent with our responsibilities as trustee of the environment for
the generations following us.<p>
<b>B.	The Commission Should Reject The Minority Scientific Opinions Expressed
By The Scientific Witnesses For Western Fuels.</b><p>
<b></b>	Some parties to this proceeding, notably Western Fuels and North
Dakota, discuss the science underlying global warming in such a way as to
greatly exaggerate the scientific uncertainties and minimize the seriousness of
the issue.  WFA Initial Brief at 33 - 43; ND Initial Brief at 25 - 42.  Not
surprisingly, their version of the global warming science is based almost
exclusively on their own scientific witnesses.  As we showed in the evidentiary
round of briefing, the WFA scientists disagree on almost all points of science
pertinent to this proceeding with the judgment of the IPCC.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn18">[19]</a>  We have also demonstrated in earlier
briefing that the IPCC reports must be seen as the definitive statement of the
views of the international scientific community, derived as they are from a
lengthy and open process involving hundreds of scientific experts from around
the world, and given the official recognition of and reliance on the IPCC
reports by the governments of the world in international treaty negotiations.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn19">[20]</a>  <p>
	Witnesses for Western Fuels allege that the IPCC reports should not be relied
on because the IPCC process has been "politicized."  Lindzen Rebuttal, Exh. 54
at 33; Michaels Rebuttal, Exh. 57 at 21-22.  We have explained the groundless
nature of these claims, and the many reasons why it is extremely implausible
that the findings of the IPCC and all the other review panels are simply the
result of politicization.  MPCA/Environmental Coalition Additional Evidentiary
Motions and Memorandum (Sept. 8, 1995) at 2-4 and Appendix A; MPCA Initial
Brief at 29-32.  Moreover, as we noted in earlier briefing, if we are to assume
that the differences in the findings of the IPCC and Western Fuels' scientists
are the result of politics or bias, there is greater reason to be concerned
about the scientific objectivity of the witnesses for Western Fuels.  Both Drs.
Michaels and Balling rely almost entirely on the fossil fuels industry to fund
their global warming work.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn20">[21]</a>  While this
reliance does not entirely preclude the exercise of independent judgment, Dr.
Lindzen himself states, in interpreting the views of one of the authorities he
cites, "if you're utterly dependent for your research support, it would be kind
of unusual to assume it would have no influence."  Tr. 8 at 183, lns. 21-23.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn21">[22]</a>  <p>
	In April of 1992, at about the time the nations of the world were meeting in
Rio&nbsp;de&nbsp;Janeiro and negotiating CO2 reductions based on the
projections of the IPCC, Dr. Lindzen made a speech to OPEC expressing his fears
that policies developed to respond to global warming will have the following
results:<p>
<p>
Wealth will be squandered that could have been used to raise living standards
in much of the world.  Living standards in the developed world will decrease.
Regulatory apparatuses will reflect (sic) individual freedom on an
unprecedented scale.<p>
Tr. 8 at 197.  Given his fears of how the world will respond, it is reasonable
to question whether Dr. Lindzen is capable of bringing complete objectivity to
his assessment of the global warming science.<p>
	However, the ALJ and the Commission need not make any conclusions about the
relative objectivity behind the conflicting science in deciding which view to
accept.  They need only decide whether it is more reasonable to rely on the
scientific judgment of the scientists presented by Western Fuels et al, or the
collective scientific judgment of the IPCC reports and the multiple scientific
review panels preceding them.  See Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;72 at 11.
Under these circumstances, the choice is clear.  The ALJ and Commission should
accept as authoritative the scientific judgment of the IPCC and disregard the
views of the WFA scientists, as they have been disregarded by the majority of
their scientific colleagues.  <p>
<p>
<b>IV.	MERCURY VALUES DEVELOPED BY MPCA THROUGH A CAREFUL BENEFIT TRANSFER
ANALYSIS ARE RELIABLE AND PARTIES ADVOCATING ZERO VALUES HAVE NOT BEEN
SUCCESSFUL IN DISCREDITING THEM</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	The MPCA And The Environmental Coalition Developed Mercury Valuation
Approaches When It Became Clear That No Damage Cost Study For Mercury Would Be
Done For This Proceeding.</b><p>
<b></b>	The MPCA would have preferred that the record in this matter include a
damage cost study of mercury emissions from electric utilities.  Unfortunately,
the legislative initiative which would have provided funding for MPCA to
conduct studies especially for this proceeding was vetoed and the early
indications that the NSP-sponsored TER Report would assess mercury damages did
not prove true.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn22">[23]</a>  At that point both MPCA
and the Environmental Coalition (EC) set out to develop mercury values with the
information and resources available to them.  <p>
	The EC witnesses, drawing on the work of the MPCA's Dr. Edward Swain and
others showing the impact of mercury on Upper Midwest lakes, developed a
proposed mercury value of $50,000,000 per ton (i.e., $25,000/pound).  They
derived this value by estimating the impact that fish advisories, largely
driven by mercury contamination, would have on Minnesota's nearly
$1&nbsp;billion per year recreational fishing industry.  Drawing comparisons
with estimates of damages to Alaska salmon fisheries resulting from the stigma
of the Exxon Valdez spill, they developed<b> </b>a scenario predicting a $225
million loss to Minnesota' s recreational fishing industry.  They attributed
this loss to mercury emissions and then assigned a fraction of the loss
proportionate to the percentage of mercury emissions from coal combustion as
the proposed environmental cost value for mercury emissions from coal-fired
utilities.  EC Initial Brief at 19-20.  The EC buttresses its mercury damages
analysis with testimony elicited from Dr. Desvousges showing that a recent
study he co-authored found among all classes of Wisconsin utility customers a
willingness-to-pay higher electric bills in order to reduce fish consumption
bans, <u>Id.</u> at 17-18, and with testimony from Dr. Julia Brody highlighting
the irreversibility of a decision to construct a new coal-fired power plant
which would emit more of the environmentally persistent mercury.  <u>Id.</u> at
18.  <p>
	The MPCA took a different tack in response to the absence of a damage cost
study for mercury emissions.  As described more fully in the MPCA's Initial
Brief at 49 -54, the MPCA selected certain criteria pollutants from the TER
damage cost study and applied to the TER values for those pollutants a
comparative toxicity ranking system developed in conjunction with University of
Toronto scientists.  This toxicity ranking system, called the "Indexing System"
in the hearing, incorporated toxicological response information for 183
chemicals from databases developed by EPA and occupational safety programs.
For purposes of comparing relative toxicity, it utilized standardized emission
scenarios and did not set up dose-response functions.  See MPCA Initial Brief
at 50, especially notes 49-50 and citations referenced therein.  Because
mercury ranked so high in the Indexing System's ranking, this benefits transfer
analysis produced a high range of values for mercury, from which MPCA selected
its proposed range of $4,379 to $9,781 per pound.  Although derived through
completely different analyses, the MPCA and EC mercury recommendations fall
within the same order of magnitude.<p>
<p>
<b>B.</b>	<b>The Benefit Transfer Methodology Is A Reliable Tool To Employ In
The Absence Of A Damage Cost Study And Was Fairly Applied In This Instance.
</b><p>
<b>	</b>The utilities and coal interest parties have attacked the MPCA
methodology for developing mercury values as unreliable (like "picking a number
out of a hat"<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn23">[24]</a>), as unrelated to health
effects, and as a ruse to impose regulations on mercury emissions which MPCA
could not do under its own authorities.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn24">[25]</a>
These criticisms, as presented in the Initial Briefs of MP and CEED, will be
shown to be unfounded and to provide no basis for rejecting MPCA's proposed
values.<p>
	MP argues that the additional mercury studies funded by the 1995 legislature
highlight the inadequacies of the benefit transfer methodology that MPCA used
"to `bootstrap' and arrive at environmental cost values which they know would
not satisfy a damage cost study, pass a cost benefit analysis or withstand any
sort of scientific scrutiny."  MP Initial Brief at 40.  Implicit in MP's
argument is that damage cost studies following the stringent TER criteria are
the only acceptable tools for environmental costs valuation.  As noted in the
MPCA Initial Brief at 14-15 and above at 5, the legislature intended the
Commission to use all reasonable methods of estimation to develop environmental
cost values.  Benefit transfer is a frequently used tool of economists,<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn25">[26]</a> was employed, for illustration, by TER and
EC in this proceeding;<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn26">[27]</a> and must be
judged in each instance on the quality of the inputs and the applications to be
made.  While a thorough damage cost study may be wished for, the MPCA benefit
transfer used inputs of high quality and can appropriately be applied to this
resource planning process.  The observation discussed above at 3 - 4 in the
burden of proof context, from Dr. Brookshire's paper, is particularly
appropriate here:<p>
<p>
	The argument that we cannot undertake a policy response without knowing the
exact nature of the functional relationship echoes the earlier implication of
the theory of the second best. . . . [Yew-Kwang] Ng demonstrates that, in the
absence of perfect information, correcting a distortion will always improve
social welfare in an expected value sense.  Decisions based on even imperfect
information, as from a benefits transfer, are superior to no decisions.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn27">[28]</a> <p>
	The very high quality of the inputs to the MPCA benefit transfer analysis has
been established through lengthy testimony and cross-examination.  The Indexing
System is fully described in the peer-reviewed publication entered as Exhibit
170, Pratt, Gregory C., et al., "An Indexing System for Comparing Toxic Air
Pollutants Based Upon Their Potential Environmental Impacts,"
<u>Chemosphere</u>, Vol. 27, No. 8 (1993), and was the subject of much of Dr.
Pratt's extensive cross-examination.  Tr. 20 at 8-71 and 107-178.  An
explanation of its function and a selection of issues covered in Dr. Pratt's
live testimony is presented in MPCA's Initial Brief on Values at 49-51.  The
Indexing System was developed in support of regulations for toxic air
emissions<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn28">[29]</a> and was suggested for use in
the setting of fees for pollutant emissions.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn29">[30]</a><p>
	The TER Report has weathered well criticisms from several directions.  As seen
in the subsequent SO2 argument, the heaviest MPCA criticism has been for what
was omitted rather than what was done.  The same MP brief which attacks the
MPCA benefit transfer approach praises TER for "a detailed, comprehensive, and
rigorous, state-of-the-art damage cost externality study."  MP Initial Brief at
16.  The MPCA benefit transfer uses TER's reported damages for the three
pollutants from coal-fired plants which TER ranks the highest in damages.  Exh.
136, V. 7 at 3-6 - 3-8.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn30">[31]</a>  The MPCA
analysis is careful to compare only inhalation-based risks for the three
criteria pollutants and mercury and to modify the results in light of
comparative factors evident from TER's discussions.  MPCA Initial Brief at
52.<p>
	Minnesota Power utilizes testimony presented by CEED witness Dr. Kenny Crump
in an effort to demonstrate the unreliability of the MPCA benefit transfer
analysis.  MP Initial Brief at 43-45; Crump Surrebuttal, Exh. 184 at 6-8.  Dr.
Crump took the carbon monoxide and lead results from TER not used by Mr.
McCarron in his calculations and applied the benefit transfer analysis to them.
Using lead, he arrived at mercury damage values seven orders of magnitude
greater than the MPCA analysis.  Using carbon monoxide, he arrived at mercury
damage values two orders of magnitude lower than the MPCA analysis.  Without
paying attention to Mr.&nbsp;McCarron's prefiled testimony,<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn31">[32]</a> he charged that "Mr. McCarron eliminated
from consideration the estimates of the environmental costs of mercury derived
from lead and carbon monoxide because these estimates were far outside the
range obtained using the other three pollutants."  Exh. 184 at 6.  In fact, Mr.
McCarron's testimony shows that he eliminated lead and carbon monoxide<b><i>
</i>before</b> ever conducting the mercury value calculations because those two
pollutants have such very different ranks in the TER damage study and in the
Indexing System.  Exh. 163 at 34; Tr. 19 at 57, lns. 3-9.  Although such
relationships would be evident to a trained economist such as Mr. McCarron,
they might not be evident to the lay person.  Accordingly, two tables are
presented below which illustrate what Mr. McCarron observed.  The first is the
Indexing System actual values table for "human inhalation only" from McCarron
Rebuttal, Exh. 163 at 31, omitting mercury (since it is not relevant to this
comparison) and reordering the criteria pollutants in order of relative
inhalation risk, and the second is the damages per ton table from Exh. 163 at
33 (based on Table 3-1 in volume 7 of the TER Report).<p>
<p>
<b>[INDEXING SYSTEM VALUES EXCLUDING MERCURY AND RANKED IN ORDER OF INHALATION
VALUES - MODIFIED FROM </b><p>
<b>MCCARRON REBUTTAL, EXH. 163 AT 31]</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>AIR TOXICS INDEX (actual values)</b>

<pre>
         POLLUTANT               INDEX VALUE HUMAN INHALATION ONLY     
                                                                       
Particulate Matter            2.88 x 1010                              
Carbon Monoxide               5.01 x 109                               
Nitrogen oxide                4.68 x 109                               
Sulfur Dioxide                1.29 x 109                               
Lead                          1.74 x 104                               
                                                                       

</pre>
<b></b><p>
<b>[TER DAMAGES FROM EXHIBIT 136 AS PRESENTED IN </b><p>
<b>MCCARRON REBUTTAL, EXH. 163 AT 33]</b><p>
<b></b><p>
DAMAGES PER TON OF POLLUTANT FOR EACH SCENARIO (1993$)<p>


<pre>
POLLUTANT             RURAL SCENARIO        METROPOLITAN          URBAN SCENARIO        
                                            FRINGE                                      
Particulate Matter    $633.00               $2,155.00             4,798.00              
Lead                  401.00                1,7129.00             3,302.00              
Nitrogen oxides       15.00                 54.00                 130.00                
Sulfur dioxide        21.00                 54.00                 126.00                
Carbon monoxide       0.29                  0.99                  1.57                  

</pre>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>(NOx-with-ozone values and 90% confidence intervals not included.)<p>
<p>
As can be seen, the rankings in order of damages or risk are particulate matter
(first), nitrogen oxides (third) and sulfur dioxide (fourth) in each study's
table.  However, in the Indexing System ranking, lead is way at the bottom,
five orders of magnitude lower than the next lowest ranking pollutant; while in
TER's ranking of damages, lead is a close second to particulate matter and more
than an order of magnitude greater than the next ranking pollutant.  Carbon
monoxide exhibits an equally dramatic reversal: holding a close second to
particulate matter in the Indexing System values, but far at the bottom in the
TER damages ranking.<p>
	It was only logical in constructing a model for benefit transfer to avoid a
cookbook approach and to build upon those relationships which show a central
tendency.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn32">[33]</a>  The relationships utilized in
the benefit transfer are valid and provide value ranges useful for resource
planning purposes.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn33">[34]</a>  The Office of the
Attorney General (OAG) has endorsed the MPCA benefit transfer methodology and
proposed slightly lower values based on that methodology.  The ALJ and the
Commission should carefully consider all the proposed mercury values.<p>
	<p>
<b>C.</b>	<b>Through the Toxicological Databases Incorporated In The Indexing
System, Health And Ecological Impacts Of Mercury Emissions Are Brought Into The
Benefit Transfer Analysis</b><p>
<b>	</b>The second prong of the challenge from Minnesota Power and CEED to the
reliability of MPCA's proposed mercury values is that it assumes relationships
"not based in fact,"<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn34">[35]</a> particularly
failing to demonstrate health effects from utilities' mercury emissions.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn35">[36]</a>  These challenges are correct so far as
they assert that neither MPCA nor the Environmental Coalition has submitted a
damage cost study for mercury such as TER has provided for criteria pollutants,
tracking emissions from the smokestack, modeling dispersal, measuring impact on
defined receptors, and then translating those impacts into dollar damages.
Belaboring the obvious--confirming what the proponents of mercury values
acknowledge they do not have to offer--does not detract from the reliable and
serious information on mercury risks that MPCA and EC have shown.  As more
fully set out at pages 43-47 of MPCA's Initial Brief, this unrebutted
information establishes that three-fourths of the mercury found in the
atmosphere in Minnesota is present as a result of human activity (i.e.,
anthropogenic sources); that coal combustion is the largest contributor of
anthropogenic mercury in the state<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn36">[37]</a>; that
once emitted, mercury is persistent in the environment and can be concentrated
many thousand-fold through bioaccumulation; that the largest share of mercury
emitted circulates on a regional/global scale; and that the Minnesota
legislature and Minnesota and federal environmental agencies are engaged in a
multi-faceted effort to understand and reduce mercury's environmental
impacts.<p>
	Minnesota Power's eagerness to discredit the proposed mercury values leads it
to mischaracterize key elements of the risk assessment incorporated within the
MPCA benefit transfer analysis.  At page 45 of its Initial Brief, MP contends
that "the Index is unrelated to the severity and type of health effects."
Review of the Pratt, et al., paper on the Indexing System, Exh. 170, shows to
the contrary that toxicological and occupational safety databases are an
essential building block for the rankings performed by the Indexing System.
While these rankings assumed standardized emission rates, they reflect the
nation's best knowledge of the health risks of airborne mercury.  Thus, they
cannot be said to be "unrelated" to health effects.  MP further
mischaracterizes the Index and the benefit transfer analysis in its critique of
Mr.&nbsp;McCarron's comparison of the TER study and the Indexing System,<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn37">[38]</a> also found on page 45 of MP's Initial
Brief.  MP states: "The Index assumes a linear response function, in which
injuries are the same whether the first pound or thousandth pound of mercury is
emitted."  Again, this characterization misstates and misleads.  Because of the
standardized emission rate used, the Indexing System has no response functions.
It is a snapshot of the 183 pollutants studied, only capturing toxicological
effects for the one, standardized emission rate selected.  Of course, the
toxicological studies on which it draws would necessarily have employed the
response curves that MP's argument goes on to discuss.  Moreover, the extreme
mobility of mercury and its impact on regional and global scales lessen the
importance of knowing the details of each emission.<p>
	The use of the Indexing System, the lack of Minnesota source emissions data
and of ambient mercury levels, and the recognition that MPCA and Environmental
Coalition methodologies are less certain than the type of study performed by
TER for NSP show that the picture of mercury damages is not yet complete.
However, the record does show major ground for concern over potential emissions
from future coal-fired plants that support the ALJ and the Commission in
establishing a range of values for mercury emissions.  The innovative MPCA
combination of TER results and the Indexing System rankings gives the ALJ and
the Commission a useful tool to accomplish that objective.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>D.	Uncertainties Over Atmospheric Transport And Transformation Processes And
Over The Relative Increases In Rates Of Deposition Provide No Grounds For
Delaying Establishment Of Mercury Cost Values.</b><p>
<b>	</b>The CEED Initial Brief at 27-33 and the Minnesota Power Initial Brief
at 46-53 urge that a mercury value not be established because of a number of
uncertainties in current understanding of the transport and transformation of
mercury in the atmosphere, in the revolatilization of mercury deposited to
soils and oceans, and in the relative deposition rate in Minnesota compared to
the rest of the world.  Dr. Edward Swain addressed these uncertainties in his
prefiled testimony.  The first substantive answer in his Surrebuttal explains
why the existing level of uncertainty about the mercury cycle should not impede
establishment of environmental cost values for mercury emissions.  In replying
to issues raised in the rebuttal testimony of MP witness Tim Hagley and CEED
witness Dr. Christian Seigneur, Dr. Swain observed:<p>
<p>
These uncertainties would invalidate efforts to value the cost of mercury
emissions if (1) mercury degraded in the environment and/or (2) dilution
eliminated the environmental damage caused by mercury.  However, because
mercury is an element, it never loses its potential to cause damage once it is
released to the environment.  Because mercury is highly mobile in the
environment, and can revolatilize after deposition, understanding the details
of dispersion and deposition are not important compared to the fact that the
mercury would have remained locked in coal for millions of years if coal
combustion for electrical production had not released it from geological
deposits.  For the purposes of this Proceeding, mercury could be regarded as
somewhat similar to carbon dioxide, in that about half of emissions eventually
join a global pool that can cause damage anywhere (Expert Panel Report [Exh.
228]).<p>
Swain Surrebuttal, Exh.  215 at 2-3.<p>
	Turning to some of the specific uncertainties raised in the cited briefs, MP
implies that electric utilities' contribution to atmospheric mercury is
overestimated because of emissions from soils and oceans.  As the quoted
passage from Dr. Swain's Surrebuttal notes, mercury is highly persistent and
highly mobile; it can be deposited and then re-emitted many times over.  It
must be remembered that most of the mercury in this "ping-pong" cycle was added
to the atmosphere as the result of human activity.  As capsulized in Dr.
Swain's Surrebuttal, the mercury released when coal is burned "otherwise would
have remained buried in the earth for millions of years."<p>
	MP, as well as CEED, dispute Dr. Swain's claim that since industrialization
the increase in mercury deposition in the Upper Midwest has been greater than
the world-wide increase in mercury emissions over the same period.  Their
criticism is in error because they ignore the components of increased global
mercury emissions that are deposited locally and regionally.  The consensus
Expert Panel Report, Exh. 228, explains the pattern of atmospheric mercury
deposition:<p>
<p>
The most recent global cycle models indicate that about half of the
anthropogenic mercury  emissions are deposited within a local or regional-scale
area about the emission source.  This is usually within a thousand
kilometers[<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn38">[39]</a>], however it is dependent on
the specific topographical and meteorological regime in the emission area as
well as the chemical and physical characteristics of the emissions.  Data on
historical deposition in lake and peat sediments are consistent with recent
estimates that global atmospheric concentrations of mercury have increased by a
factor of about three since pre-industrial times.  Greater increases could have
occurred in localized/regional situations.<p>
<p>
Exh. 228 at iv.  Thus, the Expert Panel estimated global increase in deposition
at a rate 3.0 times pre-industrial levels.  Dr. Swain's reported observation of
3.4 times pre-industrial levels in the Upper Midwest suggests that Minnesota is
one of the areas with a regionally elevated deposition pattern.  Swain Direct,
Exh. 213 at 7.<p>
	While there are uncertainties about the environmental behavior of mercury,
they should not distract the ALJ and the Commission from the damages of mercury
emissions.  As Dr. Swain noted: "The environmental damage that mercury causes
is not altered by whether we know precisely what facility emits what amount of
mercury; mercury contamination is a real cost that occurs whether we have
studied it and understand it in all its detail."  Swain Surrebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;215 at 2.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>E.	CEED And Minnesota Power Are Wrong In Arguing That MPCA Is Seeking To
Have The Commission Do Its Work By Imposing Mercury Regulations On Utilities.
</b><p>
<b>	</b>CEED argues that it is unconstitutional and inappropriate for the
Commission to adopt mercury values.  Couched as an "unlawful delegation" to an
agency not equipped to impose environmental regulations, CEED's argument has
constitutional, policy, and credibility facets.  CEED Initial Brief at 5-7,
26-27, 36-37.  Minnesota Power echoes CEED's argument: "[MPCA staff] are asking
the Commission to do what they know they do not have enough information to do:
regulate utility mercury emissions."  MP Initial Brief at 39.  The
constitutional and policy arguments fall of their own weight; neither the ALJ
nor the Commission are free to reject the legislative wisdom behind the
environmental costs statute.  The challenge to MPCA's credibility and motives
deserves a further response.<p>
	CEED and MP charge that MPCA is singing one tune to the legislature and
another to the ALJ and the Commission.  CEED Initial Brief at 26-27; MP Initial
Brief at 46.  In fact, there is no inconsistency in MPCA both urging that
mercury values be established in this proceeding and explaining to the
legislature that further information is needed before the Agency is prepared to
regulate specific mercury air emission sources.  During cross-examination, Dr.
Swain stated that MPCA had not proposed limits for mercury emissions from
coal-fired power plants because of insufficient data<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn39">[40]</a> and that the 1994 MPCA report "Strategies
for Mercury Control in Minnesota"  recommended a number of areas for additional
research needed to implement mercury reduction strategies.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn40">[41]</a>  On re-direct examination, Dr. Swain
explained that many more pieces of information were needed to develop a
state-wide mercury emissions reduction program than were needed to develop the
general environmental costs of mercury emissions.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn41">[42]</a>  For example, cost, efficiency and
reliability information on control strategies were needed for the reduction
program in order to "reduce mercury emissions at the lowest cost for society,"
but such information was not necessary to estimate emission costs.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn42">[43]</a>  <p>
	In general, MPCA in this proceeding has responded to the directive of the
environmental costs statute.  It has not been pursuing any "secret" agenda or
seeking to nudge the Commission into entering the field of environmental
regulation.  As Mr. McCarron testified:  "[W]e made a conscious decision to
stick to the issue of environmental costs. . . .We wanted to present ourselves
as representing the environmental regulator in Minnesota and not making
recommendations on how the utility regulators should proceed."  Tr. 19 at 59,
lns. 10 - 16.  MPCA's participation has been fully in accord with the statutes
governing it and the Commission, and in furtherance of the broad public
interests at stake here.<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>V. 	THE ALJ AND THE COMMISSION SHOULD ADOPT THE VALUES FOR CRITERIA
POLLUTANTS PROPOSED BY THE MPCA.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Environmental Costs Can And Do Occur At Ambient Air Levels Below The
NAAQS.</b><p>
<b>	</b>Otter Tail Power and Minnesota Power have argued that there are zero
environmental costs occurring at ambient pollution levels below the National
Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS), and particularly at ambient levels
occurring in most of Minnesota, because the NAAQS are set at fully protective
levels, and routinely updated to ensure they reflect the latest scientific
information.  OTP Initial Brief at 12 - 21; MP Initial Brief at 10 - 13.  The
MPCA, the state agency that under the Clean Air Act implements the NAAQS on
which these parties rely, has provided evidence showing that environmental
costs can and do occur at ambient levels below the NAAQS.  In this portion of
the brief we will show that (1)&nbsp;the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
(EPA) process has not kept up with emerging scientific evidence showing effects
below the existing NAAQS; and (2)&nbsp;the evidence overwhelmingly supports the
existence of environmental costs at ambient pollution levels that are below the
NAAQS and that are found in Minnesota. <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.	While the Clean Air Act process is supposed to ensure that the NAAQS are
set below the "no effects" threshold, such thresholds are not clearly
established for most pollutants;  scientific advances routinely discover
effects at levels previously thought safe, and the NAAQS have not kept up with
those advances.</b><p>
<b>	</b>Otter Tail Power and Minnesota Power argue that the Clean Air Act
process under which the EPA establishes and maintains the NAAQS ensures that
there can be no costs occurring at ambient levels below the NAAQS.  OTP Initial
Brief at 12; MP Initial Brief at 10.  This view of environmental costs assumes
that there is a threshold below which no costs occur, and that our current
science is good enough to detect that threshold with precision.  Unfortunately,
that view is not supported by the record.<p>
	Otter Tail Power quotes from the leading case of <u>Lead Industries Ass'n v.
Environmental Protection Agency</u>, 647 F.2d 1130 (D.C. Cir. 1980) <u>cert.
denied</u> 449 U.S. 1042 (Dec. 8, 1980) for the proposition that NAAQS
represent pure health-based standards set at the level at which there is an
absence of adverse effects.  OTP Initial Brief at 16.  However, the language of
the <u>Lead Industries</u> case quoted by OTP describes what the NAAQS are
<i>supposed</i> to be under the Clean Air Act.  A fuller reading of the court's
opinion reveals why, as a practical matter, the absence of a clearly-identified
"no-effects" threshold prevents the EPA from achieving this statutory ideal.
The court quotes the EPA Administrator on the absence of clear thresholds:<p>
<p>
The Administrator notes that protecting the public from harmful effects
requires decisions about exactly what these harms are, a task Congress left to
his judgment.  He notes that the task of making these decisions is complicated
by the absence of any clear thresholds above which there are adverse effects
and below which there are none.  Rather, as scientific knowledge expands and
analytical techniques are improved, new information is uncovered which
indicates that pollution levels that were once considered harmless are not in
fact harmless.<p>
<u>Id.</u> at 1152.  Moreover, the court quoted at length the legislative
history of the 1977 Amendments to the Clean Air Act, revealing that even
Congress was aware that the EPA had not and could not set fully protective
standards.  The House Report on the 1977 Amendments, which was quoting a
National Academy of Sciences report, observed the following:<p>
<p>
However, in no case is there evidence that the threshold levels have a clear
physiological meaning, in the sense that there are genuine adverse health
effects at and above some level of pollution, but no effects at all below that
level.  On the contrary, the evidence indicates that the amount of health
damage varies with the upward and downward variations in the concentration of
the pollutant, with no sharp lower limit.<p>
H.R. Rep. No. 95-294, 95th Cong., 1st Sess. at 110 (quoting 1974 National
Academy of Sciences Report at 17), quoted by <u>Lead Industries</u>, 647 F.2d
at 1153, n. 43.  The court also quoted from the Senate debate on the 1977
Amendments the comments of Senator Muskie who summarized the problems faced by
the Administrator of the EPA in implementing the NAAQS provisions:<p>
<p>
* * * I wish it were possible for the Administrator to set national primary and
secondary standards that fully implement the statutory language * * *.<p>
* * * The fact is, as testimony and documents disclose, the standards do not
fully protect in accordance with the statutory language which gives the
Administrator authority to provide for additional protection.  He has had to
make a pragmatic judgment in the face of the fact that there is no threshold on
health effects, which makes it very difficult then to apply absolute health
protection, and he has not been able to do that.<p>
123 Cong. Rec S.9426 (daily ed. June 10, 1977), quoted by <u>Lead
Industries</u>, 647 F.2d. at 1153, n.&nbsp;43.  Finally, in language
immediately following that quoted by Otter Tail Power on the issue of the
margin of safety built into the NAAQS, the court says:<p>
<p>
Moreover, it is significant that Congress has recently acknowledged that more
often than not the "margins of safety" that are incorporated into air quality
standards turn out to be very modest or nonexistent, as new information reveals
adverse health effects at pollution levels once thought to be harmless.
(Citation to House Report omitted.)<p>
<u>Lead Industries</u>, 647 F.2d at 1154.<p>
	The record in this proceeding also establishing that the target of a "no
effects" threshold is a moving one, shifting downward as our scientific
knowledge progresses.  The absence of a clear no-effects threshold for criteria
pollutants is testified to by Dr. Morton Lippmann, past chair of the Clean Air
Scientific Advisory Committee (CASAC)<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn43">[44]</a>,
the very body EPA relies on to help it determine the health and welfare effects
of criteria pollutants and to keep the NAAQS up to date.  Lippmann Direct, Exh.
130 at 1; Tr. 16 at 17, lns 13-24.  Dr. Lippmann, in rebutting the assertion of
Dr. Sansom, an economist, that a no-effects threshold exists, has testified
unequivocally that "[m]uch of the more recently published data are highly
relevant, and clearly undermine the existence of definable thresholds."
Lippmann Surrebuttal, Exh. 132 at 2.  <p>
	Otter Tail Power and Minnesota Power ask the ALJ and the Commission to assume
that the reality matches the statutory ideal, and that the NAAQS are
established based on clearly recognized no-effect thresholds below which there
can by definition be no costs.  Unfortunately, in reality, these thresholds
have not been defined, and as science progresses we continue to find effects at
lower and lower levels of pollution.  As shown in the discussion of the <u>Lead
Industries</u> case above, the absence of thresholds is acknowledged by the
EPA, by the National Academy of Sciences, by Congress, and by the court in that
case.  The absence of thresholds has been acknowledged in this proceeding by
the former chair of CASAC and by the state agency that implements the NAAQS.
The absence of thresholds must be recognized by the ALJ and the Commission as
well.   <p>
<b></b><p>
<b>2.	The NAAQS do not reflect recent evidence of environmental effects at
levels below the existing standards.</b><p>
<b></b>	Otter Tail Power points out that the Clean Air Act requires the EPA to
update the NAAQS every five years so that they will continue to reflect the
most recent scientific advances.  OTP Initial Brief at 19.  Unfortunately, the
EPA has been unable to satisfy this requirement.  The record clearly
establishes that the EPA is continually behind in its attempts to review the
NAAQS.  Dr. Pratt testified that "[t]he NAAQS are required to be reevaluated
every five years, but the EPA has not reviewed any of its standards in a timely
fashion and has been challenged numerous times in the courts to get on with its
work in this area."  Pratt Direct, Exh. 175, attached paper at 1.  As a result
many of the existing NAAQS are based on criteria documents that are many years
outdated and do not reflect the most recent evidence, which in many cases shows
health and welfare effects below the NAAQS.<p>
	The NAAQS for particulate matter less than 10 microns (PM10) was established
in 1987, but Dr. Lippmann, who was chair of CASAC during this period, testified
that it was based on a criteria document which relied on published data as of
1985.  Lippmann Surrebuttal, Exh. 132 at 2.  The EPA was sued for failure to
keep this NAAQS up to date, had to concede to the court that it had indeed
missed the statutory deadlines, and is currently under court order to finalize
its particulate matter review process by January 1997.  <u>American Lung
Association v. Browner</u>, 884 F.Supp. 345 (D.Ariz. 1994); Pratt Direct, Exh.
175, attached paper at 5.<b>  </b>Dr. Lippmann describes in his direct
testimony that numerous studies in recent years show that there are
statistically significant rates of <i>excess daily mortality</i> and increased
rates of hospital admissions for respiratory diseases at ambient levels below
the existing PM10 NAAQS, and evidence of elevated rates of mortality in
communities with annual average PM10 concentrations approaching the existing
annual standard.  Lippmannn Direct, Exh. 130 at 2.<b></b><p>
<b> 	</b>The NAAQS for ozone was formally retained in 1993, but is based on a
draft criteria document dated 1986 and an addendum dated 1988.  Pratt Direct,
Exh. 175, attached paper at 1.  Dr. Lippmann testified that there is now:<p>
<p>
strong clinical and epidemiological evidence that exposures of healthy normal
people at concentrations below the NAAQS produces: 1) reduced lung function, 2)
symptoms, including shortness of breath, chest tightness, pain on deep
inspiration, cough, etc.; and 3) inflammation of lung airways.  In children
with asthma, such exposures also produce increases in the frequency of use of
prescribed asthma medications.  There are also increases in admissions to
hospitals for asthma in children, and for a variety of respiratory diseases in
older individuals.<p>
Lippman Direct, Exh. 130 at 2-3.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn44">[45]</a>  <p>
	Given this evidence of health effects below the ozone NAAQS it is not
surprising that the EPA was sued for relying on outdated science when it
retained the ozone standard in 1993, and in response to this suit the EPA has
agreed to review its decision by 1998.  Pratt Direct, Exh. 175, attached report
at 2.  The agency is considering several alternatives for a more stringent
standard to be set in 1998, including establishing an eight-hour standard of as
low as 0.06 parts per million (ppm).  <u>Id.</u> at 2.  The current standard is
a one-hour standard of 0.12 ppm, and Minnesota is barely staying in attainment
of it, with maximum ozone concentrations in Minnesota reaching approximately
0.11 ppm in recent years.  <u>Id.</u> at 1.<p>
	The SO2 NAAQS, originally set in 1971, is currently under review.  Pratt
Direct, Exh.&nbsp;175, attached paper at 2.  The EPA is considering more
stringent proposals for a shorter term standard to protect more adequately
against short term irritation that can, among other things, lead to asthma
attacks.  <u>Id.</u>  The existing SO2 NAAQS are based on annual, 24-hour, and
3-hour averaging periods (with an additional 1-hour averaging period adopted by
the MPCA), Minn. R. 7009.0080, but one of the options the EPA is considering is
a new standard with a five-minute averaging period.  <u>Id.</u>  <p>
	There are without question environmental costs occurring at pollution levels
below the existing NAAQS.  For the ALJ and the Commission to assume that the
NAAQS are fully protective, as Otter Tail Power and Minnesota Power argues,
would be to ignore the compelling evidence to the contrary.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>3.	The TER/DPS cost estimates for criteria pollutants are supported by
compelling evidence of environmental costs due to ambient pollution
concentrations found in Minnesota. </b><p>
<b>	</b>The record shows that the cost estimates for criteria pollutants
presented by TER as modified by DPS' witness Dr. Thayer are only those that can
be expected to result from ambient levels of criteria pollutants found in
Minnesota.  This is ensured by two of the stringent criteria applied by TER in
its analysis of which effects to include:<p>
<p>
--Scientific evidence must demonstrate that this effect is caused by exposure
to ambient levels of this pollutant.<p>
<p>
--Scientific evidence must allow for us to determine a concentration-response
function and to estimate the prevalence of this effect.<p>
TER Report, V.1 at 2-1.  While these stringent criteria result in the
unnecessary exclusion of many costs that are properly attributable to energy
production, there can be little question that they ensure that the costs that
are included in the TER estimate have a firm basis in science and apply to
ambient conditions found in Minnesota.<p>
	As part of its analysis, TER has determined the ambient levels of the various
pollutants in the study area, relying on actual monitoring data from 1991.  TER
Report, V.1 at 4-7 and 5-6.  Next they modeled throughout the study area
precisely what the ambient levels would be in response to the emissions
resulting from their selected hypothetical resource scenarios.  TER Report,
V.1, Section 5.  While TER's modeling approach minimized some exposures in
certain areas and excluded the effects of long-range transport and
transformation products, Pratt Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;176 at 3-4, the overall
process ensures that the ambient concentrations of criteria pollutants are not
overestimated. <p>
	To determine the costs that should be associated with the ambient
concentrations projected, TER uses for each health effect the
concentration-response function chosen by the health researchers to quantify
the relationship between air pollution and health.  TER Report, V.2 at 2-10.
Moreover in the selection of the studies to include in its analysis, TER
excluded many health studies showing effects only at ambient concentrations
higher than those found in the study area.  See e.g., TER Report, V.2 at 3-4 to
3-10.  Most of the concentration-response functions used in calculating
agricultural damage were taken from the National Crop Loss Assessment Network
(NCLAN).  TER Report, V.4 at 3-4.  <p>
	DPS witness Dr. Thayer reviews in detail the TER approach, and particularly
the concentration response functions used for each of the health effects
considered.  Thayer Report, Exh. 187 at 40-56.  The Thayer analysis provides
additional support for the costs calculated by TER, though it also provides
compelling evidence that TER underestimated costs in various important
respects, particularly due to the exclusion of costs associated with long-range
transport and transformation products, discussed more fully in our discussion
of SO2 in part VI of this brief.<p>
	The detailed modeling of projected changes in ambient concentrations and the
use of concentration-response functions for each health and agricultural effect
ensures that only costs attributable to ambient levels that exists (or would be
caused) in Minnesota are used.  In light of the TER and Thayer analyses, the
claim by Otter Tail Power and Minnesota Power that there are no costs from
criteria pollutants in areas attaining the NAAQS is manifestly untrue; on the
contrary, the evidence of such costs is strong.  The ALJ and the Commission
should not ignore this detailed and compelling evidence of environmental costs
below the NAAQS simply because the Clean Air Act should be preventing such
costs.  The costs may indeed violate the ideal sought under the Act, but they
are entirely consistent with the reality of its implementation.<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>B.	Cooperative Power's And Otter Tail Power's Criticisms Of MPCA's Proposed
VOC Values For Agricultural Effects Are Founded On Mischaracterizations Of The
Record On Ozone Damages And Misunderstandings Of The Environmental Costs
Statute.</b><p>
<b></b>	Dr. Gregory C. Pratt of the MPCA has developed a value of $86 per ton
for volatile organic compounds (VOCs) emitted by coal-fired power plants.
Pratt Rebuttal, Exh. 176 at 6-9.  VOCs react with NOx in the presence of
sunlight to form the photochemical oxidant ozone (O3).  Exposure to ambient
ozone decreases the productivity of crops.  Using information from Adams, et
al, "An Assessment of the Economic Effects of Ozone on U.S. Agriculture," Dr.
Pratt has calculated the national crop damage from ozone (in dollars per ton of
NOx or VOCs) for the major crops grown in Minnesota and included in that
assessment.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn45">[46]</a>  Since national NOx and VOC
emissions are almost identical and since the two pollutants contribute equally
to ozone formation on a per mass basis, Dr. Pratt performed the calculations
given on page 8 of Exh. 176 to arrive at a minimum value for both NOx and VOCs
of $86 per ton.  He did not have adequate information to distinguish these
damages among the three geographic scenarios used by TER.<p>
	Otter Tail Power (OTP) and Cooperative Power Association (CPA)<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn46">[47]</a> in their initial briefs urge zero values
for VOCs and rejection of MPCA's proposed values because of data inadequacies,
the relative amounts of national VOC production attributable to electric
utilities, the failure to value human health effects of ozone, the questionable
"benefits" to be gained by valuing VOCs, and, most implausibly, Dr. Pratt's
lack of qualifications.  Each of these objections will be addressed.<p>
	The data deficiencies raised by CPA appear to focus on lack of monitoring data
and use of national economic data.  While ambient VOC data is lacking, the
contribution of VOCs by electrical generating plants in Minnesota is clearly
established by an exhibit and testimony.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn47">[48]</a>
There is also extensive record evidence on ozone concentrations.  Dr. Pratt's
Direct states that maximum one-hour ozone averages in Minnesota have recently
been at .11 ppm, close to the .12 ppm standard.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn47">[49]</a>  He also explains
that important crops suffer adverse impacts from ozone levels below current
standards and that U.S. EPA is considering establishment of more stringent
ozone standards for 1998.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn48">[50]</a>  Both the TER
Report and the exhibits to Roth Direct give extensive ozone data across the
Upper Midwest.  See, e.g. Exh. 136, vol. 1 at 5-6 through 5-15; Exh. 150,
attachments HDR 24 - 25.  National economic data on crop damage is appropriate
to use where Minnesota-specific data is not available, especially since Dr.
Pratt included only those major crops grown in Minnesota.  Moreover, he cites
extensive references in support of the other inputs to his damage calculation.
Exhibit 176 at 8.<p>
	The <u>de</u> <u>minimis</u> argument made by CPA at page 16 and OTP at pages
29-30 of their initial briefs should be rejected.  Although the VOC output of
electric utilities may be only a small fraction of national VOC emissions,
those VOCs do participate in the regional phenomenon of ozone formation and
should be considered for environmental cost values.  Like all the cost
estimates in this proceeding, these estimates are expressed on a per ton of
pollutant basis.  The relative overall contribution of the pollutants from the
utility industry is wholly irrelevant to determining the costs associated with
the tons that they do emit.  Otter Tail's further argument that Dr. Pratt
should have viewed power plant emissions of VOCs in isolation from other VOCs
makes no scientific sense for any of the pollutants, but particularly not in
the ozone context,<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn49">[51]</a> and its legal inadequacies have been discussed
earlier.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn49">[52]</a><p>
	Similarly ill-conceived are CPA's arguments that agricultural damage values
for VOCs should be rejected because MPCA did not also propose a human health
damage value and because "there is no indication any values the Commission
adopts for VOCs will actually have any beneficial effect."  CPA Initial Brief
at 16-17.  As noted in the previous discussion of mercury values, the
Commission has not been directed to assume the MPCA and U.S. EPA
responsibilities for environmental regulation.  It is only determining
environmental cost values for its resource planning process.  CPA's arguments
make little sense when viewed in the correct context established by the
environmental costs statute.<p>
	Finally, a brief response is required to Otter Tail Power's attack on Dr.
Pratt's qualifications.  OTP Initial Brief at 28-29.  As to agricultural
damages from ozone, it would be hard to find anyone in Minnesota more qualified
to testify than Dr. Pratt.  His Ph.D. dissertation at the University of
Minnesota was titled "Effects of Ozone and Sulfur Dioxide on Soybeans."<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn50">[53]</a>   He has published at least a half-dozen
articles addressing impacts of NOx, SO2, and ozone on crops, with a focus on
those grown in the Upper Midwest.  In addition he has extensive professional
experience in air transport and dispersion, and related computer modeling.
See, e.g., Tr. 20 at 110-120 (cross-examination by Mr. Witham), Exh. 176 at 4-6
(critique of TER air dispersion modeling), and Exh. 177 (Pratt Resume).<p>
<p>
<b>VI.	SO2 EMISSIONS RESULT IN ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS FAR TOO SIGNIFICANT TO BE
WRITTEN OFF IN FUTURE RESOURCE PLANNING BECAUSE OF AN ERRONEOUS APPLICATION OF
ECONOMIC THEORY THAT DEFIES COMMON SENSE.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>A.	Oversimplification Of Allowance Trading And Misapplication of
"Internalization" Theory Should Not Be Accepted In Addressing SO2 Costs.</b><p>
<b>	</b>The initial briefs of NSP, the Department of Public Service, and MPCA
set forth three competing approaches to valuation of SO2 emissions in light of
the national emissions trading program for SO2 being established pursuant to
Title IV of the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn51">[54]</a>  The NSP approach is the simplest:<p>
<p>
Dr. [Albert] Nichols explained that under a trading system with a cap (such as
SO2 allowance program) the total level of emissions is fixed; any increase from
a new plant must be offset by equivalent reductions in emissions from one or
more existing plants.  Thus, if environmental damages per ton are the same at
different locations, there is no net increase in environmental damages; the
damages from the new plant are exactly balanced by reduction in damages from
the other plants.<p>
NSP Initial Brief at 15.  NSP's brief gives no further attention to the
consequences when the environmental damages per ton are not the same at the new
and the offsetting sources.  However, NSP witness Dr. David Harrison, Jr., a
colleague of Dr. Nichols at National Economic Research Associates (NERA)
testified on cross-examination that it would make no difference in his<b>
</b>view since the costs of SO2 were internalized by the exchange regardless of
how the respective damages compared. Tr.&nbsp;2 at 20, ln. 17 - p. 21, ln. 3.
Therefore, NSP advocates a zero value for SO2 emissions.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn52">[55]</a><p>
	Both of NSP's economist witnesses from NERA, Drs. Harrison and Nichols, view
any "peppercorn" of  cost recognition for environmental damages as
"internalization" which removes those damages from any consideration in an
environmental cost proceeding.  Thus, they repeatedly testified that
correlation, or lack thereof, between the cost of purchased SO2 allowances and
marginal damages had absolutely no significance. Tr. 2 at 27, ln. 1 -
p.&nbsp;29, ln. 6 (Harrison); Tr.&nbsp;27 at 83, ln. 21 - p.&nbsp;84, ln. 20
(Nichols); also see Dr. Nichols questioning by Judge Klein discussed in MPCA
Initial Brief at 62.  To these witnesses, internalization is like pregnancy:
the condition exists or it does not, but there is no part way.  Logically
pursued, the NERA economists view of internalization would mean that the
Commission could ignore almost all of the criteria pollutants.  Since utilities
in Minnesota must pay emission fees based on their emissions of all of the
criteria pollutants except carbon monoxide,<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn53">[56]</a> those residual emissions are
"internalized" under NERA's theory and can be blithely ignored (at least as to
Minnesota generating plants) by the Commission.  Such a bizarre result defies
common sense and could not be what the legislature intended in calling for
establishment of a range of environmental cost values.  See the legislative
history of section 216B.2422, subd. 3, discussed in MPCA's Initial Brief at
13-15, and the general canons of statutory construction in Minn. Stat.
[[section]][[section]]&nbsp;645.16 - .17.  The plain meaning of the statute
should not be distorted by misapplied economic theory.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn54">[57]</a><p>
	DPS pursues more thoughtful analysis of the issue, addressing the real-world
fact that damages almost always will differ at the new and offsetting
sources:<p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>The Department recognizes that this conclusion will not hold if the
damages from additional SO2 emissions at the sites of the seller and buyer
differ.  In other words, the simplified explanation offered above assumes that
the damages imposed by the buyer's ability to generate additional SO2 with
purchased allowances is offset exactly by the damages avoided at the seller's
site.  DPS Exh.&nbsp;37 at 26.  But since damages are site-specific, the
probability of equal incremental damages at the two sites is very low.<p>
DPS Initial Brief at 33.  After acknowledging that net damage will vary with
each trade, the DPS brief argues that only "modest welfare gains at best" could
be expected from examining site-specific damages and urges that the Commission
adopt a zero value.  <u>Id.</u> at 34-35.  Even though DPS acknowledges that
SO2 emissions "cause significant damages"<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn55">[58]</a> including "exacerbation of respiratory and
cardiovascular problems,"<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn56">[59]</a>  and the
trading program would not eliminate SO2 damages,<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn57">[60]</a>  it tells the Commission that SO2 values
are not worth its effort.<p>
	MPCA agrees with  the DPS' premises that damages will differ between the two
sites and that a new source acquiring SO2 allowances may have a good case for
some reduction in environmental costs of its new facility based on reductions
in SO2 emissions at the seller's site.  However, MPCA does not agree with DPS
that the statutory directive to establish costs should  be ignored because
subsequent site-specific applications may require some offsets.<a
href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn58">[61]</a>  Just as other future possible
applications of the environmental cost values have been deemed by the ALJ
inappropriate for this proceeding, so too should the extent to which allowance
trades call for offsets in SO2 costs be reserved for later, site-specific
determinations. <p>
<p>
<b>B.</b>	<b>As Demonstrated Best By DPS' Own Witnesses, The Costs Of Ignoring
SO2 Damages Are Extremely High.</b><p>
<b></b>	The TER Report recommended damage ranges for SO2 based on studies
showing health effects from exposures of the same magnitude anticipated by the
TER study scenarios. Exh. 136, v.&nbsp;2 at 3-3.  TER reached this
recommendation without evaluating the health, visibility, or other effects of
transformation products caused by the reaction of SO2 emissions with other
chemicals in the atmosphere.  Desvousges cross-examination, Tr. 17 at 259,
ln.&nbsp;6 - p.&nbsp;260, ln.&nbsp;23.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn59">[62]</a>
Dr.&nbsp;Morton Lippmann, New York University Professor of Environmental
Medicine, pointed out that TER drew on a poor data resource for SO2 health
effects, leading it to ignore some of the important health consequences flowing
from SO2 emissions, "the strongly acidic aerosols (H2SO4 and NH4SO4)."  Exh.
131 at 2, lns. 20-21 (emphasis omitted).  MPCA research scientist Dr. Gregory
C. Pratt explained in greater detail the reactions which lead from SO2 vapor to
the acidic aerosols, "small particles typically less than one micrometer in
diameter."  Exh. 175, attached paper at 3.  Dr. Pratt explained that sulfate
aerosol particles can be very damaging to lung tissue and are not taken into
consideration in the National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) for SO2.
<u>Id.</u><a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn60">[63]</a>  Because of the failure to
include these important transformation products in its damage studies and
because of other exclusions,<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn61">[64]</a> <b>
</b>MPCA in its Initial Brief urged that the median SO2 values from the TER
report be the lower end of the range for that pollutant, and that other
proceedings before the Commission examine the impacts of these transformation
products.<p>
 	Because the initial round of briefs show that MPCA now stands as the only
advocate for positive values for SO2 beyond the year 2000, it has reexamined
the record to present the strongest evidence to the ALJ and the Commission of
the mistake it would be to assign zero values to SO2.  That evidence can be
found in the Rebuttal Testimony of Dr. Mark Thayer, and in the accompanying
critique of the TER Report by Thayer &amp; Associates, both sponsored by DPS.
Exhs. 186-187.  At page 21, the Thayer Report states that power plants can be
significant contributors of secondary sulfate and nitrate; that TER arbitrarily
and wrongly assumed SO2 and NOx to be nonreactive (i.e., contributing no
secondary sulfate or nitrate); and that this assumption "may seriously
underestimate the total environmental damages."  Using data from two locations
in the TER Study area,<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn62">[65]</a> the Thayer Report
then demonstrated the serious consequences of TER's failure to include these
transformation products.  After reciting that the TER urban scenario calculated
increased direct PM emissions of 1,047 tons per year, the Thayer Report went on
to show how significant an undercounting had occurred by TER ignoring the
secondary particulates:<p>
<p>
Based on typical sulfur oxidation and deposition rates, it is reasonable to
assume that about 10 percent of emitted SO2 will be converted to airborne
sulfate aerosol (Latimer, et al., 1990).  Ten percent of 10,210 tons/year is
1021 tons/year of SO2, nearly equal to the rate for directly emitted PM.  If we
account for the greater molecular weight of ammonium sulfate compared to SO2,
we need to increase this by a factor of about 2 (132/64).  <u>Thus by including
secondary sulfate we would increase total PM impacts by a factor of 3</u>.
Including nitrates would be even higher.<p>
<p>
Thus, the assumption used in the TER/NSP study that secondary aerosol can be
ignored results in a serious underestimate of environmental externalities.<p>
Thayer Report, Exh. 187 at 23 (emphasis added).  Examination of values proposed
by NSP and DPS discloses that PM values are the highest of any values
recommended by those parties.  As footnoted in the comparative table of DPS and
NSP recommended values, Exh. 190 (reprinted as the first attachment to DPS'
Initial Brief),  "the DPS values do not include damages attributable to
secondary particulate formation."  Dr. Desvousges' testimony previously cited
shows that NSP also included none of these damages in its SO2 or PM values.  <p>
	As evident both from the Thayer Report excerpt cited above and the redirect
examination of Dr. Thayer cited in MPCA's Initial Brief at 63-64, the
questionable "internalization" theory used by DPS kept out of its value tables
significant particulate matter additions which Dr. Thayer would have made as a
conscientious environmental economist examining total damages.<a href="pcabrf2_fn.html#fn65">[66]</a>
The several-fold increase in already high PM values which Dr. Thayer would have
made to reflect SO2 transformation products shows  how serious a damage issue
underlies the dispute over the SO2 allowance trading program. These costs are
far too important for the Commission to ignore because of economists' theories
that have no basis in the statutory directive to the Commission.  The
Commission would be derelict in its responsibilities if it does not establish
positive SO2 values in this proceeding and call for careful examination of the
secondary aerosol impacts in future proceedings on coal-fired electricity
generation.<p>
<p>
<b>VII.	CONCLUSION</b><p>
<b></b>	For the foregoing reasons, the values summarized in the MPCA Initial
Brief should be adopted.<p>
<p>
Dated:&nbsp;&nbsp;February 16, 1996.		HUBERT H. HUMPHREY III<p>
Attorney General<p>
State of Minnesota<p>
<p>
