<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>MPCA Findings of Fact and Conclusions</title></head><body>

<b>MPCA Findings of Fact and Conclusions</b>
<b>FINDINGS</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>I.	JURISDICTION</b><p>
<b></b>		The Commission has jurisdiction to establish environmental cost values
and to consider the related issues identified by the Commission as set forth in
the Statement of the Issues pursuant to Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422,
subd. 3(a) (1994).<p>
<b></b><p>
<b>II.	EVIDENTIARY STANDARD AND TREATMENT OF UNCERTAINTY</b><p>
		Under OAH rules at Minn. R. 1400.7300, subp. 5 (1995), the proponent of
action must prove facts at issue by a preponderance of the evidence unless
substantive law provides otherwise. <p>
		In this case, Minn. Stat. [[section]] 216B.2422, subd. 3(a) does provide
otherwise by requiring the PUC to adopt values to the extent practicable.  The
OAH rule cannot be applied consistently with section 216B.2422, subd. 3(a),
because it would place a burden on those proposing to do what the law requires.
Hence, the burden and standard of proof provisions of Minn. R.&nbsp;1400.7300,
subp. 5 have been overridden.   <p>
		Because this proceeding is establishing the record upon which the PUC will
comply with the requirement to adopt values under [[section]] 216B.2422, subd.
3(a), there is no burden on the parties per se.  However, there is an
underlying burden on the PUC to meet the minimum standards, including
evidentiary standards, applied to any administrative action.  <p>
		The establishment of values involves both fact-finding, a quasi-judicial
function, and policy choices, a legislative function.  If the adoption of
values were under judicial review, the quasi-judicial aspects of the adoption
would be upheld if they were based on substantial evidence.  The legislative
aspects of the adoption would be subject to an even more deferential standard
of review.   <u>Arvig Tel. Co. v. Northwestern Bell Tel. Co.</u>, 270 N.W.2d
111, 116 (Minn. App. 1978)<p>
		If values can be established that would pass the standards of judicial review
routinely applied to administrative actions, then the establishment of those
values is "practicable" under section 216B.2422, subd. 3(a), and the law
requires their establishment.<p>
		A major issue in this proceeding is the approach that should be taken in the
face of uncertainty.  At some point, the degree of uncertainty associated with
a value becomes so great that its quantification would not be "practicable"
under the statute.<p>
		The quantification of environmental costs necessarily involves the
consideration of scientific evidence that may not provide definitive answers,
calling upon the Commission to make inferences or judgments about the
environmental cost in question.  <p>
		A variety of economic methodologies can be employed to transform the
scientific evidence of costs into dollar figures, and these methodologies may
produce varying estimates.  Whatever methodology is applied, it necessarily
involves making judgments and estimates in the face of some uncertainties. <p>
		Deciding how much uncertainty can be accepted before quantification becomes
"impracticable" under the statute requires consideration of not only the
scientific evidence and assessment methodologies, but also the intent of the
legislature and the use to which the values will be put.  <p>
		In adding [[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 3(a) in 1993 and repealing
language formerly at Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;216B.164, subd. 4(b), the
legislature abandoned its preexisting "adder" approach to environmental costs,
under which quantified environmental costs would have been automatically added
to the price paid to power producers who were qualifying facilities.  <p>
		Under [[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 3(a) the values will be considered by
the Commission in future resource planning proceedings, and balanced against
other factors important to the public interest, including socioeconomic
factors.  <p>
		Legislative history reveals a legislative intent to make it easier for the
Commission to adopt values under the existing law than it had been under the
previous version of the law.  It cites with approval other states' cost
valuations necessarily made in the face of considerable uncertainty.<p>
		In reviewing resource plans, the Commission is required to use its best
judgment to find the mix of resources that will be in the public interest, not
just today but in the years to come.  This process already requires the
Commission to make predictions on many issues based on uncertain evidence,
including likely growth in electricity demand, future fuel prices, future
changes in federal regulation, and the effects of emerging competition among
utilities.  Under most circumstances, the assumptions made by the Commission on
these issues are not assumptions that lend themselves to "proof," but rather
must be based on the Commission's judgment as informed by the available
evidence.<p>
 		Given the inherent scientific and economic uncertainty that attaches to what
the legislature has required the Commission to do, and given that the purpose
of these values is to help the Commission to determine the future long-term
public interest (which necessarily requires the Commission to make predictions
about many factors), it would be unreasonable to refrain from adopting values
simply because to do so would require the exercise of administrative judgment
in the face of uncertainty.<p>
		Refusing to adopt values until they can be proven by a preponderance of the
evidence would build in a pervasive bias in favor of zero, resulting in likely
underestimation of environmental costs.  This approach is not supported by the
legislative history which shows a legislative intent to make it easier to adopt
values, and is inconsistent with the goal of informing the Commission's
planning process.  <p>
		Therefore, values will be found to meet the practicability standard if the
record establishes that the values are reliable enough to assist the Commission
in determining the resource choice most in the overall, long-term public
interest.  Conversely, values would be found impracticable to establish if the
record did not provide substantial enough evidence to yield values with enough
meaning to assist the Commission in determining the resource choice most in the
overall, long-term public interest.<p>
		In determining whether proposed values are reliable enough to be useful in
resource planning, it is assumed (and recommended) that the Commission will
apply the values with an understanding and an ongoing recognition of the types
of costs they do and do not reflect, how they were calculated, what assumptions
were made in arriving at them, and the types of uncertainty associated with
them.  Given the evolving nature of the underlying science, it is also
recommended that the Commission consider in subsequent resource planning
proceedings any significant and pertinent scientific developments occurring
after the record in this proceeding closed. <p>
		In quantifying environmental costs, once there is evidence that the cost
exists, it is appropriate to attempt to arrive at the best estimate of the
range within which the cost is likely to lie based on the evidentiary record.
Such costs will not be assumed to be zero unless the evidence suggests that
zero is the most accurate estimate of the cost, or unless the evidence is so
lacking that no meaningful estimate of costs can be made. <p>
<b>III.	CONSIDERATION OF COSTS OCCURRING OUTSIDE OF MINNESOTA</b><p>
<b></b>		Some parties to this proceeding argue that the only environmental
costs that should be quantified are those costs that are incurred within the
borders of Minnesota, excluding all costs that occur outside of the state's
borders (hereafter "extraterritorial costs"). <p>
		Interpreting the law in this fashion would greatly reduce the environmental
costs associated with mercury and all but eliminate the costs associated with
carbon dioxide.  This is because a significant portion of mercury emissions
travels beyond the locality of the source, contributing to the regional and
global mercury concentrations.  Carbon dioxide emissions have no particular
local costs, but contribute to global costs when aggregated with all other
global emissions.  These pollutants are discussed in further detail in
subsequent findings.<p>
		The ALJ finds that excluding extraterritorial costs from quantification is
not supported by the plain language of [[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 3(a).
<p>
		There is also no basis in the legislative history to read such an exclusion
into the statute.  On the contrary, the legislative history makes specific
reference to greenhouse gases and mercury, and it is presumed that the
legislature knew that these problems were of a regional and global nature.
Previous legislative efforts addressing regional and global environmental
problems, such as laws relating to chlorofluorocarbons, acid rain, and mercury,
also establish the legislature's interest in the extraterritorial environmental
effects of Minnesota's actions.<p>
		Excluding extraterritorial costs would also be inconsistent with the
requirement under Minn. Stat. [[section]] 116D.03, subd. 2(e), which requires
all state agencies to recognize the worldwide and long-range character of
environmental problems and to lend appropriate support to interstate, national,
and international efforts to protect the world environment.<p>
		Some parties to this proceeding have argued that the constitution or inherent
limits in the state's police powers prevent the Commission from considering
extraterritorial costs of Minnesota resource decisions.  Case law does not
support these claims. <p>
		The ALJ therefore interprets [[section]]&nbsp;216B.2422, subd. 3(a) to
require the Commission to quantify environmental costs associated with
electricity production, regardless of whether those costs fall within the
borders of Minnesota or elsewhere.<p>
<b>IV.	CARBON DIOXIDE VALUES</b><p>
<b><u>Carbon Dioxide and the Greenhouse Effect</u></b><p>
<b></b>		Carbon dioxide (CO2) is one of several gases known as "greenhouse
gases" because they have the effect of  warming the Earth.  This warming effect
comes about when energy from the sun in the form of short-wave, visible, solar
radiation passes through the  atmosphere, is absorbed by the Earth, and then is
emitted as long-wave, infra-red (invisible) terrestrial radiation.  Some of the
infra-red radiation, instead of radiating directly into space, is absorbed and
re-emitted by the greenhouse gases, thus warming the surface and lower
atmosphere of the planet.  <u>Climate Change, The IPCC Scientific Assessment
(1990)</u>, attached to Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 (hereafter "IPCC 1990
Report") at xiii-xiv.  <p>
		Since preindustrial times, human activities have resulted in increased
concentrations in the atmosphere of CO2 and the other naturally occurring
greenhouse gases, and the introduction of new greenhouse gases that do not
occur naturally, such as chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs).  Through these activities,
humankind is capable of raising the global-average annual-mean surface-air
temperature (hereafter "global temperature").  This effect is called "global
warming" or the "enhanced greenhouse effect", to distinguish it from the
substantial natural greenhouse effect.  IPCC 1990 Report at
xiv.<b><u></u></b><p>
<b><u></u></b>		Carbon dioxide emissions have a very long-term effect on global
CO2 concentrations.  Once CO2 is emitted, the resulting higher concentration of
CO2 in the atmosphere will persist for centuries.  IPCC 1990 Report at 5; M.
Davis Rebuttal, Exh. 77 at 9.  <p>
		The CO2 emitted in any particular place is well-mixed with global levels of
CO2 and contributes to the planet-wide global-warming effect.  Warming in
Minnesota, for example, will be caused not just by Minnesota's CO2 emissions,
but by the global concentration of CO2, which derives from global emissions.
Similarly, Minnesota's CO2 emissions cannot be said to warm Minnesota's
environment any more than they warm the rest of the planet.  Tr. 12 at 17
(M.&nbsp;Davis).<p>
<b><u>Conflicting Scientific Perspectives</u></b><p>
		The Minnesota Pollution Control Agency (MPCA) has placed into the record the
1990 Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), cited in
Finding 37 and the summary of the 1992 IPCC Report supplementing the 1990
Report.  Attached to Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 (hereafter "IPCC 1992
Report").  In these reports the IPCC makes predictions about the amount of
warming most likely to occur as a result of given levels of greenhouse gas
buildup.<p>
		Western Fuels Association, the Lignite Energy Council, the Center for Energy
and Economic Development and the State of North Dakota (hereafter "Western
Fuels, et al.") have sponsored the testimony of five scientists, four of whom
express views on the overall issue of how much global warming is likely to
result from the buildup of CO2 and other greenhouse gases.  Lindzen Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;54; Michaels Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;57; Balling Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;63;
and Seitz Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;100.<p>
		The views of the scientists sponsored by Western Fuels et al. differ from
those expressed by the IPCC in several respects, including the overall amount
of warming to be expected, whether the amount and type of global warming that
has occurred over the past century conflicts with the predictions of the IPCC,
whether the computer models underlying the IPCC predictions are credible, and
the effects of natural feedback mechanisms on overall warming.  In general
these witnesses anticipate much less global warming than is predicted by the
IPCC.  Lindzen Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;54 at 30-31; Tr. 9 at 107 (Michaels);
Balling Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;63 at 16; Seitz Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;100 attached
report FS-6 at 25.<p>
		Given the differences between the scientific views presented by the witnesses
for Western Fuels et al., and those expressed by the IPCC, and given the highly
technical nature of these differences, the opposing scientific views cannot be
reconciled in this proceeding.  The ALJ is therefore required to choose between
these two competing scientific perspectives.<p>
		The IPCC was formed in 1988, by the World Meteorological Organization (WMO)
and the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) for the purpose of
assessing the scientific information related to climate change.  The IPCC 1990
Report was written by 37 lead authors, and contributed to by 170 scientists
from 25 different countries, with further review by an additional 200
scientists, involving most of the active scientists working in the field.  IPCC
1990 Report, Preface at iii, Foreword at v, and Appendices 3 and 4.  The IPCC
1990 Report was followed by a 1992 Supplement, which was written by 22 lead
authors, with 126 contributors.  IPCC 1992 Report, Appendices 2 and 3 attached
to Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72.<p>
		The IPCC 1990 Report provided the scientific basis for the global warming
negotiations that took place in 1992 at the Rio de Janeiro "Earth Summit,"
which ultimately resulted in an international treaty known as the "Framework
Convention on Climate Change" (Framework Convention).  The Framework Convention
was signed by 128 countries, including the United States and most of the
industrialized nations of the world, and commits countries to actions to limit
global warming with the aim of reducing CO2 emissions to 1990 levels by the
year 2000.  In the spring of 1995, the tenure of the IPCC as the scientific
review body of the parties to the Framework Convention was extended.
Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 at 3; Bernow Direct, Exh.&nbsp;111 at 4-5.<p>
		Since 1979 the science underlying the global warming problem has been
reviewed by many other scientific review panels in addition to the IPCC,
including reviews by the National Academy of Sciences, the World Meteorological
Organization, and U.S. Department of Energy.  In general, these panels have
projected a range of warming in response to increased greenhouse gases
consistent with the range projected by the IPCC. Ciborowski Surrebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;72 at 11.  <p>
		Three of the scientific witnesses sponsored by Western Fuels, et al., suggest
that the findings of the IPCC have been affected by political or other
influences.  Lindzen Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;54 at 33-34; Michaels Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;57 at 21-22; Seitz Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;100, attached report FS-1 at
9.  However, the record does not include any credible evidence of such
influences or any other basis on which to seriously question the scientific
objectivity of the IPCC Reports.<p>
		The ALJ finds that the scientific judgments and predictions of the IPCC have
greater weight and credibility than those advanced by the scientists sponsored
by Western Fuels et al.  It is reasonable to rely on predictions and
conclusions expressed in the IPCC's reports in this proceeding for purposes of
quantifying the costs associated with carbon dioxide.<p>
<b><u>Global Warming Predictions</u></b><p>
		The amount of warming expected due to increased greenhouse gases is expressed
in terms of "climate sensitivity."  Specifically, climate sensitivity means the
amount of warming expected to result from a doubling of the concentration of
CO2 in the atmosphere (above preindustrial levels) or a doubling of the
"equivalent" CO2 levels.  Use of equivalent CO2 levels allows scientists to
recognize the combined consequences of all greenhouse gases, expressed as the
amount of carbon dioxide it would take to cause that consequence.  IPCC 1990
Report at xxv and xviii - xix.<p>
		The climate sensitivity of the Earth is likely to fall within the range of
1.5deg.C. and 4.5deg.C.  IPCC 1990 Report at xxv; IPCC 1992 Report at 5.<p>
		This range of climate sensitivity is based largely on the results of general
circulation models (GCMs).  GCMs are complex computer models that synthesize
scientists' knowledge about the physical and dynamical processes of the overall
climate system.  To make a climate forecast, the model is first run for a few
simulated decades.  If the model is a good one, it will statistically describe
a climate closely resembling the climate of the real atmosphere and ocean.
Then the exercise is repeated with increasing levels of greenhouse gases, and
the difference between the two computer runs is an estimate of expected climate
change.  IPCC 1990 Report at xx and xxv.<p>
		The climate forecasts made by the various GCMs in use today depend on
comparatively crude descriptions of some climate processes.  As a result,
considerable uncertainty attaches to the projections of climate changes, and
this uncertainty is reflected in the range of climate sensitivity values given.
IPCC 1990 Report at xx and xxii.<p>
		Scientific witnesses for Western Fuels et al. have testified about the
uncertainties associated with GCMs, and expressed their judgments that the
GCM-based predictions are not reliable enough to be the basis of policy
decisions.  Lindzen Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;54 at 19; Seitz Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;100, attached report FS-4 at 11.<p>
		In contrast, the IPCC concludes that, despite the uncertainties, GCMs are the
best tools scientists have for predicting the effects of increasing greenhouse
gases.  IPCC 1990 Report at xx.  The IPCC has expressed "substantial
confidence" in the ability of GCMs to predict the broad-scale features of
climate change.  IPCC Report at xxvii-xxviii.  GCMs are able to simulate with
considerable skill the large-scale distribution of pressure, temperature, wind
and precipitation of the existing climate, in both summer and winter.  GCMs
have also been successful at simulating the climates of the distant past, known
as "paleo-climates."  IPCC 1990 Report at 125-126.<p>
		The IPCC's model-based predictions are the basis of the Framework Convention
and ongoing international treaty negotiations on global warming.  Concerns
about global warming, based largely on GCM predictions, were one of two reasons
why Congress adopted under the Clean Air Act extensive provisions regulating
chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), which are another category of greenhouse gas.  The
legislative history reflects the substantial concern of Congress that CFCs are
contributing to two distinct but related "global environmental crises," namely,
damage to the ozone layer and global warming.  Senate Comm. on Env't &amp;
Public Works, Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, S. Rep. No.&nbsp;101-228, 101st
Cong., 2nd Sess; reprinted in 1990 U.S.C.C.A.N., Vol. 6, 3385, 3760.<p>
		The ALJ finds that the uncertainties associated with the GCM predictions are
not sufficient to disregard the global warming predictions of the IPCC.  This
finding is based on the confidence expressed in the GCMs by the IPCC, on the
ability of the GCMs to simulate past and current climates, and on the fact that
GCM predictions are the basis of policy negotiations and decisions on the
national and international level.<p>
		Within the range of climate sensitivity of 1.5deg. to 4.5deg.C., the
"best-estimate" of climate sensitivity is 2.5deg.C.  In other words, climate
sensitivity is more likely to be 2.5deg.C. than any other number within the
range, although the scientific evidence supporting this figure over other
numbers in the range is modest, and the possibility of other climate
sensitivities within the range certainly cannot be excluded.  However, based on
the GCM results, on sensitivity analyses attempting to quantify the
uncertainties of the GCM results, and on observed levels of warming over the
past century, 2.5<sup>o</sup>C. is the best estimate of climate sensitivity in
the light of current knowledge.  IPCC 1990 Report at xxv and 138-139.<p>
		The IPCC 1990 Report includes a scenario of future accumulations of
greenhouse gases based on their previously-established emission trends.  This
scenario is known as the business-as-usual scenario.  Under the
business-as-usual scenario, equivalent CO2 concentrations are expected to
double (from preindustrial levels) before 2030 and to quadruple before 2100.
IPCC 1990 Report at xx, Figure 6, and xxxiv.<p>
		Assuming business-as-usual emission trends and using the best estimate of
climate sensitivity, warming by the year 2100 is likely to be 4deg.C. above the
preindustrial level, with additional warming following after that year as the
Earth continues to adjust to the increased CO2 concentrations.  IPCC 1990
Report at xxii.  It is reasonable to calculate costs based on the assumption of
business-as-usual emission trends and using the best-estimate of climate
sensitivity.<p>
<b><u>Projecting Global Costs As a Percent of GDP</u></b><p>
<b>	Economic Projections</b><p>
		The MPCA has presented a method of calculating costs/ton of CO2 based on the
published projections of four economists that have estimated the economic costs
likely to result from the IPCC best-estimate warming prediction.  The costs are
expressed by these economists in terms of the percentage of future gross
domestic product (GDP).  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 at 24 (Table 3) and
40 (Table 4).<p>
		Three of the economists -- W. Cline, S. Fankhauser, and J. Scheraga --
estimate U.S. costs for several identified sectors amounting to 1.1, 1.3, and
0.8 percent of U.S. GDP, respectively.  Specific costs sectors for which
estimates are provided by one or more of the three economists are:  coastal
defense, dryland loss, wetland loss, species loss, agriculture, forestry,
fishery, energy, water, amenity, life/morbidity, air pollution, migration, and
natural hazards.  Scheraga's cost estimate is based on consideration of only
three of these sectors. Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 24. <p>
		One additional economist, W. Nordhaus, made cost estimates for four cost
sectors (coastal defense, dryland loss, agriculture, and energy) amounting to
approximately .25% of U.S. GDP, but he recognized that this figure was "clearly
incomplete" and suggested that consideration of non-quantified costs could
raise total costs to 1% of GDP.  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 at 24;
Bernow Direct, Exh.&nbsp;111, attached report at 35.<p>
		Two of the aforementioned economists have also published estimates of the
likely costs of global warming on a global basis, expressed as a percentage of
global GDP.  Nordhaus estimated global GDP losses of 1% of GDP, and Fankhauser
estimated global GDP losses of 1.5% of GDP.  Both these estimates were for
costs incurred at the year 2050, before the greater warming projected for later
in the century occurs.  Costs in developing countries are estimated to be about
twice those in the developed world.  These studies constitute substantial
evidence that costs due to global warming on the global level will be at least
as high as costs projected for the U.S. as a percentage of GDP.  Ciborowski
Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 at 26-27.<p>
<b>  	Cost Sectors Not Adequately Addressed</b><p>
		Economist Cline stated that consideration of the cost sectors that are
ignored or not adequately addressed in his analysis, such as costs to unmanaged
ecosystems, species diversity and air pollution, could easily double the costs
as a percentage of U.S. GDP, raising them from approximately 1% to 2%.
Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 at 25.<p>
		An example of the type of costs to unmanaged ecosystems not adequately
reflected in the 1% cost estimates are those related to the decline of forest
ecosystems.  Two scientists specializing in the study of forest response to
climate change testified in this proceeding, Dr. John Pastor and Dr. Margaret
Davis.  Both are highly qualified experts in their field and their work
predicting the responses of tree species to climate change has been relied on
by the IPCC.  Exh.&nbsp;80 (M. Davis C.V.); Exh.&nbsp;68 (Pastor C.V.); IPCC
1990 Report at 296, Figure 10.2, and 298-99, Figure 10.4.  <p>
		 The best estimate prediction of warming for the next century will result in
dramatic changes to forest ecosystems, particularly where they exist at the
edge of their ranges, such as the boreal forests of northern Minnesota.  M.
Davis Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;77 at 7-8; Pastor Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;65 at 7-8.<p>
		The rate of the best estimate of future warming is substantially faster than
the natural climate changes which have in the past resulted in widespread "tree
migrations", evidenced by the fossil record.  M. Davis Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;77
at 9-10.<p>
		The conditions under which forest ecosystems would have to migrate to new
regions as the climate changes are also more difficult than they were in the
past.  Many of these ecosystems are now in relatively isolated areas, and their
natural migration corridors are interrupted by roads, farms, and other human
developments.  Some of the species that in the past would have assisted in the
migration, such as the carrier pigeon, are now extinct.  M. Davis Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;77 at 11.<p>
		While foresters would be able to assist in the migration of commercially
valuable tree species, this would not result in the re-establishment of the
natural forest ecosystems currently in existence, which reflect a variety of
plant and animal species.  While humans could endeavor to transplant to new
regions the wide variety of plant and animal species currently found in natural
forests, it is not clear that such efforts would be successful, and they would
likely be costly.  M. Davis Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;77 at 11; Tr.&nbsp;12 at 22-24
(M. Davis).<p>
<b>	Assumption of Linear Warming.</b><p>
		The four cost projections mentioned all assume that warming will occur in a
steady, linear fashion.  If warming does not occur in a steady fashion, costs
can be expected to be higher than those projected.  Ciborowski Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;70 at 25; Tr.&nbsp;11 at 194 (Ciborowski).<p>
		Because of the various factors which influence climate, warming over the next
century is not likely to occur in the steady and gradual fashion assumed by the
economic studies.  IPCC 1990 Report at xxii.  Since they assume warming will be
steady, the economic analyses are likely to underestimate costs.<p>
<b>	Exclusion of Inherent Risks</b><p>
		A global warming of 4deg.C. above preindustrial levels by the year 2100 would
constitute a very large change in the Earth's climate.  The warming predicted
for the next century approaches in magnitude the difference between average
global temperatures during the ice ages and average global temperature today.
NAS Report at 279, attached to Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70.  For the past
several million years the Earth has oscillated between conditions that have
been approximately 4 to 5deg.C. cooler than today (during the ice ages) or at
about present levels of warmth.  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 15.  By the
middle of the next century the projected global warming (based on the IPCC's
best estimate of climate sensitivity) would make the global mean temperatures
higher than they have been in the last 150,000 years.  IPCC 1990 Report at
xxviii.  The warming projected by the year 2100 would make the planet warmer
than it has been for millions of years.  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 15.
<p>
		Global warming of the magnitude projected raises the possibility of several
responses that would result in severe costs which are not reflected in the
costs estimates.  For example, the last time the earth was as warm as it is
projected to become, several million years ago, the Arctic basin was seasonally
clear of floating pack ice.  Because of the role played by floating ice sheets
as a driving force of ocean circulation, this raises the possibility of the
collapse of the major global oceanic currents, such as the Gulf  Stream, which
would dramatically change the global climate.  Ciborowski Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;70 at 15-17; M. Davis Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;77 at 9.  There is also
evidence that the Earth may respond to the build-up of greenhouse gases with an
abrupt leap resulting in large-scale reorganization of the Earth's climate
system, as it appears to have done at times in our geologic past.  Ciborowski
Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 at 18.  <p>
		Another risk not reflected in the cost estimates is the risk that warming
could trigger large emissions of greenhouse gases from the organisms of the
Earth, known as the "biosphere."  Carbon is continuously cycling through
plants, soil, and the atmosphere.  From 1920 to 1970, much of the carbon in the
atmosphere was absorbed through an unidentified mechanism in the biosphere, and
then it stopped.  There is reason to fear warming could trigger the reemission
of this carbon, thus amplifying the greenhouse effect (i.e., creating a
positive feedback).  Tr.&nbsp;12 at 58-59 (M. Davis); Ciborowski Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;70 at 13.  This positive feedback is not reflected in the IPCC
predictions because the GCMs do not yet take greenhouse gas feedbacks into
account.  IPCC 1990 Report at xx.<p>
		The record does not establish that any of the results discussed in Findings
74 and 75 are likely.  However, it does establish the possibility of such
consequences, and the likelihood they would be quite costly if they occurred.
The record also establishes that the best estimate of global warming for the
next century will result in a climate and environment with which humankind has
no experience.  Thus, the potential for costly climatic surprises such as those
discussed or others not yet thought of, is very high.  National Academy of
Sciences Report (1987) at 20, quoted by Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;72 at
13.  The cost estimates do not reflect these risks in any way.<p>
		The ALJ finds that Cline's projection of 2% of GDP costs is a more inclusive
and therefore more accurate estimate of overall costs associated with global
warming than the 1% cost estimates.  This finding is supported not just by the
costs Cline identified as missing from his 1% estimate, but by the recognition
that warming is not likely to be steady and that the economic cost projections
do not include any quantification of the underlying risks inherent in climate
change of the magnitude predicted.<p>
<b><u>Calculating Costs On A Per Ton Basis</u></b><p>
<b><u></u></b>		The MPCA has taken the estimates of global costs due to global
warming expressed as a percentage of GDP and developed then into a cost per ton
of CO2.  	<p>
		The cost estimates provided by the MPCA were calculated by MPCA policy
analyst Peter Ciborowski.  Mr. Ciborowski has a masters degree in public policy
from the Humphrey Institute and as a policy analyst is trained in making cost
projections.  He has 13 years of experience focusing primarily on global
warming, including the underlying scientific and policy issues.  During this
time he has developed a very broad and detailed understanding of the basic
responses of the climate system, emissions and emission sources, rates of
accumulation of greenhouse gases, responses of natural systems to climate
change, and the effects of global warming on humans and unmanaged systems.  Tr.
13 at 44-45 (Ciborowski); Exh.&nbsp;87 at 1 (Ciborowski C.V.); Tr.&nbsp;13 at
56 (Ciborowski).  He is qualified to undertake the cost calculation presented
by the MPCA.<p>
		To calculate the costs associated with future emissions of CO2, the 4deg.C.
warming projected for the year 2100 was reduced to exclude the amount of
warming attributable to other greenhouse gases and the amount of warming
attributable to past emissions of CO2.  The amount of the IPCC's global warming
predictions which it attributes to non-CO2 emissions or to past CO2 emissions
is calculable from the IPCC Reports, and yields a balance of approximately two
degrees of warming attributable to future CO2 emissions.  Ciborowski Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;70 at 39 (corrected by errata sheet, Exh.&nbsp;71); Tr.&nbsp;11 at
116-120 (Ciborowski); IPCC 1990 Report at 57.<p>
		Translating costs from a percentage of future GDP to dollar amounts requires
an estimate of existing global GDP and an estimate of likely growth in GDP over
the next century.  <p>
		An estimate of existing global GDP is taken from the Central Intelligence
Agency.  Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 at 41.<p>
		A high and low estimate of long-term economic growth is taken from a 1990 EPA
report to Congress, analyzing policy responses to global warming.  The EPA
projections are similar to projections of economic growth over the next century
made by the IPCC to inform ongoing international treaty negotiations.
Ciborowski Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;70 at 40-41 (text and notes to Table 4); IPCC
1992 Report at 12.  There is no evidence in the record suggesting that the
range of likely economic growth assumed in the MPCA's cost calculation is too
high or too low.<p>
		There is dispute among the parties to this proceeding over whether it is
practicable to make estimates of long-term growth over such a long period.
Clearly, such projections are subject to substantial uncertainty.  However, it
is found that the uncertainty underlying these estimates is not so great as to
render the economic growth estimates impracticable.  Despite the inherent
degree of uncertainty in such long term economic projections, it is reasonable
to make them to facilitate the Commission's consideration of the long-term
effects of CO2 emissions.<p>
		In order to determine the present value of a stream of costs projected out
over the next century, a discount rate must be applied.  A discount rate
reflects the relative value present decision-makers place of costs incurred in
the future.  A high discount rate means that future costs are valued at much
less than costs incurred today.  A low discount rate means that future costs
are given a value closer to the value given to current costs.  Tr.&nbsp;2 at 53
(Harrison); Tr.&nbsp;12 at 71-72 (Ciborowski).<p>
		There has been substantial dispute in this proceeding over the appropriate
discount rate to apply to the long-term costs that are the subject of this
calculation.  Because the costs in question span multiple generations, at issue
is the relative weight to be given to the interests of future generations.
<p>
		The MPCA proposes the use of a relatively low discount rate of 1 or 2 percent
to reflect the fact that the costs fall on multiple generations.  A discount
rate of approximately 1.5% is supported by Cline on the grounds that future
global-warming related costs will draw both from society's investment budget,
and from the amount it would spend on consumption.  Applying a low discount
rate to consumption, as is appropriate in this multi-generational context, and
applying a much higher discount rate to investments, yields a weighted average
discount rate of approximately 1.5%.  Tr.&nbsp;13 at 95-96 (Ciborowski).<p>
		The Environmental Policy Act, at Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;116D.02, subd.
2(a) (1994), recognizes an ongoing responsibility of state government to
implement state programs in such a way as to "fulfill the responsibilities of
each generation as trustee of the environment for succeeding generations."  <p>
		All state laws must to the fullest extent practicable be interpreted and
administered in accordance with this responsibility toward future generations.
Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;116D.03, subd. 1.<p>
		The ALJ finds that the use of discount rates of 1 to 2 percent is
economically rational as explained by Cline, and is most consistent with this
generation's role as trustee of the environment for succeeding generations.
Higher discount rates, more typically used to calculate the value of a stream
of costs or benefits accrued over shorter periods of time, should not be used
where as here the costs will be incurred by multiple generations.<p>
		The calculation provided by the MPCA, based on the assumptions discussed in
the previous findings, results in a cost range of $4.28 to $28.57 per ton of
CO2.<p>
		The MPCA's cost estimate depends on making a series of assumptions about the
shape of the distant future and about climate processes that are not fully
understood.  As a result, considerable uncertainty attaches to the cost
range.<p>
		However, each assumption made in the calculation of the range of costs is a
reasonable best estimate based on substantial evidence, and therefore the final
range represents a reasonable best estimate of costs.  <p>
		The ALJ therefore finds that the range of $4.28 to $28.57 represents a
practicable quantification of the environmental costs associated with CO2, and
recommends its adoption.<p>
<b>V.	MERCURY VALUES</b><p>
<b>	</b>	Mercury is a contaminant found in even the most remote lakes of the
Upper Midwest and virtually all mercury in these lakes is believed to have
reached them by atmospheric transport.  Methylating bacteria found in the lakes
convert the mercury deposited to methylmercury which is taken up through the
food chain and "bioaccumulated" up to a million-fold.  Ninety-four percent of
lakes surveyed by the Minnesota Department of Health, selected because of their
popularity with anglers, have fish consumption advisories because of mercury.
These fish advisories have been posted because consumption of fish with high
mercury concentrations poses risks of nervous system damage, especially for
pregnant women and young children.  Wildlife which eat contaminated fish also
are at risk.  Swain Direct, Exh. 213; Exh.&nbsp;216 (1995 Minnesota Fish
Consumption Advisory Update); Tr. 24 at 56 (Swain); Tr. 26 at 180 (Shapiro).<p>
		Extensive public comment was received about mercury contamination negatively
impacting recreational fishing and posing greater risks to communities
dependent on local fisheries.  Native Americans testified at several hearings
about additional risks posed to Indian anglers, and their families, who rely on
locally caught fish and consume up to nine times as much fish as non-Indian
people.  E.g.,  Public Hearing Tr. at 40-42 (Bemidji - Plymouth Teleconference,
April 27, 1995).  Similar dependence on locally caught fish by recent Southeast
Asian immigrants was described by a public health nurse.  Public Hearing Tr. at
40-41 (Roche<p>
ster Hearing, April 25, 1995).  Also see Swain Direct, Exh. 213 at 11.<p>
		Only in the last decade has the "cycling" of mercury in the biosphere been
well understood.  It is now believed that the emissions from a given
anthropogenic source will be divided roughly equally between a
global-hemispheric pool and local-regional deposition(with the regional share
amounting to four times more than the local share).  Mercury does not degrade,
is highly mobile, and can be re-emitted to the atmosphere after initial
deposition to soil or water.  The process of coal mining and burning adds
mercury to the atmosphere which otherwise would have remain locked in
geological formations for millions of years.  Swain Direct, Exh. 213; Swain
Rebuttal, Exh. 215; Tr. 23 at 84-85 (Swain).<p>
		Three-fourths of mercury deposited in Minnesota can be ascribed to
human-generated sources.  Although mercury emissions from coal-fired power
plants are, compared to most criteria pollutants, not well quantified and quite
small, coal-fired plants are estimated to be the source of one-sixth to
one-fourth of the anthropogenic mercury emissions in the state.  With the
effects of the 1991 federal ban on mercury in paints and fungicides, coal
burning has become the leading source of mercury emissions to the air in
Minnesota.  Swain Direct, Exh. 213, especially exhibit 2 thereto; Hagley
Rebuttal, Exh. 226 at 6-7; and Whitelaw Direct, Exh. 234 at 17-18.<p>
		No damage cost study of mercury emissions was performed for this proceeding.
Estimates of mercury damages based on benefit transfer analyses were offered by
the Environmental Coalition (EC) and the MPCA.  <p>
		The EC's benefit transfer analysis looked to the relative damages suffered by
Alaska's salmon fishing industry because of the stigma of the Exxon Valdez oil
spill and projected a setback of the same relative proportion to Minnesota's
recreational fishing industry because of the stigma associated with
mercury-based fish consumption advisories.  Through this methodology, the EC
derived a value of $25,000 per pound of mercury.  Whitelaw Direct, Exh. 234 at
20-22.  <p>
		MPCA's benefit transfer analysis looked to the damages for criteria
pollutants estimated through the TER study and then projected damages from
mercury emissions by comparing mercury and the TER results through the use of
an "Indexing System" for toxic air emissions developed by MPCA in conjunction
with the University of Toronto.  The Indexing System "assesses and compares the
environmental fate and human and ecological toxicity potential of chemicals
emitted to the air in Minnesota."  Pratt, et al., Exh. 170 at 1360.  It
utilizes toxicological information from databases relied upon by the U.S. EPA
and the Minnesota Department of Health, as well as from occupational safety
databases.  Pratt, et al., Exh. 170 at 1364-71<b>;</b> McCarron Rebuttal,<b>
</b>Exh. 163 at 37.  Through this benefit transfer, MPCA developed values for
mercury in the range  $4359 - 9781 per pound.  McCarron Rebuttal, Exh. 163 at
28-43.  <p>
		The Office of the Attorney General (OAG) has endorsed the MPCA benefit
transfer approach while recognizing that it has less certainty than the damage
cost approach employed by TER.  Taking a slightly different view of the TER
inputs to the MPCA benefit transfer, OAG has recommended values for mercury in
the range of $1429 - 4359 per pound.  OAG Initial Brief on Substantive Issues
at 29 - 33.<p>
		Several parties urging zero values for mercury have challenged the MPCA
benefit transfer analysis, particularly its failure to connect damages to
specific utility emissions, its failure to show actual health effects from
those emissions, and its lack of prior applications and lack of reliability.
The parties raising these challenges also point to ongoing EPA and MPCA studies
related to mercury as further grounds for not quantifying mercury values in
this proceeding..  <p>
		The ALJ recommends rejection of these challenges.  Since mercury is a
persistent and highly mobile pollutant with 90% of emissions having impacts on
a regional or global level, it is not necessary for establishing values to
attribute specific contamination to a specific source.  Similarly, while the
health effects of emissions from specific mercury sources have not been
studied, it is clear that mercury has potential to cause nervous system damage,
ranks second out of over 180 substances ranked in the Indexing System for
health and ecological effects, and has led to widespread imposition of fish
consumption advisories by the Department of Health.  Swain Direct, Exh. 213 at
11-12; Pratt, et al., Exh. 170 at 1375-77; Tr. 26 at 180, lns. 14-16 (Shapiro);
Public Exh. 7 (1994 Minnesota Fish Consumption Advisory).<p>
		The MPCA benefit transfer analysis utilizes sound inputs and explains each of
its steps in such a way as to present a useful tool for quantification of
environmental costs of mercury emissions.  While less convincing than the
damage cost approach applied by TER to criteria pollutants, it furthers the
legislative objectives of quantifying environmental costs to the extent
practicable.  Therefore, the ALJ recommends adoption of mercury values in the
range of $4359-9781 per pound  As the ongoing studies previously noted come to
conclusion, it is recommended that the Commission incorporate their results
into future proceedings modifying or applying environmental costs for mercury
emissions.<p>
<b>VI.	CRITERIA POLLUTANTS</b><p>
<b><u>Costs Below the NAAQS</u></b><p>
		Under the Clean Air Act, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has
set National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) for six pollutants commonly
known as the "criteria pollutants":  sulfur dioxides (SO2), nitrogen dioxides
(NO2), carbon monoxide (CO), ozone (O3), particulate matter smaller than 10
microns (PM10), and lead (Pb).  Ozone is a pollutant caused by the
transformation of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and volatile organic compounds (VOCs)
in the presence of sunlight.  Pratt Direct, Exh. 175, attached report at 1;
Pratt Rebuttal, Exh. 176 at 6, n.1; Exh 136 ("Assessing Environmental
Externality Costs for Electricity Generation," hereafter "TER Report"), V. 1 at
5-
                                                                                        
1
to 5-3.<p>
 		The Clean Air Act requires the NAAQS to be established at levels that are
protective of public health and welfare, including a margin of safety.  It also
requires the EPA to review the NAAQS every five years to ensure that the NAAQS
reflect the most recent scientific data.  42 U.S.C. [[section]]&nbsp;7409.  <p>
		Some parties have argued that as long as emissions do not cause ambient air
concentrations to exceed the NAAQS, there can be no costs associated with the
emission.  This argument assumes that there is indeed a discrete threshold
concentration of the criteria pollutants below which no costs occur, and that
the NAAQS are set below that threshold.<p>
	 	However, the record shows that there are as yet no defined thresholds below
which no effects occur.  As science progresses, pollution concentrations
previously thought to be safe are determined to cause negative effects.  This
has been acknowledged by both the EPA and Congress in the legislative history
to the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1977.  <u>Lead Industries Ass'n v.
Environmental Protection Agency</u>, 647 F.2d 1130, 1152-1154 (D.C. Cir. 1980),
<u>cert denied</u> 449 U.S. 1042 (Dec. 8, 1980).<p>
		EPA has not kept the NAAQS updated, and therefore the NAAQS do not reflect
the latest scientific knowledge.  In fact, there is substantial evidence of
health effects or other environmental costs at concentrations below the NAAQS
for several of the criteria pollutants, and particularly for PM10 and ozone.
Pratt Direct, Exh. 175, attached paper at 1-5; Lippman Direct, Exh. 130;
Lippman Surrebuttal, Exh. 132; TER Report, V.&nbsp;2 and V.&nbsp;4.<p>
		The ALJ therefore finds that the NAAQS are not necessarily set at no-cost
levels, and will not disregard evidence of environmental costs simply because
they are associated with ambient levels below the NAAQS.<p>
		TER's analysis of environmental costs applied stringent criteria that costs
had to meet before being counted in the analysis.  As a result of these
criteria, the TER analysis includes only effects (1) demonstrated to occur at
ambient levels, and (2) for which a concentration-response function can be
determined.  TER Report, V. 2 at 2-1 <p>
		TER determined the ambient levels of the various pollutants in the study area
drawing on available modeling data, and estimated the ambient levels that would
result from their selected resource scenarios using computer modeling.  TER
Report, V.&nbsp;1 at 4-7 and 5-6.<p>
		TER used concentration-response functions to quantify the relationship
between ambient levels and effects.  DPS witness Dr. Thayer reviewed in detail
the TER approach, and particularly its use of concentration response functions.
TER Report, V.&nbsp;2 at 2-10; TER Report, V.&nbsp;4 at 3-4; Exh. 187 (Thayer
Report) at 40-55.<p>
		The methodology employed by TER and reviewed by Thayer effectively screens
out costs associated with ambient pollution levels that are higher than those
currently in Minnesota (or expected to result from the scenario studied).  <p>
<p>
<b><u>VOCs and NOx - Agricultural Effects</u></b><p>
<b><u></u>	</b>	Volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and oxides of nitrogen (NOx)
react in the presence of sunlight to form ozone (O3).  TER Report, Exh. 136, V.
1 at 5-1  to 5-3; Pratt Rebuttal, Exh. 176 at 6, n. 1.<p>
		VOCs comprise a wide variety of organic compounds that exist in the gas phase
in the atmosphere and contribute to ozone formation.  Pratt Direct, Exh 175.,
attached paper at 3.  About 1% of VOCs are attributable to utility emissions in
Minnesota.  MPCA 1992 Emissions Inventory Survey, Exh. 183, last page; Tr. 20
at 165, lns. 7 -10 (Pratt).  The relative amount of VOCs emitted by utilities
is not relevant to the determination of the environmental cost per ton of VOC
emissions.  Tr. 20 at 165, lns. 11-15 (Pratt).<p>
		Maximum ozone concentrations in Minnesota have reached .11 ppm, close to the
NAAQS one-hour standard of .12 ppm.  Pratt Direct, Exh. 175, attached paper at
1.  Levels well below the current standards have been shown to cause
significant damages to agricultural crops, and EPA is presently reconsidering
the adequacy of its ozone standards.  The National Crop Loss Assessment Network
(NCLAN) has attributed crop losses from ozone nationwide in the billions of
dollars annually, much occurring in rural areas that attain all current ozone
standards.  <u>Id.</u>, at 2.  <p>
		Drawing on NCLAN and other crop loss information, TER reported that soybean
damage from ozone would constitute the largest agricultural damage measured in
its study.  Corn damage ranked second.  Corn and soybeans are, respectively,
the first and second ranking crops in Minnesota.  TER Report, Exh. 136, V. IV
at 5-1; V., VII at 3-19 through 3-20. <p>
		TER underestimated agricultural damages due to ozone because its modeling
incorrectly assumed that high NOx from a new power plant would scavenge
existing ozone, reducing the existing ozone's impact in the immediate vicinity
of the plant.  Pratt Rebuttal, Exh. 176 at 7.<p>
		TER's study lacked an adequate model for ozone, putting in doubt its effort
to develop a concentration-response function for agricultural effects of ozone.
Pratt Rebuttal, Exh. 176 at 6-7; Thayer Report, Exh. 187 at 2, 33-36.  On
difficulties of ozone modeling, also see Tr. 17 at 226, ln. 21 - p. 227, ln. 3
(Balentine).  In response, Dr. Pratt undertook an estimate of ozone damages
based directly on NCLAN national data on crop impacts of ozone.  Pratt
Rebuttal, Exh.&nbsp;176 at 7-9.<p>
		Dr. Pratt's calculation first takes national crop damage figures for ozone
from NCLAN, excludes damages for crops not grown in Minnesota, and then
performs a damage calculation which divides the remaining crop losses by the
total tons of ozone precursors NOx and VOCs emitted nationally.  Since NOx and
VOCs are both major contributors to ozone formation, the assumption of equal
contributions is warranted, and since national emissions of the two precursors
are virtually the same, the damage calculation yields a figure of $86 per ton
for each ton of NOx and each ton of VOCs.  Pratt Rebuttal, Exh. 176 at 8-9.<p>
		In the absence of good ozone modeling data for Minnesota, it is appropriate
to calculate VOC and NOx contribution to ozone agricultural damages using
national crop damage figures adjusted to include only crops grown in Minnesota.
Accordingly, the ALJ finds $86 per ton to represent a practicable
quantification of VOC damages to agriculture and recommends its adoption.<p>
		The ALJ further finds that $86 per ton also represents a practicable
quantification of NOx damages to agriculture and recommends that it be included
in the total NOx damage figures.<p>
<p>
<b><u>SO2</u></b><p>
<b>	</b>	Sulfur dioxide (SO2) emissions from coal-fired power plants, even when
within National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS), cause damage to public
health and the environment.  TER Report, Exh. 136, V. 2, [[section]]&nbsp;3, V.
4, [[section]]&nbsp;3.5, V. 5, [[section]][[section]]&nbsp;2-3, V.&nbsp;7,
tables 3-1 and 3-2; Pratt Direct, Exh. 175 attached paper at 2-3; Thayer
Report, Exh. 187<b> </b>at 17, 38-40.<p>
<b>	</b>	SO2 damages quantified in the TER Report included only direct effects
of SO2 and excluded all damages from secondary particulates (or "transformation
products") formed from reactions of SO2 in the atmosphere.  Tr. 17 at 259, ln.
6 - p. 260, ln. 23 (Desvousges).  The SO2 transformation products have
significant near-field and long-range impacts on public health, visibility, and
ecological systems.  Pratt Direct, Exh. 175, attached paper at 3; Thayer
Report, Exh. 187 at 19-33.  Thayer &amp; Associates estimated that counting
effects of those SO2 transformation products could triple the damages
attributed to PM10 by TER.  Exh. 187 at 23; Tr.&nbsp;21 at 119,
ln.&nbsp;19-p.&nbsp;120, ln.&nbsp;15 (Thayer).  Since PM10 damages are much
higher than SO2 damages, as reported by TER, the increase in TER's estimated
SO2 damages would be many-fold if damages from SO2 transformation products were
included and attributed to SO2 rather than PM10.  Dr. Thayer agreed that it
would be fair to allocate to SO2 damages from SO2 transformation products.  Tr.
21 at 141.<p>
		SO2 emissions from coal-fired electric generating units are addressed by
Title IV of the federal Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, 42 U.S.C.
[[section]][[section]]&nbsp;7651-7651o.  As evident from its title "Acid
Deposition Control" and from the Congressional findings in 42 U.S.C.
[[section]]&nbsp;7651(a), this part of the 1990 legislation primarily sought to
reduce acid deposition by reducing its "precursors," SO2 and NOx, emitted from
electric generating units.  As it relates to this proceeding, Title IV
establishes a national emissions cap for utilities' SO2 emissions to become
effective in the year 2000 and allocates to utilities SO2 emission allowances
("rights" to emit SO2) generally based on historic emission rates with some
additional allowances granted to politically strategic regions.  McCarron
Direct, Exh. 163 at 2-3; Tr. 8 at 116, ln. 25 - p. 117, ln. 7 (Brockett)<p>
		A key feature of the Title IV program is that utilities can buy and sell the
allowances, ideally resulting in firms with high pollution control costs
purchasing allowances to emit from firms with low control costs.  This process
is intended to achieve the national cap with total control costs kept to a
minimum.  McCarron Direct, Exh. 163 at 3.  A number of parties, relying on the
economists' concept of  cost "internalization," argue that zero value should be
assigned to SO2 emissions because some allowance payment or foregone
"opportunity cost" (in the event a firm uses its own allowances) will be paid
for every new plant that will emit SO2. <p>
		Even proponents of zero values conceded that if national SO2 emissions are
reduced below the cap so that allowances lose all value, then it would be
appropriate to assign a positive value to SO2.  Tr. 8 at 122, lns. 19-20
(Brockett); Tr. 27 at 116, ln. 15 - p. 118, ln. 23 (Nichols).<p>
		It is clear on the record that SO2 trading program is directed to
ameliorating acid rain and visibility concerns from long-range transport of
transformation products.  Tr. 7 at 129-30 (Sansom); Senate Comm. on Env't &amp;
Public Works, Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, S.&nbsp;Rep. No. 101-228, 101st
Cong., 2nd Sess., reprinted in 1990 U.S.C.C.A.N., vol. 6, 3385, 3645 <u>et</u>
<u>seq</u>.  It does not eliminate and, at most, would have only an indirect
effect on the localized, geographically-sensitive SO2 damages measured by TER.
McCarron Direct, Exh. 163 at 8-12.  Most importantly, there is no connection
between the price of allowance trades and the marginal damages of new SO2
emissions.  Tr. 2 at 20, ln 17 - p. 21, ln. 3 (Harrison); Tr. 7 at 128, ln. 19
- p.&nbsp;129, ln. 7 (Sansom); Tr. 27 at 120, lns. 13 - 15 (Nichols); McCarron
Direct, Exh. 163 at 5.<p>
		The record is bereft of evidence on what trades are occurring, between which
geographical locations, and at what prices.  It only discloses that some
utilities are finding it unnecessary to use the allowances currently granted
them so they are "banking" those allowances for future credit.  Tr. 27 at 116,
lns. 4 -14(Nichols).  It is clear that the proponents of zero values for SO2
are urging application of the economists' view of the trading scheme in the
abstract, or as a matter of "policy."  E.g., Tr. 16 at 95, ln. 9 - p . 101, ln.
10 (Desvousges); Tr.&nbsp;21 at 119, ln. 19 - p. 122, ln. 6 (Thayer).<p>
		It would follow from the zero value proponents' view of allowance trading
that, hypothetically, one dollar paid for the right to emit necessarily
eliminates from environmental cost consideration $100,000 in damages such as
chronic pulmonary impairment, crop losses, impaired visibility, and lake
acidification that may result from new SO2 emissions.  The legislative mandate
is to establish the "environmental costs" of electricity generation and
accepting this conceptual approach would directly violate that mandate.  <p>
		Actual reductions in emissions resulting from allowance purchases, as
contrasted to use of "banked" allowances, are true environmental benefits that
appropriately could be considered by the Commission in specific resource
planning proceedings.  The "Pandora's box" that allegedly will be opened by
assessing environmental costs and then crediting actual environmental offsets
is not an appropriate factor for this proceeding because it falls within the
applications issues previously excluded.  The ALJ recommends that the
Commission not let such future tasks obstruct establishment of values for the
important criteria pollutant SO2.<p>
		The ALJ finds that the median TER values are appropriate minimums for SO2
environmental costs.  These values are $21/ton (rural), $54/ton (metropolitan
fringe), and $126 (urban).  A high end for the SO2 range cannot be set at this
time since the record is incomplete on the significant SO2 costs attributable
to secondary particulates.  The ALJ recommends that the Commission direct
parties to future proceedings involving SO2 costs to include damages from
secondary particulates in total SO2  damage calculations.<p>
<p>
Dated:&nbsp;&nbsp;February 23, 1996.		HUBERT H. HUMPHREY III<p>
Attorney General<p>
State of Minnesota<p>
