<HEAD><TITLE>Sample Letter to Representative in Support of Making EPA Mercury Study Public Information</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H3>Sample Letter to Representative in Support of Making EPA Mercury Study Public Information</H3>



<HR>

Dear Representative/Senator _____________:<P>

Your help is urgently needed to assure that a four-year, 1,700-page study of the health and environmental effects of mercury, a toxic heavy metal, is submitted to Congress promptly, as required by law.<P>

Mercury is a heavy metal known to be poisonous at high concentrations.  It can cause severe, irreparable injury to human and animal nervous systems.  Unnaturally high levels of mercury are found in a wide variety of wildlife, ranging from lake trout to deep ocean fish to loons to Florida panthers, even in remote wilderness areas.  It is also found in people who routinely consume fish for subsistence.  A 1990 study in Wisconsin, for example, found that many Chippewa Indians have blood mercury levels above five parts per billion, which is believed to be high enough to injure developing fetuses.<P>

Although releases of mercury to the environment have declined dramatically in the United States over the past three decades, its continued presence throughout the Unites States continues to raise grave concerns.  For this reason, the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments required the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency to conduct a study of the metal's sources and effects and to identify control options.  The study does not propose any new rules or regulations or otherwise trigger new controls.  It does, however, provide valuable and timely information that can be used by the public, as well as by state, local and federal governments.  The study was effectively completed in December, 1995 after thorough internal and external peer review.  Instead of submitting the report directly to Congress, however, the Agency has sent it to its Science Advisory Board for a review that will delay the report's release until 1999 or later.  It could literally be the next millennium before the report becomes final.<P>

EPA is delaying the report because "new studies are expected to be published over the next several years."  Some of these studies have not been completed, let alone peer reviewed or published.  In the meantime, the public must make decisions in the absence of a final report containing literally thousands of important and relevant facts and findings.<P>

We believe the mercury study should be submitted to the Congress now, not in the next century.  Some members of Congress, including Senator Leahy, are organizing efforts to cause this to happen.  We hope you will not only support those efforts, but also initiate your own.<P>

Sincerely,<P>

<BR>
__________________<P>

<HR>
Here is a link to the <A HREF="http://www.me3.org/mailreps.html">E-mail addresses of the Minnesota Congressional Delegation</A> and to the <A HREF="http://www.geocities.com/CapitolHill/1007/">E-mail addresses of all members of Congress.</A><P>



Just cut and paste from the sample message above and/or add what you want to say.<P>

<HR>
