<HEAD><TITLE>EPA's Mercury Study to Congress</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H3>EPA's Mercury Study to Congress</H3><P>

The EPA's report to Congress is contained in seven volumes which are briefly described below.<P>

<B>Volume I</B>	Executive Summary<P>

<B>Volume II</B>	Inventory of Anthropogenic Mercury Emissions in the United States<P>

The EPA Mercury Study Report to Congress estimates that the anthropogenic emissions of mercury in the U.S. are between 200 and 300 metric tons per year.  An estimate of the total annual input from anthropogenic sources globally is approximately 4,000 tons.  This is a best estimate given the available data.  The largest sources of mercury emissions in the U.S. are:  incinerators that combust mercury-containing waste (municipal or medical), the combustion of fossil fuels in utility, commercial, and other boilers, and smelting operations. Manufacturing plants are another large source of mercury emissions.<P>

<BR>
<B>Volume III</B>	An Assessment of Exposure from Anthropogenic Mercury Emissions<P>

An exposure assessment was divided into two components in the EPA's study - a long range transport analysis and a local impact analysis.  Representative emission types were modeled and located in various terrains and climates.  Exposure estimates were developed through fate and transport modeling for mid-range exposure as well as for populations that were expected to have higher mercury exposures.  <P>

<BR>
<B>Volume IV</B>	Health Effects of Mercury and Mercury Compounds<P>

Methylmercury can produce a variety of adverse effects, depending on the dose and time of exposure.  The risk assessment process for methylmercury depends in part on available data describing dose-response and exposure to methylmercury.  As additional data are available, risk assessments may be modified.  Neurotoxicity is the effect of greatest concern when exposure occurs to the developing fetus during pregnancy, as well as when children and adults are exposed to methylmercury.  Outward signs of methylmercury poisoning include impairment of the peripheral vision; disturbances in sensations (pins and needles, numbness);  uncoordinated movements, as in writing;  impairment of speech;  impairment of hearing;  impairment of walking;  delays in motor and language development, and mental disturbances.<P>

<B>Volume V</B>	An Ecological Assessment of Anthropogenic Mercury Emissions in the U.S.<P>

Current levels of mercury in freshwater fish in the United States are such that advisories have been issued in 35 states that warn against the consumption of certain amounts and species of fish that are contaminated with mercury.  On average, fish from marine species have mercury concentrations below the level necessary to trigger an advisory.<P>

<BR>
<B>Volume VI</B>	Characterization of Human Health and Wildlife Risks from Anthropogenic Mercury Emissions in the United States<P>

Humans and wildlife within the U.S. that routinely consume certain species of fish, or routinely consume fish from contaminated waters are potentially at an increased risk of methylmercury poisoning.  There are also several subgroups that are at an even heightened risk.<P>

Methylmercury is bioaccumulated, so the concentration factor is extreme in animals that are higher up on the food chain, like piscivors.  Although sub-lethal effects of methylmercury poisoning include a number of different organs, reproductive effects in animals are the primary concern.  These occur at concentrations far lower than those that cause acute toxicity.<P>

<BR>
<B>Volume VII</B> 	An Evaluation of Mercury Control Techniques and Costs<P>

Effective control of mercury emissions may require a mix of strategies including pollution prevention, materials separation, and conventional regulatory strategies to control mercury emissions at the stack.<P>

<BR>
<B>Supplement A</B>	Summary of the Scientific Peer Review<P>

<HR>
