<HEAD><TITLE>Mercury Report Process</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<H3>Mercury Report Process</H3><P>

The Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 required the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) to produce a study of mercury emissions, including the sources, rates and amounts, control technologies and their costs, and health and environmental effects.  The report was generated with input from interested parties through meetings with the EPA authors and public presentation of preliminary assessments at conferences and scientific meetings.  Internal scientific review was begun in November 1994.  Federal interagency review (by the Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry, the National Institute for Environmental Health Sciences, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, the U.S. Department of Agriculture, the Department of Energy, the Food and Drug Administration and the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service) and subsequent external review by non-Federal experts was conducted beginning in January 1995.  Revisions continue to be made in response to these reviews, further internal review, and comment by OMB.<P>

A court order resulting from a suit brought against EPA by the Sierra Club and the Natural Resources Defense Council required that EPA transmit the report to Congress by December 15, 1995.  To date, the report has not been released in final form.  EPA's rationale for not meeting the deadline was that two human epidemiological studies on mercury exposure from fish and shellfish were expected to be published in January 1996 and inclusion of results from these studies was important.  Previous epidemiological studies involved severe poisoning and more subtle indications of mercury-induced disease were desired to assist in estimating a level of mercury exposure which would not cause adverse effects.<P>

The studies, which are being conducted in the Seychelles Islands and the Faroe Islands, have not been published in full to date, and results from them will not be available for several months at a minimum.<P>

<HR>
