<HEAD><TITLE>Chronology of Events: EPA Mercury Study</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H3>Chronology of Events: EPA Mercury Study</H3><P>

<B>Statutory Requirements</B><P>

1990: Section 112(n)(1) of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 requires EPA to submit Mercury Study to Congress by November 1994; regular meetings between EPA, industry representatives, and other interested parties begun.<P>

<B>EPA Efforts</B><P>
<UL>
<LI>1992:  Work on Mercury Study begun; to date, approximately $1 million in Federal contract funds and the effort of many Agency scientists has been expended in preparing this report.<P>

<LI>1992:  EPA national study indicates widespread mercury contamination in freshwater fish in U.S. surface water.<P>

<LI>December 1993:  EPA publishes interim final emissions inventory as a technical report.<P>
</UL>

<B>Peer Review</B><P>
<UL>
<LI>November 1994:  Statutory deadline for Mercury Study to be submitted to Congress; Scientific review of Mercury Study begun by 7 federal agencies and 16 outside experts.<P>

<LI>January 1995: Interagency and external review meetings held.<P>

<LI>July 1995:  Two additional external review panels convened to review fish consumption analysis and risk characterization aspects of draft study.<P>

<LI>August 1995:  Mercury Study redrafted.<P>

<LI>October 1995:  Department of Health and Human Services convenes panel of Environmental Health Policy Committee to address risk communication issues and other scientific questions.<P>

<LI>February/March 1996:  2 more drafts circulated for interagency review.<P>

<LI>June 1996:  EPA Science Advisory Board scheduled to review study.
</UL><P>

<B>Court Orders</B><P>
<UL>
<LI>December 15, 1995: Court order deadline (resulting from a suit brought against EPA by the Sierra Club and the Natural Resources Defense Council) for EPA to transmit the report to Congress; study not released.<BR>
<LI>April 15, 1996: EPA again misses commitment to the court to transmit the study to Congress.
</UL><P>
