<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Science Behind the Mercury Study</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<H3>Science Behind the Mercury Study</H3><P>

Science is a dynamic, iterative and necessarily democratic process.  EPA's Mercury Study Report to Congress involved stakeholders from state and federal government, academia, and public and private interests working together to advance the public's understanding on the complex nature of mercury and focus public discourse on outstanding issues that demand further investigation.<P>

The Mercury Study that began in 1991 in response to Section 112(n)(1) of the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments required EPA to assess the emissions, health and environmental effects, control measures and costs associated with reducing mercury emissions in the U.S.  EPA's study closely followed federal risk assessment guidelines including recent recommendations by the National Academy of Sciences to improve risk characterization practices.  An extensive scientific peer review was conducted both within EPA and through a formal external peer review process in early January, 1995.<P>

In December 1995, EPA postponed the release of the Mercury Study until the publication of the Seychelles Island study that reportedly provided a basis for adjusting the current reference dose for methylmercury.  However, only the partial results of the Seychelles Island study were published in January 1996, and those results represent only the first portion of a study that assesses developmental effects of methylmercury in children.  Several additional research studies are expected to be published over the next several years that will provide reduce the uncertainties surrounding EPA's reference dose, or the dose-response estimates intended to be protective of public health.  EPA has committed to reviewing these complete studies and re-examining and adjusting the reference dose as needed.<P>

"The draft report and reviewer's comments clearly show that, while we do not know nearly as much as we would like to about environmental mercury, we know a lot." -February, 1996 comment of Mercury Study Peer Review Workshop Chair Paul Mushak, Ph.D.<P>

<BR>
<B>What do we know about the human health effects of mercury</B>?<P>

Methylmercury is a potent toxin that causes impairment of the central nervous system (CNS) and developmental toxicity in humans.  The primary route of exposure for humans and wildlife to methylmercury is consumption of contaminated fish.<P>

Although the toxic effects of mercury have been known for over a century, two poisoning epidemics link methylmercury in food to neurological disease in humans and animals.  One of the earliest recorded poisonings was from consumption of fish and shellfish contaminated with methylmercury in Minamata Bay and Niigata, Japan.  The effect of greatest concern identified after this poisoning epidemic was the observation that infants, born of mothers who had consumed the methylmercury contaminated food, showed nervous system damage.  A study following a mass poisoning resulting from consumption of mercury fungicide treated-grains (used to make bread) in Iraq in the early 1970's confirmed methylmercury as a developmental neurotoxicant.  Delays in motor and language development (e.g., delayed walking, delayed talking), seizures or delayed mental development, and low scores on clinical tests of nervous system function were the endpoints used to document the effects of methylmercury in children exposed in utero to relatively high levels of methylmercury.<P>

Although human health effects at lower levels of methylmercury exposure cannot be discerned from these poisoning episodes, we do know that methylmercury easily crosses the placenta and may concentrate in the fetus during central nervous system development.  Therefore, methylmercury may produce more subtle neurodevelopmental effects such as impairment of sensory or cognitive systems at lower levels of exposure.  These subtle indicators of neurotoxicity are important in identifying levels of exposure not likely to cause adverse effects.<P>

Although the U.S. populations that obtain their fish commercially are not believed to be adversely affects by methylmercury if they consume fish in moderation, people in the U.S. who routinely consume certain species of fish or fish from highly contaminated areas are potentially at increased risk.  In particular, women of child-bearing age are considered of concern because of adverse effects of methylmercury on the developing nervous system.  In addition, children ages 1 and younger are of concern because they have higher exposures to methylmercury from fish on a per kilogram body weight basis compared with adults.  The Mercury Study presents a summary of the risk management activities over the past two decades of the U.S. FDA, U.S. EPA and state and local agencies that specifically issue fish consumption advisories or other guidance that targets these high risk groups.<P>

<BR>
<B>What is a reference dose and how is calculated?</B><P>

Because of the widespread contamination of fish and potential for adverse health effects from methylmercury exposure, especially in pregnant women and children, several risk management activities to limit fish consumption have been undertaken by local and state agencies, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA), the World Health Organization, and the U.S. EPA.  State fish consumption advisories are often issued to address local conditions and are generally based on the Food and Drug Administrations' (FDA) action level for commercial fishing of 1 ppm.  The U.S. EPA uses the reference dose (RfD) method to estimate a daily exposure to the human population that is likely to be without appreciable risk of deleterious effects during a lifetime.<P>

EPA calculated an RfD for methylmercury using data on neurologic changes in Iraqi children who had been exposed in utero from mothers who ate contaminated bread during pregnancy.  The RfD is the midpoint in an estimated range of about an order of magnitude that is protective of human health.  Uncertainties in the RfD accounted for in this range include the reliability in recording or classifying events several months after the child's birth, other factors in estimating the maternal dose of methylmercury, and the size of the population studied in Iraq.  The weight of evidence from additional studies of developmental delays in children exposed in utero to methylmercury among the Cree Indians in Canada and New Zealanders, and animal studies, support protective public health measures to reduce exposures of high risk groups to methylmercury.<P>

<BR>
<B>What are the implications of other studies underway that address methylmercury exposures associated with neurological effects?</B><P>

Several research studies, most notably the Seychelles Island and Faroe Island studies, are underway to address the question of low level methylmercury exposure from consumption of ocean fish and neurological effects in children exposed in utero.  In the January 1995 peer review draft of the Mercury Study, EPA discussed both the value of these studies for the evaluation of more subtle neurological effects of methylmercury exposure than was possible in previous studies, and reduction of uncertainties associated with the current RfD.  EPA committed to evaluate these and other forthcoming studies in order to adjust the RfD as needed to reflect the best available health effects data.<P>

One reason for delaying the release of the Mercury Study in December 1995 was the impending publication of the Seychelles Island study that was thought to provide a substantial basis for adjusting the current RfD.  However, only the partial results of the Seychelles Island study were published in NeuroToxicology at the end of January 1996, representing only the first portion of the study that assesses developmental effects of methylmercury in children up to the age of 29 months.  Additional data on children up to 6 years of age are expected to be published in the next year.  Measuring subtle neurotoxic effects requires that children be tested at an age (in some cases, much later than 29 months) when these subtle effects can manifest.  Therefore, it is critical that the complete results of the study be evaluated before any conclusions can be drawn regarding safe levels of methylmercury.  The Seychelles Island researchers conclude that "[a]dditional follow-up data are necessary to determine if more adverse effects occur at older ages and if those effects are related to mercury."<P>

Until results from the Faroe Island study are published, the current RfD developed in May 1995 based on the Iraqi study remains the best available scientific understanding of data associating maternal exposures to methylmercury with adverse neurological effects in the developing infant.  As additional studies become available, EPA is expected to re-examine the RfD and adjust it as necessary.<P>

<BR>
<B>What have we learned from lead that may apply to mercury?</B><P>

Lead is similar to mercury in that it also is known to affect the functioning of the central nervous system.  Lead exposure through both inhalation and ingestion is widely recognized to be detrimental to children and adults alike, and aggressive action has been taken in recent years to reduce lead exposures.  Current research suggests a non-threshold, linear dose-response relationship between lead exposure and reduced cognitive development in children. The "action" level of exposure to lead has been consistently reduced as additional scientific evidence of this nature is presented.<P>

<HR>
