<HEAD><TITLE>Reference Dose</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<H3>Reference Dose</H3><P>

<B>What is a reference dose and how is calculated?</B><P>

A reference dose (RfD) is defined as an estimate (with uncertainty spanning perhaps an order of a magnitude) of a daily exposure to the human population including sensitive subgroups that is likely to be without an appreciable risk of deleterious effects during a lifetime.  An RfD can be understood as a level of exposure not likely to cause adverse health effects.  The revised RfD used for methylmercury by the EPA was published in May of 1995.  It is based on the scientific understanding of the best available data associating maternal exposures to methylmercury with adverse neurological effects in the developing infant.<P>

<B>How do EPA and FDA mercury standards compare?</B><P>

The EPA's RfD is a risk assessment level which is expressed in terms of a daily intake.  The RfD is not directly comparable to the FDA's action level, which is a risk management level limiting the concentration of mercury that can be present in fish sold in commerce to 1 ppm.  The FDA action level takes into account the health effects of mercury, how much fish the average person consumes, the variety of fish that people consume, and how often they eat fish.<P>

FDA's Acceptable Daily Intake (ADI) level of 0.47 micrograms per kg of body weight per day can be compared to EPA's RfD; it is about four-fold greater than EPA's RfD of 0.1 micrograms per kg of body weight per day. This difference can be attributed to the different populations for which these values were calculated.  EPA's RfD is intended to protect fetuses from harmful developmental effects,whereas FDA's ADI is intended to protect the average adult person who would be able to tolerate higher levels of methylmercury. FDA has acknowledged that the fetus may be more sensitive than adults to the effects of mercury.  In fact, the FDA has advised pregnant women and women of child-bearing age to limit their consumption of fish known to have high levels of mercury.  This FDA advice demonstrates a concern for protecting the most sensitive populations that appears to be contradicted by FDA's apparent reluctance to approve the release of the Mercury Study to the public.<P>


<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD>Regulating Agency</TD><TD>Reference Dose (or ADI)</TD><TD>Based On</TD><TD>How Used</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>EPA</TD><TD>0.1 micrograms per kg of body weight per day</TD><TD>An RfD is based on the scientific understanding of the best available data associating maternal exposures to methylmercury with adverse neurological effects in the developing infant.</TD><TD>Setting national standards for mercury emissions limits.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>FDA</TD><TD>0.47 micrograms per kg of body weight per day</TD><TD>The health effects of mercury, how much fish the average person consumes, the variety of fish that people consume, and how often they eat fish.</TD><TD>Regulating the mercury levels of fish sold in commerce.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>States</TD><TD>varies; usually based on the FDA level</TD><TD>The health effects of mercury, how much fish the average person consumes, the variety of fish that people consume, and how often they eat fish.</TD><TD>Used to determine if fish advisories are required for fresh water fish.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
