<HEAD><TITLE>>Populations at risk of methylmercury</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<H3>Populations at risk of methylmercury</H3><P>

<B>Pregnant Women and the Developing Fetus</B><P>

Neurotoxicity is the effect of greatest concern the developing fetus is exposed during pregnancy.  The effects of methylmercury on the central nervous system of the developing fetus were seen in the Minamata Bay mercury poisoning outbreaks in the 1950's, and in an Iraqi mercury poisoning incident which occurred in the 1970's.  In both cases, a large population was exposed to high methylmercury levels in food.  Several endpoints, including late walking, late talking, seizures, nervous system dysfunction, and delayed mental development were seen in children who were exposed to high levels of methylmercury in utero.<P>

It should be noted that some of the developmental delays were substantial - for example, a child being unable to walk two steps without support at two years of age, inability to talk based on use of two or three meaningful words by 24 months, and the presence of generalized convulsive seizures.  In many cases, infants born of mothers who had consumed methylmercury, particularly during the second trimester of pregnancy, have shown nervous system damage even though the mothers themselves were only slightly affected.  Research needs include studies that will delineate the most appropriate indicators for neurotoxic effects for individuals exposed to methylmercury in utero.<P>

<B>Children</B><P>

Persons within the U.S. that routinely consume certain species of fish, or routinely consume fish from contaminated waters are potentially at an increased risk of methylmercury poisoning.  There are also several subgroups that are at an even heightened risk.  Young children are one of these groups of concern.  Since methylmercury intake is expressed on a per kilogram body weight basis, the exposure of children age 14 and under is approximately 2-3 times that of the adults, because of their higher food intake per bodyweight.<P>

There are approximately 665,000 children in the United States who consume fish in the quantity of 100 grams per day or more (the standard used to evaluate rate of adult fish consumption).  100 grams is slightly less than a quarter of a pound of fish.  Since children have a smaller body weight as compared with adults, consumption of less than 100 grams of fish per day could also be a concern for children under the age of fourteen. Methylmercury is bioaccumulated, so the concentration factor is extreme in animals that are higher up on the food chain, like humans.  Children have a longer time period in which to bioaccumulate this mercury and to register its effects.  Symptoms of mercury poisoning are the following:  impairment of the peripheral vision; disturbances in sensations (pins and needles, numbness);  uncoordinated movements, as in writing;  impairment of speech;  impairment of hearing;  impairment of walking;  delays in motor and language development, and mental disturbances.  In extreme cases, death can occur.  Methylmercury poisoning can also have an impact on the central nervous system, and is hypothesized to effect the reproductive system, the immune system, and to have genotoxic effects.  However, data is absent, inadequate or conflicting in these areas.<P>

<HR>
