<b>Footnotes-Reply Brief of the Environmental Coalition</b><p>
<a name="fn0">[1]</a><u>Webster's Ninth New Collegiate
Dictionary</u> (Merriam-Webster, 1984) notes that "one who attempts to avoid
danger by refusing to face it" is labelled an ostrich because of "the belief
that the ostrich, when pursued, hides his head in the sand and believes himself
to be unseen."<p>
<a name="fn1">[2]</a>It is ironic that several of the parties that argue that
the criteria pollutants should not be valued because they are subject to
regulatory controls also contend that carbon dioxide and mercury should not be
valued because these pollutants <u>are not</u> yet regulated.<p>
<a name="fn2">[3]</a>The Natural Gas Utilities' brief, at 21, incorrectly
states that "the eleven studies . . . estimate the cost of controlling carbon
dioxide levels through taxes."  These studies examine a wide range of carbon
dioxide emission abatement techniques.<p>
<a name="fn3">[4]</a>Minnesota Power also suggests that any losses to the
recreational fishing industry associated with mercury emissions will be made up
as people substitute casino gambling, deer hunting, boating, etc.  <i>MP, at
50.</i>  Whether this is true or not, it is not relevant to the Environmental
Coalition's testimony, which used expenditures on recreational fishing to
determine what people are willing to pay to catch fish -- not the impact on the
state's economy.  <i>See EC, at 19-20 and Ex. 234, at 20.
</body></html>
