<HEAD>
<TITLE>Global Climate Change and Mercury Pollution:  Issues in Minnesota's Environmental Externalities Decision</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><CENTER><H1>Global Climate Change and Mercury Pollution:  Issues in Minnesota's Environmental Externalities Decision</H1>
Jeremy Schreifels<P>
Michael Noble<P>
Janet Drake Hamilton<P>
September 1996</CENTER><P>

<H2>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</H2>
It is widely recognized that the generation of electricity from the combustion of fossil fuels is accompanied by unwanted environmental effects. Those effects impose costs on Minnesota's citizens and the economy. Since such costs are not included in the market price of energy, economists regard these costs as environmental "externalities."<P>
In mid-September 1996, the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (Commission) will begin consideration of a public record compiled in 1994 and 1995 for the purpose of establishing environmental-cost values for pollutants from electricity generation. In March 1994, the Commission set interim values for environmental costs based on the findings of the Department of Public Service and ordered a formal evidentiary hearing to establish final values for these costs.<P>
The Commission will base its final values, in part, on a decision by Judge Allan W. Klein, the Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) assigned to conduct the evidentiary hearing and make findings and recommendations in the case. The ALJ's recommendations were made after a formal evidentiary hearing with many parties sponsoring expert testimony. Those parties included utilities, fuel suppliers, state agencies, and environmental groups (Appendix I provides a complete list).<P>
By agreement of the parties, testimony focused on environmental-cost values associated with air emissions from fossil fuel generation. Expert testimony was filed regarding carbon dioxide (CO2), carbon monoxide (CO), lead (Pb), mercury (Hg), methane (CH4), nitrogen oxides (NOx), particulate matter smaller than ten microns (PM10), sulfur dioxide (SO2), and volatile organic chemicals (VOCs). In large part, the ALJ's findings and recommendations are based upon the weight of the expert evidence in the record which, in most cases, constitutes the best scientific understanding of the costs and damages related to each pollutant.<P>
However, for two emissions, carbon dioxide and mercury, the ALJ's findings and recommendations are inconsistent with the weight of evidence in the record, evidence that is increasingly being confirmed by major new scientific agreements reached since the closing of the record. In the case of carbon dioxide and mercury, the ALJ's findings and recommendations are inconsistent with the most recent information from the scientific community. This must be corrected by the Commission in its final decision. To correct the values the Commission must make three modifications to the ALJ's recommendations.<P>
First, the Commission must take administrative notice of the Second Assessment of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), and use  a damage-cost estimate more consistent with current scientific consensus. Where the ALJ relies on some evidence in the record supporting a finding that damage to the world's economy (and by extension, Minnesota's) will be one percent of gross world output, the consensus of the Second Assessment is that it will more likely be "a few percent." A conservative estimate of two percent of global gross world output more accurately represents the environmental costs of electricity generation, yet adheres to the ALJ's recommendation to use conservative values.<P>
The ability of the Commission to take judicial notice of a document released after the close of the official record is fully consistent with Minnesota law because the document is essential to a complete and fair determination of the case. The importance of the Second Assessment to a complete understanding of the issue is evidenced by the strenuous arguments of the Western Fuels Association attorney seeking to prevent the Commission from taking notice of the current scientific consensus on global climate change.<P>
Second, the ALJ's selection of a social-discount rate of three to five percent has the effect of trivializing enormous damages, marginalizing our grandchildren, and effectively arguing that it is not cost-effective to avoid future damages that are long-term, irreversible, and potentially catastrophic. While social-discount rates and how they are set can generate considerable debate, this report will persuasively argue that the use of such rates must pass the test of common sense, and that huge long-term irreversible damages cannot reasonably be discounted to negligible costs in present value.<P>
Because of the intergenerational scope of global climate change the most appropriate discount rate is zero percent. Even a discount rate of between one and three percent is more appropriate than the three to five percent recommended by the ALJ. Discount rates of one and three percent, coupled with a reasonable estimate of two percent of gross world output, provide a range of environmental cost values for carbon dioxide of $5.84 to $28.58 per ton. This range of values is fully supported by the evidence presented in the IPCC's Second Assessment as well as the evidentiary hearing.<P>
Third, the ALJ affirms that the record shows strong consensus that mercury pollution causes great damages to Minnesota's economy and the health of its citizens and ecosystems. The failure to establish a value for mercury is equivalent to establishing a value of zero - this is clearly inconsistent with the record and intent of Minnesota law.<P>
Because of the extremely high risks associated with mercury pollution, interim values should be adopted until more complete studies can provide the necessary information to determine a final range of values. The range of values proposed by the Minnesota Office of the Attorney General (OAG) should be used to establish an interim range of values of $1,429 to $4,359 per pound of mercury. The ALJ supported these values as the best representation of the environmental costs, and stated, "[t]he OAG calculation is the best one on record..."<P>
At issue here is the health and quality of life of the citizens of Minnesota and the rest of Earth. The Minnesota legislature took a significant first step by requiring utilities to account for environmental costs in their resource planning decisions. It is now the responsibility of the Commission to amend the ALJ's recommendations and establish a reasonable range of values for carbon dioxide of $5.84 to $28.58 per ton and an interim value for mercury of $1,429 to $4,359 per pound.<P><P>

<H2>INTRODUCTION</H2>
In 1991 the Minnesota Legislature passed a law to protect Minnesota's environment and the health of its citizens by requiring the quantification of the environmental costs (including human health costs) of electricity generation.1 In 1993, the Legislature revised the law and set a timetable for the formulation of environmental cost values.2 The statute required the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (Commission) to establish a range of estimates for the environmental costs of electricity generation. Coal industry rhetoric to the contrary, this valuation exercise does not raise the cost of electricity, does not bind the Commission to order the selection of noneconomic energy resources, but only requires the Commission to estimate the real costs. The original statute required a very liberal application of these external costs, requiring that independent renewable-energy power producers be paid an 'adder', or bonus, for the value of the avoided environmental damages. In the 1993 revision, the legislature backed away from this requirement, asking for a much more conservative review of the costs. The Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) argued that the values themselves should be very conservative; instead, they should be as accurate as science will allow, and conservatism can be used in the application of these costs to policy decision-making.<P><P>

<H3>Summary of the Methods and Findings Regarding Regulated Pollutants</H3>
In March 1996, the ALJ released his findings, conclusions, and recommendations. The report recommended ranges of values for the environmental costs of several pollutants for different geographical regions (Table 1). These regional groupings were necessary because much of the damage caused by most pollutants depends largely on site-specific factors including the concentrations of the pollutant and the density of populations exposed to pollution. To simplify the process three regions were created: rural, metropolitan fringe and urban.<P>
