<P>


<H3>Inadequacies of the ALJ's Recommendation for Carbon Dioxide</H3>

In recommending a range of values for carbon dioxide, the ALJ embraced the breadth of evidence recognized by the world's climate scientists. Scientific consensus is articulated by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) created in 1988 by the World Meteorological Organization and the United Nations Environment Programme to evaluate the environmental impacts associated with anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide. The IPCC consists of 2,500 scientists from around the globe; this group of scientists is regarded as the "definitive clearinghouse for research on [global climate change]."<P>
The ALJ categorically rejected hours of testimony of the so-called professional global-warming skeptics, the scientific voices from the thin right edge of the bell curve reflecting scientific consensus on the issue. The appearance in Saint Paul of professional naysayers such as <P>
Lindzen, Michaels, Balling and Idso was discussed in a December 1995 Harper's Magazine essay, "The Heat is On," whose author visited Saint Paul's hearing room to hear the testimony.4 These same skeptics have enjoyed thorough media coverage, most recently in the New York Times, which did a feature on MIT's Richard Lindzen.5<P>
In embracing mainstream global-warming science, the ALJ demonstrated that the State of Minnesota should recognize the need to curb global climate change. Unfortunately, however, there are two inadequacies in the ALJ's finding that severely skew the range of economic values he assigns, effectively rendering the damage cost estimate insignificant, giving the coal industry a victory, even in defeat. The range of values recommended by the ALJ does not properly address the impacts of global climate change. Based on current scientific understanding, a higher range of values-between $5.84 and $28.58 per ton of carbon dioxide emissions-would be more appropriate.7<P><P>

<H3>Inadequacies of the ALJ's Recommendation for Mercury</H3>
For the pollutant mercury, the ALJ recommended that no value be used until more information becomes available. This decision is very troubling considering the agreement among parties that mercury posed a significant threat to the environment and human health. No knowledgeable witness in the hearings denied the threat posed by mercury.51 Testimony at the public hearing and public letters showed a great consensus in favor of establishing values for mercury. The ALJ declared, "It is frustrating to conclude that there is insufficient evidence to recommend a value for mercury in light of the broad consensus about mercury's toxicity and the need to reduce human (as well as animal) exposure."52<P>
Although there are some uncertainties regarding a valuation for mercury, it is not a satisfactory excuse for inaction. There is sufficient evidence to support a range of values for mercury of between $1,429 and $4,359 per ton.53<P><P>
<P>
<H2>GLOBAL CLIMATE CHANGE</H2>

The greenhouse effect is a natural process that is well understood. Many aspects of the greenhouse effect remain wholly undisputed by any credible voice. Through the presence of carbon dioxide - and a host of other greenhouse gases, including chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), water vapor, methane, nitrous oxide and others - heat is trapped in the atmosphere. As greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide are emitted from anthropogenic sources, they build up in the atmosphere. The accumulation of carbon dioxide acts like the glass roof of a greenhouse and prevents radiation from escaping.  This is called the greenhouse effect.<P>
Global emissions of carbon dioxide have continually increased since the beginning of the Industrial Revolution. During the latter half of this century, global carbon emissions from the burning of fossil fuels have increased 374 percent. This is an undisputed scientific fact (Figure 1).<P><P>
<IMG SRC="mercuryfig1.GIF" WIDTH=328 HEIGHT=205><P>
Concentrations of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere have risen since fossil fuel burning began in the middle of the 1800s. At that time, carbon dioxide concentrations were 280 parts per million.  In 1995 carbon dioxide concentrations were 361 parts per million - a 30 percent increase over pre-industrial levels8 (Figure 2). This is a fact universally agreed to by scientists.<P><P>
<IMG SRC="mercuryfig2.GIF" WIDTH=316 HEIGHT=210><P>
A third undisputed scientific fact is that carbon dioxide and other atmospheric greenhouse gases are long-lived. Because emissions we give off today can remain in the atmosphere for more than 200 years, any consequences of global warming are irreversible in time frames of human significance.<P><P>

<H3>The Status of Scientific Consensus on Climate Change</H3>
Testimony from the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency provided the ALJ with an excellent summary of the results of the then-published work of the IPCC. This information was the foundation of the ALJ's dismissal of the high-profile parade of professional global warming skeptics sponsored by coal intervenors such as the Lignite Energy Council, Western Fuels Association, and Center for Energy and Economic Development. Since the ALJ embraced the expertise of the earliest reports of the IPCC, it is essential that the Commission take notice of the Second Assessment of the group, published shortly after the formal closing of the record. <P>
The findings of the IPCC provided the scientific basis for the Framework Convention on Climate Change signed by 128 countries, including the United States and most of the industrialized nations of the world.  The Convention commits countries to limit global warming by reducing carbon dioxide emissions to 1990 levels by the year 2000. It provides a guideline for decision-making when considering global warming :<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>[T]ake precautionary measures to anticipate, prevent or minimize the causes of climate change and mitigate its adverse effects. Where there are threats of serious or irreversible damage, lack of full scientific certainty should not be used as a reason for postponing such measures...10</BLOCKQUOTE><P>
The IPCC forecast an increase in global average temperature of about 1.8 degree  F (1degree C) to 5.4 degree F (3 degree  C) by the end of the next century. The IPCC's forecast is based on a doubling of the atmospheric concentration of carbon dioxide equivalent. That means that concentrations of carbon dioxide equivalents in the atmosphere are double that of pre-industrial concentrations. Under a "business as usual" model - no actions taken to reduce carbon dioxide emissions - the carbon dioxide concentrations by the year 2030 will be double that of the pre-industrial concentrations with a further doubling by 2100.<P>
The commitment made by the signatories of the Framework Convention for Climate Change to stabilize emissions of carbon dioxide at 1990 levels by the year 2000 represents only a modest first step. The IPCC estimates that it would require a reduction of carbon-dioxide emissions to fifty percent of 1990 levels to stabilize Earth's climate.11<P>
The IPCC Second Assessment was widely reported as scientists having found the smoking gun in the close correspondence between the climate record and computer simulations. The conclusion that was widely reported was the IPCC consensus finding that "[t]he balance of evidence suggests that there is a discernible human influence on global climate change."12<P>
<H3>IPCC Second Assessment and the Media</H3>

The "Jury is In: Global Warming is Real" read an editorial in the Minneapolis Star Tribune.13 The St. Paul Pioneer Press ran a front-page article titled, "Greenhouse Effect is Real".14 It is no wonder journalists are figuring this out - the world continues to break meteorological records at a dizzying pace. In a Harper's Magazine article last year, Ross Gelbspan expressed, "[n]ew record-setting weather extremes seem to have become as commonplace as traffic accidents."<P>
According to preliminary figures from the Goddard Institute for Space Studies at NASA, the average surface temperature of Earth rose to a record high in 1995. Despite an unusually cold winter in North America and Europe, the average surface temperature for 1995 was 59.7degree F (15.39 degree C).15 Newspapers across the country declared 1995 to be the hottest year on record.<P>
Over the last century the average surface temperature has risen by 0.54 degree F (0.3 degreeC) to 1.08degree F (0.6 degree C) - the fastest warming since the last ice age 10,000 years ago - with the hottest ten years in recorded history occurring during the eighties and nineties.16<P>
At the same time that temperature measurements at Earth's surface broke all records, global emissions of carbon also broke a record. In 1995 carbon emissions of 6.06 billion tons17 demonstrated that many nations are having difficulty meeting their goal, set in the Framework Convention on Climate Change, to reduce carbon-dioxide emissions to 1990 levels by the year 2000.  It is for these reasons that NASA's James Hansen believes that  "[t]he climate system is being pushed hard enough that change will become obvious to the man on the street in the next decade."18 His views were reported in a January 1996 Newsweek cover story. <P>
<H3>Global Climate Change and Minnesota </H3>
The ALJ placed considerable weight on the argument that Minnesota alone cannot address the problem of climate change, and argued this case in his discussion of carbon dioxide. But in his criticism as to why Minnesota cannot address this issue alone, the ALJ provides the argument as to why Minnesota must take a moral leadership role, as it has done on so many issues of public policy.<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The [ALJ] agrees with the public testimony from Willmar cited earlier to the effect that the real resolution of the global warming problem must come from a global emissions-reduction effort, or at the very least, a national effort. One state, especially a state like Minnesota, can not make much of a difference. In fact, even if Minnesota's utilities stopped emitting any carbon dioxide, the global problem would be virtually unaffected by our act, except as our action, and similar actions of others in this country and abroad, cause national governments to take the kind of actions that will make a difference.19<P></BLOCKQUOTE>
There are three compelling reasons why Minnesota should take bold leadership on decreasing carbon-dioxide emissions: <P>
1) Minnesota's position in the world economy carries a moral obligation and a political imperative to lead;<P>
2) Enormous economic opportunities exist; and<P>
3) Minnesota's own resources and quality of life are seriously at risk.<P>
First, there is no doubt that climate change is a planetary issue, not a local one. Most frequently-cited impacts often sound far away, both in time and space. Inundation of coastal areas or island nations, famine and drought in marginal agricultural economies, hurricanes in coastal cities are all impacts that will affect other continents and regions beyond the upper midwest of the United States. It should be considered that many political observers believe that the most serious result of climate change will be global political instability that results from catastrophes that selectively befall certain nations or populations. Therefore, Minnesotans must be concerned with developing leadership on the issue of climate change to catalyze a world response. Only this kind of effort can avoid political instability caused by populations deprived or destroyed by shifts in climate. Those peoples may well look to regions with the highest standard of living and the highest carbon emissions for retribution or redress of their grievances.<P>
Second, jobs and wealth await the states or nations that lead the world in the environmental and energy technologies that mitigate climate change once the reality of the world's situation is embraced by policy makers and citizens. Considering just one such technology, Royal Dutch Shell estimates a $30-billion-dollar annual world market in wind energy in 2030, a technology area where Minnesota arguably has a competitive advantage over most U.S. states. In July of 1996, an expert's report to the Minnesota legislature on energy technology for the future advised that up to 20 percent of Minnesota's energy could be readily derived from wind power - without the need for energy storage technologies.<P>
The IPCC states that it is technically possible and economically feasible to reduce greenhouse gas emissions significantly, including carbon dioxide. This can be achieved by increasing energy efficiency and replacing carbon-intensive fossil fuels with renewable energy sources.20 William Nordhaus, a Yale economist, has argued that cuts in carbon-dioxide emissions of ten to 47 percent would actually yield economic benefits in excess of costs. Other studies suggest if "best practices" were initiated in energy production, housing, manufacturing, and transportation sectors, carbon-dioxide emissions could be cut by 25 percent with significant savings.21<P>
In addition to the savings from increased efficiency, new jobs would be created in the environmental technology sector and the economy would be given a boost. A recent studies by the American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy show that every dollar invested in clean technologies (e.g., renewables or efficiency) creates at least twice as many jobs as a dollar spent on dirty technologies (e.g., coal or oil).22<P>
Third, global climate change poses dramatic threats to Minnesota's environment as well as the health of its citizens. Some of Minnesota's most prized resources are at risk: agriculture, the health of the poor and the elderly, the treasured boreal forest ecosystems, wetlands, and fish populations sought by local anglers and tourists from around the nation.<P>
<B>Agriculture. </B>As the global climate changes, Minnesota farmers will feel the effects first. Increased temperatures will bring about a change in the water cycle. Rainfall patterns will shift and the frequency and severity of droughts and floods will increase. The higher temperatures will also increase evaporation, leading to drier soils. Pests, including insects, rodents and weeds, that are seldom a problem in Minnesota will become common as their ranges expand with the warming climate. Increased heat stress and pests, severe floods and droughts, and decreased soil moisture will likely devastate agricultural yields.<P>
The costs to Minnesota agriculture will be extremely high. The drought of 1988 lowered crop yields around the United States by 30 percent. The reduced yields cost an estimated $40 billion (1988 dollars). With an estimated increase in frequency and severity of floods and droughts of between five and 50 percent due to global climate change, the annual losses from droughts could be as high as $18 billion.23<P>
<B>Vulnerability of the Poor and the Elderly.</B> Global climate change will also have direct effects on the health of the urban poor and elderly. During 1995 over 700 residents of Chicago died from a heat wave.24 Chicago was not alone, however; New York and parts of Europe also suffered from a surge of heat waves in 1995.<P>
The cities most vulnerable to heat waves in the United States are in the North and Midwest25, including Minnesota. In its Second Assessment, the IPCC stated, the "less resilient population - the poor, the disabled, the sick and the aged - are at greatest risk." In addition to the threat of heat stress, other health effects are magnified by higher temperatures. For example, as temperatures increase the concentration of ground-level health-threatening ozone increases. <P>
Increased temperatures can also encourage infectious diseases. With longer, warmer seasons disease-spreading insects thrive. In 1995 Voronezh, Russia experienced an outbreak of malaria, over a hundred cases - the city's first major outbreak in 40 years. Cholera also broke out in Russia during the hot, dry weather. The reduced stream flows, concentrated pollutants and higher water temperatures created a breeding ground for the disease.26 Epidemiologists cannot predict what infectious diseases may appear in a place that previously did not host such infections.<P>
<B>Boreal Forests. </B>Minnesota's forests are central to the region's economy and natural splendor, but they are at risk from global climate change. Forests will migrate northward and boreal forests - spruce/pine/fir forests of northern Minnesota - will have significant die-back.27 The increased temperature, coupled with more frequent droughts, will create conditions for increased forest fires.  The resultant forest losses will have an impact on the timber industry, recreation and tourism, watershed protection, and wildlife habitat. The estimated costs to the United States could be as high as $75 billion annually.28<P>
<B>Wetlands. </B>Minnesota prizes its wetlands for their benefits to water quality and as habitat to wildlife. The IPCC Second Assessment Report warns, "[t]he geographical distribution of wetlands is likely to shift with changes in temperature and precipitation." The quantity and quality of wetlands will be altered by changes in the water cycle. Droughts will lead to loss of wetlands; agriculture, fisheries, transport, and recreation will all be impacted. In addition, as the water evaporates, pollutants present in a wetland will become more concentrated. This will present serious health and ecological threats.<P>
<B>Fisheries. </B>Fish will be affected in many ways as a result of global climate change. The changes in the water cycle will mean the possibility of increased levels of pollutants from excess runoff during floods and increased evaporation during droughts. A recent report by the United States Environmental Protection Agency shows that cool-water fish, like walleye and trout, will be impacted as water temperature changes. The study estimates that eight to ten states could lose cool-water fish completely within 50 to 60 years while 11 to 16 additional states could experience a 50 percent loss.29 In Minnesota, where recreational fishing contributes an estimated $850 million to the economy each year, losses of habitat for certain species poses an unimaginable impact on our economy and culture.<P>
The potential impacts to Minnesota from global climate change are significant. According to the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency, "The ecological heritage of Minnesota is especially at risk from a climatic warming. The ecological modeling reveals that virtually any amount of warming would result in widespread alterations of natural landscapes in Minnesota and losses of many ecological systems that many Minnesotans consider to be their birthright. Particularly sensitive are the boreal and northern hardwood forests and related wildlife habitat of northern Minnesota. Virtually all of the ecological modeling shows that these systems will be lost with a sustained warming."30<P>
<H3>Consideration of the Second Assessment of the IPCC Should Raise the Commission's Estimate of Damages to Two Percent of World GDP</H3>
The scientific evidence clearly identifies a link between anthropogenic emissions of carbon dioxide and global climate change. The ALJ agreed with the science of the IPCC and declared, "The IPCC reports are the most authoritative sources available for information on climate change issues. The IPCC research and peer review process evaluates all available scientific information on factors affecting climate change."31<P>
Unfortunately, because the IPCC's Second Assessment was not then available, the ALJ made findings and recommendations that essentially negate his recommendation that the IPCC consensus be adopted. For carbon dioxide, he recommended a range of environmental cost values of $0.28 to $2.92 per ton of carbon dioxide, instead of the more appropriate values of  $4.28 to $28.57 recommended by the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency.32<P>
The fact that the ALJ recommended a value for carbon dioxide was not insignificant with respect to policy. It is a signal that the State of Minnesota is ready to recognize global climate change. However, the values are insignificant from an economic point of view. If considered as part of a decision regarding the full costs of a high-carbon energy option and a zero-carbon energy option, they would only be useful if the two technology choices had virtually identical market prices. <P>
Pretend for a minute that one actually had to pay the costs as they are incurred. For example, at the low end,  the "global warming damages" of running an unneeded 100-watt light bulb for a year would be about 25 cents, which is hardly enough of a 'price signal' to merit turning off the light at any time that year.<P>
How did this happen? The ALJ embraced the IPCC. He dismissed the coal industry's black hats and their advocates. Yet, despite the overriding concern and evidence, if you had to pay the costs recommended by the ALJ, it wouldn't make sense to walk across a room to turn off a light.<P>
There were two problems, one small and factual and easily corrected, the other large and difficult to grasp. The small problem will be easily remedied if the Commission reviews the Second Assessment, as it should. The ALJ's recommendations were made without the benefit of the IPCC's Second Assessment. The Second Assessment, released in September 1995, presents additional scientific evidence of global climate change and summarizes the social and economic dimensions of that change. The Second Assessment represents several additional years of global climate science, which the ALJ did not have available to him when making his decision. The Commission, using current information, should adopt higher values.<P>
The ALJ's range of values was calculated by using the damage estimates of William R. Cline, an economist at the Institute for International Economics. Cline estimated environmental costs to be 1.1 percent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) for an average global temperature increase of 4.5 degree F (2.5 degree C).33 This value was then discounted to a present value using a discount rate of three percent for the upper end of the range and five percent for the lower.34  Both of these major assumptions - that one percent is the most probable damage and that three to five percent is the 'correct' range of discount rates - are not supported by the published views of the IPCC in the Second Assessment, released only weeks after the close of the record.<P>
There is substantial evidence supporting long-term cost estimates of at least two percent of global GDP from a warming of 4.5 degree F (2.5 degree C). While the methodology and cost sectors addressed vary in the studies presented in the hearing, all of the results are relatively close.  Substantial evidence exists that demonstrates the true level of cost is likely to be twice the estimated one-percent vicinity. In Cline's cost estimate of 1.1 percent of GDP, he acknowledges that costs to unmanaged ecosystems, species diversity, and air pollution, if included, could easily raise the expected GDP loss to about two percent.36 The IPCC, in their Second Assessment report declared, "The assessed literature quantifying total damages from [3.6 degree - 5.4 degree F (2 degree - 3 degree C)] warming provides a wide range of point estimates for damages, given the presumed change in atmospheric greenhouse gas concentrations. The aggregate estimates tend to be a few percent of world GDP..."<P>
Higher values are justified because the lower value of one percent, derived from Cline's study:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Does not take into account several cost sectors.
<LI>Has a short time frame. The studies only estimate costs until the year 2050, before the greater warming period predicted to come at the end of the next century.36
<LI>Assumes that the predicted warming will occur in a linear pattern, rather than a step-like pattern as demonstrated by ice core samples and the IPCC report; the assumption of linearity results in underestimates of the magnitude of disruptions and costs.37
<LI>Overlooks the fact that for economies with a diversified, industrial base and an educated work force, costs of one to a few percent of GDP are sufficient, while economies that rely heavily on resources with a labor force tied to the land will suffer a percentage several times higher.38
<LI>Does not account for the change in the rate of emissions of carbon dioxide caused by the effects of temperature. There is danger that rising temperatures and carbon-dioxide concentrations could contribute to amplifying feedbacks resulting in greater warming and higher costs.39
<LI>Does not contain a valuation of the enormous risk associated with replacing the existing, natural climate with a fundamentally different anthropogenic climate.40
</UL>
Given these arguments, a range of values employing two percent of GDP is a very conservative estimate, and is consistent with the ALJ's preference for conservatism. In addition, this would be consistent with the intent of the Minnesota Environmental Policy Act (MN Statute &sect;116D) that declares "[a]ll departments and agencies... shall... [r]ecognize the worldwide and long range character of environmental problems and... lend appropriate support to initiatives, resolutions, and programs designed to maximize interstate, national and international cooperation in anticipating and preventing a decline in the quality of the world environment."41<P>
<H3>Using a Common-Sense Discount Rate</H3>
Benefits of environmental policies typically accrue over time, but the costs of the policies usually come immediately. Any costs incurred today to reduce the potential of global warming from the burning of fossil fuels will provide a benefit for the grandchildren of our grandchildren. Economists use discount rates to convert these future benefits to present-day values. The gap between the initial investment and the eventual benefit can be extremely wide. <P>
Discount rates can be thought of as an interest rate. The level of interest rate reflects the required compensation for postponing consumption today. For example, $100 today is worth more than $100 next year because the money could be invested and earn a return equivalent to the discount rate.<P>
The higher the discount rate used, the more likely environmental costs will be passed to future generations.  Benefits today become more worthwhile, even at the expense of our grandchildren. If a discount rate of ten percent per year was used to determine whether to prevent a $1 million ecological disaster that would occur 100 years from now, it would not make economic sense to prevent the disaster if the costs were more than $73. On the other hand, if a discount rate of only one percent were used, the cost at which it would no longer be economically sensible to prevent the disaster would be $369,711.<P>
People acting in their own best interest discount future values. Mortality and uncertainty make it sound for people to discount. Communities, however, are quasi-immortal and do not suffer as much risk as their individual citizens. Because of this, social decisions involving mortality should use a discount rate of zero42 and when mortality is not a factor, discount rates should be reduced to recognize the lower risk assumed by a community. Society, and many people, work to make the world a better place for future generations (e.g., schools, parks, college funds) effectively applying a negative discount rate by valuing the future more highly than today.43<P>
Discount rates treat all things as equal to money in the bank. This assumes that everything will grow like money in the bank. When economists try to discount happiness the model breaks down. Happiness does not grow, it is experienced and then becomes a memory. There is no way to store happiness. Discount rates also have difficulty when applied to natural systems. A fish population or a forest will grow in the short-term, but there is a maximum capacity that will eventually be reached. This may justify discounting in the short-term, but demonstrates the long-term difficulties of discounting.44<P>
When values are discounted over multiple generations other problems come into view. To calculate costs and benefits it is necessary to assume the preferences of future generations. One hundred years ago, people valued farm implements to do their work and horses and carriages for transportation. Most could not predict our current reliance on computers, automobiles and jet aircraft. What makes us think we can predict the preferences of future generations?<P>
Some economists argue that when welfare of future generations is at stake no discount rate should be used and the costs and benefits should be treated as if they occurred in the present.45 A.C. Pigou, a highly respected economist, stated:<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>There is wide agreement that the state should protect the interests of the future in some degree against the effects of our irrational discounting, and of our preference for ourselves over our descendants. The whole movement for "conservation" in the United States is based upon this conviction. It is the clear duty of government which is the trustee for unborn generations as well as for its present citizens, to watch over and if need be, by legislative enactment, to defend exhaustible natural resources <P>
of the country from rash and reckless spoliation.46<P></BLOCKQUOTE>
Nobel Laureate Robert Solow commented:<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>[T]he idea is that each generation is allowed to favor itself over the future, but not too much. Each generation can, in turn, discount the welfare of all future generations, and each successive generation applies the same discount rate to the welfare of its successors. To make [resource] conservation an interesting proposition at all, the common discount rate should not be too large. You may wonder why I allow discounting at all. I wonder too: no generation "should" be favored over any other.47<P></BLOCKQUOTE>
According to the IPCC's Second Assessment, discount rates used for climate change analysis fit into two categories. One approach discounts intergenerational issues using a "social rate of time preference" which is the "pure time preference," or impatience, added to the increased welfare from higher incomes in the future. The discount rate for this approach gives discount rates of between 0.5 and three percent per year. The second approach uses a discount rate equal to the market returns for a long-term, risk-free investment. This approach yields a discount rate of between three and six percent per year.48<P>
The discount rate is a critical factor in any decision-making process when several generations are involved. Future generations are not able to assist in the decisions that will affect their welfare. In some cases where the decision results in an effect that is irreversible or cannot be reversed within a reasonable amount of time, such as global climate change, it may be impossible to pay future generations for their losses.<P>
The ALJ recommended a discount rate of three to five percent for reducing future environmental-costs to current values.49 This, coupled with the decision to use low environmental-cost values, creates a range of values that do not represent the true costs to the environment from carbon-dioxide emissions. Because low environmental costs were selected it becomes extremely important to use a discount rate that does not zero out the environmental and human-health costs borne by future generations.<P>
The intergenerational scope, the long-term nature, and the tremendous risk associated with global warming make it necessary to use a low, if not zero, discount rate. A low discount rate is consistent with the requirements of the Minnesota Environmental Policy Act. There is ample evidence to support a discount rate of between one and three percent. If a future value of one percent of global GDP is used with a discount rate of between one and three percent the resulting environmental cost values from carbon dioxide are $2.92 to $14.29 per ton. If a future value of two percent of global GDP is used with a discount rate of between one and three percent the environmental cost values are between $5.84 and $28.58 (see Table 2).<P>
Sufficient evidence has been provided by Cline and the IPCC to establish values using the higher damage estimates (two percent of global GDP). Consistent with the common sense that we value our children's lives and welfare as we do our own, a discount rate of zero percent is entirely defensible. Because of the intergenerational scope of the problem and its irreversibility, climate change may be one of those future costs for which a zero discount rate is most appropriate. In keeping with the ALJ's emphasis on the need for conservative assumptions in calculating environmental costs, a range of one to three percent is a reasonable alternative to a zero discount rate.<P>
<H3>A Time for Global Action...<BR>
A Time for Local Action</H3>
In 1896 Svante Arrhenius, a Nobel-prize winning scientist from Sweden, forecast that the burning of fossil fuels would result in a rise in global temperatures.50 Now, 100 years later in 1996, some governments are attempting to deal with the problem of global climate change and it is time for the U.S. and Minnesota to join the leaders. Had the issue been dealt with a century ago the price may have been virtually unnoticeable. Now, because of inaction we are staring at fast-approaching deadlines with higher price tags. The longer we delay action, the more expensive the solution will become. William Cline estimates the costs to industry may be one to two percent of GDP if we take action now, but the figure could be as high as six to 20 percent if action is delayed. <P>
Internationally, the Undersecretary of State Tim Wirth advanced a new U.S. position on climate change in July of 1996. The U.S. now contends that voluntary efforts to reduce climate change will be insufficient to meet our international agreements on stabilization of carbon dioxide emissions. Instead, the U.S. is now calling for standards and agreements that would be enforceable by international law.<P>
In Minnesota, the Public Utilities Commission has the opportunity to review the 151 Findings and three Recommendations of the ALJ, and with the changes outlined in this report, adopt values for the cost of our climate interference that will help move Minnesota to the lead of the policy direction that will soon be embraced by the people of the world.<P><P>
Table 2:   Proposed Environmental Cost Values for Carbon Dioxide (dollars per ton)<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1 CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1>
<TR>
	<TD>
	<TD><B>1% of Global GDP</B>
	<TD><B>2% of Global GDP</B>
<TR>
	<TD><B>Discount Rate of 3%</B>
	<TD>$2.92
	<TD>$5.84
	<TR>
