<P>
<H2>MERCURY</H2>

For the pollutant mercury, the ALJ recommended that no value be used until more information becomes available. This decision is very troubling considering the agreement among parties that mercury posed a significant threat to the environment and human health. No knowledgeable witness in the hearings denied the threat posed by mercury.51 Testimony at the public hearing and public letters showed a great consensus in favor of establishing values for mercury. The ALJ declared, "It is frustrating to conclude that there is insufficient evidence to recommend a value for mercury in light of the broad consensus about mercury's toxicity and the need to reduce human (as well as animal) exposure."52<P>
Although there are some uncertainties regarding a valuation for mercury, it is not a satisfactory excuse for inaction. There is sufficient evidence to support a range of values for mercury of between $1,429 and $4,359 per pound.53<P>
<H3>What Effect does Mercury Have in Minnesota?</H3>
Mercury is a heavy metal that can damage the central nervous system and, in many cases, cause death. As mercury enters the environment it is converted by bacteria into methyl mercury. Once in the environment mercury does not degrade and can be re-emitted. Mercury is a class of persistent chemicals called bioaccumulators. The bioaccumulatory nature of mercury means that once it is ingested by an animal in the food web; it is stored in the fatty tissues and remains until the animal is eaten. The mercury is then transferred to the next animal in the food web where it remains until that animal is eaten. Eventually the higher members of the food web accumulate large amounts of mercury, resulting in mercury poisoning. This spells danger for humans as we are at the top of the food web.<P>
In Minnesota, mercury contamination is pervasive.54 Because of mercury contamination, the Minnesota Department of Health has issued fish consumption warnings for 94 percent of Minnesota lakes surveyed. Fish advisories have been posted because the concentrations of mercury pose serious health threats to those who consume the fish, especially pregnant women and children.55 In northeastern Minnesota concentrations of mercury in northern pike are 225,000 times higher than mercury concentrations in the water around them.56<P>
In a state like Minnesota, where recreational fishing contributes an estimated $850 million to the economy each year, the potential impacts from fish advisories are significant. As the public's awareness of mercury-related fish advisories increases, the stigma on Minnesota's fish could damage the recreational fishing industry and impact Minnesota's economy.<P>
Minnesota wildlife will also be affected. Loons are especially vulnerable because of their position at the outer edges of the food web. Mercury can lead to shorter life spans, altered behavior, and reduced reproductivity. These problems and others led the coordinator of the United States Environmental Protection Agency's Great Waters Program to state, "[m]ercury is one of the most, if not the most, important chemicals we are concerned about."57<P>
<H3>Science of Mercury</H3>
The process of generating electricity from coal-fired plants accounts for one-sixth to one-quarter of the state's anthropogenic mercury emissions. Coal burning is now the leading source of mercury emissions in Minnesota.58<P>
Although much is known about the health effects of mercury, there is uncertainty in data regarding mercury. In particular, the ALJ cited four areas of omission:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Current models cannot simulate the complex cycling of mercury within the atmosphere;
<LI>The quantity and form of mercury emitted from coal burning is uncertain;
<LI>The quantity and form of mercury emitted from natural sources is uncertain; and
<LI>Studies are unable to estimate accurately the effect of changes in mercury concentration on fish.59
</UL>
Studies that may overcome some of these uncertainties are being conducted by the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency and the United States Environmental Protection Agency. The Environmental Protection Agency is conducting a study on mercury emission rates, sources, health and environmental effects as well as a study on toxic emissions from coal-burning power plants. The Minnesota Pollution Control Agency is performing a Minnesota-specific valuation study for mercury.60 These studies on the effects of mercury on human health and the environment may not be completed for some time. <P>
<H3>The Flaw in the ALJ's Ruling on Mercury</H3>
The ALJ's decision to recommend no value be used for mercury until more research is available is puzzling. There is strong evidence about the harmful effects mercury has on animals, particularly on human health. During the hearings not one knowledgeable witness denied the threat posed by mercury.61<P>
Although more research will increase certainty, the delay will lead to significant and unacceptable health threats from mercury pollution. By using no value, the ramifications are equivalent to setting a zero value. This certainly does not represent actual damages, damages that will continue to occur while waiting to establish a range of values for mercury. An article in the Harvard Law Review summarized the situation:<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>While it is difficult to quantify external costs, one cannot escape setting some value. A decision not to consider external costs in itself quantifies them by setting their value at zero. This is unreasonable, given both the strong evidence that the costs are massive, and the significant difference between the external costs of traditional central station plants and alternative energy facilities. A crude approximation, made as exact as possible and changed over time to reflect new information, would be preferable to the manifestly unjust approximation caused by ignoring these costs.62<P></BLOCKQUOTE>
Until more information becomes available an interim value for mercury should be used. The Minnesota Pollution Control Agency proposed a range of values for mercury using the damage-cost study presented in the evidentiary hearing by Triangle Economic Research (TER) as a basis for formulating the values. The Minnesota Office of the Attorney General (OAG) then modified the values to exclude particulate values. The resulting range of environmental cost values for mercury - between $1,429 and $4,359 per pound of mercury -  received a qualified endorsement from the ALJ when he said, "the OAG calculation is the best one in the record." The OAG proposed range of values is supported by both the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency and the Environmental Coalition.63<P>
<H2>CONCLUSION</H2>
The ALJ's recommendations for criteria pollutants are sound, but the carbon dioxide and mercury values must be adjusted. The record, coupled with the recent report by the IPCC - the Second Assessment - strongly supports higher environmental damage cost estimates for global climate change of between one and a few percent of global GDP. Two percent would be a conservative low-end estimate for the Commission to use. One percent, as recommended by the ALJ, is inconsistent with the finding of the scientific world that damages will most likely be "a few percent" after a doubling of carbon-dioxide levels. The record also presents strong arguments for a discount rate of between one and three percent if a discount rate is used at all. Using these values, an appropriate range of environmental cost values for carbon dioxide would be $5.84 to $28.58. These values are consistent with the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency recommendation of  $4.28 to $28.57. <P>
There is sufficient evidence that mercury poses a serious threat to wildlife, human health, and the economy of Minnesota. There is also sufficient evidence to prove that between one-sixth and one-fourth of all anthropogenic emissions of mercury come from coal-burning power plants. The OAG's recommended range of $1,429 to $4,359 per pound of mercury is supported by the record; in fact, the ALJ commented that the OAG's range of values was the best on record. It is essential that the Commission set values for mercury because the failure to reach a value is the functional equivalent of setting a value of zero. The OAG's values will provide a suitable place holder until additional studies can be completed to answer the unresolved questions in the record. <P>
