Footnotes-MPCA Initial Comments<P>
<a name="fn0">[1]</a>If the record is incomplete on
certain matters, the underlying statute may well require the Commission to
undertake additional factfinding on those matters. <u>See</u> <u>Industrial
Union Department, AFL-CIO v. Hodgson</u>, 499 F.2d 467 (D.C.Cir. 1974),
discussed <i>infra</i>, in which the court reviewed OSHA's rule limiting worker
exposure to asbestos dust.  OSHA had postponed compliance dates for all
affected industries, even though the record showed that only some industries
needed the extra time.  OSHA claimed that there was insufficient information at
the time of formulation of the standards to differentiate among industries.
The court wrote, "[t]hat may be true, but it is unclear whether the lack of
information is a cause or result of the Secretary's
approach.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;The lack of more specific information may
be partially attributable to the Secretary's failure to seek it." The court
then remanded this issue to OSHA for further consideration.  <u>Hodgson,</u>
499 F.2d. at 480.<p>
<a name="fn1">[2]</a>While the Commission's quantification of values, following
as it would a contested case hearing, would normally subject it to these tests
under Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;14.69, Minnesota courts have recognized that
where an agency decision is based not just on factual determinations but on
quasi-legislative policy judgments, an even more deferential standard of review
will be applied.  <u>Arvig Tel. Co. v. Northwestern Bell Tel. Co.</u>, 270
N.W.2d 111,116 (Minn. 1978).<p>
<a name="fn2">[3]</a>It is reasonable to assume that if a quantified value can
pass the standard of review traditionally applied to agency actions, then its
quantification is practicable.  Indeed, it could hardly be considered
"impracticable" if it is comparable to the types of decisions routinely made by
agencies and routinely upheld in court.  Similarly, if it is not practicable to
quantify the value, then the value would presumably fail the "substantial
evidence" test or violate the "arbitrary and capricious" prohibition. <p>
<a name="fn3">[4]</a> "The difference between the two laws represents movement
from an `adder' approach toward a `total cost minimization' approach.  The
change might also be viewed as movement from a pricing approach to a planning
approach, since the new law applies environmental costs only to resource
evaluation and selection."  Order Establishing Interim Environmental Cost
Values (March 1, 1994), pp. 2-3.<p>
<a name="fn4">[5]</a> Reply Brief on Evidentiary Issues of the Office of the
Attorney General, especially pages 10 through 14.<p>
<a name="fn5">[6]</a> This argument differs substantially from earlier
assertions by several parties to this proceeding that the ALJ and Commission
should conclude it is not practicable to quantify values because of the
negative consequences that might follow as a result of the decisions made by
the Commission in future proceedings where the values would be considered.
That argument, which has been rightly rejected by the ALJ and the Commission,
Order Modifying Administrative Law Judge's Fifth Prehearing Order on the
Consideration of Socioeconomic Factors (Oct. 28, 1994), depended on making
assumptions about what decisions the Commission would make in those
proceedings.  The ALJ and Commission should not in setting values make any
presuppositions about what the Commission will decide to do in those future
proceedings, or about the consequences of those decisions, because to do so
denies the discretion the Commission will have in those proceedings (and
ignores the opportunity all parties will have in those proceedings to raise the
issues that are of concern).  However, the ALJ and the Commission can and
should, in setting the values, recognize that their intended purpose is to be
used by the Commission in the exercise of its discretion in future
proceedings.<p>
<a name="fn6">[7]</a> The court wrote, "we find there is no explanation of how
the conflicts and ambiguities in the evidence are resolved, no explanation of
any assumptions made or the suppositions underlying such assumptions, and no
articulation of the policy judgments.  In short there has been no
<i>reasoned</i> determination of why a level of 0.5 ppm was selected."
<u>Manufactured Housing</u>, 347 N.W.2d at 246 (emphasis in original, citation
omitted).  This lack of explanation was particularly striking given that the
ALJ had characterized the Commissioner's original choice of 0.4 ppm as "like
picking a number out of a hat."  Id. at 244.  The ALJ recommended a level of
0.8 ppm instead, and then the Chief ALJ, agreeing that the 0.4 ppm value was
unreasonable, recommended a limit of 0.5 ppm or higher.  The Commissioner then
adopted the 0.5 ppm level, simultaneously adopting findings of the ALJ
suggesting that such a level was not supported by the record.  <u>Id.</u> at
243 - 245.<p>
<a name="fn7">[8]</a> In making this finding, the court stated:  "Contrary to
the apparent suggestion of some of the petitioners, we need not seek a single
dispositive study that fully supports the Administrator's determination.
Science does not work in that way;  nor, for that matter, does adjudicatory
fact-finding.  Rather, the Administrator's decision may be fully supportable if
it is based, as it is, on the inconclusive but suggestive results of numerous
scientific studies. By its nature, scientific evidence is cumulative:  the more
supporting, albeit inconclusive evidence available, the more likely the
accuracy of the conclusion.  <u>Id.</u> at 37-38.<p>
<a name="fn8">[9]</a> See footnote 1, above, explaining one of the grounds on
which the rule was remanded and the obligation of OSHA to seek out available
information.<p>
<a name="fn9">[10]</a> For example, the TER Report submitted by NSP states that
the damage-cost approach "is the only approach for estimating externality costs
that is consistent with broadly accepted economic principles."  TER Report at
2, attached to Desvousges Direct, Exh. 135.  The TER Report also limits itself
to costs that can meet its three "stringent" methodological criteria.
<u>Id.</u> at 5. <p>
<a name="fn10">[11]</a>
 In her comments to the Senate Committee on Jobs, Energy, and Community
Development, Senate author Janet Johnson expressed her concern that despite the
previously adopted law requiring quantification of costs: <p>
<p>
...how to quantify these environmental costs has been open to debate, and a
year and a half later the Commission still has not seen these costs.  And
Massachusetts and Nevada have led the way in this approach requiring utilities
to appoint environmental adders to the cost of energy when comparing
investments in new power plants.  Wisconsin and Iowa have also followed suit.
Yet in Minnesota we are still waiting for the Commission to quantify
environmental externalities.  A technical advisory group has met to work on
quantifying environmental externalities but to date, they have not been able to
reach a consensus and settle on a value.<p>

Comments of Sen. Johnson, Senate Committee on Jobs, Energy and Community
Development, March 31, 1993 (transcribed from tapes available at the Minnesota
Legislative Reference Library). <p>
<a name="fn11">[12]</a> The larger context of Senator Johnson's comments are:
"A couple of years ago you voted for some language dealing with environmental
externalities.  Unfortunately, it's been difficult for the Public Utilities
Commission to come to closure with the advisory committee on how to quantify
environmental costs and as a result we've kind of been in a stalemate for a
year and ten months now.  So this language would make it easier for the
Commission to quantify and establish a range of environmental costs associated
with each method of generation.  It was language agreed upon by all of the
interested parties, the utilities, the environmentalists and labor and we're
looking forward to passage of this legislation."  Comments of Sen. Johnson,
Senate Floor, May 15, 1993.  <p>
<a name="fn12">[13]</a> See record of Senate Committee comments in footnote
11.<p>
