is to advise Congress on scientific matters, which it has done since the 19th
century.  The administrative arm of the NAS is the National Research Council
(NRC) which establishes committees and publishes reports for Congress to use in
setting policy.  Tr. 12 at 48, ln. 24 - p. 49, ln. 11. <p>
<a name="fn19">[21]</a> While more recently an NAS panel, in a 1992 policy
report distinct from its earlier scientific analyses, broadened its range of
predicted warming by half a degree in both directions in response to ongoing
concerns about the uncertainty of model projections, it reaffirmed that
"[n]umerical computer simulations using general circulation models (GCMs) are
generally considered the best available tools for anticipating climatic
changes."  Exh. 76 at 17.  It also recommended that the nation implement a
number of policies in response to the threat of global warming, particularly
centering on policy measures to reduce U.S. emissions of CO2 associated with
fossil fuel consumption.  Ciborowski Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 at 14.<p>
<a name="fn20">[22]</a> Dr. Margaret Davis elaborated on this point on the
witness stand.  With respect to the reliability of model predictions, she
stated:  "They're improving all the time.  Now the way that one might judge
their reliability is to see how well they're able to simulate the climate of
the past.  We can validate those predictions by checking them against the
fossil record.  There's been considerable success, for example, in predicting
the climate of the last glacial maxima.  There is a model which attempts to
predict the vegetation using input from the general circulation model, and
these results correspond quite well with what we know from the fossil record
for that period."  Tr. 12 at 44, lns. 14-22.<p>
<a name="fn21">[23]</a> Not only are predicted warming levels unprecedented in
human history, but Professor Margaret Davis testified that we do not have
detailed paleorecords of climate from a time when atmospheric CO2
concentrations were as high as they are today because they have not been at
such high levels "since the modern flora and fauna developed on the Earth."  M.
Davis Rebuttal, Exh. 77 at 4.<p>
<a name="fn22">[24]</a> See IPCC 1990 Report at 296, 298.<p>
<a name="fn23">[25]</a> The IPCC 1990 Report, chapter 10, discusses some of the
historic changes in the geographic distribution of ecosystems due to
temperature changes of the predicted magnitude. <p>
<a name="fn24">[26]</a> And the evidence from past climates suggests that when
Minnesota becomes warmer, it indeed becomes dryer.   Davis Rebuttal, Exh. 77 at
6.  8000 to 4000 years ago Minnesota experienced a warm, dry interval
characterized by advances of the prairie, retreat of the forests, replacement
of maple forests by oak scrub, an increase in fire frequency, and drops in
prairie lake levels. <u>Id.,</u> and Tr. 12 at 53, ln. 11 to p. 54, ln.4.  This
was followed by a cooler, wetter period allowing the forests to readvance.
Davis Rebuttal, Exh. 77 at 6.<p>
<a name="fn25">[27]</a> Dr. Davis testifies:  "Conditions for dispersal of both
plants and animals are very much less favorable than in the past, because
corridors for plant dispersal have been disrupted and interrupted by roads,
cities, and cultivated land.  Animals that may have facilitated seed dispersal
in the past, such as the passenger pigeon, are now extinct."  Exh. 77 at 11.<p>
<a name="fn26">[28]</a> Scenario A showing major changes by 2010 assumes that
CO2 concentrations do not double until 2070, but that the onset of warming
occurs rapidly.  Scenario B showing major changes by 2040 assume CO2 doubles by
2040, but the onset of warming is delayed.  Botkin and Nisbet, at 284 and 287,
attached to Exh. 69.<p>
<a name="fn27">[29]</a> The record includes a list of 17 scientific reviews
(other than the IPCC's) and their climate sensitivity predictions.  Ciborowski
Surrebuttal, Exh. 72 at 11.<p>
<a name="fn28">[30]</a> We note that two of the witnesses for Western Fuels
have particularly close ties to the fossil fuels industry.  Virtually all of
the funding of Dr. Balling's work in global warming has come from the coal
industry or the government of Kuwait.  See Tr. 10 at 107, ln. 15 - p.&nbsp;112,
ln. 22 and Dr. Balling's resume, attached to Balling Rebuttal, Exh. 63 at
21-23.  His book "The Heated Debate" was published not by a scientific
organization but by the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, which Dr.
Balling recognizes is a "conservative public policy group."  Tr. 10 at 112,
lns. 8-11.  Similarly, Dr. Michaels' research directly relating to global
warming has apparently been funded entirely from the coal and electric
industries and anonymous sources, and for three years he published a quarterly
review of global warming issues that was funded entirely by the Western Fuels
Association.  See Michaels' resume at 15, attached to Michaels Rebuttal, Exh.
57; and Tr. 9 at 86, ln.20 - p. 89, ln. 12.  Their apparent inability to
attract research funding from non-industry sources suggests that their research
may not be highly regarded in the scientific community. (It is instructive to
compare the sources of funding for the work of Drs. Michaels and Balling with
the more traditional and neutral research funding that Drs. Davis and Pastor
have attracted .  Exh. 80, at 3, and Exh. 68, at 405.)  One might also
reasonably conclude that if Drs. Balling and Michaels did not continue to
arrive at scientific conclusions downplaying the threat of global warming,
their funding would almost completely dry up -- as would the considerable
national attention both have recieved as greenhouse skeptics (we note that the
majority of their lectures and speeches on global warming are not to other
scientists in their fields but to industry, political, and press groups) . See
Michaels Resume at 8-12, attached to Exh. 57, and Ballings Resume at 29 - 37,
attached to Exh. 63.  Awareness that their funding and continued attention to
their views depends so much on what they conclude might bias their scientific
judgment.         <p>
<a name="fn29">[31]</a>There is no dispute that CO2 emission are well-mixed in
the environment and contribute equally to global costs regardless of where they
are emitted.  See Tr. 11 at 94, lns. 16-20; and NERA Report at 52, attached to
Harrison Direct, Exh. 8.<p>
<a name="fn30">[32]</a> IPCC assigns an atmospheric lifetime of 50 to 200 years
to CO2, which is not the turnover time of CO2 in the atmosphere, but rather the
time it takes to reach a new, higher equilibrium level.  IPCC 1990 Report at 5
and 8.  "Consequently, CO2 emitted into the atmosphere today will influence the
atmospheric concentration of CO2 for centuries into the future."  IPCC 1990
Report at 5.<p>
<a name="fn31">[33]</a> See also, "The Environmental Costs of Electricity
Production," attached to Ciborowski Direct, Exh.69.  Mr. Ciborowski testifies:
"One analyst estimates the costs of global warming in the United States, for a
likely case, at 1 to 2 percent of gross domestic product in any given year.
Pessimistic case losses are estimated at about 6 percent of gross domestic
product."  (footnote citing Cline, W., <i>Global Warming:  The Economic
Stakes,</i>  Institute for Environmental Economics, 1992, p. 103.)<p>
<a name="fn32">[34]</a> Dr. Davis testified at the hearing about the
possibility of triggering a positive feedback from the biosphere:  "The rate at
which carbon seems to be disappearing from the atmosphere has been changing, so
there was an increased storage of carbon in some unknown sink from 1920 to
1970, and then the increase in that sink stopped, so it seems to have remained
rather constant for the last 20 years.  Now, the sink is not -- has not been
identified.  There's a lot of speculation about what is absorbing the carbon.
But the fact that it's changing suggests that its sensitive to temperature
and/or CO2 levels, and we can't be sure that its going to continue to absorb
CO2 from the atmosphere.  The danger is that it might start emitting CO2
instead, which would augment the greenhouse effect."  Tr. 12 at 58, ln. 15 -
p.&nbsp;59, ln. 5.  Elsewhere she testifies that triggering such a feedback
could set off a climate change much larger than would be produced by CO2
emissions alone, illustrating the dangers of incremental CO2 emissions. Tr. 12
at 28, lns. 1 - 7.<p>
 <a name="fn33">[35]</a>The MPCA has not explicitly endorsed adoption of this
range before, but has always endorsed a range of values similar in significance
to the interim CO2 range of $5.99 to $13.60 per ton.  Ciborowski Direct, Exh.
69 at 3.  The MPCA has also previously endorsed the use of the 2% damage
function and a 1 to 2 percent discount rate in the rebuttal testimony of Mr.
Ciborowski. Exh. 70 at 41. Table 4 establishes a range of $4.28 to $28.57 based
on the preferred damage function and discount rates.  The MPCA therefore
believes that this is the range of values best supported by the record.<p>
