<a name="fn59">[64]</a>The legislative history of Title IV of the Clean Air Act
Amendments of 1990 explains the acid rain problem and the areas of greatest
impact.  Senate Comm. on Env't &amp; Public Works, Clean Air Act Amendments of
1990, S. Rep. No. 101-228, 101st Cong., 2nd Sess., reprinted in 1990
U.S.C.C.A.N., vol. 6, 3385, 3645 et seq.  Former EPA Assistant Administrator
for Air and Water Robert Sansom testified in this proceeding that the
legislation was driven by not only the acid rain problems of the Northeast but
also by visibility concerns in the West. Tr.&nbsp;7 at 129-30.  SO2 of course,
is involved in both acid rain and visibility effects.  Pratt Direct, Exh 175,
attached paper at 2 - 3.<p>
<a name="fn60">[65]</a>The extra allowances granted utilities in Illinois,
Indiana, and Ohio are provided for by 42 U.S.C. [[section]]&nbsp;7651c(a)(3).
