(ranking "wind and solar" first and "coal and nuclear power" last.)<p>
<a name="fn62">[67]</a> Whether some "opportunity costs" should be ascribed to
such a situation is a Department/NSP concern best addressed if the situation
ever arises in a site-specific determination.  MPCA contends that "opportunity
costs" are distinct from "environmental costs" and that the governing statute
requires offset to the environmental damages resulting from new emissions
source only to the extent it is demonstrated that ongoing damages elsewhere
have been reduced as part of an allowance trade.  Although the Department and
NSP maintain that damages beyond Minnesota's borders (or the slightly larger
TER study area, in the case of NSP) are irrelevant, MPCA has argued that such
damages must be considered.  Joint Reply Brief of MPCA and Environmental
Coalition on Evidentiary Issues at 6-21 (October 6, 1995).  If the Commission
follows MPCA's recommendation to examine costs without regard to borders,
reductions to environmental damages through allowance trades should also be
considered regardless of location of the allowance seller.<p>
<a name="fn63">[68]</a> Scott Brockett, acting manager of energy planning for
DPS and a proponent of zero values for SO2, acknowledged that if the allowances
were to lose all their value because of lack of demand,  "then it may be
appropriate to assign an environmental cost for SO2 greater than zero." Tr. 8
at 122, lns. 19 - 20.  A similar acknowledgement was made on cross-examination
by NSP consulting economist Albert Nichols, Tr. 27 at 116, ln. 15 -
p.&nbsp;118, ln. 23.<p>
