<a name="fn71">[76]</a>Once SO2 values are in place, the simplest case for an
adjustment would be the situation where one Minnesota utility is shutting down
and selling the allowances for the plant to be closed to another utility
wanting to construct a new plant in the state.  The values developed in this
proceeding could be applied in conjunction with site-specific modeling to come
up with an appropriate credit for the allowances purchased.  If the allowances
were purchased from a Wisconsin utility, a similar analysis could be undertaken
with further adjustment for the greater population densities likely impacted by
the closing of the Wisconsin plant. (See TER Report, Exh. 136, vol. 7, Table
3-1<b> </b>for the 6-fold difference in SO2 impacts between rural and urban
scenario, also see Rebuttal Exhibit of Dr, Mark Thayer, Exh. 187 at 21, for
discussion of importance of population densities.)  Many utilities are
currently banking their allowances.  Tr. 27 at 116, lns. 4 -14.  The use of
banked allowances or allowances purchased from multiple, scattered allowance
holders, and resulting valuation questions, might necessitate more complicated
calculations.  See Brockett Direct, Exh. 37 at 26-27.  However, as Mr. Brockett
suggests, some weighted national average could be used as a default in a more
complicated scenarios.  Brockett Direct, Exh. 37 at 26, ln. 24 - 27,
ln.&nbsp;3.  The Commission in this proceeding is taking on daunting valuation
issues; it can surely handle the lesser challenge of valuing specific allowance
swaps.<p>
<a name="fn72">[77]</a> The political judgment extended to allocation of
allowances.  Department witness Scott Brockett acknowledged that extra
allowances were granted for political reasons to the dirtier coal-fired plants
in the Ohio Valley.  Tr. 8 at 116, ln. 25 - p.&nbsp;117, ln. 7.  These
politically necessitated distortions of the allowance allocation scheme are
further evidence that the allowance trading program is not designed to bring
SO2 emissions to a socially optimal level..  Even if that were its objective,
it would still leave residual environmental costs for the Commission to
evaluate.  If the Commission wishes more information on the very political
genesis of the allowance trading system, if should overturn the rulings of the
ALJ striking testimony of the MPCA witnesses McCarron and Pratt and NSP witness
Patricia Boyce (Leaf).  Post-Hearing Rulings on Evidentiary Motions at
[[paragraph]][[paragraph]]&nbsp; 3, 13, 21.<p>
<a name="fn73">[78]</a> Exh. 188, following page 8.<p>
<a name="fn74">[79]</a> The Congressional Office of Technology Assessment's
overview of utility environmental cost studies suggests that consideration of
externalities is "another stage" beyond environmental costs.  OTA Report in
Exh. 164 at 13.  Dr. Elion Amit, economist for the Department, also
acknowledged that environmental costs exist independent of internalization of
the costs of residual emissions.  Tr. 4 at 120, lns. 2 - p.&nbsp;13; Tr. 4 at
129, lns. 4 - 7.<p>
<a name="fn75">[80]</a> Partial internalization is mentioned in the OTA
Report's overview of economic theory. Exh. 52[also Exh. 164], Box 2 - 2, at 14.
Economists Sansom and Nichols agreed with the general concept that there could
be partial, or proportionate, internalization of costs that once had been
entirely external.  Sansom, Tr. 7 at 127, lns. 9 - 25; Nichols, Tr. 27 at 72,
ln. 19 - p.&nbsp;73, ln. 20.  However, they, and Dr. Nichols colleague Dr.
David Harrison, Jr., nonetheless concluded that the tiniest of payments for an
SO2 allowance meant full internalization of the environmental costs, however
great they may be.  See, e.g., Harrison Tr. 2 at 27, lns. 1 - 6.  Whatever may
be the correct conclusion in economic nomenclature--partial or full
internalization--the mandate of section 216B.2422, subd. 3, is clear and
direct:  "establish the environmental costs" of all the harmful emissions.<p>
<a name="fn76">[81]</a> NSP, the party to this proceeding which should know the
most about actual operation of the allowance system, has fought to keep such
information from the record. First, it successfully moved to strike Mr.
McCarron's Rebuttal discussion of experiences under the trading system.  Exh.
163 at 18 - 21; Post-Hearing Ruling on Evidentiary Motions
[[paragraph]]&nbsp;13.  When its witness was asked on cross-examination about
NSP experience with allowances, NSP counsel was sustained in a relevancy
objection.  Tr. 27 at 86, ln. 4 - p.&nbsp;87, ln. 7. <b> </b>This kind of
information should be developed in any future proceeding where a utility is
claiming setoff to environmental costs for allowance purchases.  Moreover, the
Commission should overrule the striking of Mr.&nbsp;McCarron's useful
information on the experience with allowance trading.  It is no different in
its hearsay characteristics than much of the extensive secondary information
relied upon by Dr.&nbsp;Desvousges in the report sponsored by NSP.  See, e.g.,
Tr. 17 at 10, lns. 2 - 14.  If Mr.&nbsp;McCarron's information in the stricken
Rebuttal were inaccurate, NSP had ample opportunity to respond in
Surrebuttal.<p>
