<b>Footnotes-Reply Brief of MPCA</b><p>
<a name="fn0">[1]</a> In this brief we will refer to each
party's brief submitted on January&nbsp;12, 1996, as its "Initial Brief."
References to briefs from the earlier evidentiary round of briefing will be
designated by their date.<p>
<a name="fn1">[2]</a> Comments of Sen. Johnson, Senate Committee on Jobs,
Energy, and Community Development, March 31, 1993.  These comments are quoted
in footnote 11 of MPCA's Initial Brief at 14.<p>
<a name="fn2">[3]</a> Comments of Sen. Johnson, Senate Floor, May 15, 1993.
The larger context of this quote, transcribed from legislative tapes, is
provided in footnote 12 of MPCA's Initial Brief at 14-15.<p>
<a name="fn3">[4]</a> Fifth Prehearing Order (August 24, 1994) and Order
Modifying the Administrative Law Judge's Fifth Prehearing Order on the
Consideration of Socio-Economic Factors (October 28, 1994)<p>
<a name="fn4">[5]</a> Joint Reply Brief of MPCA and Environmental Coalition on
Evidentiary Issues (Oct. 6, 1995) at 11-14 and 21.<p>
<a name="fn5">[6]</a> One additional point deserves a response.  As LEC points
out, the <u>Proctor and Gamble</u> case in dicta states that the ban could not
be upheld based on an intent to have a "coercive" effect on other
jurisdictions.  LEC Initial Brief at 51.  There is absolutely no support for
the implication that a desire to "coerce" other states lies behind the statute
or MPCA's proposed values.  <i>If</i> the Commission adopts values reflecting
out of state costs, and <i>if</i> the Commission someday decides to make a
resource choice partially motivated by a desire to reduce those
extraterritorial costs, and <i>if</i> one of the motivations is to affect the
behavior of other states, it would be a case of leading by example, not a case
of coercion.  The court in <u>Proctor and Gamble</u> clearly upholds the
validity of adopting laws in order to set an example for other jurisdictions.
<u>Proctor and Gamble</u>, 509 F.2d at 81.<p>
<a name="fn6">[7]</a> See our Initial Brief at 1-5 and section I of this brief
for our discussion of the appropriate proof requirements to apply in this
docket; and our Initial Brief at 7 through 15 for our discussion of the
uncertainties inherent in the legislature's assignment to the Commission, and
the need to proceed despite them.   <p>
<a name="fn7">[8]</a> See our Initial Brief at 14, footnote 11, where we
transcribe the comments of Senator Janet Johnson to the Senate Committee on
Jobs, Energy, and Community Development, March&nbsp;31, 1993.<p>
<a name="fn8">[9]</a>Similarly, the reports of the National Academy of Sciences
included in the record by the MPCA and quoted and relied on by Mr. Ciborowski
are written at least in part for non-scientists, given the official role of the
National Academy to advise Congress on scientific matters.  Tr. 12 at 48, ln.
24 - p. 49, ln. 11.<p>
<a name="fn9">[10]</a> The entire IPCC 1990 Report, <u>Climate Change, The IPCC
Scientific Assessment (1990)</u>, is attached to Ciborowski Surrebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;62 (hereafter IPCC 1990 Report).  The Policymakers' Summary of the
1992 Report, <u>Climate Change 1992, The Supplementary Report to the IPCC
Scientific Assessment (1992)</u>, is attached to Ciborowski Rebuttal,
Exh.&nbsp;70 (hereafter IPCC 1992 Report).  Western Fuels quotes from the body
of the IPCC 1992 Report in its Initial Brief at 38.  However, the body of the
IPCC 1992 Report is not in the record and that quotation should be stricken. <p>
<a name="fn10">[11]</a>See Mr. Ciborowski's C.V., Exh. 87.<p>
<a name="fn11">[12]</a> Dr. Harrison testified that he did not receive the
calculations far enough in advance of the surrebuttal deadline to address them
in his surrebuttal.  Harrison Surrebuttal, Exh. 10 at 9.  However, counsel for
NSP requested and received the agreement of counsel for the MPCA that they
could file supplemental surrebuttal without MPCA's objection if Dr. Harrison
found something worth rebutting in Mr. Ciborowski's calculations.  They made no
attempt to file supplemental surrebuttal.<p>
