<a name="fn16">[17]</a> The one study showing a possibility that Minnesota
would be benefitted is the so-called Mendelsohn study, which finds that
Minnesota would either benefit or be harmed by warming, depending on amount of
precipitation assumed by the model.  TER Report V.6 at 2-4; Tr. 13 at 86.
However, the scenario resulting a benefit to Minnesota agriculture depends on a
highly idealized view of a future climate where temperature is assumed to be 5
degrees warmer than present in all months, and precipitation is assumed to be 8
percent higher in all months.  Tr.&nbsp;13 at 87.  Moreover, most climate
models predict a decline in the agronomically important spring-summer soil
moisture throughout midcontinental areas of North America.  Ciborowski
Rebuttal, Exh. 70 at 26.<p>
